<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9917 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-SAMMY-AZR &LR;      02-27 1934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAMMY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SAMMY TO THE CORE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER AND DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Salvatore Gravano never said he was a changed man.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the nation's most infamous mob turncoat had moved to
Arizona and started a construction business. Yes, he got along with
the neighbors, who sometimes stopped by with a cup of coffee from
Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter found him living in Tempe, the 54-year-old, who
once admitted to 19 murders, even grinned as he gave an interview.
He soft-pedaled the chance that his old mob buddies would track him
down and knock him off.
</P>
<P>
   But even in repose, Gravano was still Sammy ``the Bull,'' as he
said in an exclusive Arizona Republic interview in July: ``I'm
Sammy. Sammy to the core.''
</P>
<P>
   With Gravano in jail again, accused of running an Arizona
syndicate that reportedly employed White supremacist gang members
to sell drugs, those comments seem eerily prescient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have my values changed?'' Gravano said during the interview.
``No. You can't change what you are inside. A leopard doesn't
change his spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Sammy's spots were indelibly imprinted growing up on the tough
streets of Bensonhurst in Brooklyn. It was there that he earned his
nickname when neighborhood wiseguys admired his grit in a fight
with two older boys over a stolen bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see this Sammy?'' one of the men remarked, according
to Gravano's biography, Underboss, written by Peter Maas. ``He's
like a little bull.''
</P>
<P>
   Sammy the Bull was born.
</P>
<P>
   An undiagnosed dyslexic, Gravano had trouble in school, was
often held back, and fell in with a bad crowd. He ran with a
notorious Brooklyn youth gang, the Rampers, and tells of a fellow
gang member being shot through the midsection as the pair fled in a
stolen car.
</P>
<P>
   The man survived, and Sammy graduated from tough kid to mobster.
For nearly 30 years, Gravano rose through the Mafia ranks,
committing burglaries, robberies and hijackings. He ran gambling
operations, fixed construction contracts and engaged in
loan-sharking. When all else failed, he pulled a gun.
</P>
<P>
   THE FIRST MURDER
</P>
<P>
   In Underboss, Gravano recalled his first killing:
</P>
<P>
   ``As the Beatles song played, I became a killer. Joe Colucci was
going to die. . . . I pointed the gun at the back of his head.
Everything went in slow motion. I could almost feel the bullet
leaving the gun and entering his skull. It was strange. I didn't
hear the first shot. I didn't seem to see any blood. . . . I shot a
second time in the same spot. This time, everything was different.
I saw the flash. I smelt the gunpowder. The noise was deafening. I
saw his head jerk back, his body convulse and slip sideways.''
</P>
<P>
   Gravano earned promotion after promotion, eventually serving as
underboss to Gambino crime family kingpin John J. Gotti.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, mob bosses were protected by the code of
silence, omerta. Old-style mobsters would do prison time before
giving up their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But with the new mob came new rules. It started with the Valachi
Papers, in which Genovese family soldier Joe Valachi revealed the
American Mafia's family structure and organization.
</P>
<P>
   Gravano had been loyal to Gotti but began to turn after hearing
his boss trash him on FBI wiretaps. After a secret meeting with
prosecutors, Gravano would change sides and testify against the
``Teflon Don.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Maas book, Gravano said he would have stuck with Gotti if
the boss had just apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had done that, I would have never cooperated with the
government, not in a million years. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``And if I lost everything and didn't want to play this game
anymore, I would have taken myself the (expletive) out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gravano was instrumental in convicting Gotti, who was sentenced
to life in prison for murder and racketeering. Gravano went on to
testify in nine trials and is credited with helping convict 39 mob
figures and their pals, perhaps crowning him as the most successful
government witness in the history of American organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   After being released from a federal prison in Arizona in 1995,
Gravano entered the Witness Protection Program and had cosmetic
surgery. Gravano said he soon quit the program because there were
too many restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't have contact with your family or anybody,'' he
said in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't exactly keep a low profile. He went on TV to promote
his book. Underboss, Sammy the Bull Gravano's Story of Life in the
Mafia was later made into a TV movie.
</P>
<P>
   The tabloids had fun with Gravano as well, calling him ``Mafia
stool pigeon'' and the ``pint-size gangster,'' referring to his 5
feet, 6 inches height.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD CALLS In the July interview, Gravano also claimed he
was offered an acting job on The Sopranos, an HBO show dramatizing
the inner workings of the New Jersey mob. The script called for
Gravano to appear as a hit man, then get killed off. He turned it
down.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was as thrilled with Sammy as Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Garofalo is suing Gravano for $50 million in the death of
her father, Edward. Garofalo told the New York Daily News that
Gravano's arrest showed he is a danger to society.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man has fooled the government and continues to fool the
government,'' she said. ``He testified just to make their case
stick, and now the joke is on them.''
</P>
<P>
   In his Arizona Republic interview in July, Gravano acknowledged
that he has other enemies more likely to use a gun than a law book.
He said there was an ``open contract'' on his life but downplayed
the chances of being killed by the mob.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Gravano said he was friendly with FBI agents and
U.S. marshals, who would drop by on vacations to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Gravano reasoned, the mob's security had been breached
by government agents, who would surely hear of any plan to kill
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mob is smart enough that when they do something, they want
to get away with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gravano had plastic surgery _ repairs to his boxer's
nose and some minor liposuction _ strangers still recognized him on
the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come right over to me,'' Gravano said. ``Some shake my
hand and congratulate me for what I did. Some want an autograph.''
</P>
<P>
   He estimated that more than 300 Phoenix area residents knew his
real identity and said sometimes he even told people his name.
</P>
<P>
   Gravano said he ruined a business deal by revealing his identity
to a prospective partner, adding, ``We thought it was ethical and
right to let them know.''
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Gravano refused to live in fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've grown up in a lifestyle,'' he said. ``There's 30,000 cops
in New York. Every time you go out, you don't know if you're coming
back. . . . I was a boxer. I know what it's like to get hit. I know
what it is to fight. And you lose your fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could go to Montana and live 20 years in a cabin and be
scared to death. Or I can live here, where I'm happy, five years. I
choose to live here.''
</P>
<P>
   He added with a smile, ``When it happens, it happens. If they
start shooting, then I'll be a little scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving witness protection, Gravano, who'd adopted the
name Jimmy Moran, began operating a pool installation and
construction business in  &UR; Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   When interviewed, he said he arose each morning at 5 and put in
a 12-hour day. He said he had always been a workaholic with ideas
racing through his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the wheeling and dealing, the business, the
whirlwind,'' he said. ``I think up deals every other minute.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was an avid chess player, often went fishing and
sometimes watched baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Gravano also said he enjoyed talking to young people. If federal
authorities are correct, Gravano was talking to them about more
than earned run averages.
</P>
<P>
   He stands accused of financing and operating a ring that
distributed as many as 30,000 tablets per week of the designer drug
Ecstasy. Authorities say that to peddle the drug, Gravano employed
a White supremacist youth gang known alternately as the Devil Dogs,
White Power and Hitler's Youth.
</P>
<P>
   The gang has terrorized minorities in the East Phoenix area in
recent years, and numerous members have been jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Gravano's family, including his wife, Debra, his two
children, Gerard, 24, and Karen, 27, and Karen's live-in boyfriend,
David Seabrook, 32, were among the 36 people arrested Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Until their recent arrests, the Gravanos had been living a quiet
life in the East Phoenix area. Gravano helped remodel his wife's
expensive Tempe house and often chatted with the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbor Vince Zajdzinski described Gravano's wife as very
sociable. He said Karen Gravano and David Seabrook recently had a
baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a problem here,'' he said. ``We're talking very
respectable people. The only problems people would have with them
is through business.''
</P>
<P>
   Zajdzinski believed that Gravano would never put his family in
danger, especially after reading Gravano's book, which praised
family ties.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Gravano lived in a modest Tempe one-bedroom
apartment to keep his family away from potential assassins. Though
he told people he was divorced, it was just a cover story to keep
his wife safe.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Gravano's son Gerard is a chip off the old
bull. He sports several tattoos attesting to his familial love,
including one on his back reading ``Blood's Thicker Than Water''
and one on his stomach reading ``Bull.''
</P>
<P>
   During his initial appearance last week in Maricopa County
Superior Court, Gerard Gravano backed up his father when the
prosecutor noted that Gerard was the son of Sammy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my father! He's a hard-working man,'' the younger
Gravano said.
</P>
<P>
   He called the drug charges against them ``petty'' and said they
were rich enough that they did not need to peddle drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's cooperated 100 percent with everybody,'' the younger
Gravano said. ``He's dealing with the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   `NATURE OF THE LIAR' Some scoff at the image of Gravano as a
concerned family man.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Cutler, a lawyer for Gotti, told the New York Times, ``We
always said that the nature of the liar and reprobate would never
change. And so it was no shock, to me, that he would do what he
does best, make money by peddling pills to children and put his own
family in harm's way.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was interviewed in July, Gravano spoke indignantly about
the treachery of others.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate his unique brand of honor, Gravano told a story
about Gotti and his trying to decide what to do about a Mafia
associate who was working with the police.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti wanted to enlist a homosexual who could destroy the
traitor's credibility by accusing him of being gay. Gravano was
horrified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `No, John, we don't do that. We're family. He's
one of us. We should just go kill him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gravano views his homicidal history in a cultural context, like
the moral relativism of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched a guy (on TV) who dropped a bomb on Hiroshima,'' he
said. ``Killed 100,000 people in one day. What's that about?''
</P>
<P>
   Gravano also boasted that each of his murders was coldblooded.
It may seem repugnant to mainstream American values, but he adhered
to the oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never killed anybody in a fit of rage,'' Gravano says.
''Everybody I killed was planned. I'm a hit man, not a serial
killer. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these things, I didn't want to do. I felt I did the
right thing in La Cosa Nostra. I was loyal to the life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was even a good person within the mob. I was
fair.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
