<SLUG> BC-BADAIR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRTY-AIR PENAL TIES TO KICK IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - For the first time, the Phoenix area's failure to
clean up air pollution is triggering federal penalties on business
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Environmental Pro tection Agency hammer falls Thursday,
and Arizona Public Service Co. will be the first business to feel
the sting of the historic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   APS must remove 2 pounds of particulates from the urban at
mosphere for every pound its expanded west-side power plant is
expected to produce.
</P>
<P>
   Particulates called PM10, be cause their size is 10 microns or
less, are tiny bits of soot and grime that can lodge deep in the
lungs. Primary sources of PM10 are unpaved roads and lots, agri
cultural activities and construc tion.
</P>
<P>
   The utility is prepared to pave streets and road shoulders to
reduce pollution.
</P>
<P>
   It could be a short-lived pen ance: The EPA notified Arizona
officials Friday that it intends to rule by early April whether a
new Phoenix area particulate-fighting plan meets federal clean-air
standards. If it does, the sanctions will be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the onset of sanctions with real bite is not a happy
occasion, even if they do prove to be temporary, said Ed Fox, a
vice president of Pinnacle West Corp., APS' parent company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think having sanctions issued against the Phoenix area
for one month is anything to be proud of,'' said Fox, a former
director of Arizona's Department of Environmental Quality.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona and Maricopa County environmental regulators said that
they hope the EPA, which last year rejected the Phoenix area's
particulate clean-up plan as too weak, will accept the new plan and
that sanctions will end before many businesses are af fected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really a short-term bump in the road,'' said
Nancy Wrona, director of the air quality division at the Arizona
Depart ment of Environmental Quality.
</P>
<P>
   Still, starting Thursday and until further notice from the EPA,
large businesses that re quire a permit to expand or open new
operations will be subject to the sanctions. This likely will
affect APS and possibly the Salt River Project, both of which plan
to expand power plants in the Phoenix area. However, the SRP's
application likely won't come up for approval by early April.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, a thumbs up on the particulate-fighting plan from
the EPA may only delay the day of reckoning. The Arizona Center for
the Law in the Public Inter est, a non-profit watchdog group,
intends to sue if the EPA ap proves the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Anderson, a lawyer with the center, said the Phoenix
area's plan lacks the most strin gent pollution controls, as re
quired by law.
</P>
<P>
   Among those measures are the adoption of cleaner-burning die sel
fuel, mandatory scrapping of old diesel trucks with high partic
ulate emissions and a halt to such farm practices as tilling and
mulching when winds exceed 25 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a long time to think about this,'' Anderson said of
the Phoenix area's battle with particulate pollution. ``We (in the
Phoenix area) have never, ever been in attainment since the Clean
Air Act amendments of 1990.''
</P>
<P>
   If a lawsuit is filed and the center prevails, the penalties
would be worse. Business sanc tions would resume, and, five months
later, the federal govern ment would be obliged to cut off
Arizona's federal freeway dol lars.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Feuerherd of the Arizona Lung Association said it's the
same old game of ``pay me now or pay me later'' when it comes to
air pollution controls.
</P>
<P>
   Two measures that could help prevent a lawsuit are before the
Arizona Legislature, Feuerherd said, although the bills are all but
dead. One would introduce CARB diesel, a cleaner-burning fuel than
what's currently in use. Another would add biodiesel to the state's
list of alternative fu els, a move favored by many school
districts. They want to use biodiesel in buses to meet the state's
alternative-fuel mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Feuerherd predicts a wave of ``frenetic construction activity''
between now and next year, when he figures the center's case will
be won and tougher sanctions kick in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is an open-and-shut case,'' said Feuer herd, the
Lung Association's pro gram director. ``People have their heads in
the sand, or maybe in the dust storm. They don't under stand the
health effects of what they're doing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
