<HEADER>
A9919 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-COMBINE-LADN     02-27 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COMBINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECEIVERS GET PLENTY OF ATTENTION AT COMBINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS -- When professional football historians look back
on 2000 there's a good chance they'll remember it as the year of
the receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Who would blame them?
</P>
<P>
   After all, the group of wide receivers invited this year's
scouting combine may be the best ever assembled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't speak about each individual specifically,''
said Bill Walsh, Vice President and General Manager of the San
Francisco 49ers. ``But, this group is really among the all-time
best. Quarterbacks were in abundance last year, but this year it's
wide receivers.``
</P>
<P>
   In all, 45 receivers are taking part in the four-day scouting
combine, an event that gives NFL teams an opportunity to scout the
top talent before April's college draft. UCLA is represented by
Danny Farmer. USC's Windrell Hayes and R. Jay Soward are also in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three, there's a good chance that Soward and Farmer will
be taken in the first round. How well they do on a variety of
physical and psychological tests administered today and Monday will
determine just how early each goes.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count Hayes out of the early rounds either.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another opportunity to show that I can play with
anybody,'' Hayes said. ``I haven't had the opportunity yet to show
what I can do. I'm going to go out and show that I can do anything
they can do -- if not better.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Soward, who grew up in Rialto, a variety of factors could
affect his fortunes. Saturday he spent several hours in an area
hospital being X-rayed from head to toe.
</P>
<P>
   One NFL scout, who asked not to be identified, said Soward's
performance so far has been less than stellar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's real flake,'' the scout said. ``That could hurt him
here.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, others Saturday continued to mention Soward in the
same breath as the creme of the crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think there'd be 4 or 5 guys taken in the first
round,'' Tampa Bay head coach Tony Dungy said. ``Warrick is going
to go high; Burress; Soward; Farmer. I think those are going to be
some of the play makers that come out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Farmer, a Loyola High graduate, said he was pretty
comfortable with the entire process, mainly because he's been
getting a lot of help from his father.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably pretty good help as Farmer's father, who grew up
in La Puente, played professionally for the Chicago Bears and
Detroit Lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been through it and he helps me out a lot,'' Farmer said.
``It's different though. Back then they didn't have this. He got a
call from a radio station (telling him he'd been drafted).`` As for
the combine: ``He just kind of said to be myself and things will
happen for the best,'' Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers, Farmer, Soward and hayes had relatively similar
1999 seasons. Soward played in 11 games, caught 51 passes for 655
yards and four touchdowns. Hayes played in 10 games, caught 55
passes for 720 yards and four touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer's season was shortened by injury to nine games. He caught
29 passes for 573 and scored 3 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   While it's likely the Cleveland Browns will take Warrick with
the first pick, both he and Cleveland General Manager Dwight Clark
praised the quality of this year's receiver class.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of them man,'' Warrick said. ``I know they are a
great bunch of guys, because if they wasn't, they wouldnt' be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark spoke more specifically about the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we decided not to go with (Warrick as) the first one, I
think we could still get a starter,'' Clark said. ``After you watch
these guys on tape and them you talk to them, you fall in love.
Today, I've been falling in love every 15 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford quarterback Todd Husak, who is attending the combine,
made his way through the lobby of the Crown Plaza Saturday
unmolested by reporters who didn't recognize him. He stopped
briefly to take in the scene and remark on a group of wide
receivers he had just met.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny seeing all these guys like Warrick and Burress,''
Husak said, with a grin. ``From a fan standpoint these are the top
guys here -- seeing all these guys is pretty cool.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
