A9921 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-FEED-AZR &LR;      02-27 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEED-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD HELP FINANCE FOOD USED AS MEDICINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Christian Conner is 3, clutching fistfuls of rubber
snakes and asking for more ce real.
</P>
<P>
   But he can't have more than the quarter-cup he had at break
fast. His mother tries to appease him with, ``Here, have some
juice.''
</P>
<P>
   The toddler has phenylketon uria, a rare genetic metabolic
disorder that forces him to follow a strict low-protein diet or
else be mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, miles from Christian's Chandler home, lawmakers will
debate just who should pay for the costly formula and special foods
that keep the little boy from losing his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, efforts like Arizona's are under way to make
insurance companies cover the cost of the medically necessary foods
such people as Christian need to stay intact.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Susan Gerard, R-north central Phoenix, introduced a bill
this session to force insurance companies to pay half, with a cap
of $4,000 a year. It goes before the full House on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   California and Montana re cently passed similar bills, though
without caps. Advocates are pushing national legislation as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ludicrous that we have to go to the Legislature to make a
medical insurance company pay for a medical treatment,'' says Susan
Cox, a genetics counselor for the University of Arizona-Phoenix
Genetics Program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only recognized treatment, and it is considered
the standard of care. Yes, it happens to be food, but if you feed
them a normal diet, they are retarded or dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies nation wide have balked at paying for the
formula, saying it is more a food supplement than medicine. In
Arizona, insurance lobbyists have agreed to Gerard's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 115 people in Arizona have metabolic disorders, mostly
phenylketonuria, or PKU.
</P>
<P>
   Sufferers lack the enzyme that breaks down an amino acid called
phenylalanine, or PHE, which is found in all proteins in varying
amounts. In their bodies, PHE builds to toxic levels, attacking the
central nervous system and causing neurological damage.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting their brains de pends on sticking to a diet of
virtually no protein. No meat. No dairy products. Limited amounts
of most everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Because they can eat so little, their only chance at survival is
a formula containing a protein sub stitute, calories, vitamins and
minerals. It costs $18 to $80 a can, depending on the disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Christian's mother weighs and measures the little food her son
can eat, writing it down in a daily log. She pays $5.59 for a loaf
of low-protein bread and $7.75 for a pound of low-protein macaroni.
</P>
<P>
   And, three times a day, Chris tian drinks a foul-smelling for
mula that gives him what he needs to grow.
</P>
<P>
   It will be like this for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Jenise Holyoak, 29, of King man, was diagnosed with PKU when she
was 3 weeks old. She goes through $30 of formula a day, a great
expense for a first-grade teacher with a husband still in college.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard's bill awaits House ap proval after weeks of wrangling
with insurance lobbyists. The bill also must be approved by the
Senate, where Sen. Russell Bow ers, R-Mesa, tacked a similar
proposal to a big insurance-reform bill.
</P>
<P>
   Formula for children diag nosed through the state's new born
screening program is provided for free until age 21. After that,
patients pay for it, as well as the food.
</P>
<P>
   Cox estimates the yearly cost for kids under 1 is $2,500, $4,500
for ages 1 to 4, and $9,900 for older kids, teenagers and adults.
</P>
<P>
   The formula and food can be used only under a doctor's super
vision. The formula is what keeps sufferers alive, Conner says; the
foods _ ordered through the mail from a handful of compa nies
worldwide _ helps fill their stomachs and gives them some semblance
of a normal life.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Burgess of Bullhead City has a paternal uncle with PKU who
is mentally retarded and living in a group home, the result of
poorly treated PKU. So, when Burgess' daughter, Lauren, 5, was
diagnosed with PKU, he and his wife vowed to keep her on a strict
diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not counting the formula, she would probably eat less in a
whole day than you or I eat in a whole meal,'' Burgess says.
</P>
<P>
   But Lauren is a happy child, playing with her sisters, Ashley,
8, and Sydney, 2. She is in kindergarten but reads at a sec
ond-grade level.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has to have the formula to sustain a quality life,''
Burgess says. ``Just like the guy who has to have insulin, she
needs it.''
</P>
<P>
   PKU has more than 220 muta tions, some more severe than others.
Doctors began screening newborns for it in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosed early and treated right, the first generation of PKU
sufferers are living normal lives as adults, going to college, work
ing and raising families.
</P>
<P>
   At first, doctors put PKU pa tients on the strict diet until age
8, figuring their brains were developed enough by then not to be
damaged. Later studies showed those patients continued to lose
brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   Holyoak's mother once saw a young girl with PKU, huddled in a
wheelchair and drooling. She decided not to take her daughter off
the diet despite doctors' as sertions that it would be OK.
</P>
<P>
   At a Tucson clinic, Cox works with two teenagers from Mexico
with PKU who were not diag nosed until they were 4 and 6. They are
severely mentally re tarded, unable to speak and prone to seizures.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Christian is fine, full of giggles and climbing on a
bright play set.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he weren't on diet, it would be a different story,'' his
mother says.
</P>
<P>
   Christian can have 288 milli grams of PHE a day. A half-cup of
Honey Nut Cheerios has 106 milligrams of PHE, and one ear of corn
on the cob has 213.
</P>
<P>
   His mother makes 2-inch patties of mushrooms and baking mix that
contain 50 milligrams of PHE. She orders a low-protein 8-inch pizza
for $6.39.
</P>
<P>
   None of it tastes very good.
</P>
<P>
   As Christian grows, his allot ment of PHE will not. As a man, he
will eat the same amount of food he ate as a toddler.
</P>
<P>
   Christian sits on the couch, knees to his chest and drinking a
bottle of the formula. Adult suf ferers often drink the formula
through straws from closed con tainers because of the smell.
</P>
<P>
   Christian doesn't complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all he's ever known,'' Conner says.
</P>
<P>
   Christian's brother, Dylan, 1, does not have the disorder. Chris
tian notes that Dylan gets scram bled eggs for breakfast while he
eats low-protein porridge.
</P>
<P>
   One night at dinner, Christian's father put a platter of chicken
on the table. The little boy quickly announced, ``I can't have
that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
