<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NESTEGGS-GONE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS TELL STORIES OF GREED, FEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID GREENBERG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Back in April 1997, while fixing machinery at a
Chatsworth business, Jerry Womack grumbled about why he was still
working as a repairman since he made $350,000 in the stock market
just the week before.
</P>
<P>
   The shop owner said he asked Womack how he, too, could get a
piece of the Wall Street pie. And so began the career of Jerry
Womack, investment guru - and authorities say conman, who bilked
$16 million from investors mainly in the San Fernando Valley and
Ventura County areas.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two years, the 50-year-old resident of Las Vegas
attracted nearly 400 more investors, enticed through word of mouth
and a series of rousing seminars at Simi Valley's Clarion Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he presided over the meetings, he looked down from the
podium as though Moses himself was delivering a sermon to his
disciples,'' said a West Hills woman, who invested $26,000 she had
saved for her retirement from her aerospace job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like, Oh, golly gee! I can't wait to give him more
money to make me wealthier. He was believable. He had people
salivating.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could liken this to a religious revival meeting, he
would have had them running down the aisle, crying and kissing his
feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Womack was running a pyramid scheme rather than
a legitimate investment enterprise. The West Hills woman lost
$16,110 of her nest egg - and most of the other investors lost
money, too.
</P>
<P>
   Now Womack is scheduled to stand trial March 14 on nine federal
counts of wire fraud - charges he denies.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Patrick Maginnis, who previously has called Womack a
``very charming individual'' with no criminal record, did not
return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   With a booming stock market and Womack's charming pitch, it was
easy to get caught up, said several investors who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   They gave Womack small amounts of money at first, then more as
he mailed them professional-looking balance sheets that boasted of
profits. Those investors said they shared news of their good
fortune with friends and relatives, who became investors
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   A Moorpark business manager said he cashed out his 401(k) plan
and refinanced his house so he could invest $150,000 - an amount
Womack claimed grew to $580,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, I'm a pretty cautious guy,'' said the man, who wound
up losing $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The temptation) was based on a cadre of people that you've
met that were in the fund, based on their professionalism and their
vocation. The guy was always visible. He had meetings and there
were hundreds of people there. The facade is there, but that
doesn't mean the substance is there.''
</P>
<P>
   During the meetings, investors said, Womack used his charm to
successfully pitch the Womack Dow Principal - his strategy for
recognizing stock trends so brokers could buy low and sell high
within a day's time, reaping fast profits.
</P>
<P>
   Womack bragged that he had two to four traders on the floor of
the New York Stock Exchange, investing in the Dow Jones industrial
average's 30 stocks solely for him, court documents show.
</P>
<P>
   And for a minimum $2,200 investment, residents could join Iris
Limited Partnership. Under the agreement, Womack would get 30
percent of the net profits, plus an additional 5 percent for
administrative expenses, records show.
</P>
<P>
   A Pasadena real estate broker said he gave $56,000 to Womack and
was told that his investment had grown to $285,000. In fact, the
59-year-old lost $48,000 - and his 84-year-old mother lost $50,000
of the money she invested with Womack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hard-earned money,'' said the broker. ``She saved
everything she could. It was part of her retirement money. I feel
worse about her losing her money than I do about mine.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is at the end of her earning potential power. It's money
that she really needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Court documents said that instead of investing the money as he
agreed to do, Womack spent it lavishly on himself and his family.
</P>
<P>
   He had a posh home in Las Vegas - complete with a fountain and a
gazebo - along with luxury cars, a boat and expensive jewelry, the
documents said. He bought his second wife a Florida home and gave
her $250,000 cash and five parcels of land in South Carolina as
part of their divorce settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Third wife Linda Lee got a Mercedes-Benz, jewelry and other
gifts before their brief 1999 marriage, records show. Womack also
gave $214,600 to her ex-husband, Rick Lee, to bolster his failing
online pornography business.
</P>
<P>
   Court records also said that Womack did pay $2 million to $3
million to investors from February 1999 through April 1999. And
since his arrest on Oct. 15, authorities have recovered about $1
million in cash and assets.
</P>
<P>
   Even before his arrest, investors were getting concerned about
their money. Meetings that previously had resembled pep rallies
turned into shouting matches, with investors demanding answers, as
well as their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Womack began to offer a multitude of excuses over a period of
time as to why he would not be able to repay the investors their
monies due. Womack never claimed to have lost any money, always
claiming that the profit and original investment was located in an
account in New York,'' the FBI said in court documents. ``Womack
always furnished various explanations as to why he could not access
the funds.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, documents said, only a couple dozen of the investors
- most of whom signed up early on - received more money than they
put in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never promised a specific return. He just told you what he
had done in the past and he would emphasize that he had doubled his
money every six months,'' said a Ventura County businessman who
invested more than $100,000 with Womack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greed and fear played a role in every single person who is
(now) honest with himself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fear that if we crossed Jerry, he wouldn't give us our
money. And it was greed - that we wanted to get as much as we can
get,'' he said. ``In retrospect, I feel it was pretty stupid to
allow myself to get carried away like that.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
