<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-COLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA BRINGS COLEY TO HIS KNEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Derrell Coley said he was going to knock out Oscar De
La Hoya Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. The way he fought, he would have had
trouble with Oscar de la Renta.
</P>
<P>
   For three rounds, De La Hoya did what he wanted with Coley at
Madison Square Garden before running into a combination early in
the fourth that ended with a stunning right that momentarily seemed
to put the four-time world champion in trouble. But when the
journeyman from Washington who had promised a knockout tried to
deliver it, he ran into a left hook that wobbled him badly and
changed his approach.
</P>
<P>
   When he came out for the fifth round, Coley was no longer trying
to land the big hook that he once hoped could change his life.
Instead, he was trying to avoid the one that could change his
profile _ but the moth can avoid the flame for only so long. In
Coley's case, it took barely six more minutes before he was burned
out, ending slumped on one knee as referee Wayne Kelly counted him
out at exactly three minutes of the seventh round.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the sixth, Coley already had run into a string of
left hooks, the last two causing him to do a stutter step to his
corner that Deion Sanders would have admired. He was not yet out,
but there was no more fight in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very strong,'' De La Hoya said. ``My jab was really
snapping out there. I was very patient early because he was boxing
a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I'd fight four times this year and get four knockouts.
No disrespect to Derrell Coley. He was just the first up. This is
just the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through one more round, it was the end for Coley not
long after he blew his nose and a red plume of blood flew out.
Seconds later, Coley's right eye began to close and it was stalking
time, not talking time, for De La Hoya (32-1, 26 KO) and he well
understood it.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the end of that seventh round, De La Hoya drove home
a left to Coley's liver and the D.C. welterweight sank to one knee.
As Kelly counted, Coley made no effort to get up, not because he
was unwilling, but because he was unwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have got up, but I didn't have it in me,'' said Coley
(34-2-2). ``I wasn't strong enough. I was too weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely able to breathe and nearly blind in one eye, Coley stayed
where it was safe for 10 more seconds and then his long night with
De La Hoya was over.
</P>
<P>
   Across the ring, De La Hoya was promising this was only the
beginning. If he ends up fighting a rematch with Felix Trinidad,
the only fighter to beat him, it now will come June 10 in Las Vegas
at 150 pounds, give or take a pound. If not, he will take on
undefeated former lightweight champion Shane Mosley June 17 in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Derrell Coley will be happy not to be there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
