<HEADER>
A9926 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-GAMACHE-GATTI-BOS     02-27 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-GAMACHE-GATTI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATTI FLATTENS GAMACHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was supposed to be a boxing match. It turned out
to be a mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   Even before former two-time world champion Joey Gamache got into
the ring Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at Madison Square Garden to face Arturo
Gatti, the issue had been decided: At the weigh-in Friday, only
three-quarters of a pound separated them, 36 hours later, 14 pounds
did. Once it became clear the junior welterweight from Lewiston was
fighting a 160-pound middleweight, what followed was sadly, and
nearly tragically, predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Barely two minutes into the bout, Gamache went down for the
first time, falling flat on his back and out of the ropes onto the
ring apron by a straight right hand from the 27-year-old former IBF
junior lightweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   Gamache's greatest ally had always been his legs, but they
wobbled beneath him when he got up. They were all that could have
saved him Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, and in less than two minutes they were
gone. Soon after, so was Gamache.
</P>
<P>
   Gamely, he got up and tried to attack, but Gatti was too strong
and Gamache too impaired to avoid what was coming. Gamache landed
three sizzling left hooks despite being all but out on his feet,
but although they snapped Gatti's head back, they did not carry
enough ammo to stop him. When he got close enough to land a left to
the body and a stinging left to the head, Gamache tumbled onto his
back a second time before the first round was over.
</P>
<P>
   Although he got up again, Gamache was like a man lost in a Maine
blizzard. He was blind and lost, wandering into deeper woods with
every step.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew after the first round I was too strong for him,'' said
Gatti (31-4, 26 KO), a fact that was to be expected when one guy
enters the ring weighing 160 pounds and the other 146.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow he survived that round, survived even a shot from Gatti
after the bell, but 41 seconds into the second round, Gamache's
boing career came to a terrifying end when Gatti nailed him with a
stunning three-punch combination: a right uppercut on the chin, a
big left hook to the face, and a final right hand to the jaw that
sent Gamache collapsing flat onto his back again.
</P>
<P>
   Before he landed he was out, his body limp and unable to break
its own fall. The back of his head slammed so hard into the canvas
it bounced back up 6 inches or more before falling to earth a
second time. By the time it landed, Gamache was asleep.
</P>
<P>
   Four doctors tried to revive him. Dazed and unseeing, Gamache
finally turned to one and said, ``Sit me up!''
</P>
<P>
   They did and within seconds he laid back down, the lights above
him swimming, his eyes seeing the black lights only a man who has
been concussed ever sees.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he revived himself again and told the physician, ``Get
me up.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor refused at first, saying he had to take him out of
the ring on a stretcher. Gamache cried the game warrior's last cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't put me on a stretcher,'' he said, and the four doctors
kneeling next to him agreed to let him try to walk. After he stood
up, long minutes after first lying still as midnight, Gamache took
a few tottering steps, like a baby first learning how to move
across a room alone.
</P>
<P>
   He weaved right and left, something he would have been better
served doing when Gatti was still throwing punches. Slowly, he
seemed to right himself until he finally was allowed to slip
through the ropes upright, avoiding one last indignity in a boxing
career filled with much glory and four nights of pain.
</P>
<P>
   This was the fourth and final loss of Gamache's long career, one
that has brought him 55 wins and two world titles. Saturday night,
though, boxing brought him what it brings everyone who tries it in
the end.
</P>
<P>
   It brought him embarrassment and unconsciousness and the kind of
bad beating a matchmaker should have been arrested for. It brought
him to St. Vincent's Hospital for a CAT scan, too.
</P>
<P>
   Gamache thought he had a chance to win Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. Maybe he
did if the dice hadn't been loaded with 14 pounds of dead weight.
Once they were, the rest was just a matter of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
