<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9932 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-WHEELCHAIR-BASKETBALL     02-27 1903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHEELCHAIR-BASKETBALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITER GETS FIRSTHAND APPRECIATION OF WHEELCHAIR BASKETBALL TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOBIAS XAVIER LOPEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fear hit me that first night as I lay awake in bed, alone in
the dark. I couldn't get comfortable, and my legs screamed out for
straightening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do this,'' I thought. ``I can't do this for a whole
week. This is a dumb idea.''
</P>
<P>
   A month earlier, I strutted into the office of Jim Hayes, coach
of the UT-Arlington wheelchair-basketball team, to discuss the idea
of joining the Movin' Mavs. Hayes agreed, only asking that the team
be portrayed as athletes and not victims.
</P>
<P>
   I had casts put on both knees, forcing me to spend 24 hours a
day for a week without use of my legs so I could try to understand
what they endure.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as I wrestled with my anxiety, I had another problem. I had
to go to the bathroom, but my wheelchair wouldn't fit through the
door.
</P>
<P>
   So I developed the butt scoot. It consisted of sitting on the
cold tile floor, looking over my shoulder and using my hands to
pull myself backward along the floor to the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   The next day at practice, Hayes greeted me with a powerful
handshake. His grip is rough, like grabbing a cheese grater, but
then these hands once pushed a wheelchair 205 miles in 25 hours
from Austin to Arlington in a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes asked me how things were going, and I told him of my
growing prowess at the butt scoot. He laughed unsympathetically,
adding, ``Welcome to our world.''  &LR; subheds:AMAZING GRACE  &LR; body:Two
and a half weeks before the National Collegiate Wheelchair
Basketball Tournament, the Movin' Mavs' scrimmage has turned almost
nasty.
</P>
<P>
   Linh Bowie sends T.K. Dannelley sprawling, and the clatter of
his chair across the floor sounds as if someone dropped a drawer
full of silverware.
</P>
<P>
   Enoch Ablorh, recognizing the mood swing, rolls to the sideline
and snags his elbow pads. Fouls are being called and vehemently
disputed. Enoch, the team's captain, fakes left, spins 180 degrees
and attempts a pass to the low post, only to have it slapped back
in his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't use that same old pass,'' Valdez Bradley yells as
punctuation. ``We all know that one. You'd better try something
new.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, there's a cymbal-like crash, and everyone pauses
until they figure out who it is. Brad Ness, a powerful 6-foot-4
Australian, rolls off the court, short a couple of spokes.
</P>
<P>
   And this is practice.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing to see how well these guys handle their lightweight
aluminum-framed wheelchairs _ aggressive yet beautiful, filled with
rapid starts and stops, 360-degree turns followed by reverse 360s.
</P>
<P>
   Their upper bodies are sculpture-perfect, muscle crafted through
honest labor. All the scene needed was symphony music and slow
motion to accentuate the graceful movements of their chairs dancing
across the hardwood.
</P>
<P>
   The Movin' Mavs have won five national championships since their
first season in 1989-90, and the competition for starting jobs
among the 12 players is one of the most intense in collegiate
wheelchair sports. Of the 12 college teams, only No. 1 Illinois and
Wisconsin-Whitewater are expected to compete with UTA for the
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Movin' Mavs also compete against semipro teams, many
sponsored by NBA teams, including the Mavericks. The National
Wheelchair Basketball Association has 250 to 300 teams in three
men's divisions, and it has a women's division and a junior
division.
</P>
<P>
   During another practice, I notice Valdez Bradley salvaging
pieces from used and battered wheelchairs. He said it's a
necessity. He has never had a custom chair, which would cost $1,200
to $2,400, so he's trying to convert a chair built for a one-legged
player into a two-legged chair to match his 6-foot-1 frame.
</P>
<P>
   He finishes wrapping plastic tape around one of the backrest
posts and asks Campbell Message for a lighter. He uses the lighter
to slightly melt the tape so it won't unravel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got shot when I was 18 and had sciatic nerve damage,'' said
Valdez, 23. ``I got shot in my back a couple times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of times?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, like four.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where was this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``New Orleans,'' Valdez said. ``The police report said it was
robbery, but they never took anything. So I'm thinking it was a
case of mistaken identity or something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an inspirational story,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Valdez responded with a laugh. ``Yeah,'' he said, ``a story of
how you can get shot and banged up and get a scholarship out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did they get the bullets out of your back?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they don't take them out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you set metal detectors off?'' Campbell asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' Valdez said. ``I thought I would.''  &LR; subheds:LEARNING
TO COPE  &LR; body:One day, I was stuck at a curb facing the street when
22-year-old Eddie McGee happened by.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie had his left leg amputated when he was 11, after cancer
invaded his knee. He is the kind of guy who would give you the axle
pins from his chair, which he did for me when we built my chair.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Eddie helped me figure a way off the curb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pop a wheelie,'' he said, ``then push your way forward till
your back wheels come off.''
</P>
<P>
   I attempted a wheelie but maintained altitude only long enough
for gravity to throw me off the edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like that?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Eddie replied, ``that's called falling off a curb.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked him what he thought of what I was doing, and he quickly
reassured me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone should have to do it, at least for a day,'' he said.
``Then they'd think twice the next time they parked in a
handicapped spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The office where I work is accessible from the parking lot.
There are ramps and a wide seeing-eye door, but what good is access
if your chair doesn't fit through the restroom door? No one should
have to butt-scoot across the company bathroom tile and stretch to
reach a sink with his face a foot away from the urinal.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes said people in wheelchairs have to come to terms with
their situations. During my week in a chair, I came nowhere near
those terms. It broke my heart that I couldn't play with my
9-month-old son, Ashton, as we had a week earlier. I was frequently
frustrated, especially when I got stuck trying to wheel through
grass, and unjustly vented at my fiancee, Stephanie. I was living
real life, in which babies cry and lovers quarrel, and I wasn't
dealing with it well at all. I wondered if I would have the inner
strength to come to terms if my situation were permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Before my final practice, I asked Jim Hayes how he helps his
players cope.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, 50, has come to terms with a broken neck he suffered
while celebrating his 18th birthday. He tried jumping into Benbrook
Lake from a barge, but his foot slipped and he landed in two feet
of water.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, life expectancy after a serious neck injury was six
years, Hayes said, but he survived through participation in
wheelchair athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple innate things just built into this program
that deal with \Rcoming to terms\S,'' he said. ``One, you will
notice from time to time a lot of arguments going on, on the court.
And I have the experience to know that you've got to let that
happen because they're venting. The other thing that's critical
about this, and the program forces this to happen, is it builds a
bridge between `Damn, I wish I could walk' and `OK, what do I do
now?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Schulte, 21, the most valuable player of the 1999 national
tournament, copes by focusing on his basketball skills, which have
earned him a spot on the United States Paralympic Team. He also
played in an exhibition during this year's NBA All-Star weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's got a disability. Some people's are just more, you
know, obvious,'' Paul said. ``I know of a lot more people who have
more mental handicaps than I do physical ones, and I play on a
wheelchair-basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul said he was fortunate his accident happened when he was
young. A head-on collision at 35 mph left a 10-year-old Paul with
lower vertebrae injuries. His lap belt held him in place but gave
his spine whiplash.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life before that, I remember it, but it's like a dream, and
so I still dream in my dreams that I can walk,'' he said. ``I don't
think you're ever completely over something like this, when you're
such a minority, when you're so different from 90 percent of the
world, you don't ever completely get over it. And some days, things
happen that remind me that I'm disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people this really brings down their confidence
because they think of what they can't do, what they can't do, what
they can't do. The real trick is to find something that you can do
and work at it and excel, because that's what drives you, you know:
Getting better at things and developing their talents.''
 &LR; subheds:THE FINAL STEP  &LR; body:My talents had improved slightly,
though I wasn't close to competing at this level. I never felt more
fatigued in my 26 years, but I did get even with the family dog for
using me as a scratching post. I ran over his squeaky chew toys.
</P>
<P>
   I was glad when it was my last day in a wheelchair, but I also
felt sadness and guilt about walking away from the team. Hayes
spoke softly about what he now called ``our story'' and how he
hoped the national wheelchair tournament would never have as many
teams as the 64-team NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the important thing,'' he said. ``Somewhere, every day,
a young kid and his family have to deal with the reality that life
has changed forever. It's our story; it's their story. What do we
do now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can show you that in that short time frame an individual
doesn't know whether he's going to live or die. And, after a
certain period of time, the individual is going to wish he were
dead because he will compare it to everything he's always been and
all the hopes of daddy for him to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be have been true in the 1930s and '40s, that life
was going to be short and it was going to be pretty miserable. But
that was before wheelchair basketball. We hope that you may scare
some young kid into not jumping off in that lake and breaking his
back. Or reminding some young kid to buckle up or to put the helmet
on before climbing on the motorcycle or to just be a little more
cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the one sport where it would not break my heart to
never have another player for those reasons. But we're going to
have them, it's going to happen, and I thank God everyday that the
university has seen the wisdom of a program like this.''
</P>
<P>
   After practice, with the setting sun peeking through the cracks
in the window paint, Eddie McGee cut loose my casts at center
court. I tried to stand, but my knees buckled twice. Linh Bowie
laughed and told me to take it slow. I brushed the plaster powder
from my leg hairs and shook their hands.
</P>
<P>
   We left, me pushing my wheelchair, this time from behind;
Stephanie, my fiancee, pushing my son, Ashton, in the stroller;
Eddie on his crutches; and Linh in his chair.
</P>
<P>
   I thought of the riddle of the Sphinx and how fortunate we are
when surrounded by good people. The riddle asks: What walks on four
legs, then two and then three? The answer: Man, who crawls as a
baby, then walks and finally walks with a cane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobias,'' Hayes called out, ``take care of that baby.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
