<HEADER>
A9935 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-RELIGION-     02-27 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-RELIGION-TEX </SLUG>
 TWO RANGERS PLAYERS SHARE CHRISTIAN
FAITH (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By T.R. SULLIVAN
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ R.A. Dickey had a right to be bitter,
resentful and angry at the Rangers, the world and life in general
in the summer of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   An All-America pitcher from Tennessee, 1996 Olympian and
first-round draft pick, Dickey was just a couple hours away from
receiving an $825,000 signing bonus from the Rangers when his dream
world came to a crashing and painful halt. The Rangers received a
medical report showing Dickey had no ulnar collateral ligament in
his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   For those scoring at home, pitchers normally can't throw without
the ligament. Those who tear it, like Kerry Wood, have to undergo
``Tommy John'' surgery and have to sit out an entire season.
</P>
<P>
   As devastating as the news was, Dickey now says it was ``one of
the greatest blessings I've ever received in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that even though that blessing included the Rangers
withdrawing their $825,000 offer and signing Dickey for $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the money I might have lost is not worth what's really
come out of the situation,'' Dickey said. ``I think I'm blessed.
It's miraculous that I'm even able to throw. I don't know many
people who are born without an ulnar collateral ligament who can
throw 90 miles per hour. God's done miraculous things in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey sincerely believes that and it's an underlying reason why
he and minor-league teammate Jonathan Johnson have founded Honoring
Thy Father, a Christian outreach organization and support group.
Foremost among their goals is to show athletes can compete at the
highest levels of professional sports and still be a witness for
Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not up to us to change people,'' said Johnson, a pitcher
and another former Rangers No. 1 draft pick who has had a difficult
time as a professional. ``That's God's job. We just want to be an
example and hope that through our example we can make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie White \Ran All-Pro defensive end\S is the best example
I can think of. He says, `Hey, I'm one of the biggest and baddest
guys on the field and I'm still a Christian.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dickey, ``Look at Kurt Warner, a guy like that who is bold
enough to step up and say, `I'm a Christian.' People see that and
say, these are the kind of heroes we need.''
</P>
<P>
   Most athletes wait until they make millions of dollars before
they start charitable organizations. Johnson and Dickey were
thinking about this as far back as 1994, when they both were on the
U.S. national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to invest in the future,'' Johnson said. ``It scares
me when I turn on the television and see so much violence in our
elementary and high schools. God has given me this platform as a
baseball player, if I can show people I'm a real man in a real job,
that can give somebody something to look up to.''
</P>
<P>
   They do so in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Witness. They have taken their message to school, athletic and
church youth groups. They have a Web site, and Dickey has been on
``Hour of Power'', the nationwide television show that has the Rev.
Robert Schuller as host.
</P>
<P>
   Benevolence. Honoring Thy Father is trying to raise $15,000 to
build a church in Mexico in the off-season. Dickey, Johnson and
other athletes plan on doing the actual construction.
</P>
<P>
   Fellowship. Honoring Thy Father consists of about 30 players
from different teams _ St. Louis Cardinals outfielder J.D. Drew and
Boston Red Sox pitcher John Wasdin are among them _ who call on
each other for support and keep each other accountable for their
actions.
</P>
<P>
   But Dickey made one thing clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have tended to see Christian athletes as soft and
non-competitive,'' Dickey said. ``That's not true. J.J. and I are
competitive, we want to get to the big leagues and stay there. The
difference is we're obedient to something greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey, overcoming his missing ligament, has slowly climbed his
way through the organization. To preserve his arm, the Rangers have
switched him to relief. He still throws 91 miles per hour with a
combination ``knuckler-splitter'' that has become his trick pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the Rangers' top draft pick in 1995, is 35-39 with a
4.48 earned-run average in five minor-league seasons. He has made
two appearances with the Rangers but mostly has been stuck the past
three years at Triple A in Oklahoma City with a combined record of
15-18 and a 5.87 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a constant battle for me, wondering why I'm not up
there,'' Johnson said. ``I wonder why these guys are in the big
leagues and I'm not. I was a No. 1 draft pick; I was drafted ahead
of them. But I work as hard as I can and pitch as best as I can. I
was blessed with talent, and it would be a sin not to use the
talent He's given me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know God has a plan for me and I have to make myself
available to him.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
