<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS END LOSING STREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Clippers win.
</P>
<P>
   Say it again?
</P>
<P>
   Nah, even though the only team that's been dragging more than
the Clips must be found at the Iditarod, they've tasted victory a
whopping one dozen times now.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday's 78-77 victory over the Atlanta Hawks (22-31)
before 14,375 at Staples Center is a fine excuse for putting
several numbers to bed.
</P>
<P>
   This triumph ends a 13-game losing streak, the last 11 defeats
pinned on interim head coach Jim Todd. It also is the Clippers'
first victory in February and the first since they've slipped past
the New Jersey Nets exactly four weeks ago. It's their third win in
the last 30 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why it doesn't happen every night I don't know,'' Todd said,
``but we'll get it together.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Anderson had 21 points to lead the Clippers (12-45).
Isaiah Rider, who has led the Atlanta renaissance since the Hawks
decided against trading him, scored 14 of his 16 points in the
second half. Rider, who is to team chemistry as Chapter 7 is to
your next home loan, nailed a 20-footer to bring the Hawks all the
way back from a 14-point, third-quarter hole and tie the score at
77 with 1:07 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Odom made 1 of 2 free throws to give the Clips their final
78-77 edge with 22.5 seconds remaining. The Hawks gagged on their
closing position, and the streak was history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get up for a team like Sacramento and Seattle,'' Hawks
coach Lenny Wilkens said, ``and we've gotta get up for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom (10 points, 12 rebounds, 7 assists) just had to get up,
period. The Clipper rookie started at point guard, but seemed a
longshot for duty after throwing up at the morning shoot around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something just told me to play,'' said Odom, whose only
apparent illness was a 4-of-16 performance from the field. ``This
has to be the biggest win of the entire season since it's been so
long since the last one.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Clippers, beating the Hawks stirred up a win-lose
situation. Thanks to last summer's sign-and-trade event involving
free-agent Clipper Lorenzen Wright, the Clips have two first-round
picks that belonged to Atlanta. The most attractive of the pair is
a protected pick that's based on the Hawks' record this season. But
if Atlanta's pick is one of the first nine, the Hawks keep it and
the Clips have it next season. Anything 10 or beyond belongs to the
Clippers this year.
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of two consecutive road victories - including a Friday
night upset at Seattle - the Hawks had the 11th-worst record in the
NBA. If draft-lottery Ping-Pong balls obey the odds, the Clippers -
who figure to lose a pair of starters via free agency this summer -
will be in business.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't exactly play with great skill Saturday, making just
37.6 percent of their field-goal attempts. They also were
outrebounded, 52-44, but weren't prepared to quibble over the
scoreboard numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed this to sleep a little better at night,'' Odom said.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: After 13 defeats in a row, the Clippers decided to Tar
Heel themselves. As expected, they signed and suited up point guard
Jeff McInnis, rescuing the ex-North Carolina player from the CBA's
Quad City Thunder. McInnis, 25, left UNC after his junior season in
1996. And it wasn't exactly shocking that the Clips also brought
back forward Pete Chilcutt (Carolina, '91), who did a 10-day tour
of duty with the team earlier this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 0212EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
