<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC TAKES A HARD FALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC's odds of making the NCAA Tournament are about
as remote as saying Brian Scalabrine will trip and fall going for
an inbounds pass with seven seconds remaining, and the season
hanging in the balance against Oregon .
</P>
<P>
   Well, considering Scalabrine did stumble on perhaps the most
important p ossession of the year, anything must be possible. But
don't expect the Trojans to be gathered around a TV on Selection
Sunday, after a devastating 80-77 loss to Oregon on Saturday before
4,355 at the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   All along, USC (14-12, 7-7) said it had to win four of its final
five games to be included in the NCAA Tournament field. Now the
Trojans must win their final four games. That's difficult under any
circumstances, but extremely unlikely when one of those games is at
No. 1-ranked Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   USC's situation is so frantic that injured forward Sam Clancy
(broken right foot) said he will try to come back for Thursday's
game at Stanford, one game earlier than planned. More on that
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to win four of the last four,'' Scalabrine said.
``Our goal can still be accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   But teammate Brandon Granville was already aware of the
circumstances mi nutes after the loss to the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to win every game, but Stanford will be tough,''
he said. ``I don't know, we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though USC plays Stanford on Thursday, it still might not
be enough time to forget how they lost to Oregon. The Trojans
trailed, 78-77, with 9.7 seconds left after a three-point play by
Scalabrine.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a gift. Oregon guard Alex Scales took the inbounds
pass, and immediately passed the ball to point guard Darius Wright
under the USC basket. Wright took his eyes off the ball, however,
and it slipped through his fingers and went out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   That gave the Trojans possession with exactly seven seconds
left. Granville, standing under the basket, threw a pass to
Scalabrine at the top of the 3-point arc.
</P>
<P>
   But Scalabrine tripped and fell to the ground, and Oregon's
Julius Hicks grabbed the loose ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I tripped on. I just fell down,'' Scalabrine
said. ` `More than likely, I was going to pass to David
(Bluthenthal). It was our game to win and we didn't. Things didn't
work out.''
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Henry Bibby was unhappy Granville even threw the pass
to Scalabrine, since he was double-teamed on the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bluthenthal was open under the basket,'' Bibby said.
``(Scalabrine tripping), that's neither here nor there. Both Oregon
guys went to Brian. We had someone open under the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   That was all news to Granville, who said, ``I don't think
(Bluthenthal) was open. I just know what I saw.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans still had a chance to tie the game after Hicks made
two free throws with 5.2 seconds remaining, but Granville's
3-pointer at the buzzer was short.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave the game away,'' Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   There were several other miscues that had the Trojans shaking
their heads:
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)With Oregon ahead, 76-74, Trepagnier dribbled the ball
off his foot with 28 seconds left. ``I gave the game away,''
Trepagnier said.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)With the score, 74-74, and under a minute remaining,
Oregon center Flo Hartenstein knocked away a Granville pass to set
up Wright's 15-footer that gave the Ducks the lead.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet)USC led, 67-61, with 4:55 remaining, but immediately
allowed Hicks to score inside, gave up a 3-pointer to Alex Scales
and allowed a three-point play by Frederick Jones.
</P>
<P>
   It took all of 1:51 for Oregon (19-7, 10-5) to score eight
straight points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had them there, but once again, our defense broke
down,'' Scalabrine said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' victory was even more unexpected because leading
scorer A.D. Smith suffered a slight concussion four minutes into
the game and did not return. Scales more than made up for his
absence, scoring 30 points on 11-for-16 shooting, including four
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine scored a career-high 29 points, and Bluthenthal added
24, but Granville and Trepagnier were a combined 4 for 18.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clancy, he dressed for the game, even though there was no
intention to play him. Clancy participated in pre-game warm-ups and
worked on some post moves, saying he felt no pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good,'' he said. ``If we didn't have to win our last
four games, I might wait. It makes it more urgent.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Laguna Beach High's Travis Hanour, a 6-foot-5 shooting
guard, attended the game as part of his official visit to USC this
weekend. . . . Other recruits at the game included 6-8 forward
David Hamilton of Compton, who has left Auburn, and has two years
of eligibility left; Compton Centennial forward Ellis Myles and
Mater Dei center Jamal Sampson and point guard Cedric Bozeman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
