<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATSON SILENCES HIS CRITICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Victims of unfair criticism have not been easy to
find at Pauley Pavilion this season. Criticism, yes. Unfair, no.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Watson might be one, though. A UCLA basketball player to
feel sorry for.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, the squarely constructed junior from Kansas City, spent
most of the year as the Bruins' point guard, charged with dribbling
the ball upcourt and passing it to someone in shooting range.
</P>
<P>
   It's a simple job if that's what you're good at. He wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Not that many of the Bruins' critics cared. The team was losing,
and Watson was bound to take the blame, because as a quarterback in
short pants he was completing as many passes to the peanut vendors
as to teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that he was playing out of position. When the manager
puts a natural-born catcher at shortstop, it's the skipper who
should get the heat for all those blown double plays, but it's the
player who winds up hearing the boos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody's taken unfair criticism,'' said teammate
Ryan Bailey, who's entitled to his opinion. ``But especially Earl,
because the point guard's everything.''
</P>
<P>
   That might be about to change.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's role has been adjusted, with new starter Bailey sharing
the point-guard responsibilities and freshman Jason Kapono bringing
the ball up now and then, and the result has been pleasing for
Watson and UCLA. The Earl-bashers have to smile, too.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon at Pauley, amid the less-than-deafening roar
of a crowd of 9,759, Watson led the Bruins with 19 points,
completing his highest-scoring back-to-back games of the season. No
coincidence, the Bruins' 69-59 victory over Oregon State gave them
their first back-to-back wins of the Pac-10 season.
</P>
<P>
   Watson and the Bruins are feeling better about their chances of
making the NCAA Tournament as a result.
</P>
<P>
   To hear them tell it, Watson and Bailey aren't sure exactly how
the role change came about, though they know it began when Bailey
replaced Billy Knight in the starting lineup for the Bruins'
home-court victory over USC six games back.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Watson has been able to spread his wings, or at
least play on the wings, crash the backboards and curl off screens
for outside shots with new freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great scorer, and when he's playing primarily point
guard he's only looking to pass,'' Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's at peace with his game right now,'' said UCLA assistant
coach Michael Holton, who coaches the guards.
</P>
<P>
   Holton downplays the role change and credits Watson for most of
the improvement, which has seen him put up a season-high 22 points
against USC and against Oregon on Thursday night, and cut his
turnovers by more than 50 percent without substantially reducing
his assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really has accepted that less is more, he's accepted not
needing to make the highlight play, just playing steady,'' Holton
said. ``He's kind of slowed things down. It's been great to see him
respecting the fundamentals and having some success. The way he's
playing is having a positive effect on everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important there be no connotation that he's been demoted
because something wasn't working,'' Holton said. ``He's freer now,
so he can do the things he's always been good at doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson was a point guard for two years at Kansas City's
Washington High, but his education at the position was interrupted
when he came to UCLA, where Baron Davis played the point until last
spring. This season amounted to on-the-job training.
</P>
<P>
   Which hasn't been easy for Watson or those watching him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Criticism motivates me,'' Watson said. ``I hope nobody thinks
they're hurting my feelings when they criticize me.''
</P>
<P>
   There's been plenty of criticism to go around as the Bruins have
stumbled into a position where - even after their best week in a
long time - they must win three of their last four games to have a
shot at the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But at least Watson should escape the talk shows' wrath after
scoring 41 points against the Oregon schools. As if he deserved it
all along.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 0236EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
