<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 03:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9945 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     02-27 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING ANOTHER BRUTAL NIGHT IN HOCKEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ My first reaction when I saw the videotape of
Marty McSorley cracking his stick on the head of Donald Brashear
wasn't the same as most viewers.
</P>
<P>
   It was sickening. But I'd seen worse.
</P>
<P>
   Worse than a premeditated stick to the head? Worse than an
obvious attempt to injure an opponent, in a game long concluded?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, worse.
</P>
<P>
   It was March 11, 1979. The Los Angeles Kings were in the early
stages of the Triple Crown era. Marcel Dionne, Dave Taylor and
Charlie Simmer comprised one of the most powerful lines in the
game, and the team was having some incipient success. But there was
one thing the Kings absolutely could not do.
</P>
<P>
   They could not beat the Philadelphia Flyers. Not figuratively,
not literally. The Broad Street Bullies routinely brutalized the
Kings, the yin to their yang, much as a young Mike Tyson once went
through opponents. The Flyers had honed a vicious style of play to
a sharp edge, winning two Stanley Cup titles (1974, 1975) while
also pushing the league's tolerance of violence beyond anyone
imagined possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings came into that game having gone 18 games against the
Flyers without a win (0-14-4). But beyond the losses, the Kings had
tired of turning the cheek. They skated into the Philadelphia
Spectrum that day determined to stand up to the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   And it was the most god-awful spectacle you've ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Did you happen to see that videotape on the news of a recent
prison riot? That's what the first period was like. Pure carnage.
Fights erupted like brush fires. One would end and another would
start before the officials could get anyone into the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had rented a goon, Randy Holt, earlier in the season
in anticipation of this, and he earned his paycheck by drawing a
NHL record 67 penalty minutes in one period, the biggest chunk of
the 372 minutes of penalties assessed in that one period six
minors, 16 majors and 28 misconducts.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't recall anything Holt did.
</P>
<P>
   No, I recall a young Dave Taylor drawn into several brutal
fights, and Dionne, blood trickling down his face from under his
helmet, throwing fists with Flyer goon Paul Holmgren, and a polite,
passive defenseman named Randy Manery being pummeled by two Flyers
in a corner some 30 feet away from the main event. And 17,077
Spectrum fans cheering wildly.
</P>
<P>
   I recall the MASH-like scene afterward, all of the bloody tape,
jerseys and towels lying on the floor of the Kings locker room as
trainer Pete Demers tried to attend to too many cuts. And I also
remember what Flyers captain Bobby Clarke said afterwards, that
fighting was part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   As resentful as any Kings player or fan might have felt at the
time, Bobby Clarke was absolutely right. He was right then, and he
would be right now.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey's been dealing with the violent side of its image since
long before the Bullies. Before there was Dave ``The Hammer''
Schultz, there was Terrible Ted Lindsey, whose elbows and sticks
always found unpadded body parts. All the '70s Flyers did was
provide a handy target for critics.
</P>
<P>
   The season after that mess, former Kings owner Jerry Buss tried
to legislate fighting out of the game during a meeting of the
league owners before the 1980 All-Star Game. His motives were pure
he truly believed hockey was as exciting as basketball when the
emphasis was on skating and shooting were all. Considering where
Wayne Gretzky took the game, Buss was psychic.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't legislate peace in a violent game unless you put
everyone in a skirt, and that's one reason why the league will
always have to deal with violent episodes. Indeed, the
McSorley-Brashear incident can be traced to anti-fighting edicts.
</P>
<P>
   Each time the league has put its foot down on fighting, it
created other problems. Hockey fights may be ugly and bloody and,
like that night in Philly, occasionally grotesque. But they rarely
do as much damage as a two-handed slash on the outside of a knee or
a jab of the top end of the stick in the ribs.
</P>
<P>
   The hit that put Paul Kariya on ice a few seasons ago was a
perfect example of an opponent looking for a way to take a player
out of a game. Kariya and the Mighty Ducks would have been much
more fortunate if Gary Suter had simply dropped his gloves and
started swinging.
</P>
<P>
   Fights like that night in Philadelphia, or that 1990
Kings-Oilers game that produced 86 penalties, may cause critics to
cluck, but nothing like they have over McSorley's stick.
</P>
<P>
   So in that vein, McSorley is most guilty of poor aim. If he
takes a hack at Brashear's thigh, it's a postscript on just another
regular season game. (And if Bruins coach Pat Burns doesn't send
McSorley on the ice in the last 30 seconds, the whole thing never
happen.)
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it takes on a life of its own as an example, right or
wrong, of why the NHL doesn't appeal to some sports fans and why
the Westminster Kennel Dog Show earns higher Nielsen ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I remember a controversy like this was in 1982,
when Kings coach Don Perry asked noted pugilist Paul Mulvey to
retaliate for a fight. Mulvey said no, and the resulting hubbub
backed the league into a similar corner.
</P>
<P>
   All we'll hear the rest of this season is sanctimonious NHL
officials decry what McSorley did and make sure his career is
finished. But it won't stop stick play any more than a ban on guns
will curtail murder.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the Kings lost that 1979 game in Philly, 6-3. Their
winless streak against the Flyers would last 8 years and 32 games
(0-27-5), finally being snapped with a win on Feb. 13, 1983.
</P>
<P>
   I can't remember if there was a fight or not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
