<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-EZZARD-COLUMN-MCCAIN0     02-27 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN-MCCAIN0228-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hanoi Hilton taught much
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sixty-two years ago in Camilla, Ga., just south of
Albany, Orson Swindle started a life's journey that led him to
share a cement pad with presidential candidate John McCain in the
infamous Hanoi Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   Raised by his grandmother, Swindle was a product of small town
Southern values that helped him survive a 6 1/2-year ordeal as a
prisoner of war (nearly a year longer than McCain endured).
</P>
<P>
   Swindle, a Marine pilot, was shot down on his 205th mission in
North Vietnam on Nov. 11, 1966. He was released two weeks before
McCain and was there to greet McCain when he limped off an airplane
at the naval air station in Jacksonville in March 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Swindle can answer the question that many Americans are asking
these days: How would those torturous years, those endless painful
nights, those daily brushes with death, affect McCain as president?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's facing human failure, knowing when you're down that you
will get up and try again and fail again,'' Swindle says. ``You
come to understand about redemption.''
</P>
<P>
   Swindle says McCain approaches his fellow man with stark
honesty. He accepts people's flaws. He sees more than one side of
people.
</P>
<P>
   Swindle still chokes up when he discusses his experience as a
POW, not over the memory of the torture he endured, but over
``submitting,'' as he puts it, to the enemy. He feels incredibly
guilty over his occasional inability to endure. McCain writes
similarly of that guilt feeling in his book, ``Faith of My
Fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   He won't discuss McCain's experience, but Swindle recalls one
form of torture he endured more than once. (McCain alludes in his
book to Swindle's withstanding ``rope torture,'' and calls him one
of his three POW ``brothers.'') After beating and interrogating him
for sleepless days and nights, Swindle's tormentors would use
parachute cord to tie tourniquets above Swindle's elbows until the
blood was cut off and he couldn't move his fingers. Then they'd
line up, three men on each side, pulling his elbows up his backbone
until his shoulders were dislocated. Then they would wrap the cord
around his whole body, tie ropes around his thumbs and lift him off
the ground by his thumbs. When that was done, they'd beat him
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were defining moments,'' Swindle says in a near whisper.
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, Swindle's voice is filled with energy about
McCain's candidacy: ``John will be a president who knows human
limitation like no other _ that gives him an accepting, inclusive
philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Swindle served from 1985 to 1989 as assistant secretary of
commerce in the Reagan administration. Before that, he was head of
the Farmers Home Administration in Georgia. Now he's a federal
trade commissioner in Washington. Aside from McCain, he admires
Ronald Reagan more than any contemporary politician. But he does
not admire so-called Christian conservatives. ``They are neither,''
he says by phone from his office.
</P>
<P>
   After the Clinton election, McCain accepted the Democratic
president's invitation to appear with him at the Vietnam Memorial.
GOP leaders and veterans, including Swindle, advised against his
appearing with a ``draft dodger'' president. But McCain thought
that honoring Vietnam veterans was the greater issue. McCain once
gave a eulogy at the funeral of a friend who was an anti-war
activist, Swindle notes, adding, ``Every life has positive
dimensions to John.''
</P>
<P>
   Swindle won't say if he disagrees with McCain on any issues. For
him, principles count for more than positions on the ``15 issues
that glow in the dark'' in any given election year.
</P>
<P>
   The issues will change, Swindle says, but POW lessons about
human failure and triumph never will.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
