<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of  &UR; MONDAY &LR; , Feb. 28:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-TALKS (Bogota, Colombia) _ Officially, peace talks
between the Colombian government and the largest rebel group are
stalled, with no date set for them to resume. Yet just the other
day, the government's chief negotiator boasted that ``we have
advanced further this month than in 40 years of conflict.'' That
apparent paradox is the result of an unusual new twist to efforts
to negotiate an end to a civil conflict that has killed 35,000
Colombians in the past decade. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CULT (Yokohama, Japan) _ It is not easy to visit the new
leader of the embattled Aum Shinrikyo religious cult who has been
holed up in the sect's branch office here since being released from
prison late last year. Visitors must pass through dozens of riot
police, submit to a body search, and often endure the heckling of
angry Japanese mobs that gather to denounce the cult, which was
behind the nerve gas attack that killed 12 people in the Tokyo
subways five years ago. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-ELECTIONS (New Delhi, India) _ Regional parties humbled
both of India's national parties in state elections whose results
became final Sunday, emphatically reaffirming that the days when a
pan-India party could dominate the nation's politics are dead and
gone. By Celia Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Because of the risk to
troops, the Pentagon has refused to allow U.S. troops to return to
northern Mitrovica, the Serb-dominated part of the divided town
that has become a flashpoint of ethnic tension in Kosovo, senior
U.N. and Western officials say. But Gen. Klaus Reinhardt, the
commander of the NATO-led peacekeeping forces in Kosovo known as
KFOR, says that negotiations are continuing with the Americans on
this question. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-ELECTION (Kiel, Germany) _ Germany's governing Social
Democrats won a comfortable victory Sunday in an election in the
northern state of Schleswig-Holstein as voters punished the
opposition Christian Democratic Union for the financial scandal
that has engulfed the party. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-JOSPIN (Paris) _ French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin has
returned from the Middle East to a dressing down on diplomacy by
President Jacques Chirac after his comments labeling Hezbollah
fighters ``terrorists.'' By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   SENEGAL-ELECTION (Dakar, Senegal) _ Senegal votes in
presidential elections. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FARRAKHAN-SPEECH (Undated) _ Nation of Islam Minister Louis
Farrakhan plans a speech before thousands _ one that could make or
break his vow to reconcile with orthodox Muslims. Among those in
attendance will be W. Deen Mohammed, an orthodox Muslim leader and
son of late Nation of Islam leader Elijah Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   LARAMIE-PLAY (Denver) _ A play called ``The Laramie Project,''
based on the Matthew Shepard case, opened in Denver on Saturday
night, and many in the audience were people who were characters in
the play and residents of the Wyoming town where the gay college
student was murdered. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-MEDIA (Seattle) _ With limited resources and a
staggering media challenge _ getting their messages out in 17
states holding primaries in the next nine days _ the four leading
Republicans and Democrats in the race for president are engaged in
a feverish hopscotch of the nation, targeting television markets in
certain states, bypassing others and relying to an even larger
extent than before on the ``free media'' supplied by the press to
make their cases. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-WASH (Seattle) _ Everyone says it's over, but Bill
Bradley has once again found his voice and hit his stride in the
unlikely battleground of Washington state. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-NY (New York) _ New York supporters of Bill Bradley are
angry over his decision to devote so much time and effort to
Washington state, while virtually ignoring New York. By Adam
Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-WASH (Redmond, Wash.) _ Washington state, which will
account for only 2.2 percent of the delegates at the Democratic
National Convention this year, has unexpectedly emerged as a
battleground for the two men seeking the party's presidential
nomination, and Al Gore spent much of the weekend here trying to
make sure Bill Bradley would have nothing to show for his huge
investment of time and energy in the state's presidential primary
on Tuesday. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-EDUC (Undated) _ Comparing and contrasting the
candidates' proposals on education. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ECON (Washington) _ If Vice President Al Gore has
counted on anything in this tumultuous political season, it has
been that the strong economy would give him the upper hand in the
general election should he win the Democratic presidential
nomination. The economy remains as strong as ever. But Gore's
strategy for using it to his advantage would have to change _ and
could in the end prove to be less potent _ if his Republican
opponent turns out to be Sen. John McCain rather than Gov. George
W. Bush. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AMTRAK-NEW-ROUTES (Washington) _ After years of trying to
balance its books by cutting service, Amtrak has concluded that to
succeed it should instead create new routes, offer more frequent
service on existing lines and organize itself more like the
airlines, so people can change from train to train and get to
places more efficiently. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   MINT-DIRECTOR-PROFILE (Washington) _ The director of the mint
introduces the country to Sacagaweya. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Commentary; subject TK. By William
Safire.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ Commentary; subject TK. By Bob
Herbert.
</P>
