<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COX-INTERNET-TAXES-02     02-27 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-INTERNET-TAXES-0228 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR GOVERNORS, INTERNET TAXES STILL JUST A HOPE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While most governors want to begin taxing goods
purchased through the Internet, they probably will have to wait
until next year for a federal green light, the chairman of the
National Governors' Association said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Because 2000 is an election year, ``nothing will likely pass
this year,'' Utah Gov. Michael O. Leavitt told reporters at the
association's winter meeting here.
</P>
<P>
   But if holiday online purchases skyrocket as expected next
Christmas, political pressure will grow to allow states to collect
taxes on interstate electronic purchases, just as they do on local
store purchases, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Internet-based companies generally do not collect and remit
sales taxes on purchases made by customers who live in other
states. Sales taxes generate more than $150 billion a year in
revenues, about a third of all state state revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Governors are not only worried about shrinking their tax base,
but also about the risk of encouraging shoppers to abandon Main
Street tax-paying merchants for ``dot.com'' companies.
</P>
<P>
   As governors talk among themselves about how to tax Internet
sales, Leavitt said, they must ask themselves: ``Do we create a
level playing field, or do we create a special privilege for one
avenue of retailing?''
</P>
<P>
   Maryland Gov. Parris Glendening, a Democrat and the group's vice
chairman, estimated that four out of five governors want to collect
online sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue is controversial. For example, Virginia Gov. James
Gilmore, a Republican, opposes online sales taxes, saying the
Internet has created so many jobs that state revenues from income,
corporate and property taxes are more than compensating for any
lost sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes, a Democrat, said he wants to ``proceed
with caution'' to avoid slowing the Internet economy. ``This is a
whole new phenomenon,'' he said, which means political leaders must
study it closely before acting.
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt, who is a Republican, said the tax issue would not be
debated in public forums during the meeting because the governors
want to remain in a low-key mode until after March 21. That's when
the 19 members of the congressionally appointed Advisory Commission
on Electronic Commerce hold their final meeting. The commission is
charged with making legislative recommendations to Congress by
April 21.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Congress imposed a three-year moratorium on new taxes
on Internet transactions. The ban expires in October, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The governors, who convened on Saturday, will meet Monday with
President Clinton and Tuesday with members of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the four-day gathering is the ``new global
economy,'' with sessions intended to stimulate ideas about such
topics as ensuring broadband access and establishing Internet sites
to provide government information and services to the citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are well aware that the digital, global economy is one
without any boundaries, and therefore challenges the very
foundations on which governments are based,'' Glendening said. ``We
must work toward redefining the way that we offer services
efficiently to citizens and re-examine the way we govern overall in
this new 24-hour, 7-day-a-week economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
