   3. FAITH OF MY FATHERS, by John McCain with Mark Salter.
</P>
<P>
   (Random House, $25.) The U.S. senator (and former
</P>
<P>
   POW) remembers his life in the Navy and those of his
</P>
<P>
   father and grandfather. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4.(x) THE MILLIONAIRE MIND, by Thomas J. Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrews McMeel, $26.95.) An analysis of the people
</P>
<P>
   who make up America's financial elite.
</P>
<P>
   5. PEANUTS: A GOLDEN CELEBRATION, by Charles M. Schulz,
</P>
<P>
   edited by David Larkin. (HarperCollins, $45.) A history
</P>
<P>
   of the popular comic strip, whose creator died this year
</P>
<P>
   at 77, illustrated with more than 1,000 strips.
</P>
<P>
   6. 'TIS, by Frank McCourt. (Scribner, $26.) An Irish
</P>
<P>
   immigrant gets used to life in America: a memoir.
</P>
<P>
   7. HAVE A NICE DAY! by Mick Foley. (ReganBooks/
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, $25.) The autobiography of a
</P>
<P>
   professional wrestler known as Mankind.
</P>
<P>
   8. GEORGIANA, by Amanda Foreman. (Random House, $29.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A biography of an 18th-century English duchess who had a
</P>
<P>
   taste for politics and scandal.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE GREATEST GENERATION, by Tom Brokaw. (Random
</P>
<P>
   House, $24.95.) The lives of men and women who came
</P>
<P>
   of age during the Depression and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   10. FROM THIS DAY FORWARD, by Cokie Roberts and Steve
</P>
<P>
   Roberts. (Morrow, $24.) Two journalists reflect on
</P>
<P>
   their life together and on the institution of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE ART OF HAPPINESS, by the Dalai Lama and Howard C.
</P>
<P>
   Cutler. (Riverhead, $22.95.) What Buddhism and common
</P>
<P>
   sense tell us about everyday problems.
</P>
<P>
   12. A HEARTBREAKING WORK OF STAGGERING GENIUS, by
</P>
<P>
   Dave Eggers. (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23.) A young
</P>
<P>
   man's account of raising his 8-year-old brother
</P>
<P>
   after their parents died just weeks apart.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE GREATEST GENERATION SPEAKS, by Tom Brokaw.
</P>
<P>
   (Random House, $19.95.) What the people who fought
</P>
<P>
   in World War II confided in letters to the author.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE NEW NEW THING, by Michael Lewis. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $25.95.) The story of Jim Clark, a technical and
</P>
<P>
   financial pioneer in the computer world. (b)
</P>
<P>
   15. GALILEO'S DAUGHTER, by Dava Sobel. (Walker, $27.)
</P>
<P>
   The life and trials of Galileo Galilei, as seen through
</P>
<P>
   the letters of his cloistered, illegitimate daughter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. WHO MOVED MY CHEESE? by Spencer Johnson. (Putnam,
</P>
<P>
   $19.95.) How to deal with changes at work and in life
</P>
<P>
   in general. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. RELATIONSHIP RESCUE, by Phillip C. McGraw.
</P>
<P>
   (Hyperion, $22.95.) A seven-step program for
</P>
<P>
   reconnecting with one's partner. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. BODY FOR LIFE, by Bill Phillips with Michael D'Orso.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperCollins, $26.) Ways to improve one's body and
</P>
<P>
   one's life. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. SUGAR BUSTERS! by H. Leighton Steward et al.
</P>
<P>
   (Ballantine, $22.) A diet designed for losing
</P>
<P>
   weight and increasing energy. (b)
</P>
