<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, March 5)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending Feb. 19 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE TESTAMENT, by John Grisham. (Island, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A reclusive billionaire, a burned-out lawyer and
</P>
<P>
   a missionary are brought together by a startling
</P>
<P>
   secret.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE GIRL WHO LOVED TOM GORDON, by Stephen King.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $6.99.) A girl who is a fan of the
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox gets lost in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   3. SSN, created by Tom Clancy and Martin Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   (Berkley, $7.99.) World War III as experienced by
</P>
<P>
   a nuclear submarine's captain.
</P>
<P>
   4. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE, by J.K.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling. (Scholastic, $5.99.) A British boy,
</P>
<P>
   neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school for witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   5. A MAP OF THE WORLD, by Jane Hamilton. (Anchor,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) When a dairy farmer's wife makes a mistake
</P>
<P>
   one morning, her life falls apart.
</P>
<P>
   6. MISTAKEN IDENTITY, by Lisa Scottoline.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPaperbacks, $7.50.) Will a lawyer's
</P>
<P>
   client, accused of murder, turn out to be her twin?
</P>
<P>
   7. FIRST LADY, by Susan Elizabeth Phillips. (Avon, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A young widow who was married to the president of the
</P>
<P>
   United States finds a new love.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE GREEN MILE, by Stephen King. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A six-part thriller set on death row at Cold Mountain
</P>
<P>
   Penitentiary.
</P>
<P>
   9. I THEE WED, by Amanda Quick. (Bantam, $7.50.) With
</P>
<P>
   the help of a legendary businessman, an Englishwoman
</P>
<P>
   tries to outwit a killer.
</P>
<P>
   10. VECTOR, by Robin Cook. (Berkley, $7.99.) A New York
</P>
<P>
   City cabdriver, once a Soviet expert in biological
</P>
<P>
   weapons, joins forces with a neofascist skinhead militia.
</P>
<P>
   11. SULLIVAN'S ISLAND, by Dorothea Benton Frank. (Jove,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) Confronted with an unfaithful husband and a
</P>
<P>
   resentful daughter, a woman returns to her family's
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina home.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) THE COWBOY, by Joan Johnston. (Dell, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A Texas woman is torn between the family that needs
</P>
<P>
   her and the man she loves.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE CIDER HOUSE RULES, by John Irving. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Life in a Maine orphanage in the first part
</P>
<P>
   of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE HOURS, by Michael Cunningham. (Picador USA, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   The lives of two modern women converge with the life
</P>
<P>
   and work of Virginia Woolf.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE NEW JEDI ORDER. Dark Tide: Onslaught, by Michael
</P>
<P>
   A. Stackpole. (Lucas/Del Rey/Ballantine, $6.99.) A ``Star
</P>
<P>
   Wars'' novel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $14 and $7.99.) An Irish-American writer recalls his
</P>
<P>
   childhood amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. GIRL, INTERRUPTED, by Susanna Kaysen. (Vintage, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A memoir of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   4. HIS BRIGHT LIGHT, by Danielle Steel. (Delta, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The novelist recalls the life of her son Nick Traina
</P>
<P>
   who suffered from manic depression and died at 19.
</P>
<P>
   5. A CHILD CALLED `IT,' by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography of a man
</P>
<P>
   who survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   6. YESTERDAY, I CRIED, by Iyanla Vanzant. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $13.) A counselor tells how she turned painful
</P>
<P>
   experiences into hope. (b)
</P>
<P>
   7. THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $10.95.) The author of ``A Child
</P>
<P>
   Called `It''' recalls his life in foster homes. (b)
</P>
<P>
   8.(x) THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $14; HarperPaperbacks, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a single
</P>
<P>
   crew.
</P>
<P>
   9.(x) THE LAST VICTIM, by Jason Moss with Jeffrey Kottler.
</P>
<P>
   (Warner Vision, $6.99.) A memoir by a man
</P>
<P>
   who became a pen pal of serial killers.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $13.) How a murderer helped James
</P>
<P>
   Murray compile the Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   12. BLIND MAN'S BLUFF, by Sherry Sontag and Christopher
</P>
<P>
   Drew with Annette Lawrence Drew. (HarperPaperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) American espionage by submarine, from the
</P>
<P>
   Cold War to the present.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE ORCHID THIEF, by Susan Orlean. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $14.) A journalist's account of a man who was caught
</P>
<P>
   pilfering 200 rare orchids.
</P>
<P>
   14. A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking the
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   15. GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance to
</P>
<P>
   geographical advantages. (b)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by Robert C. Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $14 and $6.99.) A physician recommends ways
</P>
<P>
   to lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. THE CARBOHYDRATE ADDICT'S DIET, by Rachael F. Heller
</P>
<P>
   and Richard F. Heller. (Signet, $6.99.) A program for
</P>
<P>
   weight loss. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. LIFE STRATEGIES, by Phillip C. McGraw. (Hyperion,
</P>
<P>
   $11.95.) How to find what matters in your life and
</P>
<P>
   what to do about it. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. THE CARBOHYDRATE ADDICT'S LIFESPAN PROGRAM, by Richard
</P>
<P>
   F. Heller and Rachael F. Heller. (Plume, $15.95.) How to
</P>
<P>
   lose weight and become fit in middle age. (b)
</P>
