<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0085 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     02-27 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 5)  
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; OUT OF THE WOODS: Stories &LR;  By Chris Offutt. Scribner, $11.
These lean tales dwell on romantic obsession, but the love object
isn't a man or woman but the state of Kentucky, whose haunted
landscape captivates the wary, mostly poor characters. The result
is ``a magical book,'' Leon Rooke wrote in The New York Times Book
Review in 1999. ``Offutt's obvious kin among contemporary American
writers are Richard Ford and Tobias Wolff.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLERIDGE: Darker Reflections, 1804-1834 &LR;  By Richard Holmes.
Pantheon, $18. The concluding volume of the author's two-part life
captures the ``brilliant, animated, endlessly provoking'' Coleridge
as he slips in and out of opium addiction and melancholy while
riveting audiences as a world-class talker and lecturer. This
account of the Romantic poet's final three decades, chosen by the
editors of The New York Times Book Review as one of the best books
of 1999, uses his own remorseful journals to flesh out a portrait
of a tormented, unstable artist whose later works included
``Biographia Literaria.'' The reviewer Penelope Fitzgerald said
``the extraordinary quality of this biography'' is ``felt on every
page.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LITTLE NOVELS OF SICILY: Stories &LR;  By Giovanni Verga.
Steerforth, $12. These earthy 19th-century tales, translated by
D.H. Lawrence, explore the strained relationship between helplessly
ignorant peasants and the exploitive landowners whose vineyards and
pastures they work. The stories ``have that sense of the wholeness
of life ... and the magnificent and thrilling vitality of major
literature,'' The New York Times Book Review said in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THE TIME BEING &LR;  By Annie Dillard. Vintage, $12. The author
explores the age-old question of how an all-merciful, all-powerful
God can allow evil to exist in the world. Last year the reviewer
Wendy Lesser found this to be a troubling, perhaps doomed, inquiry
that founders ``nobly, courageously and with the best of
intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFE BEFORE DEATH &LR;  By Abby Frucht. Scribner, $12. In this
lighthearted novel about _ of all things _ death from cancer, the
relentlessly cheery narrator, a 40-year-old single woman, splits
her remaining time between the dreary present and a wished-for
future. In 1997, Molly Giles said the author's ``fluid, sensual
style ... perfectly captures her heroine's longings.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAIRO: The City Victorious &LR;  By Max Rodenbeck. Vintage
Departures, $14. Part travelogue, part history, this affectionate
account explores the physical and human topography of an ancient
city that has reinvented itself many times. The book conveys the
city's ``unique charm'' and ``should greatly enhance any vacation
or business trip to Cairo,'' Edward Mortimer wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THURGOOD MARSHALL: American Revolutionary &LR;  By Juan Williams.
Times Books/Random House, $16. The first black Supreme Court
justice is portrayed as a dedicated lawyer (he won Brown vs. Board
of Education in 1954) and a lifelong champion of civil rights who
became embittered in his later years by the court's swing to the
right. ``The book is a strong piece of journalism crammed with
fascinating detail,'' David K. Shipler said in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; THE WORLD OF BENJAMIN CARDOZO: Personal Values and the
Judicial Process &LR; , by Richard Polenberg (Harvard University,
$19.95), another eminent jurist is depicted as a hopeless moralist
whose adherence to higher ideals guided his decisions, first on the
New York state Court of Appeals and then on the Supreme Court.
Cardozo emerges as ``witty, sweet tempered, gentle ... and as
self-doubting as a judicial saint can be,'' Jeffrey Rosen wrote in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LAST LOVELY CITY: Stories &LR;  By Alice Adams. Washington
Square/Pocket $12.95. These tales are populated by lonely
middle-aged women searching for love and, for the most part, coming
up empty. Last year the reviewer Susan Bolotin said the stories
explore ``what happens to people who have no experience being alone
but no success being together.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SAFEGUARD OF THE SEA: A Naval History of Britain, 660-1649 &LR; 
By N.A.M. Rodger. Norton, $17.95. Drawing heavily from the archives
of the Royal Navy, a historian chronicles Britain's growing mastery
of the seas, which was essential to the nation's survival, and
provides copious detail on strategy, ship design and the officers
and men who served the crown. ``The result is a masterpiece,''
Geoffrey Parker wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SALESMAN &LR;  By Joseph O'Connor. Picador USA, $14. Billy
Sweeney is a guilt-ridden ex-teacher who takes revenge on the
ringleader of a gang who raped his daughter, only to develop a
bizarre emotional bond with the sociopath. Last year James Saynor
called this a ``brutal yet contrite novel.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOOD KING HARRY &LR;  By Denise Giardina. Fawcett/Ballantine,
$12.95. This novel's narrator is King Henry V of England, who
chronicles his nine-year reign and his youthful devotion to a
peasant girl named Merryn. ``The unfolding of this unlikely romance
... is as satisfying as the best of BBC's Masterpiece Theater
series,'' Barbara Tritel said in 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
