<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HEALTHCARE-ONLINE-ART     02-27 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-ONLINE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHEON/WEBMD FILLS IN THE BLANKS IN DRIVE TO PUT MEDICAL WORLD
ONLINE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphics are
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is show-me time for Healtheon/WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet-based company has riveted investors the last year,
as its stock price rode a roller coaster while Healtheon announced
a dizzying array of mergers and alliances. This month alone,
Healtheon has used its stock in $5.7 billion worth of takeover
deals for three companies.
</P>
<P>
   And backers and partners like Microsoft, Rupert Murdoch's News
Corp. and DuPont have lent credibility to Healtheon's ambitious
talk of transforming the nation's unruly, fragmented health system
into a digitally disciplined online universe. The vision is to link
patients, doctors and insurers online with just about every player
in the vast industry, promoting self-help for patients while saving
untold time and money by eliminating paperwork and insurance
company phone centers. But now comes the time when analysts say the
company must start delivering on its promises, before investors
lose confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey T. Arnold, the 30-year-old Atlanta marketing
entrepreneur who started WebMD in October 1998 and became chief
executive of Healtheon/WebMD after the companies agreed to merge
the following May, has heard Wall Street's message _ that it is
time to start demonstrating that Healtheon is more than an
acquisitive holding company.
</P>
<P>
   After more than 80 deals in 18 months, ``we now have the assets
in place to execute,'' Arnold said. ``We will put everything we've
got into making this work.''
</P>
<P>
   But Healtheon/WebMD's potentially volatile stock poses risks for
investors, in the view of Dr. Bruce Hochstadt, a health care
analyst at Thomas Weisel Partners, a merchant bank based in San
Francisco. The stock was above $100 last May, before the announced
merger of Healtheon and WebMD, then traded as low as $30 last
August. But the share price is up 60.8 percent since the beginning
of the year. The shares closed at $60.3125, down $2.4375, Friday in
Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the 900-pound gorilla in Internet health care; there
is not much room for error,'' Hochstadt said. ``Once investors
caught wind that things were moving slower than expected or were a
little stalled, some wouldn't have the tolerance to stick around.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Healtheon is not a stock play for the impatient, as
it tackles a daunting task that analysts say may take years to
accomplish. By most projections, the company will not become
profitable until at least 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to slow down, take stock and actually execute some
of the necessary integration of the purchases,'' said Mike Davis, a
research director in Denver for the Gartner Group, a technology
consulting firm. ``They have to merge into a consolidated
organization and culture. That's where most companies fail. It's
not going to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   In deals this month alone, Healtheon bought the Medical Manager
Corp., a profitable company that provides office management
software for doctors; CareInsite, an Internet company that was
Healtheon/WebMD's biggest competitor in the physician-to-insurer
linkage field; and the OnHealth Network, a Web site that provides
health care information for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   It was the stock price that has made possible the many
acquisitions _ more than six dozen so far _ and it was the shares
that attracted a $930 million investment last month by the Janus
Capital Corp. ``Janus is considered to be very smart money,''
Hochstadt said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company has been spending about $250 million a year
_ investors call it the burn rate _ working capital should not be
an immediate problem. Besides the $930 million infusion from Janus,
Healtheon/WebMD says it has nearly $800 million in unspent
commitments from some of its stakeholders and corporate partners.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold, the chief executive, said that by June, Healtheon/WebMD
would make online connections available to 400,000 doctors, 900
insurance companies, 46,000 pharmacies and 4,500 hospitals. The
Healtheon piece of the operation, based in Santa Clara, Calif., has
close to 1,000 software programmers and computer engineers working
full steam on producing the links under the supervision of Pavan
Nigram.
</P>
<P>
   Nigram is a computer wizard originally hired by Jim Clark, the
Silicon Valley billionaire who previously founded Silicon Graphics
and Netscape. Nigram was given the technical challenge of bringing
reality to Clark's dream, conceived four years ago, to somehow
capitalize on the nation's health care economy.
</P>
<P>
   Since Healtheon went public a year ago, Clark has moved on to
less world-shaking Web-based ventures like helping rich people
manage their money and consumers store family photos. Clark is
still on the board, however, and still owns Healtheon shares worth
$700 million at current prices. And one of his initial concepts
remains central for Healtheon: playing a gatekeeper role in the
daily transactions of the nation's medical money machine.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, online transactions _ medical bills, drug
prescriptions, lab results and so on _ may cost as little as 25
cents each, compared with $8 or $10 currently for transactions by
paper, fax or phone. UnitedHealthcare, a unit of the UnitedHealth
Group and a minority owner of Healtheon/WebMD, is encouraging the
300,000 doctors in its networks to submit bills and check patient
coverage online. At least 100,000 are already doing so, a
UnitedHealthcare official said.
</P>
<P>
   The potential market is a mind-boggling 30 billion health care
transactions annually. They include hospital and doctor bills,
insurance approvals, drug prescriptions, lab reports and referrals
to specialists.
</P>
<P>
   The first task, Arnold said, is to connect the nation's myriad
disparate computer systems to the Internet and to make them
accessible with Web-browser software _ an effort likely to get a
big push as new federal regulations take hold over the next two
years. Under a 1996 law, the Health Insurance Portability and
Accountability Act, all external transactions between hospitals,
doctors and insurers must be in standardized electronic language,
with safeguards to protect patients' privacy and prevent
unauthorized access.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every health care company says it needs a Web strategy,''
Arnold said. ``We will provide them with the technology that meets
the Hippa requirements,'' he said, referring to the 1996 law.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon acquired a crucial piece of this capability with a
deal in January to buy the electronic billing company Envoy from
the Quintiles Transnational Corp. for $2.5 billion in Healtheon
stock. Envoy is a profitable business, dominating the small
fraction of the country's medical bills that are delivered
electronically, from computer to computer. But it is not the Web _
yet.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say that electronic transactions, alone, are not
sufficient to wring costs from the nation's medical system. As long
as health care providers continue to do most of their business the
old-fashioned, more expensive way by using paper, fax and the
phone, there are costly inefficiencies _ even if the information is
subsequently converted to digital form for transmitting online,
said Janice Young, another research director at the Gartner Group.
</P>
<P>
   And while Healtheon, as evidence of a trend, says it counted 1
million transactions online to insurance companies and laboratories
in a single month last fall, some analysts have calculated that
fewer than 100,000 of those actually originated as computerized
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are waiting to see the number of doctors actually using the
Internet,'' said William McKeever, an analyst at PaineWebber
Securities. ``They run the gamut from just signing up to visiting a
physician portal to using the Internet for transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin J. Wygod, chief executive of Medical Manager and
CareInsite, who will be co-chairman of Healtheon/WebMD when the
sale of his companies is completed, is a big promoter of the online
business model. ``We can change the entire continuum of care and
reduce not only the administrative expense but the actual cost of
care by getting the right information to the doctor when he is
seeing the patient,'' Wygod said.
</P>
<P>
   Wygod said that health insurers like United, and several that
signed on with CareInsite in New York, New Jersey and
Massachusetts, would be key to overcoming the reluctance of doctors
to try new systems. He predicted that the health insurers
themselves would be lured by the potential online cost savings,
which he said might allow the insurers to eliminate thousands of
employees who now deal with doctors by phone and process faxes.
</P>
<P>
   Since most doctors do business with a number of health plans,
their interest in going online is likely to be greater if they can
deal with more than one insurer on the same Web site. In New York,
for example, CareInsite has contracts with Empire Blue Cross and
Blue Shield, HIP, and Group Health Inc., and Healtheon serves
United.
</P>
<P>
   But Young at the Gartner Group said that in some regions,
dominant health insurers were developing their own online systems _
and thus might hesitate to share access to doctors with
Healtheon/WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   Besides transactions, which Arnold said would generate about
half the revenue, the company is placing other bets. It has a big
staff of writers and doctors producing up-to-date health care
information for consumers and to attract physicians to its news and
information Web site, WebMD.com. The site's producers also create
broadcast material to which the News Corp.'s Fox television unit
has acquired syndication rights.
</P>
<P>
   Mimicking the America Online model, the WebMD.com site can
generate advertising revenue and ``carriage'' fees from health care
companies that doctors and consumers link to through the WebMD.com
portal. For example, Medibuy, an online supplier of medical
products and services, is paying $45.5 million for such a link. In
addition, Healtheon/WebMD will get royalties from online sales from
partners like the CVS drugstore chain. But for analysts, the big
questions remain how quickly and how well Healtheon/WebMD will be
able to integrate not only the nation's bewildering health care
system but, first, the many pieces of its own far-flung,
two-chairman empire.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Wygod, the other co-chairman will be W. Michael Long.
Long sold his financial technology consulting company, Continuum
Inc., to the Computer Sciences Corp. for $1.4 billion, in 1996 _
which is why he was available in 1997 when Healtheon's venture
capital backer went looking for someone to bring focus to the hazy
plans Clark had spun for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Besides having three entrepreneurial types atop the company
seeking management cohesion, Healtheon/WebMD also has an
integration challenge that is purely geographic. Arnold remains in
Atlanta, where the WebMD business is based. Long still lives in
Austin, Texas, though he spends considerable time at the Healtheon
operations in Santa Clara. Wygod lives near San Diego, far from
Medical Manager and CareInsite, which are based in Elmwood Park,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the enormity of the task before him,
Healtheon/WebMD's Arnold tends to speak in measured tones about his
prospects. When Jim Clark was wooing early investors, he used to
talk about a revolution in health care that would eliminate $250
million of waste from the $1.3 trillion system. Arnold speaks more
modestly about evolution.
</P>
<P>
   The company will ``work with the current systems: they can keep
doing it by phone, paper and fax,'' Arnold said. ``We are just
asking for access.''
</P>
<P>
   A foot in the door, in other words. A very big foot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
