<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0089 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MAGAZINES-SEX-MEDIA-A     02-27 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINES-SEX-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S MAGAZINES TURN TO SEX TO SPICE UP SALES
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deeply offended by the sexually explicit magazine covers
spreading across newsstands, a watchdog group called Morality in
Media last month lobbied the Kroger supermarket chain to conceal
explicit cover lines like this one on Cosmopolitan: ``Sex Tricks
Only Cosmo Would Know: 20 Earth-Quaking Moves That Will Make Him
Plead for Mercy _ and Beg for More.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the targeted magazines, besides Cosmopolitan: Glamour,
Mademoiselle and Redbook.
</P>
<P>
   Redbook? The inclusion of the member of that prim cadre of
magazines known as the Seven Sisters, which are aimed most intently
at married women with children, might come as a surprise to readers
who still associate it with tuna casserole recipes, diet tips and
articles about calcium supplements, not the ``steamy sexercises''
in the February issue.
</P>
<P>
   But the move shows how the world has changed for the 97-year-old
Hearst magazine and the heretofore sacrosanct sisterhood of women's
magazines and how they are feeling the same pressures that have
prompted many U.S. consumer magazines to heat up frank sexual
discussion to spur sales in the magazine market.
</P>
<P>
   These seven titles, most of which were founded a century ago _
Redbook, Ladies' Home Journal, Good Housekeeping, McCall's, Family
Circle, Woman's Day and Better Homes &AMP; Gardens _ have long been
known for their coverage of such domestic subjects as
child-rearing, recipes, health and home decoration. Unlike Glamour,
Cosmopolitan and Mademoiselle _ which seek younger, unmarried urban
women as readers _ the Seven Sisters are known as ``women's
service'' magazines and were in the past traditionally aimed at
stay-at-home mothers with hungry children and distracted,
overworked husbands.
</P>
<P>
   Redbook and Ladies' Home Journal are the only two that now
regularly include the more explicit sexual content. But their shift
toward sexier stories _ the February Ladies' Home Journal, for
example, featured a new sex column, and Redbook's February issue
had sex-oriented features like ``What Your Sex Dreams Say About
You'' and also started a sex column, ``Red Hot Sex,'' with its
March issue _ reflects only a part of the changing dynamics of the
magazine industry, which can best be described in a shorthand
equation known to marketing executives the world over: Sex sells.
</P>
<P>
   Most magazines have become more aggressive about luring
consumers at the newsstand, because consolidation at both the
wholesale and retail level has slowed sales for most magazines. In
Redbook's case, the magazine even runs different headlines on
issues going to subscribers and issues for sale on the newsstand.
On the March issue going to subscribers, the top headline reads
``Intimate Secrets of Women Men Love''; on the newsstand, where
headlines have to be eye-catching, that line reads ``Sex Secrets''
_ in capital letters _ ``of Women Men Love'' and there is an extra
headline advertising the ``New! Sex Column.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually the entire women's service category has suffered from
shrinking circulation in recent years. Each issue of Woman's Day,
published by Hachette Filipacchi, sold 10 million copies on the
newsstand 20 years ago, but both newsstand and subscription sales
now amount to 4.1 million copies. Since 1994, Ladies Home Journal
is down to 4.5 million from 5 million; Redbook is down to 2.8
million from 3.2 million; Good Housekeeping 4.6 million from 5.1
million; Woman's Day to 4 million from 4.6 million; and McCall's to
4.2 million from 4.6 million. Family Circle and Better Homes &AMP;
Gardens have remained flat, at 5 million and 7.6 million,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been a brutal cut in the Seven Sisters'
circulation. The legislation against American Family Publishers and
Publishers Clearing House has soured consumers on the notion of
buying their magazine subscriptions from sweepstakes houses. Since
most of the Seven Sisters have relied in the past on attracting a
majority of subscribers through sweepstakes campaigns,
subscriptions are down.
</P>
<P>
   So they are retooling their images. The 117-year-old Ladies'
Home Journal had a first in its February issue: a sex column,
``Behind Closed Doors,'' which according to the magazine's table of
contents ``takes a new look at making love _ and making it
better.'' A recent cover line on Ladies' Home Journal included
``Grown-Up Sexxx: He Needs It, You'll Love It.''
</P>
<P>
   Myrna Blyth, the editor in chief, said that the service category
had always featured sex on some level, but that now there is an
effort to write saucier headlines to attract consumers. The January
cover of Ladies' Home Journal featured this headline at the top:
``Make Love: Have the Best Sex of Your Life _ Tonight!'' and,
inside, an article titled ``101 Ways to Sex Up Your Marriage.''
(The issue, however, also featured articles titled ``When a Cold
Won't Go Away'' and ``Food Journal: Three Delicious Skillet Recipes
That Get Dinner on the Table in Thirty Minutes.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``We have used sex as a cover line, or in a title for a
relationship article, for a long time,'' Blyth said. ``But one
thing that is interesting now is that we are living in an
optimistic period. People want to have fun in their lives and sex
is seen less as a problem and more as a reward, as enjoyment, than
ever before. So there is a difference in how we promote those
articles on the cover now.''
</P>
<P>
   Samir Husni, a professor of media studies at the University of
Mississippi and a close observer of the magazine industry, said
that one reason the women's service magazines are featuring more
sex is that they are keeping pace with the rest of the field. ``The
Seven Sisters are all general interest magazines, and now you have
targeted women's magazines like Elle and Jane that are nibbling
away at their circulation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Redbook has made the biggest effort to adjust its image and
position and has added more sexual content under the guidance of
Lesley Jane Seymour, the editor in chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to pull away from the rest of the Seven
Sisters,'' Seymour said. ``We are moving it slightly younger, to
fill that gap between the younger fashion magazines and the older,
full-fledged Seven Sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Redbook, Seymour pointed out, has run sex stories for decades.
But now every issue features a prominent headline at the top of the
cover, touting some new sexual position or trend. The October 1999
issue featured a cover story titled ``Intimacy Required! The Move
That Brings You Closer'' and inside ran step-by-step instructions
for ``Redbook's Hot New Sex Position,'' the
``guaranteed-to-make-him-moan'' Passion Flower. (``Sit in the
center of your bed facing each other,'' the instructions begin.
``Wrap your legs comfortably around his body so that you are
sitting on his thighs.'')
</P>
<P>
   And judging from the headlines a decade ago, Redbook has
certainly amped up its sex play on the cover. The headlines that
ran most prominently on covers in 1989, for example, were ``Our
Award-Winning Diet: Drop a Dress Size Fast'' and ``Nails Now ...
Gorgeous Newest Colors, Shapes, Tips.''
</P>
<P>
   Seymour said she had changed Redbook to reflect the way women's
lives have changed, and that her reader is less a housekeeper for
her children than a fashion-conscious working woman who happens to
have children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to move Redbook between the young fashion
magazines which are totally me-oriented, and the older magazines
which are totally oriented toward your family,'' Seymour said. ``If
you notice, when you get to a magazine like McCall's, it's suddenly
all about family. Redbook is for the young working mom with kids
and all those things she has to juggle and who still cares about
herself. Our best readers come to us post-Glamour and post-Cosmo.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Husni characterized the shift: ``Redbook is trying to
position itself for the woman who believes there is life after
marriage. Or, sorry, sex after marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the Seven sisters, however, are rushing to publish
guides to new erotic zones or architectural drawings of sexual
positions. Jane Chestnutt, the editor in chief of Woman's Day, said
the readers of her 65-year-old publication remained concerned about
strengthening their parenting skills, not their _ as suggested in a
recent Redbook article _ pubococcygeal muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our readers make it clear that what they want is romance, not
sex,'' Chestnutt said. ``They are busy and their husbands are busy,
and they've got kids and they don't have enough time to be with one
another. So we give them ideas to strengthen their relationships,
and we believe they can take care of the rest themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Levine, the editor in chief of Good Housekeeping _ who
began her career at Woman's Day and was editor in chief of Redbook
_ said that change is inevitable, even at the vaunted women's
service magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that many of these magazines were formed around the
turn of the century when women didn't even have the vote,'' she
said. ``They have to evolve. But life is clearly very different
than it was five years ago, or 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine pointed out that even the term ``Seven Sisters'' is an
outdated marketing canard invented by advertising executives _
mostly men _ in the 1950s. And she said that she herself had
wondered if the magazines' decline in readership had anything to do
with the fact that women no longer like to perceive of themselves
as housewives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a magazine that is 115 years old, you have to
wonder about that,'' she said. ``But I don't think readers'
interest in those things is dying out at all. Every few years you
have a whole new generation that needs to learn those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always going to have to know how to get the spot out
of,'' Levine paused before alighting on a word that would not imply
housewifely duties _ then said, ``a spot out of your dress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
