<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000227.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0091 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRAIN-DRAIN-MEDIA-(97     02-27 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-DRAIN-MEDIA-(970)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET DRAINING TALENT FROM PRINT MEDIA
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER and ALEX KUCZYNSKI 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet, a phenomenon that has filled the pages of
newspapers and magazines since 1995, is now emptying a few of their
newsroom cubicles.
</P>
<P>
   Beautyscene.com, Business.com, Cybergold.com, Drspock.com,
Goodhome.com, Office.com, Petopia.com, Rivals.com, VoxCap.com,
Women.com. The names are new enough to befuddle even the most
dot-com obsessed observer, but they are becoming irritatingly
familiar to newspaper and magazine editors, as one seasoned
journalist after another is lured away to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The sites listed above, for instance, have recently attracted a
Los Angeles bureau chief from The Wall Street Journal, a New York
Times copy editor, a Seattle Times sportswriter, an assistant city
editor at The San Francisco Chronicle, a Chicago bureau chief from
Business Week, a business writer and a copy editor from The San
Jose Mercury News, the beauty director of Elle, a Fortune columnist
and the editor of American HomeStyle and Gardening.
</P>
<P>
   A more complete list, including better-known sites like
Forbes.com, CNN.com, America Online, Salon.com, Slate and
TheStreet.com, and Internetcentric magazines like The Industry
Standard, Red Herring and Fast Company, might fill an entire column
of newspaper type. If journalists from trade publications and
recent journalism school graduates were thrown in, the names and
their associated dot-coms would fill a whole page.
</P>
<P>
   Publications in the West Coast high-technology centers like
Seattle, San Francisco and San Jose are particularly vulnerable, as
are those covering financial news, technology, sports, health and
beauty _ the niches that draw the biggest and most devoted online
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Even journalists closely acquainted with the unproven financial
strategies of many sites have taken the leap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six months to a year ago, I wouldn't have dreamed that I would
be leaving The Journal and doing anything like this,'' said Peter
Gumbel, the departing Los Angeles bureau chief of the Dow Jones
newspaper and the incoming editor of Business.com, a business
information site created by eCompanies of Santa Monica, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an opportunity The Journal couldn't provide,'' Gumbel
added. ``I had this image of my daughter saying to me in 20 years'
time, `What did you do in the Internet revolution, Daddy?' If I had
to stand there and say, `Nothing special, dear ...'''.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gumbel, a former foreign correspondent, added that he had
found the technology revolution just as transforming as the
collapse of communism, which he had covered. Only this time, he
asked himself, ``Do I want to be an observer or a participant?''
So, at 42, Gumbel is pocketing a fistful of stock options in his
new company and preparing to be editor in chief of an enterprise
whose journalists are mostly yet to be hired and whose editorial
product is yet to be shaped.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine industry, too, has been losing people for several
years, most recently the head of one of the top magazine companies.
</P>
<P>
   John Heins, the chief executive of Gruner &AMP; Jahr Publishing _ a
unit of Bertelsmann that publishes Family Circle, McCall's and
Parents _ took a job as a vice president of sales and international
operations at Netscape, a unit of America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Heins said that he had been exploring ways to bring Gruner &AMP;
Jahr up to Internet speed when he became intrigued with Internet
culture. ``I became fascinated by the industry,'' he said. ``I
wanted to be in the middle of it.''
</P>
<P>
   At Gruner &AMP; Jahr, he found it hard to keep the dot-com raiders
from his staff. ``We have had an incredible number of cases where
you have a person making $60,000 a year who gets lured away with
$100,000 and stock options,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The exact number of Internet journalism jobs is impossible to
pin down. But Marsha Stoltman, who is vice president and general
manager of conferences for Editor &AMP; Publisher and ran a recent
session on interactive newspapers, said the migration from old
media to new media ``has yet to peak.''
</P>
<P>
   Editors like Michael R. Fancher of The Seattle Times and David
Yarnold of Knight Ridder's San Jose Mercury News, while
acknowledging some irritating losses, see the phenomenon as part of
a broader dynamism within the newspaper industry _ driven by a
booming economy and old media's need to hire for its own Internet
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The total loss last year was 11 people,'' Yarnold said about
his newspaper, ``and 11 people out of 400 or more does not
constitute a crisis or a brain drain.'' With the newsroom expanding
by 26 people _ including 16 technology reporters _ the newspaper is
on a hiring binge.
</P>
<P>
   Still, aware of the high premium that Internet companies place
on journalists who know their world, he said that The Mercury News
pays technology reporters a premium of perhaps 10 percent more than
it does other reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The lure of dot-com companies, he said, is less salary than
stock options, which could be worth hundreds of thousands _ unless
the company crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Outing, who has covered Internet journalism for years for
Editor &AMP; Publisher Interactive, does not have as sanguine a view as
Yarnold. ``Is it a real brain drain?'' he said. ``My perception is
that it is. It's hard to quantify.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the real impact is likely to be felt by the
smallest newspapers. ``They get people right out of college,'' he
said. ``They don't pay well. When I got out of college _ this was
1978 _ the major alternatives were public relations or technical
writing. One of the offers I got was a technical writing position,
which paid double the newspaper salary. I took the newspaper job
because it was more exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now would a kid coming out of college take a newspaper job
because of the glamour? I doubt it, because the dot-coms are
glamorous themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Cowan, dean of the Annenberg School for Communication
at the University of Southern California, estimated that 10 percent
of the journalists who graduated in June went to Internet concerns.
But, he added, ``The dot-coms are paying in the high 40s and low
50s, whereas the print outlets are paying their entering
journalists in the high 20s.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Wang, who began teaching this year at the graduate school
of journalism at the University of Missouri after four years in
online journalism, said, ``Clearly the students have no desire to
get a fact-checking job with Esquire when they can get $50,000 plus
options at a Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web sites that are most attractive to magazine employees
tend to be those that cover beauty, home design and decoration and
finance. In 1999, almost a dozen editors left women's magazines
like Glamour, Allure, Cosmopolitan and Vogue to join beauty retail
sites like Eve.com, Beautyjungle.com, Beautyscene.com and
Sephora.com.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Jean Godfrey-June, the beauty director of the
Lagardere magazine Elle for six years, left the magazine last
August to become Beautyscene.com's editor in chief, and Elle was
not able to fill the post until January.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Turshen, editor in chief of Goodhome.com, left his job last
September as editor in chief of American HomeStyle and Gardening,
published by Gruner &AMP; Jahr. Turshen said the attraction Net sites
associated with home design is their depth and retail
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you presented rooms and merchandise in a magazine, well,
you had rooms and merchandise,'' he said. ``On a Web site, you can
present a room full of ottomans, and the viewer can buy
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   At The Seattle Times, which lost people to Microsoft in the
mid-1990s and to MSNBC.com three years ago, the last year has been
marked by attrition of a different sort. ``Only a handful of the
people who left went to interactive media,'' Fancher said. ``In our
case, the drain is not to new media, it's to traditional media in a
very competitive market.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, people are joining sites they wrote about just
weeks before, a situation that makes some journalists
uncomfortable. One who was undeterred was Jodi Mardesich of the
Time Warner magazine Fortune. In a column on Fortune's Web site
last week explaining why she was leaving Fortune's Silicon Valley
bureau for Drspock.com, she wrote: ``What if I could write about a
topic that's meaningful to me and create something valuable at the
same time?''
</P>
<P>
   But some defectors return. Danny O'Neil was a summer intern in
The Seattle Times' sports section in 1997 before he headed for the
Internet, eventually landing at ESPN.com. Last year, he came back
to The Times to cover high school sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came back for less money,'' he said. ``I want to write. In
my experience, people in the Internet are looking for scores. They
don't digest long articles. They go from one file to another
without reading more than four paragraphs.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 1643EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000227.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-Y2K-LEAP-COMPUTERS-AR     02-27 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-LEAP-COMPUTERS-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR 2000 ROLLOVER PROBLEM, THE SEQUEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years ago Tuesday, on Feb. 29, 1996, malfunctions in
computers that did not recognize that year's leap day forced
Belgium to close its stock exchange, stopped the Arizona State
Lottery from selling tickets and locked all the doors at Johnson
County Community College in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Such experiences led to warnings during the height of the Year
2000 computer preparations in 1998 and 1999 not to forget that 2000
was also a leap year. Experts had been predicting that on Feb. 29,
2000, breakdowns might be especially burdensome if businesses and
governments had not yet fully recovered from computer malfunctions
that were widely expected to strike in January.
</P>
<P>
   The betting now, though, is that the government's Year 2000
command center, which reopened Monday after a month's hiatus, might
be a good place Tuesday for a peaceful nap. Because computers have
encountered far fewer Year 2000 date failures than anticipated, the
assumption is that computer users also fixed nearly all the
potential leap-year faults, too, as they were spending billions on
Year 2000 precautions. And programmers are thought to be better
prepared than ever to spot and quickly fix any date problems they
missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real threat is gone,'' said Howard Adams, an information
technology analyst at Giga Group, a research and consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   There is still widespread debate on just how great the threat
ever was. Clearly, many computers would have been unable to
interpret dates with the year expressed by just the two digits 00 _
the Year 2000 problem _ had they not been repaired. And some
experts like Peter de Jager, a Canadian consultant, contend that
even though the repair effort consumed $200 billion or more, the
global total of Year 2000-related date malfunctions has already
topped a million.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the number, though, the great majority have been
problems so minor that they could be dealt with without their ever
coming to the public's attention or overwhelming the computer
staffs of the companies experiencing them. Many problems that
became public, like Internet sites suddenly displaying dates like
1900 or even 19100, produced giggles rather than harm.
</P>
<P>
   Other breakdowns were too isolated to cause concern, as when 800
slot machines failed in Delaware and toll roads around Sao Paulo,
Brazil, could not provide valid receipts.
</P>
<P>
   Through the end of January, just 21 companies had asked the IRS
for permission to delay tax payments without penalties because of
Year 2000 problems, under a special rule adopted late last year,
said Daniel Boone, an IRS spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   There were Year 2000 problems that might have been serious under
different circumstances, like the failure of a reporting system for
radiation levels at Japan's Shika nuclear plant. Around the world,
numerous building security systems froze, including one at the
Canadian government's National Defense Headquarters in Ottawa.
France was unable to communicate with a military satellite and, in
perhaps the most widely reported breakdown, the Pentagon was unable
to process images from a spy satellite.
</P>
<P>
   One clear example of how disruptive Year 2000 could have been,
had no one taken precautions, involved a credit card payment system
made by Cybercash, in Reston, Va. A small number of the 100,000
restaurateurs and other small businesses that use Cybercash did not
update their system software and unwittingly billed their customers
day after day for the same transaction. Some consumers who monitor
their credit card balances online noticed the problem quickly and
got their bills corrected. But many more did not find out until
opening their monthly bills and finding hundreds or even thousands
of dollars in erroneous charges.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The easy part was stopping the charges, once we found out on
Jan. 13, but we still haven't settled everything,'' said Tzu Ming
Yang, owner of the Kawasaki Japanese Seafood restaurant in
Baltimore, which uses the Cybercash system. He said that Kawasaki
had issued more than $82,000 in credits to customers based on
records from National Data Corp., its processor. But because
processors like National Data and banks issuing credit cards are
both part of the accounting chain, the dates when the transactions
are credited may vary, and some consumers ended up in disputes over
finance charges, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
   Yang said it was too soon to try to assign blame. Because of
special rules aimed at discouraging Year 2000 litigation passed
last year by Congress, lawyers say it will be spring at the
earliest before lawsuits emerge involving the Cybercash breakdowns
or any others.
</P>
<P>
   So far, courts are saying that the law does not apply to suits
filed by companies seeking reimbursement from insurers for the
millions of dollars the companies spent avoiding possible Year 2000
losses. GTE, Xerox, Kmart and Nike are among the major companies
that filed such suits last year, all of which are in the early
pretrial stages.
</P>
<P>
   No one now expects the litigation toll to reach the $1 trillion
figure once bandied about. But the number of lawsuits is expected
to increase in the coming months, said Ronald N. Weikers, a
Philadelphia lawyer who has closely tracked Year 2000 legal
developments.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts now say that 2000 will be remembered mostly as
the occasion for a thorough housecleaning and updating that left
them primed for a rapid expansion of e-commerce and other new
electronic technologies.
</P>
<P>
   With leap day shaping up as a nonevent, the major remaining
question related to Y2K seems to be whether the lessons learned,
and the investments made, will be fully exploited. And on that
point, there are plenty of skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of every 100 companies that want to leverage their Y2K
work, about 15 will really do it,'' predicted Adams, a former
computer manager at Bank of America who has followed Year 2000
computer problems for Giga Group since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But some experts say the lasting effects may be greater than the
skeptics expect, just as the success in dealing with Year 2000
flaws was. Thousands of businesses and government agencies now have
up-to-date, streamlined systems, top managers with a better
appreciation of information technology's vital role, and better
understanding of their suppliers' operations.
</P>
<P>
   Some ad hoc Year 2000 groups, like the High Technology
Consortium, a group of nearly 40 companies like Intel, Motorola,
Hewlett-Packard and Cisco Systems, have already met to discuss how
to continue their coordinated efforts to deal with matters like
contingency planning and maintaining continuous links with
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals and human services agencies that teamed up in Bell
County, Texas, to create a list of ``medically fragile'' residents
to monitor during the rollover, are seeking grants to continue and
extend their database to cover up to 10,000 people, including area
residents with mental health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even if companies are tempted to fall back into bad
programming and maintenance habits, insurers are likely to pressure
them to shape up, said Harris Miller, executive director of the
Information Technology Association of America. ``The same things
that helped companies deal with Y2K set them up to practice good
security, which insurers want so they can avoid payouts for
breaches,'' Miller said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
