<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Feb. 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A small, but intense disturbance along the Maine coast will
cause a period of heavy rain in central and eastern New England on
Monday. In western sections, enough chilly air will sweep in to
cause wet snow, which may accumulate 6 inches or more in the Green
and White Mountains. Since the jet stream disturbance will be
changing its orientation over the Northeast, clearing will be slow
along the southern New England coast. Winds will be blustery from
the northwest with gusts over 30 mph from Pennsylvania to the
Middle Atlantic shores.
</P>
<P>
   The South will be bright and very pleasant though not as warm as
recent days. High pressure stretching from the Ohio Valley to the
upper Great Lakes will sponsor mainly sunny skies and seasonably
mild conditions in most of the Mississippi Valley. A surge of
warmer air into the Dakotas will promote clouds and gusty winds.
Brisk winds from the south will reach 30 mph over the central
Plains.
</P>
<P>
   An elongated cold front moving east of the Rockies will produce
periods of wet snow along the west slopes of the mountains from
western Wyoming through eastern Utah and into southwest Colorado.
Valley showers are likely in this same region. Meanwhile, high
pressure building into California will cause sunny and more
pleasant conditions after morning fog lifts. The Northwest Coast
will turn dismal as a warm front sends steady rain into Oregon and
showers along the Washington shoreline. Snow levels will rise in
the Cascades. Winds will reach gale force later Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Balmy in Buffalo
</P>
<P>
   In spite of frozen Lake Erie just a few miles away, the mercury
rose to 71 degrees on Saturday afternoon in Buffalo establishing a
new all-time record for February. The previous record of 70 was set
just three years ago on February 21, 1997. In a city where the joke
is that there are two seasons, winter and the Fourth of July,
Buffalo can manage to bask in winter warmth when a persistent wind
from the south sets in. Indeed for three days, a balmy breeze has
blown. The air descended from the hills of northwest Pennsylvania
adding a few extra degrees, enough to eclipse the record.
</P>
</TEXT>
