<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCORD ON DIGITAL TV TECHNOLOGY STILL LACKS HOLLYWOOD'S INPUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under threat from the chairman of the Federal
Communications Commission, the cable television and
consumer-electronics industries have said, once again, that they
have solved a vexing problem slowing the transition to digital TV.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue is still not fully resolved. It is the second time
the two organizations have made such an announcement. And just like
the last one, this agreement is notable as much for what it does
not include as for what it does.
</P>
<P>
   The arcane but critical problem concerns how to connect a
digital television set to a digital cable box. No appropriate
digital connector exists. But because more than two-thirds of the
nation's television viewers subscribe to cable, digital sets must
be cable-compatible if the transition is ever to succeed. The
television sets available today are not.
</P>
<P>
   The two industries have been arguing over this issue for two
years. Last month, FCC Chairman Bill Kennard angrily warned that if
they did not solve the problem by April, the commission would
impose a regulatory solution of its own.
</P>
<P>
   That led to the announcement on Wednesday, which brought
congratulatory remarks from Kennard and the leaders of the two
industries. But little mention was made of a lingering, underlying
problem: Hollywood and the industries have not decided on a
copy-protection standard, making the whole agreement hollow, in the
view of some analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood will not release digital copies of current movies for
use on cable unless they are protected against the making of
multiple copies. Though current analog programming has long been
available for copying on videocassettes, such copies degrade over
time. The studios fear releasing digital versions of films into
general circulation because those can be copied endlessly without
degradation.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of deja vu hangs over all of this.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1998, a few months after the problem was first
disclosed, Kennard wrote a sharp letter to the cable industry and
the set makers, demanding they solve it by Nov. 1 of that year.
``These compatibility problems must be resolved quickly to ensure
that American consumers are able to enjoy the benefits of digital
television starting this fall,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He and others in government were anxious to speed the transition
to digital television because at the end of the phase-in period,
all the older, analog stations now broadcasting are to be turned
off, with those parts of the airwaves reclaimed and auctioned for
other uses.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, on Nov. 2, 1998, the cable and consumer-electronics
industries announced an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Kennard called it ``an important milestone.'' And
Decker Anstrom, who was head of the National Cable Television
Association, promised: ``This will help ensure that digital TV sets
compatible with cable will be available in retail stores by
November 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was one problem: The industries had no copy-protection
plan to address Hollywood's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Kennard said he knew that at the time
but decided ``this was an evolutionary process, and they had at
least made some progress.'' The industries pledged to solve this
and other remaining issues quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But by the start of this year _ a month after the
cable-compatible digital TVs were supposed to have reached the
stores _ Kennard said he was fed up with the delays and issued his
warning. Solve the problem by April, he said, or the FCC will solve
it for you.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1998, the two industries chose which sort of cable
they would use, a digital connector known as Firewire. On
Wednesday, almost 16 months later, they said they had worked out
the related software issues and the protocol for transmitting
on-screen program guides for the digital broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   But once again, they had not resolved the copy-protection
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro said once again that the industries would resolve it
soon. Meanwhile, he added, even without copy protection, digital-TV
viewers should be able to receive nonpremium cable fare using the
technology agreed upon so far. Starting now, he said, the
cable-compatible sets can be designed, and the copy protection
software can be added later in the design process, before the sets
reach the market.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the industry said that the sets should arrive in
stores 12 to 18 months from now (though the Sony Corp. says its
versions will be available this year.) But there is no guarantee
that Hollywood will agree to copy protection protocols in time.
</P>
<P>
   Most consumer-electronics companies have settled on a standard
known as 5C, for the five companies that devised it: Hitachi,
Intel, Matsushita Electric, Toshiba and Sony. It allows a movie to
be transmitted with a marker that will allow it to be copied
freely, copied just once or not copied at all. Hollywood and the
cable companies must agree on how movies are to be marked.
</P>
<P>
   The cable industry has added 5C as the standard for its
digital-cable boxes, and several television manufacturers are
building it into their sets. But the major Hollywood studios have
not agreed on whether or how the 5C system will be used.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with executives at two studios show widespread
disagreement on the issue. 20th Century Fox, for example, the
studio owned by News Corp., does not think 5C is secure enough.
Other studio executives who may be comfortable with the technology
resent the idea that the industries have decided to deploy it
before they have worked out arrangements with the studios.
</P>
<P>
   Some studios, one senior executive said, ``are concerned that
this is being rolled out before all the standards have been set,
and that gives them much less flexibility in negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   One senior electronics executive said his industry was
essentially playing chicken with Hollywood. ``They will just have
to take 5C,'' he said. ``We're forcing the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with all that still in play, Kennard praised the industries
on Wednesday, saying their announcement would ``jump-start the
digital revolution for television.'' In his interview, he also
vowed to ``keep pressing them on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Some others were less enthusiastic. Susan Ness, an FCC
commissioner, said, ``We can't declare victory when the game's only
at halftime.'' And the National Association of Broadcasters, which
has been agitating about this issue for years because its member
stations want their programs to be available to cable subscribers,
said: ``The agreement is a sham.''
</P>
</TEXT>
