<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD-FASHIONED REPORTING, NEW MEDIUM 
LINDBERGHS EXPRESS DISMAY OVER BIOGRAPHY 
QUIZ SHOW DRAWS MORE WOMEN CONTESTANTS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In many ways, the world-beating scoop last week by
TheSmokingGun.com, which revealed that the ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire?'' groom, Rick Rockwell, was once the subject of a
restraining order, says a lot about the fledgling Internet's place
in the new order of American journalism.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a classic tale of basic gumshoe reporting. The
site, largely unrecognized until its ``Multimillionaire'' score, is
edited by William Bastone, 38, an investigative reporter for The
Village Voice, and Daniel Green, 36, a freelance reporter and
editor.
</P>
<P>
   Bastone said he and Green started the Web site three years ago
on a monthly budget of about $500 and the idea that it would be a
good place to display the raw materials of journalism _ police
reports, lawsuits, affidavits and the like. They discovered they
could greatly increase traffic by displaying documents from major
news stories _ for example, the recent arrest of Sean Combs _ and
by persuading news sites, search engines and Web portals to set up
links to the site.
</P>
<P>
   Their work on the Rockwell case started as most investigative
projects do: a gut feeling. A friend told Green that he thought the
groom was worth a closer look, and Green took it from there. He
searched Web sites and directories, and one person he interviewed
suggested he check court files in California.
</P>
<P>
   Green looked in San Diego, where Rockwell lives, and found
nothing. But he figured that since Rockwell had been an
entertainer, he must have spent time in Los Angeles, and there he
found the 14-page restraining order that had been imposed on
Rockwell. Then he confirmed that the Rockwell in the court document
was the same one on the Fox television show.
</P>
<P>
   An article was posted on the site with the documents and then
daily newspapers were informed. The page was cited in several news
accounts and traffic soared, with more than 1 million visitors to
the site in one day, usually what the site attracts in a month.
</P>
<P>
   The site's profile has grown since it was incorporated in 1998.
Playboy.com established a link to it, and it does regular features
in New York magazine. An advertising company now sells banner
space, and the site had 1999 revenue of $60,000 to $70,000. And the
owners are now on to other stories. On Thursday, they offered a
look at Darryl Strawberry's probation report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to come up with our second act,'' Bastone said
with a laugh. ``We're telling people we might take a hard look at
that kid on `Malcolm in the Middle.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Christian Berthelsen
</P>
<P>
   Lindberghs Express Dismay Over Biography
</P>
<P>
   At 99 and immobilized by strokes, Anne Morrow Lindbergh's is a
voice that is silent on the topic of an unauthorized biography that
explores her peripatetic life and marriage to the aviation pioneer
Charles A. Lindbergh.
</P>
<P>
   Not so the Lindbergh family, which has let it be known that they
are so disturbed with the form of Susan Hertog's recently published
book, ``Anne Morrow Lindbergh: Her Life'' (Nan A. Talese/Doubleday)
that they moved to prevent the author from using any excerpts from
Lindbergh's previously published diaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a great deal of anger and resentment,'' said
Reeve Lindbergh, the youngest daughter of the Lindberghs, who noted
that she had not read the book but was upset that Hertog had
published a traditional biography instead of a ``feminist study''
of the women and relatives in the aviator's life. Her mother, she
said, did not want a biography written about her during her
lifetime and surely would not have cooperated in such an effort.
</P>
<P>
   Those objections are also shared by another biographer, A. Scott
Berg, who said that when he undertook his long research project
about Charles Lindbergh with the support of the family he was
assured that Hertog was doing a book on ``the Lindbergh women.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg said that if the framework of the book had changed, Hertog
should have approached the family to explain what she was doing.
</P>
<P>
   For Hertog, the family's resistance meant that she had to
rewrite portions of the book to excise diary entries, delaying
publication of her first book for almost two months until late in
the Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the very beginning,'' she said, ``I told the Lindberghs
that I was writing a biography, and in fact Reeve was very
encouraging and introduced me to her mother, and Mrs. Lindbergh
invited me back 10 times, and we have years of correspondence.''
</P>
<P>
   She offers documents showing that in 1992, she sent a letter to
Reeve Lindbergh describing the thrill of obtaining a contract ``for
my biography of your mother.'' Hertog said the family may have
objected to her interpretations of the Lindberghs' political views
or her description of ``Charles' six-year extramarital relationship
with another woman, which I was able to verify.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Doreen Carvajal
</P>
<P>
   Quiz Show Draws More Women Contestants
</P>
<P>
   Still concerned that lack of diversity among the contestants is
the one flaw in the otherwise idyllic success of ``Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire,'' Michael Davies, the show's executive producer,
said he was gratified by the initial results of an on-air appeal
for more women and minority viewers to enter the selection process.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday night, he was edging toward elation. For the first
time, the show featured all female contestants, four in all.
</P>
<P>
   That raised the proportion of women contestants since the appeal
to almost 40 percent. It had been only about 11 percent before Feb.
1, the night the show's host, Regis Philbin, made the unusual
announcement that the program was encouraging people who were not
white males to sign up.
</P>
<P>
   The show still has not had a single black make it to the chair
opposite Philbin, though the overall number of contestants has now
reached 119. Davies acknowledged he was ``fairly depressed'' about
the lack of racial diversity on the show, but was more hopeful than
ever because, since the February appeal, two blacks have been among
the 10 finalists who compete during the show to make to it to the
``hot seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Only three had made it that far during the show's first three
months on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Davies said he had retailored some of the show's questions to
include what he called more ``female material.'' This has included
more female names among those that contestants have been asked to
arrange in some form of chronological order to make it to the
actual game. Similarly, he said, the questions have been adjusted
in subtle ways to include names from black culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to do more,'' Davies said. ``I think this
problem will end soon.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Bill Carter
</P>
</TEXT>
