<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-GOP-VIRGINIA-0228 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCAIN MOUNTS VIRGINIA DRIVE
 &HT;    Moving in the Washington (w) and political (p) categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. - Sen. John McCain of Arizona stepped up his
presidential campaigning in Virginia on Sunday in an effort to hand
Texas Gov. George W. Bush his first Republican primary defeat in
the South.
</P>
<P>
   With a major TV advertising campaign and last-minute personal
appearances, McCain sought to bring core Republican conservatives
into the coalition of moderates, veterans and high-tech interests
that have lifted his presidential campaign to unexpected heights.
</P>
<P>
   His TV ad, running in the northern Virginia, the state's most
populous region, presented him as ``a proud Reagan Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the McCain surge, Bush enjoys the backing of the GOP
establishment in Virginia, including Gov. James Gilmore, Sen. John
Warner and former Gov. George Allen, the most popular figure in
state Republican circles and a current Senate candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor also has a county-by-county organization in
Virginia that is focusing on mustering the core Republican vote.
</P>
<P>
   The state GOP's first open and binding presidential primary was
supposed to have been little more than a victory lap for Bush. In
his previous Southern encounter with McCain in South Carolina, the
Texas governor won convincingly.
</P>
<P>
   Since McCain's surprise victory in Michigan last week, however,
the polls in Virginia have narrowed, prompting a major push by
McCain in the final days before Tuesday's voting. A recent poll
shows Bush's once-commanding lead over McCain narrowing to 8
points.
</P>
<P>
   And the round of local TV appearances by McCain Sunday morning
suggested a bruising battle in the Old Dominion state.
</P>
<P>
   Unapologetic, McCain said he would continue using a telephone
campaign against Bush that criticizes the Texas governor for
speaking at the conservative Christian Bob Jones University and not
disavowing anti-Catholic statements of its founder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to tell the facts,'' McCain said in an
interview on WRC-TV in Washington. ``If Gov. Bush wishes to go to
Bob Jones University ...peopleople should know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's chief campaign strategist, Karl Rove, appearing on
Fox-TV's ``Fox News Sunday,'' called the McCain campaign's
telephone calls ``a sleazy, anonymous smear phone campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain sought to make an issue of telephone calls made in
Michigan by the Virginia-based tele-evangelist Pat Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of thing we will have nothing to do with,'' McCain
said of the prerecorded Robertson calls, which referred to his
campaign chairman, Warren Rudman, as ``a vicious bigot.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-six nominating convention delegates are at stake in the
Virginia primary. But, more importantly, Virginia can help provide
the winner with momentum for Super Tuesday contests in California,
New York and 10 other states on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was traveling to Seattle on Sunday. Washington's primary
also is Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain adjusted his schedule in an effort to capitalize on
narrowing polls in Virginia. He had a rally outside his campaign
headquarters in Alexandria before traveling to Virginia Beach.
</P>
<P>
   In previous primaries, McCain has benefited from overwhelming
support from independent and Democratic-leaning voters.
</P>
<P>
   But in Virginia, he is trying to court a core of about 300,000
party regulars by claiming the mantle of Ronald Reagan, the
political icon of the modern Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain strategy in Virginia has also focused on independents
and Democratic leaning voters of northern Virginia, where a
high-tech industry has grown up around the America On Line
headquarters, and military veterans in the coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
