<HEADER>
A0110 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-REORGANIZE-AD-COLUMN-     02-27 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REORGANIZE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OMNICOM AND GREY SHORE UP FAST-GROWING MEDIA BUSINESSES WITH
REORGANIZATIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two giant agency companies _ the Omnicom Group and Grey
Advertising Inc. _ are making changes in fields outside the realm
of traditional advertising. The moves are indicative of the
additional emphasis being placed on fast-growing services like
media as well as the increasing importance of segments of the mass
market like youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   On the media front, Omnicom, the world's largest agency company
in revenue and second largest in billings, will reorganize its
various planning and buying shops, which handle media accounts with
total billings estimated at $17.5 billion to $18 billion, into two
worldwide networks. The centerpiece of the realignment, to be
formally announced Monday, is the amalgamation in the United States
of many media tasks that had been handled separately at the three
largest Omnicom agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're building two networks with different cultures,'' said
Daryl Simm, chief executive at the Omnicom Media Group in New York,
the media division of Omnicom. He offered a preview of the plans in
a telephone interview on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   One network, Optimum Media Direction, ``will reflect the
heritage and scale of our global advertising agencies, with a
sensibility of service,'' Simm said, adding that the other, PhD,
``will reflect the culture of our independent and entrepreneurial
media companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization creates an American unit for Optimum Media
Direction, named OMD USA, that will pool resources like broadcast
media buying and research for BBDO Worldwide, DDB Worldwide and the
TBWA/Chiat/Day unit of TBWA Worldwide. OMD USA will buy commercial
time on local and national television and radio outlets with
billings estimated at $4.1 billion; total Optimum Media billings
are estimated at $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Optimum Media began in Europe in 1996 and now operates in 30
countries including Australia, Britain, Canada, France, Germany,
Hong Kong and Italy. Its expansion to the United States had been
widely anticipated but was delayed amid discussions that lasted
about a year regarding its scope and structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep in mind we have about 90 clients'' coming
together at OMD USA, Simm said. ``Steve, Dan and Annette spent what
I would say is a very careful amount of time to make sure each was
on board.''
</P>
<P>
   That reference was to the three executives being named to top
posts at OMD USA. Steve Grubbs, 47, executive vice president for
national television buying at BBDO New York, will be managing
partner and chief executive. Dan Rank, 45, who had been director
for local and national broadcast at Optimum Media, the DDB media
unit, will be managing partner for national broadcast. And Annette
Cerbone, 46, who had been in charge of the corporate media group at
TBWA/Chiat/Day, will be managing partner for local broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   All told, about 250 employees of BBDO, DDB and TBWA/Chiat/Day
will join OMD USA. The employees at the three agencies who handle
media planning will remain at their respective agencies, as will
executives like Page Thompson, worldwide media director and
president of Optimum Media at DDB, and Monica Karo, corporate media
director at TBWA/Chiat/Day.
</P>
<P>
   Trade publications had speculated that OMD USA would also take
on the media buying functions for the smaller Omnicom American
agencies like GSD&AMP; M in Austin, Texas; Goodby, Silverstein &AMP;
Partners in San Francisco; and Martin/Williams in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, is not the case, Simm said, adding that the
status of the media operations of those agencies ``remains
unchanged.'' He declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The other media network, PhD, will oversee autonomous agencies
like Advanswers and Creative Media in the United States, Harrison
Young Pesonen &AMP; Newell in Canada and New PHD in Britain. David
Pattison, 43, who had been chief executive at New PHD in London,
will be chief executive at PhD.
</P>
<P>
   The American agencies that will be part of PhD handle media
chores on accounts with billings estimated at $1.5 billion; total
PhD billings are estimated at $2.5 billion to $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to Grey, the world's eighth-largest agency company in
revenue and ninth-largest in billings, two specialty units are
being merged to form an agency with 110 employees handling accounts
with estimated billings of $310 million for clients like GT
Interactive, SFX Entertainment and Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Grey Entertainment, founded in 1974, which specializes in
entertainment marketing, is being merged with G Whiz, founded in
July 1999, which specializes in marketing to children and
teen-agers. The merged agency will be named _ what else? _ G Whiz
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, a merger of two such disparate shops seems as
logical as merging agencies devoted to, say, health care
advertising and direct marketing. But the combination makes sense,
said Edward H. Meyer, chairman, president and chief executive at
Grey, because ``today, much of entertainment marketing is targeted
to teens, kids and young adults.''
</P>
<P>
   At G Whiz Entertainment, Barbara Martino, 38, will be president
and chief executive and Gerry Logue, 45, will be vice chairman. She
had been president at G Whiz, the smaller of the two agencies, and
he had been president at Grey Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment marketing operations of the merged agency will
be overseen by Rob Jacobson, 35, senior vice president and senior
creative director, and Steven Yorra, 41, senior vice president and
account services director. Both had held similar posts at Grey
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The general youth marketing operations of G Whiz Entertainment
will be overseen by Brett Howlett, 38, senior vice president and
creative director, and Doug Zarkin, 29, vice president for client
services. Both had held similar posts at G Whiz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 1740EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
