u e BC-TV-GRAPEVINE-REVIEW-N     02-27 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GRAPEVINE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GRAPEVINE': HANDSOME, NARCISSISTIC AND TANGLED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(ms) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the new romantic comedy ``Grapevine,'' a group of thirtyish,
preternaturally good-looking men and women live in Miami, gaze
directly into the camera and explain the tangled, ever-changing
lines of love and friendship that connect them. What they don't say
is: We are so self-absorbed we make the women of ``Sex in the
City'' look like a band of Mother Teresas.
</P>
<P>
   There's something to be said for self-absorption, of course; if
a character doesn't like himself, who will? But it's hard to build
a series around relentless navel gazing and a narrative gimmick
that creates more talk than action.
</P>
<P>
   The show's creator, writer and director, David Frankel, has
given himself a tricky high-wire act. That act works with
effortless charm whenever Steven Eckholdt is on screen as the
central character, a restaurant owner named David. And the entire
show tumbles off the wire as soon as his character disappears.
</P>
<P>
   Eckholdt (who played the friend who lived in Los Angeles in last
year's smart but failed sitcom ``It's Like You Know'') is so
winning he almost rescues the series from itself. At the start he
looks into the camera, gives a warm but slightly abashed smile and
tells us about Susan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Susie's elevator doesn't always go all the way to the
penthouse,'' he says. ``She happens to be the marketing director of
a cruise line, but could easily have been a clown. I've been in
love with her since the day we met.'' Obviously he finds those
qualities more charming than most viewers will, but we're convinced
that he's convinced, which makes him engaging and likable even when
he's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The other characters and their extended circle of guest friends
(who also talk to the camera), can become unintentionally annoying,
though. Susan (Kristy Swanson) really is an airhead and a meddler
in other people's lives. Matt (David Sutcliffe), a hotel manager
who doesn't appear until next week's episode, is colorless. Hardest
to take is David's brother, Thumper (George Eads), a sports
broadcaster described by David as a guy with no professional
qualifications beyond being ``handsome, charming'' and full of hot
air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God for television,'' says Thumper, whose job on the
local news allows his second career as a womanizer to flourish.
Let's face it, viewers are never going to believe in a character
named Thumper unless he's Bambi's pal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grapevine'' is a good sign that CBS is at least trying to
shake its geezer image, but its sense of hipness is tame. Where
``Sex in the City'' takes its characters' upscale lives and
arrogance for granted without apologies, ``Grapevine'' assumes an
ingratiating tone. And despite its MTV speed, the dialogue is often
a staid he said, she said descended from ``When Harry Met Sally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I came this close to kissing her,'' David tells the camera
about Susan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came this close to slapping him,'' she says of the same
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Three episodes of the series' scheduled six-week run were
available for review. Next week Thumper dates Matt's ex-wife,
Yancy, until Susan tells Matt to give the marriage another try, but
not before she has fixed up Matt with Gina, who once had a bad
experience with Thumper. Despite its sporadic charm and captivating
leading actor, ``Grapevine'' doesn't give viewers a good enough
reason to follow this group as it goes around in circles.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GRAPEVINE'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   9:30 p.m. ET Mondays on CBS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Frankel, creator, writer and director; David Frankel and
Barry Jossen, executive producers. Produced by CBS Productions in
association with Paramount Network Television.
</P>
<P>
   With: Kristy Swanson (Susan), Steven Eckholdt (David), George
Eads (Thumper) and David Sutcliffe (Matt).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 1752EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000227.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PRUDENTIAL-EQUITABLE-     02-27 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRUDENTIAL-EQUITABLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN'S PRUDENTIAL CONSIDERS BID FOR RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Prudential PLC, the British insurance company, is
considering a bid of as much as 4 billion pounds, or $6.4 billion,
for its rival, the Equitable Life Assurance Society, executives
close to the company said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential is weighing its options after a rash of consolidation
in the insurance industry in Britain including the $12 billion
merger of CGU PLC. and Norwich Union PLC last week, which created
an insurance giant that comes close to surpassing Prudential as
Britain's largest insurer.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear when Prudential might approach Equitable
Life, but the executives noted that no bid was imminent and that
the company could still decide to abandon the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Financial services companies and insurers throughout Europe are
scrambling to find merger partners to cut costs and to be able to
add size and muscle to repel bids from larger institutions. Though
Prudential ranks as Britain's largest insurer, it remains tiny
compared with some of its European counterparts like Allianz of
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Equitable Life might have became a ripe target
last week after it lost an all important appeal in High Court here
that effectively forces the company to pay as much as $324 million
for guaranteed annuities.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential is going through a transition of its own as Jonathan
Bloomer assumes the chief executive post, replacing Peter Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomer, who was the company's chief financial officer, is keen
to shake up Prudential, an executive close to the company said.
Bloomer was responsible for leading the creation of Egg, an
Internet bank, in 1998 that Prudential financed and is now worth
$6.4 billion. Just this week Prudential announced that it planned
to sell a quarter of its stake in Egg in a initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to Prudential said it had hired Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter as its adviser, though a spokesman for the investment
bank declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Prudential could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Nash, managing director of Equitable Life told Bloomberg
News he was unaware of Prudential's interest. ``We have had no
approach from the Prudential and would not welcome one,'' he said.
``Our belief is that mutuality is in the best interests of our
members.'' News of a possible bid was reported today in several
British papers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 1757EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000227.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0121 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-IRWIN-DANE-REVIEW-NYT     02-27 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRWIN-DANE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HARD-TAPPING TRIBUTE, HOBBYHORSES INCLUDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill Irwin, as urbane a clown as ever, did a Whoopi
Goldberg, changing costumes between acts. While host of a program
aptly titled ``The Elegance of Tap and the Comedy of Tap,'' he also
pretended he could tap dance only with the aid of kneepads and a
harness that kept him from toppling over the nonexistent
footlights.
</P>
<P>
   Among his co-conspirators last Friday night at Town Hall were a
trio of Russians encased in hobbyhorses who cantered around
hilariously and gleefully. Buster Brown, at 86 still the master
hoofer, added his elegant skimming steps. Jennie Nau, an
eighth-grader from Florida, brought cheerleader freshness to the
toe dancing she did in her tap shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Committee to Celebrate National Tap Dance Day,
headed by Al Heyward and Carl Schlesinger of the New York
Foundation for the Arts, organized the one-night program, a prelude
to the annual Tap Extravaganza at Town Hall on May 28.
</P>
<P>
   Gimmicks were part of the evening, but that is par for the
course. Tap is not only style and technique, it is also a form of
personalized expression.
</P>
<P>
   The wild-ranging event last Friday was part of a lively
ethnic-dance series being presented by Town Hall. The inclusion of
tap is no surprise. In Europe tap is considered an ethnic export,
peculiarly American. The Russian trio learned from American tap
teachers in Moscow. Jerry Ames, the veteran performer whose silvery
rhythms, with Rolf Barnes at the piano, infused his class act, had
just returned from teaching in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin has been called a new vaudevillian, which means that he
has a healthy respect for the old vaudevillians and that he does
know how to tap, rubber-leg style. Brenda Bufalino, another
veteran, was his teacher. She put on her usual excellent display of
complex, close-to-the-ground rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   Loosely speaking, the evening was divided between those who
favor percussion tap, in which sound is primary, and those who set
the entire body in motion, often describing character. The
sophisticated jazz style of the Frank Owens Trio (Owens, Lisle
Atkinson and Bernice Brooks) provided most of the music.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography that Susan Hebach and Jennifer MacQueen did for
the Tap Collective had everyone (including Cintia Chamecki, Lynn
Schwab and Sherry Stregack) doing their arm-swinging thing.
Individuality in performance was everything. Jess Jurkovic, Tim
Ferguson and Terry Vinyard were their musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel and McCain had Winston Samuel and Ralph McCain,
deceptively urban in their caps and T-shirts, delivering polished
cool in their singing and tap dialogue, choreographed by Luther
Fontaine. Nau took with relish to the high-kicking mix of ballet
and tap by Robin Dawn.
</P>
<P>
   The team of Sergey and Vasiliy consists of Sergey Kusyakov and
Vasiliy Myshletsov. They are wonderful clowns who went to circus
school in Moscow, and their comedy sacrifices nothing to basic
technique. Yelena Tishunova was the filly who joined them in
Myshletsov's choreography.
</P>
<P>
   Chamecki, a Brazilian, wore the heavy shoes of the current
percussion stylists but shared the fluency of her Brazilian
musicians, Tomas Marsh and Tisza Coelho. Nicole Hockenberry and Amy
Browne Smith, with Andy Wasserman at the piano, were sparkling,
wholesome dancers. Sam Seimiya offered a change of pace. He had an
extraordinary way with understatement, even while building up his
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Cornell's choreography for Manhattan Tap, with Keith
Saunders as pianist, was a sure-fire hit. A sexy, hip-swinging
quartet, Charon Aldredge, Mari Fujibayashi, Rhythm Kaneko and
Olivia Rosenkrantz, offered a powerhouse display, which included a
chair-sitting number. Melissa Giattino and Richard Schwartz had a
winning zaniness in the musical comedy numbers choreographed by
Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   Baraki Wilder, who succeeded Savion Glover in ``Bring In da
Noise, Bring In da Funk,'' made an unscheduled and virtuosic
appearance with a solo that introduced Jason Samuels. Samuels, a
big man with a big talent, gives the current new urban style and
its powerful steps his own unpredictability. Shoehorn (Michael
Conley) is more predictable simply because his specialty is a
signature, playing the saxophone as he taps. In all, it was a true
variety show, and Irwin did a fabulous job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 1802EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
