<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HARLEM-MUSEUM-2TAKES-     02-27 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-MUSEUM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEADERS WANT A HIGHER VISIBILITY FOR A HARLEM MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The revitalization of 125th Street, one of
Manhattan's premier commercial boulevards, is well under way. Shops
are looking smart; Old Navy and Starbucks have arrived. And beyond
commerce there are major changes at one of the street's cultural
landmarks, the Studio Museum in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, just over three decades old, has long been a
respected if taken-for-granted presence in the New York art world.
But with the recent hiring of a new director and deputy director,
both from the center of the art world, its visibility is sure to
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The new director is Lowery Stokes Sims, 51, a curator of
20th-century art at the Metropolitan Museum of Art for more than 20
years. The new deputy director for exhibitions and programs is
Thelma Golden, 33, who resigned as a curator at the Whitney Museum
of American Art in 1998 when a curatorial restructuring put into
effect by its director, Maxwell L. Anderson, left her without a
slot.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction in the art world to the Studio Museum appointments has
ranged from high enthusiasm to consternation, which is not
surprising given the complex nature of the museum itself.
</P>
<P>
   Founded during the social upheavals of the 1960s, it is small
and ethnically defined. It is the country's only accredited museum
devoted to African-American art and as such is a monument to black
cultural accomplishment. It has documented the history of
African-American art when few other institutions were doing so and
has provided support for generations of artists who were excluded
from the larger art world.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years that larger world has begun, however
tentatively, to change. Mainstream museums have started to produce
historical shows of black art. Opportunities have broadened for
African-American art professionals. And after the multiculturalist
thinking of the 1990s, traditionally defined notions of racial
identity and ethnic group have been thrown into question.
</P>
<P>
   How a museum stays flexible enough to respond to these changes
while retaining a sense of its original mission will be one of the
museological questions of the new decade. The arrival of Sims and
Golden in Harlem comes at an interesting and difficult moment and
has already produced repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   To a museum named for a specific community, Sims and Golden
bring the glamour of high-powered institutions elsewhere. Their
hiring marks a potentially far-reaching break in the Studio
Museum's pattern of training and promoting its curators and
administrators from within.
</P>
<P>
   Their move uptown also leaves a significant gap in the art
world. The departure of Sims from the Metropolitan and Golden from
the Whitney has taken black curators from two of the city's leading
museums, which might well be seen as a step backward in the
far-from-resolved battle to break the art world's color barrier.
</P>
<P>
   For Sims and Golden the new assignments bring professional
challenges. Sims switches from her experience as a curator to the
untested role of fund-raiser, and both move from rich museums to
one of slender resources. At the same time the two women appear to
make a complementary team, well-balanced in their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Sims has a doctorate in modern art and a record of scholarly
shows at the Met, including surveys of Hans Hofmann and Stuart
Davis. She began there 27 years ago with a job in the education
department and gradually rose through the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Golden, for whom things have happened faster, is well known
internationally for her intense interest in new art. (She was
originally scheduled to organize this year's Whitney Biennial.) She
is also still associated in many minds with her important Whitney
exhibition ``Black Male'' (1994-95), which played in provocative
ways with stereotypes of African-American masculinity.
</P>
<P>
   That show was critically pummeled but brought a large, racially
mixed audience to the Whitney. And it sparked rancorous reactions
among certain African-American artists, many of them of an older
generation, who found the deliberately ambiguous use of black
stereotypes irresponsible. Their anger was also directed at some
artists Golden favors, among them Kara Walker, whose potent wall
pieces include satirical images of slaves.
</P>
<P>
   The fracas had many ideological and personal elements.
Resentment was perhaps particularly keen because Golden's Whitney
job involved acquiring work, and she was perceived as being in a
position to help shape the historical picture of African-American
art in the museum, which she did.
</P>
<P>
   In addition she has a staunch and powerful ally in the art
patron Peter Norton, who provided much of the money for ``Black
Male'' and has put his weight as a collector behind the careers of
artists she endorsed. Norton resigned as a museum trustee when
Golden left, and she subsequently worked for his foundation as a
special projects curator.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With her new appointment in Harlem, speculation rose that Norton
would become more involved with the Studio Museum. (He has been a
donor in the past.) Those observers who disagree with his taste and
hers and fear his influence view the alliance with apprehension.
Others, however, feel that his support of the new administration's
progressive aims would help bring a new vigor to the institution.
</P>
<P>
   When asked recently about the extent of Norton's future
involvement, Sims responded: ``Our board of trustees has four empty
chairs, and our nominating committee is considering candidates.
That's all I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   However that arrangement works out, Sims and Golden have already
begun to formulate ideas for the directions they mean to take.
</P>
<P>
   Sims says that certain essential features of the museum will not
change, notably the artist in residence program, which has been its
most consistently dynamic element. Many well-known artists got
their start here, including Chakaia Booker, Willie Birch, Leonardo
Drew, David Hammons, Kerry James Marshall, Alison Saar and Nari
Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for extensive physical renovations, started by the
previous director, Kinshasha Holman Conwill, who is now director
emeritus, will go forward more or less as planned, with completion
projected for 2002. They include adding an auditorium, a cafe, a
new 125th Street facade and two galleries for the display of the
permanent collection.
</P>
<P>
   Sims and Golden both point to collection building as a priority.
``The trend of African-Americans getting involved in collecting and
donating art is just starting,'' Sims said, ``so it would behoove
the museum to catch that wave.'' A temporary exhibition of objects
from the holdings will open March 9.
</P>
<P>
   She said she also hoped to attract new audiences, both from the
neighborhood and beyond. The number of visitors annually is now
around 100,000, a fraction of what the Met can pull for one of its
blockbusters. ``There are plenty of people in New York who don't
know we exist,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason Golden is there. ``The first thing I wanted
to do was hire Thelma,'' Sims said. ``I gave her the title of
deputy director of exhibitions and programs because I wanted
programming to be strong. It has a big impact on membership.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden welcomes the role. ``I'm passionate about art and
artists,'' she said, ``and public programs to me are as important
as exhibitions. I'm as interested in music and literature and dance
as I am in the visual arts.'' She envisions the museum as a place
for performances, film screenings, literary readings, publishing
ventures and a historical archive, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also plans to extend the museum's activities into the
diverse neighborhoods that make up Harlem. ``This is an amazing,
complicated community,'' she said. ``It's engaged in a commercial
revitalization, but it still struggles to define itself within the
city around issues of class and race. There are great spaces,
streets that feel like Europe and quirky, abandoned industrial
sites.'' She refers to the area collectively as ``a work of art in
the public realm.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of community was central to the Studio Museum's
origins. Sims and Golden are reappraising it. ``The museum was
founded when the mainstream wasn't paying attention to
African-American art. As an institution, it was a response to that
neglect,'' Sims said. ``Then in the 1980's the mainstream woke up
and started to take notice, so it's time for us to re-examine our
mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden said, ``I think all museums are community based, but how
the community is defined is wide.'' For her, the Studio Museum
belongs to ``the Harlem community, the African-American community,
the art community, the media community, the international
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Both women are considering ways to position the museum more
firmly in an international context. Sims mentions the possibility
of bringing portions of African biennials, such as those in Dakar
and South Africa, to New York.
</P>
<P>
   And both say that the definition of ``African-American artist''
needs to be broadened. Historically, Sims said, the term has been
so politicized that important kinds of art, notably abstraction,
have been overlooked, even disparaged in favor of more politically
specific work.
</P>
<P>
   Golden echoed the thinking of many young artists today when she
said: ``The definition of blackness as it relates to art has
changed and moved around. Exactly how it's changed hasn't quite
landed, though it is certainly a more self-defined category now.''
</P>
<P>
   While the museum's schedule will not fully reflect the thinking
of the new team for a couple of years, a few things have been
settled on. One is a scholarly survey of African-American
abstraction from the 1960s and '70s. Another, for this summer, is
the traveling show titled ``Beads, Body and Soul: Art and Light in
the Yoruba Universe,'' which the Studio Museum will share with the
Museum for African Art in SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the Studio Museum's expanding scope, African-American
art will remain its focus. ``There will always be a need for
institutions like this,'' Golden said, ``because they are special.
Like alternative spaces, they galvanize a certain kind of energy.
Some people might say of me that I've always worked within a museum
context, as if I were at an alternative space.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims added: ``African-American artists who are growing are going
to need to be nurtured. That's essentially what we have to do. And
despite the much-vaunted concept of globalism, I personally feel we
all still need a sense of our uniqueness on this planet, and that's
where a Studio Museum comes in, where people know that their
culture is being promoted and preserved, and where they can always
go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
