<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-RESEARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERIOUS ABOUT RESEARCH, MICROSOFT HAS TIME FOR A GAME
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ When Rick Rashid, Microsoft's vice president
for research, utters, ``Set your phasers to stun,'' he isn't
preparing to launch one of his company's famous take-no-prisoners
assaults on some hapless competitor.
</P>
<P>
   A soft-spoken expert in operating systems design, Rashid joined
the company nine years ago when Microsoft's chief technology
officer, Nathan Myhrvold, set about to create a world-class
advanced research laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   But like many computer hackers, Rashid also happens to be a
passionate ``Star Trek'' devotee and hard-core computer gamer. So
in what little spare time is left to a Microsoft Corp. vice
president, Rashid began more than three years ago to satisfy his
hacker urges by programming an ambitious prototype for a computer
game.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, at its Gamestock event to be held here, Microsoft is
preparing to unveil the fruits of Rashid's hobby, a new ``massively
multiplayer'' Internet game called ``Allegiance.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a pure, unadulterated space-war game with impressive 3-D
graphics and a plot sure to seduce any Trekkie. The game, which
requires a powerful desktop computer, a fast graphics accelerator
card and an Internet connection, can be played simultaneously by
thousands of computer users.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allegiance'' also reveals something about the character of the
research laboratory. The lab was conceived by Microsoft's chairman
and co-founder, Bill Gates, in 1991 as a way to give the company a
competitive edge and to counter the widespread industry view of
Microsoft as an imitator rather than an innovator.
</P>
<P>
   More than just another product, ``Allegiance'' reveals the
freewheeling, uninhibited nature of a research center peopled by a
world-class collection of scientists, engineers and hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Today many of the world's computer laboratories are cutting
budgets and narrowing their focus to research that promises more
immediate product applications and financial payoffs. But Microsoft
Research will grow by as much as 20 percent in the next year, and
part of its work deals with technologies that are not expected to
result in products or profits for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, under Rashid's direction, Microsoft Research embraces
almost the full breadth of computing and software.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a huge amount of flexibility about what we do,'' he
said. Indeed, the lab's projects frequently cross the line between
traditional categories like basic and applied research.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I want to create a small team to do a start-up development
project, then spin them off into the product organization, we can
do that,'' Rashid said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of this freedom, the group has managed to hold
on to its talent. While Microsoft as a whole has a 7.4 percent
worker turnover rate and the rate in Silicon Valley has risen to 15
percent annually, at Microsoft Research, turnover has stayed below
1 percent, an almost unheard-of number for a high technology
research laboratory during the peak of the Internet start-up boom.
</P>
<P>
   The research investment _ in part evident in two new four-story
office buildings full of researchers here on the sprawling
Microsoft campus _ appears to be paying off.
</P>
<P>
   Among computer science researchers, the company is beginning to
win respect for making serious investments in basic research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft Research is very strong in fields such as computer
graphics, databases and operating systems,'' said David Patterson,
a computer science professor at the University of California at
Berkeley. ``It is also clear that they are a formidable competitor
for researchers on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The direction of Microsoft Research has changed little in the
year since Myhrvold, an extroverted physicist, abruptly left
Microsoft on a sabbatical from which people both inside and outside
Microsoft expect he will not return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we miss is Nathan's laughter in the hallways,''
said Rashid, who was at Carnegie Mellon University and already one
of the nation's leading computer scientists when Myhrvold recruited
him in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Although some research here in fields like algorithms and
quantum computing is likely to have no commercial payoff any time
soon, most of the researchers are pursuing projects designed to
nurture Microsoft's increasingly diverse businesses over the next
three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge opportunity to make an impact here,'' said
Daniel Ling, an electrical engineer and former IBM computer
designer who is director of research at Microsoft and Rashid's
second in command.
</P>
<P>
   Ling and Rashid became friends back in the early 1970s, while
freshmen at Stanford University. Now, three decades later, the two
have created a research culture in which experiments can be
transformed into commercial products that will end up in millions
of offices or under Christmas trees. That potential clearly
motivates many of the researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Bahl, an expert in wireless networking who came to
Microsoft from Digital Equipment Corp. several years ago, is
working on a product for expanding wireless data networks into
public places like airports and shopping malls. ``I do see it as
more than a research project,'' he said. ``I have to make people
believe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Allegiance,'' which will soon be running on hundreds of
thousands, perhaps millions of computers, is another example of
that urge to transform projects into products. It also illustrates
the intertwined history of software games and computer research.
</P>
<P>
   While a graduate student at the University of Rochester in the
mid-1970s, Rashid and a fellow student, Gene Ball, wrote one of the
first networked computer games. Known as ``Alto Trek,'' it was
among the first programs written for the Xerox Alto, a
then-revolutionary computer designed at Xerox's legendary Palo Alto
Research Center (PARC).
</P>
<P>
   The University of Rochester, which is near the Xerox campus in
Rochester, was one of the first sites at which the Altos were
installed. In an interview in his cramped Microsoft office, which
is littered with ``Star Trek'' memorabilia, Rashid recalled that
there was just one catch: The machines arrived with no software _
not even an operating system. But they did come with an
experimental version of an early local area network known as
Ethernet, and ``Alto Trek'' was written to take advantage of that
technology to enable players to compete without being in the same
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alto Trek'' quickly became so popular that it would overload
the fledgling network at PARC during lunch time and after work.
</P>
<P>
   Many years later, Rashid dug up an old copy of the program and
decided that he would rewrite it using Microsoft's most advanced
graphics technology, known as DirectX. With Ball, who now works in
Microsoft's user interface group, he added modern PC graphics to
the original program. The results were so impressive that Rashid
was able to persuade Microsoft's game division to finance
development of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Now that ``Allegiance'' is ready for the Internet, Rashid is
turning his full attention once again to other research. But that
doesn't mean an end to science-fiction-inspired passions to take
computer research where no hacker has gone before.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a framed poster that sits unobtrusively on the floor in
a corner of his office sums it up best: ``Everything I need to know
in life I learned in `Star Trek.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
