<SLUG> BC-TV-BROWN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JOHN BROWN': MADMAN OR MARTYR, HE ENDURES AS AN ANTISLAVERY
CHAMPION
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Broadcast notes at end of review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Check local listings.) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the North's abolitionists John Brown was a martyr. To many
Southerners he was a fanatic murderer. ``John Brown's Holy War,''
Monday night's 90-minute account of his committed life and
memorable death, finds justification for both opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Through his years of scraping out a living as a tanner in the
Pennsylvania wilderness and then in Ohio, Brown was an antislavery
man. Fired up by religious zeal, he risked his life guiding black
fugitives across the Ohio River on the Underground Railroad. And he
went further than most abolitionists in sharing family meals with
black guests and calling them ``Mr.'' and ``Mrs.''
</P>
<P>
   Emotional stability, Monday night's historians agree, was not
one of Brown's qualities, but there was never any question about
the force of his faith. He declared, at 37, ``Here before God, in
the presence of these witnesses, I consecrate my life to the
destruction of slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   His pledge found a field of action after the Kansas-Nebraska Act
of 1854, promoted by Southern legislators, gave settlers the right
to decide whether slavery would be allowed in the heretofore free
territories. Five of Brown's sons, all abolitionists, settled in
``bleeding Kansas,'' where the abolitionists were outgunned by
proslavery vigilantes from Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Brown joined his family in the battle from the Brown
homestead, leading a band that killed five men in what became known
as the Pottawatamie Massacre. ``Brown's men split open heads, cut
off arms,'' says Monday night's narrator. A historian calls it
``coldblooded murder.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Northern press Brown became a celebrated guerrilla
fighter, traveling in quest of money and guns and meeting
personages like Ralph Waldo Emerson, Henry David Thoreau and
William Lloyd Garrison. His sympathies, however, were with the more
radical abolitionists, and in 1859 he led a group that included his
sons, fugitive slaves, free blacks and college students in his
famous raid on the federal arsenal at Harper's Ferry in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   He was defeated in a bloody battle, but his fame increased, and
he capitalized on it for the sake of his cause. A historian says,
``He understands, as almost no American does at the time, the value
of the newspapers, the value of propaganda.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he crazy? A biographer sums up: ``He was obsessed; he was
fanatical; he was monomaniacal; he was a zealot and psychologically
unbalanced.'' But the diagnosis ends with a question: ``Does all of
that add up to madness?''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the answer, when his lawyer tried to have him declared
insane, he denounced the idea, martyrdom having far more attraction
than an asylum. Brown was hanged in December 1859, only months
before the outbreak of the Civil War, and the song that
immortalized him goes marching on.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE AMERICAN EXPERIENCE: JOHN BROWN'S HOLY WAR'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Monday night at 9 ET
</P>
<P>
   A Robert Kenner Films production for ``The American
Experience.'' Produced and directed by Robert Kenner; written by
Ken Chowder; Joe Morton, narrator. ``The American Experience'' is
produced by WGBH/Boston. Margaret Drain, executive producer; Mark
Samels, senior producer; David McCullough, series host.
</P>
</TEXT>
