<HEADLINE>
G.E. JOINS EFFORT TO ADVANCE FINANCIAL LITERACY  
 A HOME-GROWN ANSWER ON CELLULAR CHARGES 
`SEINFELD' ACTRESS IN NEW ROLE GIVING ADVICE ONLINE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.J.)  (EDS: Bylines at end of items) 
(rk) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unsure if your financial plan will put your children through
college? Don't really know how a mutual fund works?
</P>
<P>
   General Electric feels your pain. On Tuesday, GE will introduce
the GE Center for Financial Learning, a Web site
(www.financiallearning.com) to battle what GE calls a ``financial
literacy crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   The site will offer advice from an advisory board of outside
experts on subjects like retirement planning and tax management. It
will feature questionnaires that measure consumers' financial
acumen, as well as self-paced courses on investments, mutual funds
and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Americans are in a real state of denial about their own
financial preparedness,'' said Kathleen S. Gurney, one of the 10
unpaid advisers and the president of Financial Psychology in
Sonoma, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The site will have links to GE Web sites, but GE will not sell
or advertise on the site, nor will it market directly to the site's
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   So why do it? ``GE is a household name in appliances, but not
when it comes to financial services,'' said J. David Mahder, chief
marketing officer of GE Financial Assurance, the GE insurance and
investment arm running the site. ``Launching this center will help
us leverage the GE brand.''
</P>
<P>
   The advisers, whose names will appear on the site, are doing
some personal brand tweaking, too. ``GE is a trusted name, and it's
going to help me reach a lot more people,'' Gurney said.
</P>
<P>
   _ CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH
</P>
<P>
   A Home-Grown Answer On Cellular Charges
</P>
<P>
   As the Federal Communications Commission continues to debate
whether users of wireless telephones should have to pay to receive
as well as make calls, IDT Corp. has taken matters into its own
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Hackensack, N.J., IDT is the communications carrier
that pioneered new services including phone calls over the Internet
and call-back _ a service that allows people overseas to slash the
rates they pay for international calls by routing them through the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Without building a wireless network, IDT is now set to introduce
a service that would offer nationwide wireless service while
eliminating the fees cellular customers typically pay for incoming
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all cellular phone subscribers, unlike users of
traditional phones, have to pay when they receive calls. As the
wireless industry trys to become a pervasive competitor to
entrenched local telephone monopolies, it is pressing the FCC to
establish rules that would extend the traditional ``calling party
pays'' billing model into the wireless arena. That would enable
wireless users who sign up for a caller-pays plan to receive calls
free.
</P>
<P>
   But IDT is not waiting. Instead, it has put together a system
that includes a feature that even the major carriers may not have
thought of.
</P>
<P>
   IDT's approach is to buy large lots of cellular subscriptions
from big carriers like AT&AMP;T. But before selling them to consumers,
IDT links the phones to a system of its own making that allows each
phone to have two numbers.
</P>
<P>
   One number has a standard area code, and when a call comes in on
that number, the wireless subscriber is billed as usual for the
incoming call. But each IDT phone also has a toll-free number. When
someone using a normal phone calls the toll-free number, they hear
a message that informs them that they will be charged _ typically
10 cents a minute _ to reach the wireless subscriber, who would
then receive the call without fees.
</P>
<P>
   The two-number system could allow a wireless subscriber to give
the toll-free number to most people while giving the receiver-pays
wireless number to close family members, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   _ SETH SCHIESEL
</P>
<P>
   `Seinfeld' Actress in New Role Giving Advice Online
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there life after `Seinfeld?''' That is the question being
asked on Oracle's e-business network, a new online service
announced earlier this month. The answer can also be found there:
Estelle Harris, the actress who played the character George
Constanza's cranky mother on ``Seinfeld,'' is starting a weekly
computer-advice program on the Oracle network.
</P>
<P>
   The program, called ``Get With It'' and scheduled to begin next
month on Oracle.com, will be a live online talk show, featuring
streaming video of interviews with celebrities and ordinary types.
One program, for example, will include segments filmed on Wall
Street, featuring Harris interviewing technology stock traders.
</P>
<P>
   But the Oracle show is just one part of Harris' new career as a
``forward-looking Internet-savvy senior geek,'' as the Oracle site
describes her.
</P>
<P>
   Harris has also started Estelle Harris Productions, a company
focused on the technology needs of people over 50. And she plans in
April to begin operating an independent Web site, to be called Ask
Estelle (www.stelstar.com). In addition to carrying her own advice
column, the site will be a portal and shopping site with
information and products for older people.
</P>
<P>
   Howard E. Wall, chairman of Estelle Harris Productions in Palm
Springs, Calif., said Harris bought her first home computer just a
year ago and was immediately fascinated.
</P>
<P>
   According to Harris' producers at Oracle, her online program _
unlike ``Seinfeld'' _ will ``not be a show about nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
</TEXT>
