<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIVIC IMPROVEMENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A developer's plan for Pier 45, presented to the San Francisco
Port Commission earlier this month, described the creation of ``San
Francisco at the Wharf.'' This $30.7 million tourist attraction
would include a 1906 ``earthquake theater'' and a ``mock Haight
Ashbury,'' an idea that was brought to the attention of veteran
Haight-Ashbury veteran  &UR; Wavy Gravy &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not go to the regular one?'' he asked. ``It's kind of a
coexistence between the punks and the hippies, a little
cutting-edge U.N. in action.''
</P>
<P>
   Likening the neighborhood to an amusement park is giving it
short shrift, said Gravy. ``They should declare the manhole cover
at the center of Haight and Ashbury as a national monument, &LR; 
because it's a power center, like Stonehenge or the pyramids.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. A passing art lover notes that the terra cotta cherubs on
the Willis Polk-designed building destined to become the Jewish
Museum San Francisco are uncircumcised, a condition that can't be
brought into religious conformance because the building has
landmark status.
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S.  &UR; Ray Vaughn  &LR; reports that the new owners of a South of
Market restaurant spent much time and money having a feng shui
expert plan the interior ``for optimum good vibes,'' but before the
place could open, a car drove straight through the front door.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - The New York Post says that  &UR; Georgette Mosbacher &LR; , former
cosmetics tycoon and former wife of former Commerce Secretary
 &UR; Robert Mosbacher &LR; , is working hard for  &UR; John McCain &LR;  because if he
wins, she wants to be appointed ambassador to France.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Country Joe McDonald &LR;  is cheered to learn that an exploratory
committee has been formed to nominate Green Party candidate  &UR; Al &LR; 
( &UR; Grandpa Munster &LR; ) &UR; Lewis &LR;  in the New York Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   - Walking past a ``The Future of Telecommunications Is Here''
banner hung outside a meeting room in a Berkeley motel,  &UR; Steve &LR; 
 &UR; Finacom &LR;  heard a speaker asking people to turn off their cell
phones so as not to disrupt the seminar.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A SCIENCE REPORT: WHY THE WIND BLOWS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   About a hundred researchers and theorists submitted explanations
for the sudden wind that blows through  &UR; Tom Geller &LR; 's open balcony
door, at the foot of Howard Street, at 5:06 every evening. Because
Personals is a democracy and not a laboratory, majority rules.
</P>
<P>
   The largest group of answers, hereby declared correct, said that
the sudden wind is caused by a change in air pressure that occurs
when the building's ventilation system switches from day to night
mode. ``Probably what is happening,'' opinions  &UR; Aloysius &LR; 
 &UR; Beerheart &LR; , ``is that the air conditioning system is shutting off
at 5:06 p.m. every day. When this happens there is no longer a
positive pressure in the room, which allows the outside air to blow
in through the open door.''
</P>
<P>
   Other readers blamed ``the wind rushing in to fill the void
caused by outrushing employees'' ( &UR; John Joss &LR; ); ``the sudden vacuum
created by the elevators as workers rush to leave'' ( &UR; Hayden
Hicks &LR; ); ``the dust devil caused by many people leaving work to get
into a hellish traffic jam'' ( &UR; Murray Rosenthal &LR; ); ``the first wave
of commuters racing to be first on the Bay Bridge reaching maximum
velocity'' ( &UR; Paula Jones &LR; ); ``all those clock watchers reach ground
floor and push open every lobby door in the city all at once''
( &UR; Dennis Green &LR; ); ``the simultaneous slamming of every car door in
every car in every parking garage'' ( &UR; Basha Hanner &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Matt Regan  &LR; identifies the Tippler Effect, ``that sudden air
disturbance caused by 10,000 postwork martini shakers tossed at
once'';  &UR; Kent Mitchell &LR;  blames the ``San Francisco Sigh'' of relief
as commuters leave (and mentions the matching morning ``moan'');
 &UR; Les Albert &LR;  opines that because the ``moving bodies'' heading for
BART stations and bus stops are on a ``rotating planet, most of
them are turning right to catch their ride home. This sets air
currents in motion that are not random; the air is moved in a
regular pattern that builds up in about six minutes, creating the
Howard Street Mistral'';  &UR; Michael Slaughter &LR;  describes an
``orographic wind'' created by the shape of the landscape of tall
buildings and narrow streets, relating to the hottest time of the
day, 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, taking into account metaphysics: ``It's the ghost of
the '89 quake'' (which happened at 5:06 p.m.), says  &UR; R.P. Delman &LR; ;
the sighs of ``a mass of commuters praying to fit on the 5:06 at
the Embarcadero BART station,'' says  &UR; Brian Knittel &LR; ; ``Tom's
brother  &UR; Uri &LR;  is up to his old tricks again,'' says  &UR; Paul Jaqua &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to dare to suck in order to be great.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Ricky Martin &LR;  in the teen magazine Twist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 1830EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
