A0135 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      02-27 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (lh) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1,  &UR; MONDAY &LR; , Feb. 28. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CALIF (Pasadena, Calif.) _ As the presidential campaign
moves to the biggest states, George W. Bush and John McCain are
battling squarely for the biggest prize of all: California, whose
once-mighty Republican Party propelled Richard Nixon and Ronald
Reagan to the White House but has languished and feuded for much of
the 1990s as President Clinton and the Democrats came to dominate
the state. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BOBJONES (Washington, D.C.) _ Gov. George W. Bush issued a
surprising apology Sunday for any offense he had caused Catholics
or others with his widely assailed visit to Bob Jones University,
expressing his regret both in a letter to Cardinal John O'Connor,
the Roman Catholic archbishop of New York, and at a news conference
in Austin, Texas. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PUERTO-RICANS (New York) _ Being Latino in New York City used
to mean being Puerto Rican. But over the last decade, the number of
Puerto Rican New Yorkers decreased for the first time since they
began arriving in the city in great numbers 60 years ago. Experts
say the decline is destined to continue. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   DIALLO-REACT (New York) _ Rallies, sermons and speeches
addressed the death last year of African immigrant Amadou Diallo
and the acquittal Friday of the four police officers charged in his
shooting. By Eric Lipton.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPLANE-COMFORT (Undated) _ Passengers flying in coach may soon
find they have more room _ if they can get seats. American Airlines
is adding space between coach seats for those paying full fares,
and others, including British Airways and United, are segmenting
economy class into premium coach and true budget service. By David
J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   POTTER-BOOK-BOOM (New York) _ Last year the sales of children's
books soared on the windstream of Harry's Nimbus 2000 flying broom.
Classics like C.S. Lewis' ``Chronicles of Narnia'' experienced an
otherwise inexplicable burst in popularity, as did newer fantasy
titles like Brian Jacques' ``Redwall'' series, which had been
selling well and steadily over the years until Hogwarts magic gave
it a sudden lift. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
</TEXT>
