<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0141 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EMTV-MUPPETS-MEDIA-NY     02-27 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMTV-MUPPETS-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR EM.TV, A MUPPET MISSION ACCOMPLISHED
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Replace double parentheses (()) with brackets) 
(nk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUNICH, Germany _ ``Here, you have to see this,'' insisted
Thomas Haffa, founder of EM.TV and Merchandising AG, as he ordered
the video to be cued.
</P>
<P>
   Three days earlier, Haffa had clinched the biggest deal of his
life: an agreement to buy the Jim Henson Co. and its legendary
Muppets for $680 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on the TV screen, up popped a Muppet in a pin-striped suit.
Produced by Jim Henson more than 20 years ago for a conference at
IBM, the Muppet begins a sonorous speech about corporate values but
soon becomes more fevered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is one word that I want to leave you with today, one
word to guide you in the future, that word is SELL!'' Whipping off
his tie and banging the podium, he embarks on a crescendo that ends
in a frenzied climax of exhortations. ``Sell for motherhood! Sell
for America! Sell for apple pie! Sell your socks off! Whatever else
you do, just get out there and sell, sell, sell, sell!''
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much captures the approach that led to Haffa's
remarkable coup. Though almost unknown outside of Germany, his
11-year-old company has been built on selling just about anything
to do with children's television.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a blitz of deal-making, the 47-year-old Haffa has
become the Magilla Gorilla of children's television. EM.TV now owns
the rights to 28,500 half-hour episodes of shows ranging from ``Tom
&AMP; Jerry'' to ``Teen-age Mutant Ninja Turtles'' and ``The
Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of those rights are limited to German-speaking
countries, while the remainder are global. EM.TV is also a prolific
merchandiser of toys, books and clothing tied to television shows.
And it is an increasingly prolific producer of shows and films in
its own right.
</P>
<P>
   Haffa is part of a new breed of entrepreneurs in Germany. Three
years ago, when small companies were shunned on the German stock
exchange, EM.TV was one of the first companies to go public on
Frankfurt's New Market.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, EM.TV shares have soared 14,000 percent. Adjusted
for splits, shares that began trading at 34 marks, or about $17,
three years ago are worth about 11,000 marks, or $5,482, now.
</P>
<P>
   Haffa and other family members still own about 52 percent of
EM.TV's stock, giving them a collective worth of several billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that rise reflects a new German mania for fast-growing
companies. Indeed, New Market is Europe's most booming market for
new issues.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholder euphoria aside, EM.TV's revenue quintupled in the
first nine months of 1999, to 257 million marks, or about $135
million. Net profit was 162 million marks, 63 percent of sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``The library is huge, and the assets have a very long life,
much longer than feature films,'' Annelie Hoppe, an analyst at
WestLB Panmure in Duesseldorf, said.
</P>
<P>
   In acquiring Henson, EM.TV will own full rights to the Muppets,
from characters like Kermit the Frog and Miss Piggy to movies like
``Muppets From Space'' and TV shows like ``Fraggle Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the best brands in the world,'' Haffa said. ``I
believe there is a huge potential for the revival of the Muppet
characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a salesman for IBM _ where he first saw the Muppet selling
video _ Haffa worked for several years at the Kirch Group for the
German media tycoon Leo Kirch. As with Haffa, Kirch's core success
came from buying German rights to a hugh library of TV programming,
mostly American. But Haffa chose to leave in 1989 and seek his own
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal announced last Monday, EM.TV will pay $680
million, half in cash and half in stock, so the deal could increase
in value as the stock price rises.
</P>
<P>
   ((Shares of EM.TV, which closed at 109.90 euros, or $107.13, the
day the deal was announced, rose to 112 euros on Thursday before
settling at 109.20 on Friday. They had traded from 101 to 104 euros
in the days just before the deal was announced.))
</P>
<P>
   The deal is a significant turning point for the children of Jim
Henson, who have led the company since he died of pneumonia 10
years ago and will continue to run it as a division of EM.TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started this process about six months ago, when we decided
to start looking around for a partner,'' said Brian Henson, Jim
Henson's 36-year-old son, who is chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially we were talking about a minority acquisition, but
being a 50-50 partner or a 60-40 partner doesn't work so well
because you end up not being a high priority for the partner,''
Henson said. ``So after a while we decided to go for a 100 percent
sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Henson already had links to EM.TV, which bought the German
rights to the Muppets years ago. But Henson said Haffa had a gift
for marketing, a Henson company weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the worldwide popularity of the Muppets, not to mention
the annual millions of dollars from merchandising tie-ins, the
company remained small because family members were leery about
tapping capital markets. ``We were very conservative financially,
always keeping a positive cash flow and holding a lot in reserve,''
Henson said. ``It was very hard for a family like ours to take on a
lot of debt.''
</P>
<P>
   In the months before he died, Jim Henson had negotiated a sale
to Walt Disney; Michael D. Eisner, the Disney chairman, even
announced a deal in August 1989. But in the months after Henson's
death in May 1990, the companies could not come to final terms and
his children kept the company independent. While no figure was ever
stated, Disney's offer was thought to have been in the range of
$100 million to $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the EM.TV deal, Brian Henson will be in charge of
creative efforts but hand the job of chief executive to the
company's longtime chief operating officer, Charlie Rivkin. Lisa
Henson, 39, Brian's sister and a longtime movie producer who had
not been part of the Henson Co., will lead its feature-film
business. Cheryl Henson, 38, another sister, will be in charge of
the Children's Television Workshop and the Henson family
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   For Haffa, the deal provides a brand that he hopes will cover
all his products. It also gives him a long-sought platform for
producing material in the United States. Most importantly, it gives
him control of anything to do with Muppets.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Lamprecht, an analyst at Hypovereinsbank Research in
Munich, said he was skeptical about whether EM.TV could keep up
with investors' delirious expectations for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing is story-driven,'' he said. ``The story is
that the management has been constantly able to reel in fantastic
new deals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
