<SLUG> BC-BOEING-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGINEERS REJECT OFFER IN STRIKE AGAINST BOEING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After three fruitless days of discussions with a federal
mediator, talks between the Boeing Co. and its striking engineers
and technical workers broke down on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company's latest offer was a step backward,'' said Charles
Bofferding, the executive director of the Society of Professional
Engineering Employees in Aerospace, which represents 20,683
employees in the talks, at least 17,000 of whom have been on strike
since Feb. 9. Bofferding said that Boeing appeared to be inviting a
long strike by crafting its latest offer with terms it knew the
union would not accept, including a medical benefits provision
little changed from one that had been rejected by 98 percent of its
members.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, in an official statement, characterized its offer as
containing ``significant movement'' and said that the breakdown in
negotiations and likelihood that the strike would continue were
``disheartening.''
</P>
<P>
   The union is seeking bonuses and other benefits that match those
Boeing gave its machinists last year. Boeing's latest offer
included a stock option plan in lieu of the average of $4,400 for
each member the union wanted in bonus money, but the union said the
option package of 100 shares over three years was worth no more
than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another sticking point is the percentage of the proposed annual
increases that is guaranteed to each member. Boeing offered 8
percent, 4.5 percent and 4.5 percent wage increases for engineers
over the next three years and 5.5 percent, 4.5 percent and 4.5
percent for the technical workers, but managers would continue to
have control over how most of the money is allocated among the
groups. An individual technical worker might emerge with an
increase of just 3 percent over the three years while a co-worker
got more than the average.
</P>
<P>
   Both the company and the union have said that they could absorb
a long strike, but both are already feeling the effects. Boeing has
missed delivery dates on several planes, and its stock, which
closed at $37.8125 on Friday, is down nearly 8 percent since the
strike began. Union members might have to begin paying for their
own medical coverage on March 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bofferding said the union would now attempt to talk to industry
analysts, Boeing customers and engineering students at universities
in an effort to increase pressure on the company. ``We will start
what we call `strike plus more','' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
