<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MAUCERI-OPERA-PROFILE     02-27 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAUCERI-OPERA-PROFILE-ART-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EPIC EFFORT REDEEMS A WEILL OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By MERVYN ROTHSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For John Mauceri the path to Kurt Weill's ``Eternal
Road,'' which he is conducting for six performances beginning
Monday night at the Brooklyn Academy of Music, has been long and
winding.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I became music director of the Scottish Opera in Glasgow
about 15 years ago, I asked Kim Kowalke, the president of the Weill
Foundation, what work by Weill needed to be done,'' said Mauceri,
now principal conductor of the Hollywood Bowl Orchestra and the new
music director of the Pittsburgh Opera. ``And he said `The Eternal
Road.'''
</P>
<P>
   Weill (1900-1950) is known as the composer of ``Mack the Knife''
from ``The Threepenny Opera'' and ``September Song'' from
``Knickerbocker Holiday'' and is also remembered on Broadway for
``Street Scene,'' ``Lady in the Dark'' and ``One Touch of Venus.''
But as far as Mauceri knew, ``The Eternal Road'' was little more
than a footnote, an epic opera about the Old Testament and Jewish
history that had long been deemed impossible to produce, because of
its size.
</P>
<P>
   So Kowalke sent over the score, which had largely been written
near Paris after Weill, who was the son of a cantor but was a
nonpracticing Jew, fled Germany and Hitler in 1933. The work had
not been performed since 1937, when it had its only production, at
the Manhattan Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   Lotte Lenya, Weill's wife, was in the cast, as were Sam Jaffe,
an 11-year-old Sidney Lumet and an 8-year-old Dick Van Patten. But
despite critical acclaim, it ran for only 153 performances.
</P>
<P>
   The three-and-a-half-hour production, the largest ever at the
Brooklyn Academy, cost $1 million and is part of the academy's
celebration of the 100th anniversary of Weill's birth on March 2.
The opera has a cast of more than 200 singers and actors, and it
uses an 80-piece orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to play the score,'' Mauceri recalled, sitting in
his office in his Manhattan apartment. ``I knew that Weill's early
style was atonal, what you might call brutalistic. And then he made
a big change in the 1920s, working with Bertolt Brecht on
`Threepenny Opera' and `The Rise and Fall of the City of
Mahagonny.' And later, when he came to America, he worked in a more
popular style with Ira Gershwin and Alan Jay Lerner, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't know what this score would sound like. I started
to play the first page, and the first melody was so overwhelming. I
was unprepared for the way it unfolded and grew, almost like a
time-lapse photograph of a flower, in such an astonishingly
beautiful way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauceri knew that some day he would have to conduct this music,
he said. But despite his reaction, he was not able to persuade
anyone to let him do it. Tentative plans for a production at the
Scottish Opera did not pan out, he said, and talks with the RIAS
Symphony Orchestra (now the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin)
and the Lincoln Center Festival also did not bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mentioned it to almost everybody,'' he said, ``but I
discovered that there was a reticence in dealing with music by
composers who were directly affected by Hitler that was written
after they had to emigrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Germany, Rolf Stiska, who had become the director
of Theater Chemnitz, was also pursuing ``The Eternal Road.'' Stiska
had come upon the work in the 1980s, when he was assistant director
of the Berliner Ensemble, the theater company founded by Brecht.
But what put ``The Eternal Road'' back onstage was the interest
that the city of Chemnitz had in its Jewish past.
</P>
<P>
   An industrial city that was known as Karl-Marx-Stadt when it was
part of East Germany, Chemnitz had decided after reunification that
it owed a debt to the Jews who had been forced to flee or had died
in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1991 the municipal council began holding annual
celebrations of Jewish culture, inviting surviving Jews who had
fled in the '30s to visit, welcoming Jewish settlers from Russia
and the east _ there are now about 300 _ and planning to build a $6
million synagogue. Construction is to begin in March.
</P>
<P>
   Stiska contacted the Weill Foundation, which wanted Mauceri to
conduct ``The Eternal Road.'' Mauceri happily agreed. ``I thought
that for Chemnitz to do `The Eternal Road' was such a beautiful
idea,'' he said. After long negotiations led by Karl-Hans Moeller,
Theater Chemnitz's chief dramaturge, a multinational production was
mounted.
</P>
<P>
   The opera opened in Chemnitz last June and returned in November,
receiving standing ovations at all 12 sold-out performances. It is
a co-production of the Chemnitz Opera (which is part of Theater
Chemnitz), the Brooklyn Academy, the New Israeli Opera of Tel Aviv
and the Opera Krakow of Poland. The director, Michael Heinicke, is
German; the set and costume designer, David Sharir, is Israeli.
</P>
<P>
   The opera, which will be performed in German with English
supertitles, begins in a synagogue in an unnamed city after the
Jews have been told they must leave by sunrise or be killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among those in the synagogue is a 12-year-old boy, the son of
a doctor who is not a practicing Jew,'' Mauceri said. ``The son
asks why this is happening: Why must we be thrown out of our homes?
And the synagogue's rabbi opens the Torah and begins to read the
story of the Jews from the moment of Abraham. And here is where the
music begins.''
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi tells the tales _ Moses, David, Solomon, the prophets,
the destruction of the temple _ which are enacted onstage. ``We
imagine the biblical scenes through the mind of the child,''
Mauceri said. In the end, soldiers force the Jews from the
synagogue, but they feel hope through the promise of a Messiah.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boy finally understands his Jewishness,'' Mauceri said,
``and that the covenant continues forever, that no matter what
happens to the Jews, they will always be the children of God.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The opera was conceived when the American producer Meyer Weisgal
asked the German-Jewish director Max Reinhardt to create a musical
drama based on the Old Testament. Reinhardt asked Weill to compose
the score, and Franz Werfel, an Austrian Jew, to write the German
libretto. The three worked on the project from 1934 to 1936.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Weill had been forced to flee, he decided to use his
musical style for `The Eternal Road' as a means of saying goodbye
to Germany,'' Mauceri said. ``He did so by making reference to the
great German ecclesiastical works. So you're never too far from
Bach or Handel. There are also references to `Don Giovanni,'
Verdi's `Nabucco,' Wagner's `Parsifal,' Schubert lieder, Mahler.''
</P>
<P>
   There are double choruses and fugues, Mauceri said, the kind of
writing not usually associated with Weill. ``And yet it is always
Weill,'' he said. ``There's the African rhythm he loved so much,
the tom-toms, the use of a solo trombone, the quirky orchestration
that becomes his signature. The musical journey is both a
compendium of the past and a fundamentally radiant vision of the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The fundamental question, then, is why, given all this, ``The
Eternal Road'' was not performed in its entirety for nearly 63
years. (A concert version of Acts 3 and 4 was presented in October
1998 at Avery Fisher Hall by Leon Botstein and the American
Symphony Orchestra.)
</P>
<P>
   The answer, Mauceri said, has to do with what he considers a
post-World War II reaction to tonal music composed in the years
before the war, as well as to the postwar work of many emigre
composers, not just Weill but also Erich Korngold, Arnold
Schoenberg, Miklos Rosza and others.
</P>
<P>
   Mauceri, 54, a protege of Leonard Bernstein and a native New
Yorker has been music director of the Washington Opera, the Teatro
Regio in Turin, Italy, and the American Symphony Orchestra, as well
as a conductor for the New York City Opera and a fellow at the
American Academy in Berlin. He has in the last decade studied,
conducted and recorded a great deal of that lushly romantic music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe that for many people it was too painful for
beauty to exist in the rubble of World War II,'' he said. ``Beauty
is seductive and leads to emotion. And one can understand clearly
why emotion could be viewed as a dangerous thing in postwar Europe.
And this vacuum, this chaos, was used to promulgate atonal music,
which would not have in it the memory of that time.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, he said, ``The Eternal Road'' s beginning to get its
due. After Brooklyn it is to be presented at the New Israeli Opera
and the Opera Krakow.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a time of complete loss, Weill found a way, through
acknowledging his own history, to create such a positive work of
art,'' Mauceri said. ``And this beautiful work, which all our
children have been deprived of hearing, is finally being heard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
