<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTON-OPERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINGO'S NEW SEASON: THE ACCENT IS SPANISH
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In announcing next season's schedule at the
Washington Opera, where he is artistic director, Spanish tenor
Placido Domingo let it be known with a smile last week that he had
just realized that six of the eight works were set in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a surprise for me, even `Parsifal,''' Domingo
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parsifal,'' Wagner's quest for the Holy Grail, although
written in German, is set in the monastery at what is now
Montserrat, 30 miles west of Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am amazed how great composers have been inspired by Spain,
particularly Seville,'' Domingo said.
</P>
<P>
   Seville is the location for two related operas on the schedule,
Rossini's ``Barbiere di Siviglia'' and Mozart's ``Nozze di
Figaro.'' Somehow Domingo missed the third Sevillian war horse,
Bizet's ``Carmen.''
</P>
<P>
   Cervantes' ``Don Quixote,'' the classic story of a knight-errant
who journeys around Spain tilting at windmills, is on the schedule
in the form of Massenet's ``Don Quichotte.'' The two other
Spanish-theme operas on the list are by Verdi: ``Il Trovatore'' and
``Don Carlo.''
</P>
<P>
   The non-Spanish works on the Washington Opera schedule next year
are ``The Consul'' by Gian-Carlo Menotti, which is set in an
unnamed but apparently middle-European city, and Puccini's
``Turandot,'' which takes place in China.
</P>
<P>
   Domingo had one other bit of Spanish opera news.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986 he appeared with the Washington Opera in the first
performance of Menotti's ``Goya,'' which Domingo commissioned as
homage to that Spanish artist.
</P>
<P>
   It has not become part of the standard repertory, as he had
hoped, but Domingo said that the Theater an der Wien in Vienna
planned to mount it in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am singing still,'' said the 59-year-old Domingo, ``I
will do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
