<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Agreement on Digital TV Appears Unfinished
</P>
<P>
   Again under threat from the chairman of the Federal
Communications Commission, the cable television and
consumer-electronics industries have said, once again, that they
have solved a vexing problem slowing the transition to digital TV,
how to connect a digital television set to a digital cable box.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue is not fully resolved. Hollywood and the
industries have not decided on a copy-protection standard, making
the whole agreement hollow, some analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Ashes of the Year 2000 Problem
</P>
<P>
   There is still widespread debate on the extent of the threat of
year 2000 computer problems. One clear example of how disruptive
year 2000 could have been, had no one taken precautions, involved a
credit-card payment system made by Cybercash. Some owners of small
businesses that use Cybercash, including Tzu Ming Yang, who owns a
restaurant in Baltimore, did not update their system software and
unwittingly billed their customers day after day for the same
transaction. Because of special rules aimed at discouraging year
2000 litigation passed last year by Congress, lawyers say it will
be spring at the earliest before lawsuits emerge involving the
Cybercash breakdowns or any others.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Contract Talks Break Down
</P>
<P>
   Contract negotiations between Boeing and the union representing
its engineers and technical workers collapsed after three days of
discussions. Both the company and the union have said that they
could absorb a long strike, but both are already feeling the
effects.
</P>
<P>
   New Chip-Making System by IBM
</P>
<P>
   Technologists for IBM will describe details this week of a
next-generation chip-making system it is developing with Nikon that
the company thinks will make it possible in the future to shrink
individual circuits to a size nearly as small as atoms.
</P>
<P>
   Offline Alliances for Online Concerns
</P>
<P>
   A recent deal between Starbucks and the urban delivery service
Kozmo.com _ in which Starbucks will essentially set aside space in
its coffee shops for Kozmo _ may be the first example of an
established retailer offering its floor space and personnel to an
e-commerce company. Industry executives and analysts predict that
such agreements will come rapidly as Internet retailers struggle to
address two glaring vulnerabilities _ customer acquisition costs
and returns _ while continuing to close the gap between virtual and
traditional stores.
</P>
<P>
   The Kermit Connection in Germany
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a blitz of deal-making, Thomas Haffa, founder of EM.TV
and Merchandising of Germany, has become the Magilla Gorilla of
children's television. EM.TV owns the rights to thousands of
episodes of children's shows and is a prolific merchandiser of
toys, books and clothing. But he recently clinched the biggest deal
of his life: the $680 million purchase of the Jim Henson Co. and
its Muppets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
