<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: NEW TESTS FOR CERVICAL CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Md.)  (lb) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Named for its inventor, George Nicholas Papanicolaou, the Pap
smear test has saved millions of women's lives since it was
introduced in the United States in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Pap test, cervical cancer is no longer the
leading cause of death among American women. But although the test
has been improved over the decades, it is not perfect. It can miss
cancerous conditions in 30 percent of women who are at risk for
cancer. And every year it gives false-positive results for 3
million otherwise healthy women who have to undergo the anxiety of
being tested further.
</P>
<P>
   Last week two companies received patents covering new approaches
to cervical-cancer testing. Each company contends that its test
promises to be much more reliable than the traditional Pap smear.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the cytotechnologist who examines a Pap smear _ which
is a scraping of cells from the cervix and vagina _ has to peer
through a microscope, hunting through tens of thousands of plump,
regularly shaped healthy cells that have small nuclei, to find as
few as a dozen misshapen, cancerous or precancerous cells that have
large or irregular nuclei.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, the physical challenge is daunting,'' said Steve
Chubb, chief executive officer of Matritech, a privately held
company based in Newton, Mass. That is, in part, why there is such
a high error rate, according to Chubb.
</P>
<P>
   Matritech, building on research done by two cell biologists at
Massachusetts Institute of Technology in the mid-1980s, has
patented a way to make cancerous and precancerous cells obtained in
a Pap smear either glow in the dark or turn bright red, thus making
them easier for the cytotechnologist to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put the cells on the slide as you would in a normal Pap
smear, but then you incubate the slide with our antibody,'' said
Ying-Jye Wu, Matritech's vice president for product development.
The antibody, called NMP179, which is tagged with a color or
fluorescent probe, latches onto a specific protein within the
abnormal cells.
</P>
<P>
   Acta Cytologica, a journal in the field of cell research,
published in its November-December 1999 issue the results of a
study in which NMP179 was used to to test 261 Pap smears. The test
detected cancerous cells in 96.7 percent of the cases that were
later diagnosed as likely to progress to invasive cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In two other preclinical studies involving atypical Pap smears _
Pap smears that were inconclusive _ the Matritech test was able to
identify 100 percent of the cases in which cancerous as well as
precancerous cells were present.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now it has been impossible to identify which of those
women with atypical specimens are at high risk,'' said Dr. Martha
Hutchinson, director of cytopathology at Women and Infants'
Hospital in Providence, R.I., and one of the authors of the
studies.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, she said, the test may be a cost-effective tool for
figuring out which women with atypical Pap smears actually have
precancerous conditions. Currently, some $3 billion is spent every
year on additional tests for women with atypical Pap smears, even
though few of those women are at risk for cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Digene Corp., a publicly traded company in Gaithersburg, Md.,
uses a different approach with its test.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of looking for cancerous or precancerous cells, it looks
for evidence of certain strains of the human papilloma virus, HPV,
a sexually transmitted virus that has been implicated in virtually
all cases of cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Two studies published last month in The Journal of the American
Medical Association found that the Digene test detected about 84
percent of cancerous and precancerous conditions.
</P>
<P>
   One drawback to the test, however, is that it is not recommended
for use in younger women. That is because HPV is present in a large
number of young sexually active women whose immune systems will
fight off the infection naturally. Thus in young women the test
would yield many false-positive results. It is only when the
infection lingers for a number of years that the cervical cancer
begins to develop.
</P>
<P>
   An advantage of the viral approach, according to Evan Jones,
chairman and chief executive officer of Digene, is that the test
can be combined with tests for chlamydia and other sexually
transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the exciting aspects is that they can all be performed
in a single clinical test,'' Jones said. And the test can be
performed by women themselves, which means that it might be more
readily adopted by women in countries where Pap smears are not
common practice.
</P>
<P>
   So what does the company's latest patent do? ``It allows us to
perform our tests on a gene-chip array,'' Jones said. ``So we can
measure the presence of the genes expressed from multiple HPV
viruses or other cancer-related genes simultaneously, with the same
diagnostic test. It's not necessary for our current generation of
products but will be applied to future tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Wu, Susan K. Keesee, and Robert Obar received patent 6,027,905,
which was assigned to Matritech. Attila T. Lorincz and Abel De La
Rosa received patent 6,027,897, which was assigned to Digene.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, DC 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
