<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0155 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GERMANY-ELECTION-ART-     02-27 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-ELECTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOHL'S PARTY, WOUNDED BY SCANDAL, FALLS IN A STATE ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEL, Germany _ Germany's Christian Democratic Union, punished
for the financial scandal that has engulfed the party and its
former chancellor, Helmut Kohl, crashed to a heavy defeat Sunday by
the governing Social Democrats in an election in the northern state
of Schleswig-Holstein.
</P>
<P>
   The loss for the Christian Democrats amounted to a stunning
turnabout. Just three months ago, opinion polls showed Volker
Ruehe, Kohl's last defense minister and the party's candidate for
premier in Schleswig-Holstein, with a seemingly unassailable 10
percentage point lead over the Social Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But then Kohl admitted taking more than $1 million in secret _
and therefore illegal _ payments from unidentified donors and the
center-right party that had governed Germany for most of the
postwar years went into a tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   For all his insistence that the vote was about conditions in
this state of 2.8 million people, and not about the Christian
Democrats' national woes, Ruehe, 57, could not reverse a slide
accentuated by Kohl's continuing refusal to obey the law and name
his donors.
</P>
<P>
   Reliable projections from German television showed the Social
Democrats gaining 43.3 percent of the vote, an increase of 3.5
percent from the last election here in 1996, and the Christian
Democrats with 34.9 percent, a drop of 2.3 per cent.
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks lit the night sky over this port city as the results
returning the Social Democratic state premier, Heidi Simonis, to
office were announced. She will continue to govern in a coalition
with the Green Party, which took 6.1 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The result amounted to the first concrete confirmation of the
Christian Democrats' electoral plight since the financial scandal
broke late last year. But it also suggested that widespread fears
that the conservative party might disintegrate as Italy's Christian
Democrats did in the 1990s are premature. ``I averted a
catastrophe,'' Ruehe insisted. ``The Christian Democratic party has
at least been stabilized.''
</P>
<P>
   A ``catastrophe'' for the Christian Democrats would have
involved a drop below 30 percent in this state, which has changed
hands many times since World War II and been a useful bellwether of
party political fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   But the evidence that any real ``stabilization'' has been
achieved appeared slender. Ruehe had a clear interest in portraying
the result in the best possible light because he is a candidate to
succeed Wolfgang Schaeuble as leader of the Christian Democratic
party. Schaeuble, who has also admitted taking illegal funds, quit
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even a figure of Ruehe's relative stature could not hurt the
Social Democrats in a state where unemployment has hovered around
10 percent. It is far from clear that the Christian Democrats have
reached the nadir of their travails.
</P>
<P>
   A strong showing by the Free Democrats, Germany's most
market-oriented party, suggested that some voters have migrated to
them from the Christian Democrats. The party's share of the vote
went up to 7.5 percent from 5.7 percent. There was no evidence here
of any migration from the Christian Democrats to far-right parties.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Merkel, the general secretary of the Christian Democrats
and one of Ruehe's chief rivals for the post of party leader, said
the party was disappointed at its loss. But in a show of
magnanimity, she praised her rival for doing better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christian Democrats are coming out of the trough,'' Merkel
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the clearest trend from the election was the
extraordinary revival of the Social Democratic chancellor, Gerhard
Schroeder, whose party lost five state elections last year as he
floundered in his first year in office, prompting widespread
suggestions that he might not survive his four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before the glorious reputation of Kohl, the unifier
of Germany, was tarnished. The former chancellor has said he cannot
break the promise he gave anonymous donors that their identities
would not be revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters have inflicted two black eyes, one on the Christian
Democrats, and one on Ruehe,'' said Franz Muentefering, the general
secretary of the Social Democratic Party, his smug expression
capturing its new-found confidence.
</P>
<P>
   After wavering as to whether his true constituency lay with the
business world, to whom he had promised a slimmed-down state and
lower taxation, or the workers and state employees that have
traditionally provided the backbone of Social Democracy, Schroeder
has acted decisively of late to cut taxes and reform what he has
called ``the German nanny state.''
</P>
<P>
   With the country's attention focused on the gathering problems
of the Christian Democrats, he has been able to do this with
relative impunity, winning votes in the center while reassuring
workers with the message that an invigorated economy will
eventually be good for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Ruehe, sometimes called the Rambo of German politics for his
bruising style, campaigned long and hard in this largely
agricultural state. His ambitions to become chancellor are well
known. Indeed, he once prompted the prickly Kohl to demand his
resignation as defense minister simply for having mentioned that he
might one day aspire to the top job. By the end of his 16-year
chancellorship, Kohl had no patience with any suggestion that his
own rule might one day have to come an end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 1909EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
