<DOCNO> NYT20000227.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDIA-ELECTIONS-ART-6     02-27 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-ELECTIONS-ART-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALLER TURNS OUT BETTER IN STATE ELECTIONS IN INDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Regional parties have humbled both of India's
national parties in state elections whose results became final
Sunday, emphatically reaffirming that the days when a pan-India
party could dominate the nation's politics are dead and gone.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party
was that two of its allies in its governing coalition _ one in the
agriculturally rich northern state of Haryana and another in the
poor eastern state of Orissa _ won thumping victories.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news for the Hindu party, one of India's two national
parties, is that its candidates performed miserably in Haryana and
came in a distant second to its ally in Orissa.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, its allies in Haryana and Orissa may well be
emboldened to demand a bigger role in the national government and a
larger share of patronage for their states.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest shock to the national party came in the most
important contest, in India's second-largest state, Bihar, in the
north. There, every pollster and Hindu party leader had predicted
the downfall of Laloo Prasad Yadav, the shrewd, resilient
politician whose state party has ruled Bihar for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   But Yadav's party has emerged with 123 seats in the state
legislative assembly, one more than Bharatiya Janata and its allies
combined. Neither side has an outright majority in the 324-member
assembly. Bihar, with a population of 100 million, now faces a
bruising contest to see whether Yadav or the alliance led by the
Hindu party can collect enough extra votes from other parties to
form a government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an era of coalition,'' said Prime Minister Atal Behari
Vajpayee, who heads the Bharatiya Janata Party, when talking about
the disappointing results for his party in Bihar. ``We have to
learn the tricks of running a coalition government.''
</P>
<P>
   Yadav faces a raft of corruption charges, and Bihar itself has
one of the most pitiful performances among Indian state economies.
But Yadav was able to hold onto enough of his core constituencies _
Muslims and members of peasant castes and of the formerly
untouchable castes now known as Dalits _ to stay in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Hindu nationalists, who draw most of their support in Bihar
from the upper castes, had allied themselves with Ram Vilas Paswan,
a Dalit leader in a regional party. But Paswan's popularity was
undermined by his association with the upper caste party, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laloo has not delivered economically, but he has been able to
give social respectability to the most depressed sections of the
population,'' said Shaibal Gupta, who heads the Asian Development
Research Institute, based in Bihar's capital, Patna.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee conceded that the results in Bihar were below
expectations. ``We will have to look into why we did not get
expected success,'' he told reporters in the city of Lucknow.
</P>
<P>
   The election results were even worse for the other national
party, the Congress Party, which suffered its worst loss ever in
the national elections five months ago and has clearly failed to
turn the tide since.
</P>
<P>
   The latest defeats are likely to continue to dim the reputation
of the Congress leader, Sonia Gandhi, widow of former Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi and the Italian-born inheritor of the Gandhi
political dynasty. Sonia Gandhi was seen as the party's savior when
she emerged to campaign for the party in the 1998 elections after
years of seclusion following her husband's assassination in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But the results in this set of elections could hardly be more
different from the Congress Party's rousing sweep of state
elections a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Congress Party, which was in power in Orissa,
suffered a crushing defeat to a state party, the Biju Janata Dal.
</P>
<P>
   Gandhi's hand-picked choice for chief minister in Orissa,
Giridhar Gamang, a tribal leader, proved highly unpopular. And the
party itself was widely blamed for mishandling relief efforts after
a horrific cyclone last year that devastated the region and killed
9,500 people.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Haryana and Bihar, Congress remained a marginal factor _ and
may have little choice but to join forces with Yadav in Bihar,
despite Congress' harsh criticism of him, to stop its Hindu
nationalist rival from coming to power there.
</P>
<P>
   As defeat loomed, Gandhi went on the offensive. During the first
days of the parliamentary session on Thursday and Friday, the
Congress Party rallied the opposition in rowdy demonstrations
against a new policy in the Hindu nationalist-governed state of
Gujarat that Gandhi decried as an attack on India's secular
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Shouting slogans and sitting cross-legged on a lawn across from
Parliament House, with a hulking statue of the the independence
leader Mohandas K. Gandhi behind her, the usually shy, reserved
Sonia Gandhi on Thursday attacked the central government for
failing to stop the government in Gujarat from allowing civil
servants to join the Hindu party's parent organization.
</P>
<P>
   That organization, the Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh, known as the
RSS, has portrayed itself as a cultural group, but opposition
leaders maintain that its political agenda is to make Hinduism the
supreme religion of India, threatening the rights of Muslims and
other religious minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Gandhi was back to being her quiet self on the floor of
Parliament on Friday and left the job of speaking to another party
leader, Madhavrao Scindia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ideology of the RSS has spread poison throughout the
length and breadth of this country,'' he said, as Hindu nationalist
members nearly drowned him out with angry shouts.
</P>
<P>
   Gandhi has made no public comment about the party's most recent
losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 1911EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
