<DOCNO> NYT20000227.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0158 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-CITY-MAYOR-NYT     02-27 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CITY-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH, CHEERFUL MAYOR OF MEXICO CITY WINS HEARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The first woman to become mayor of Mexico City,
Rosario Robles Berlanga, liked what she heard from her police chief
over her cellular phone. She snapped it shut and broke into one of
her broad, beaming smiles.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, 2,000 policemen, in a wildcat protest, blocked
several avenues and created a traffic catastrophe downtown. The
rampage started over a bonus the city said it had accidentally
failed to pay, but it continued even after cashiers rushed to the
mutinous precinct to make amends.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of risking violence by sending other policemen against
the rebel officers, Robles simply took to the airwaves to demand
order. The next morning her police chief called to report that she
had won the showdown. At dawn the protesting officers skulked back
to their station, apologizing sheepishly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're hung over and repentant,'' she said triumphantly,
``like bad husbands.''
</P>
<P>
   In the five months since she took over as mayor, Robles has
surprised beleaguered residents of the capital city by convincingly
and cheerfully taking command of one of the largest and most
chaotic metropolises in the world.
</P>
<P>
   She had held the second-highest job in city government since
1997, when Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, Mexico's best-known opposition
politician, won the first election ever held for mayor. Last Sept.
29 Cardenas tapped Robles, his deputy, to complete his term, which
ends next fall, when he stepped down to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   But awkwardly for both Cardenas and his successor, Robles
quickly proved to be spunkier, more efficient and more appealing
than her dour mentor.
</P>
<P>
   As early as Dec. 6, in a survey by the newspaper Reforma, the
city residents who were polled gave her an approval score of 6.6 on
a scale of 10. Cardenas' highest grade in the quarterly polls was
5.5.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of Robles, 44, is part of a boom for women in Mexican
politics. Never before have so many women been in such high places.
In this crucial election year, Amalia Garcia, 48, is president of
Robles' left-of-center Party of the Democratic Revolution. Dulce
Maria Sauri Riancho, also 48, is president of the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party. There are two women in the
cabinet, Foreign Minister Rosario Green, 58, and Environment
Minister Julia Carabias, 46. Maria de los Angeles Moreno, 55, is
president of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Women won suffrage in Mexico in 1955. But in the 1990s, as the
authoritarian country opened up to electoral competition, parties
on all sides began to see that they needed women's votes and
therefore needed women in high-profile positions.
</P>
<P>
   After striving for decades to ascend in the power structure,
many capable women were ready to jump on the opportunities that
finally opened up to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firm government with a soft hand,'' is Robles' motto. She made
her mark with a move that would have been unthinkable just a few
years ago. When President Ernesto Zedillo decided to go on an
official tour of the city for the first time since the opposition
took over, he did not call to invite Robles to come along until the
day before.
</P>
<P>
   So she stood him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the people in the city, who are Mexican women, felt
avenged,'' she said in an interview in the jaunty black jeep in
which the mayor, who hates helicopters, whizzes between speeches
and ceremonies. ``Men are always leaving us in the lurch. This
time, for once, it was the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   She has issued a 10-point code of conduct for the unruly
metropolis. She exercised a kind of maternal authority to ask
citizens to be nicer to one another. Point No. 1: do not
double-park. Previous Mexico City rulers were either too distant or
too corrupt to be able to call on citizens to change their habits.
</P>
<P>
   With Robles, residents were pleased by her confidence that they
could be more civil, although it is too early to tell whether they
will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad government has damaged the city's social fabric,'' she
said. ``There is too much disorder. People are crying out for
rules. The key thing is to arrive at the rules by popular
consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   One challenge was the long student strike at the national
university, whose campus occupies a huge corner of the city. At one
point the strikers decided to march, at rush hour and without a
permit, down the main commuter highway around the capital. In an
afternoon of high drama, Robles sent unarmed mounted police
officers to block the protesters' path, then negotiated on the spot
to persuade them to detour onto a service road instead.
</P>
<P>
   Both major television networks covered the standoff live for
hours. When the students finally agreed to leave the highway
peaceably, the whole city sighed in relief. The strike was finally
ended early this month when the federal police raided the campus.
</P>
<P>
   Political opponents who tangle with the mayor often get bruised.
In January Robles published, with great fanfare, her personal
financial statement and challenged Oscar Espinosa Villareal, the
last appointed mayor from President Zedillo's party, to do the
same. When Espinosa put up a series of conditions to reveal his
holdings, she immediately agreed to all of them. In the end he
retreated into silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my skirt on straight and I accept my
responsibilities,'' she told the press, recasting a classic Mexican
phrase defining macho men as having their pants on straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is bold but not foolhardy,'' said Alfonso Zarate, a
political analyst who lives in Mexico City. ``She is warm, a little
coquettish, but you never doubt for a minute that you are dealing
with a woman of power.''
</P>
<P>
   A self-declared ``woman of the left,'' Robles got her start in
politics as a student radical and her training as a leader of the
tough employees' union at the national university, where she was a
professor of economics. She is married to a college professor she
met two decades ago in the student movement and has one teen-age
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   While she remains devoted to her former boss, Cardenas, she
treads a fine line, trying to boost his presidential campaign with
her strong performance without eclipsing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really I am just harvesting what he planted,'' she said
diplomatically. While it is true that Cardenas devised programs
that have reduced crime and police corruption and improved air
quality, it is Robles' flair for connecting with constituents that
has made them appreciate the gains.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere she goes, when people see her open face topped by
girlish bangs, they drop formalities and call her instinctively by
her first name. At a recent public meeting held in a working-class
borough to discuss her anti-crime programs, women from the audience
flocked to hug and kiss her like a long-lost friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, on every corner where I stop, I see the response of
the women,'' Robles said. ``When we grew up, the faces in the
political photos always belonged to men. Now I send a powerful
message.''
</P>
<P>
   In a megalopolis where politics is often grim and wearing,
Robles gives the impression that she is having the time of her
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it all,'' she said. ``I love being in contact with
people. I love to have an impact on their lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
