<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0167 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-AIRPLANE-COMFORT-ART-     02-27 1458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPLANE-COMFORT-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME AIRLINES REVAMPING THEIR COACH SECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Passengers who fly economy class may soon find the back of the
plane a little more comfortable _ if they can find seats.
</P>
<P>
   In the first widespread change in the passenger cabin since the
creation of business class two decades ago, several large airlines
are now overhauling their coach sections.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to increase profits, but different carriers are
trying far different routes to that end. British Airways and United
Airlines are dividing their coach cabins into two classes _ premium
and economy _ and charging passengers more if they want the extra
legroom of premium. American Airlines, meanwhile, is removing two
rows of seats in coach cabins to give all passengers three more
inches of sprawl space at no extra charge. Only one other carrier,
Virgin Atlantic, offers gradations within coach, having introduced
them several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some passengers are decidedly enthusiastic. ``This extra room in
coach will make a big difference for me,'' said Harry Dodge, a
retired owner of an oil well services company, who is 6 foot 4
inches tall. ``I have taken some transcontinental flights and
developed some painful cramps in my legs. I swore that I would
never fly again.''
</P>
<P>
   But passengers paying rock-bottom fares _ whether keeping the
same legroom, on British Air and United, or getting slightly more,
on American _ will have fewer seats available to them. This will
often lead to more crowded planes _ and more competition for
coveted overhead luggage space.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines are betting that in a booming economy, enough
passengers will be willing to pay more for extra legroom _ 3 to 7
inches, depending on the airline. By creating premium economy
service _ separate from existing business class _ the carriers can
accommodate more business travelers, who buy only 20 percent of all
airline tickets yet account for half the industry's profits. At the
same time, the airlines can rely less on budget passengers, whose
fares are sometimes so low that the carriers lose money on them.
</P>
<P>
   How much more will travelers pay? That could vary widely. On a
United flight from New York to Chicago, for example, an Economy
Plus ticket sells for $1,094 (compared with $1,602 for first
class), while the cheapest economy seat is priced at $324. On
American from New York to Chicago, the lowest fare is $209. But
with fewer coach seats available, that fare is likely to sell out
faster, forcing economy passengers to pay at least 20 percent more
for the next available discount fare.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways said it has yet to finalize the fare structure
for its premium economy cabin, to be called World Traveler Plus.
Some seats will cost 20 percent more than the full-coach fare,
although discounts will be available.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the changes will merely sort out some of the
disparities that are already widespread among coach passengers,
where a business traveler paying, say, $1,000 for a flight might be
seated next to a vacationer paying $200. Often, airlines will give
higher-paying ticket holders more elbow room, but there is no
guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy is risky. If the economy turns sour and
travelers cut back, the carriers will have to slash fares to tempt
them back on board. The airlines making the changes will have fewer
coach seats to sell to generate volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``American's move is a big win for consumers,'' said Samuel
Buttrick, an airline analyst at PaineWebber. ``But it's not a way
to increase profitability. What's good for consumers is not always
good for the airline industry.''
</P>
<P>
   But the changes could work against some travelers. They could
prevent ``backpackers,'' as airlines derisively call bargain
hunters, from finding as many low-cost fares. And budget travelers
may soon find less room for their carry-on luggage, since some
airlines are increasing the baggage weight limit for higher-paying
passengers and that might lead to allowances for bulkier bags.
</P>
<P>
   The move to give coach passengers more legroom _ especially by
American _ has also ignited a nasty spat among the world's largest
carriers. Gordon M. Bethune, chairman and chief executive of
Continental Airlines, said he was looking at the changes at United
and American, but apparently not very seriously. In a recent
interview, he dismissed both carriers' moves as ``fads.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe at Continental in giving people what they will pay
for,'' Bethune said. ``And at the end of the day, many passengers
want to pay the cheapest airfare. There's more to a good product
than a few inches of extra legroom. That's a dumb approach by a
bunch of mediocre airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, United takes exception. ``Every airline is
different,'' said Matthew Triaca, a United spokesman. ``During the
past few years, we have captured a large share of the business
traveler market. They have told us that they want a product that
rewards them when they pay a full fare.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every airline is tinkering with its coach cabin. Delta Air
Lines has said it is ``evaluating various options'' regarding its
economy seats. But many industry consultants said they were unsure
if the trend toward offering more legroom in coach would sweep the
business.
</P>
<P>
   Despite often hostile complaints about cramped seating, some
travelers are not overly concerned. A recent internal Delta survey
of its passengers suggested that most choose their carriers based
on flight schedule, price and frequent flier miles. Few Delta
passengers have asked for more legroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seat size and the quality of meals are way down the list,''
said David S. Stempler, president of the Air Travelers Association,
a Washington-based group for passengers. ``A lack of privacy is an
issue with some passengers. The extra space may help alleviate
that. But some passengers will always go for the cheap fares.''
</P>
<P>
   Airline executives expect the roomier cabin space _ notably from
United, British Air and Virgin Atlantic _ to attract many frequent
travelers. But the biggest market for the seats is among business
travelers, who often pay a lofty full-coach fare and wind up
sitting next to the restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This class of cabin has worked well for us,'' said Richard
Branson, Virgin's chairman. ``Why should someone pay full-coach
fare and get the same exact service as someone who paid $99 for a
ticket? There's no other industry where that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Presser, a New York investment banker, recently sat in
United's Economy Plus cabin on a flight from New York to St. Louis
and immediately became a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``A week earlier, I had paid full-coach fare on a trip to
Chicago, and I had to sit near the back of the plane,'' he said.
``I hated it. But the Economy Plus was surprisingly good. I had
enough room to pull down the tray table and work comfortably on my
computer.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Carriers create extra space in premium economy by removing one
row of seats and then redistributing the space.
</P>
<P>
   American will remove two rows, each taking up 37 inches seatback
to seatback. That is enough for at least three extra inches in each
of the 21 rows of, say, a typical Boeing 737. The $70 million plan
to increase the distance between seats gives economy passengers
more legroom than they have had on any domestic carrier in 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``By having a better product throughout coach, we think that we
will be the first call that discount travelers make,'' said Mike
Gunn, American's executive vice president for marketing and
planning. ``We also expect to attract more business travelers who
are willing to pay a higher-yielding fare.''
</P>
<P>
   Passengers may have to wait several months, though, before
landing a coach seat with more legroom. American plans to convert
half its planes _ including those serving the New York area _ by
June, and the rest by year-end. British Airways will begin premium
economy service between New York and London in August before
expanding it to all its planes within the next 18 months. United
said premium economy should be available on all domestic flights by
mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   When American's refurbishing is complete, it will have 6.4
percent fewer economy seats. United is removing coach seats on all
its domestic fleet, including 5 percent of the economy seats on its
737s. Low fares from, say, New York to London's Heathrow Airport
may also become more difficult to get.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting a cheap seat is kind of a pastime among people who
like to travel,'' said Martha Fay, a free-lance writer in New York
who frequently flies coach. ``Not getting a low fare will make a
difference. If I can't go to California for $250 but have to pay
$400 instead, then I may not take my daughter. Or I may just not
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Bethune, of Continental, concurred with the strategy of trying
to reduce the number of low-fare passengers. He noted that such
travelers tend to file more lost-luggage complaints than
first-class travelers, who can carry on more and whose checked
luggage is often treated more carefully. When an airline has
already lost money on the fare, the last thing it wants is to lose
money on the baggage, too.
</P>
<P>
   Since carriers are fiercely competitive _ moving almost
immediately to match fares and in-flight services _ some airline
executives are concerned they may be forced to realign their coach
seats if more carriers do so.
</P>
<P>
   That possibility riles several industry executives, who are
worried about frequent fliers and employees, who are allowed to fly
free when seats are available.
</P>
<P>
   One high-level executive, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
noted that about 80 percent of frequent fliers on major carriers
fail to get their first-choice flights when trying to redeem miles.
What are the chances of that percentage increasing, the executive
said, if the major carriers have fewer coach seats?
</P>
<P>
   A roomier coach cabin may also be troublesome to airline
employees, who have become accustomed to free air travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to think about your employees' morale,'' Bethune
said. ``Those are your employees' seats that you're taking away.
And if you don't have good employee morale in the airline business,
you don't have anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
