</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-JOSPIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE'S PREMIER UNDER FIRE FOR MIDDLE EAST TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Prime Minister Lionel Jospin of France came close to
celebrating a highly successful first 1,000 days in office Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he awoke to an avalanche of criticism, as journalists
and political analysts here replayed the weekend's events before
examining what most considered to be his biggest political blunder
to date: his trip to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Splattered across the front pages of France's newspapers were
less than flattering images: Jospin running from a mob or huddling
in his car as Palestinian demonstrators kicked it.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Jospin angered the Arab world, departing from
France's usual cautious diplomacy to call acts committed by
Hezbollah guerrillas in Lebanon ``terrorist.'' But back home the
blunder was as much about French politics as about Arab-Israeli
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   France's Middle East policy has traditionally tilted more toward
the Arabs, a stand personified by the shouting match between French
President Jacques Chirac and Israeli security guards when he
visited East Jerusalem in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two years, the Socialist Jospin and the Gaullist
Chirac have been reluctant partners in what the French call
``cohabitation.'' Though they will surely be adversaries in the
next elections in 2002, they have rarely criticized each other
bluntly: Polls show the voters don't like it. Instead, they try to
outmaneuver each other, quietly, to little effect. So far, no doubt
to their mutual frustration, they have nearly the same popularity
ratings, which have risen and fallen together.
</P>
<P>
   In reaching into what has traditionally been Chirac's realm _
foreign policy _ Jospin was no doubt looking to upstage the
president in his own back yard. But last week's incident simply
left Jospin looking rash and clumsy.
</P>
<P>
   Editorialists took him to task for not even informing Chirac of
the line he intended to take, making France look scattered and
inconsistent in foreign policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Sunday was supposed to be the day Lionel Jospin
celebrated his 1,000 days in office,'' one article in Le Journal du
Dimanche said Sunday. ``But catastrophe struck on the 999th day.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said Jospin wanted to ``kill three birds with one
stone'' by pleasing Jewish voters, displaying foreign policy skills
and speaking as frankly abroad as he does at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``On all three points, this was a total failure,'' the newspaper
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, Jospin's blunder was made worse by the fact that
the prime minister began his career as a diplomat and said last
month he could do better than Chirac in foreign policy if he were
not held back by cohabitation, a statement the news media were only
too glad to recall Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, Jospin quickly pulled back from his use of the word
terrorist, substituting acts of war. But it was too late. The rocks
were flying and Chirac was able to look sage, demanding that Jospin
report to him directly as soon as he got home Saturday night.
Jospin retorted that he would not be available until Wednesday. So
Chirac called him.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrations against Jospin did not end when he left Israel.
Sunday, thousands of angry Palestinian students burned French flags
and pictures of the prime minister in Hebron. There were also
demonstrations in the West Bank town of Nablus, where hundreds of
students shouted, ``Down with France, America and Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the debacle, few analysts expect Jospin to stop looking
for ways to undermine Chirac's authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the elections approach, the prime minister will want to be
more present on the international scene,'' wrote Pascal Boniface,
head of the Institute for International and Strategic Relations, in
the Journal du Dimanche. ``The tone will get tougher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 1949EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
