<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0174 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-COUNTDOWN-NYT &LR;      02-27 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-COUNTDOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH OLYMPIC CONSTRUCTION DONE EARLY, SYDNEY TRIES TO REBUILD
SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two hundred days before much of the world turns its attention to
Homebush Bay, the unlikely hub of the next Summer Olympics, there
is only one building crane still in operation on the vast site that
was once a slaughterhouse and then a dumping ground for household
and industrial waste in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The crane looms over the 5-year-old Aquatic Center, where a
construction crew is increasing the seating capacity to 17,500 for
the swimming events that are expected to bring the hosts more
medals and delight than any of the other events when the Games
begin Sept. 15 and run through Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of a water polo complex in Ryde and a
volleyball stadium that has generated resistance from the residents
of Bondi Beach, the rest of the sites are completed. And what is
finished is generally impressive if nowhere near as architecturally
daring as the Opera House with which Sydney is associated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I think they are far ahead of most Games I have
experienced,'' said Dr. Jacques Rogge, the Belgian who is chairman
of the International Olympic Committee's coordination commission
and who has been involved in 14 previous Summer and Winter Games.
``I think never was there such an advancement in the preparation.
Construction is essentially finished six months before the Games;
this has never happened before.''
</P>
<P>
   But the twist in Sydney, a city whose serpentine harbor has
plenty of twists, is that there is already reconstruction work to
be done: reconstruction of public trust, reconstruction of public
enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The really sad thing is that, for a lot of the public, the joy
has gone out of the Games,'' Michael Knight, Olympics minister for
the state government of New South Wales and president of the Sydney
Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games, said in an interview
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more negative now than it was a year ago, and I think it
is going to be very hard to turn that around,'' said John Boultbee,
the director of the Australian Institute of Sport in Canberra,
where many of the country's elite athletes are based.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it particularly difficult is what happened last
October, when it was revealed that most of the tickets for events
with the greatest cachet in Australia were no longer available to
the public. Of the 3.5 million tickets expected to be available to
the public, it turned out that 420,000 had already been set aside
by the budget-conscious organizing committee for clubs and
individuals of means, some of them paying more than face value. And
that was beyond the tens of thousands of tickets traditionally set
aside for sponsors in Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Such a revelation would not have generated big waves in a
country that is as evangelically capitalistic and conditioned to
high ticket prices as the United States. But Australia, despite
significant wealth disparities, still has a strong egalitarian
streak, and the idea that the common people did not have equal
access to the Games in a sports-minded country was a most unpopular
idea _ particularly for the some 250,000 Australians (out of a
population of 19 million) who applied for tickets and received none
and who had not been told of how slim their chances were when the
process began.
</P>
<P>
   Rogge said the organizing committee ``did wrong in not
announcing the premium ticket sales.'' Premium sales were also
organized in Atlanta, he noted, ``but in Atlanta they announced it
and it was not an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Boultbee said: ``The really sad thing, is that it was ready to
turn. The good results in sports and excitement of Australia doing
well last year was about to take over the public attitude when the
ticketing thing, which has been just so much more harmful than any
other thing, came along.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight, the politician who is paid to oversee the organization,
decided in February to transfer a considerable number of the
organizing committee's responsibilities, including the operation of
all sites, to the Olympic Coordination Authority, which has
successfully overseen the construction of $2.03 billion worth of
stadiums and facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The arc of public opinion in Summer Olympic host cities has
become predictable. There is euphoria at the announcement seven
years before the Games, then growing disenchantment as the
construction begins and inconveniences and taxpayer costs increase,
then renewed excitement as the event gets close. Sydney will be no
exception, but the IOC scandal and its fallout, which received
considerable attention here throughout 1999, put a damper on the
usual renewal of enthusiasm and the ticketing problems deadened it
again _ at least until late May when the teen-age sensation Ian
Thorpe and the enormously popular Olympic veterans Kieren Perkins
and Susie O'Neill compete in the Australian Olympic swimming trials
at Homebush Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, 100 days before the Games, the Olympic flame
will arrive in Uluru, the site of Ayers Rock, which is the huge,
red symbol of traditional Aborigine life. The first torch bearer
will be Nova Peris-Kneebone, who in 1996 became the first Aborigine
to win an Olympic gold medal as part of the women's field hockey
team.
</P>
<P>
   Barring protests by Aborigine groups _ who are still debating
how they want to use the global platform of the Games to increase
awareness of their unfortunate past and uneasy present _ the
torch's arrival should lift morale, as well. But what Boultbee and
others worry about is what the public reaction will be if, as is
customary, hundreds of seats are left empty by sponsors and their
guests once the Games begin.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 1953EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000227.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0175 &Cx1f; var-z
u s BC-OLY-COUNTDOWN-2NDTAKE     02-27 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-COUNTDOWN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
Undated: begin.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet for all the grumbling and the loss of Olympic innocence,
there is ample optimism here. Melanie Boyd, a 23-year-old water
polo player who works at the Sutherland Leisure Center where Thorpe
trains in Sydney's southern suburbs, said: ``I think the media here
have taken the negativity further than the public perception. I was
there in Sydney the night we won the Olympics in my school uniform.
I was a private school girl out in the city with all my mates and
we were wearing, `Thank you Sydney' stickers. That memory has stuck
with me. I think when the Olympics get here, a lot of these issues
will seem very small.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogge, who has visited Sydney 12 times in his oversight role,
has a similar, if wider, view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six months before the Games in Los Angeles, we faced a boycott
by the communist countries,'' he said. ``Six months before the
Games in Moscow, we had the Jimmy Carter boycott and ultimately the
United States and a dozen other countries did not participate. Six
months before the Games in Seoul, the situation was very tense with
students protesting in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six months before the Games in Montreal, we still did not know
if we would have an Olympic stadium because there were strikes and
the stadium was not finished. So when you compare that, I'm saying,
frankly speaking, they did a good job in Sydney and the preparation
was almost trouble free.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying in Rogge's good graces over the next 200 days will
require the Sydney organizers to recruit, train and manage 60,000
contracted workers and 40,000 volunteers. It will require
Sydneysiders to abandon the use of their cars en masse temporarily
during the Games to make sure the roads are not clogged. It will
also require technology and security to be essentially bug free.
But Sydney's hardware is there, much of it in Homebush Bay, where
the opening and closing ceremonies and 15 of the 28 sports _
including the main attractions swimming, track and field,
gymnastics and basketball _ will be staged about nine miles west of
Sydney's center.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Homebush is already in use. Earlier this month gymnasts
competed in the test event at the new 20,000-seat Superdome
(Luciano Pavarotti was the opening act last year). For the past
four days, the 110,000-seat Olympic Stadium has been the site of
the Australian track and field championships. One of the champions
was a 15-year-old named Georgie Clarke, who won the women's 1,500
meters. A distant relative of the former Australian star Ron
Clarke, Georgie has run the race in 4 minutes 6.77 seconds and
might not be running quite so fast so young if the 2000 Games were
not there as a carrot.
</P>
<P>
   There are other Australian teen-agers running against the clock
in other sports, and those that make it in time will end up a short
drive from the stadium in the Olympic Village in Newington, which,
with its 513 new houses and 355 new apartments and freshly laid
roads, looks more like Olympic Suburbia. Construction only began
here in May 1998, and there is still a lot of land to scape and
rooms to furnish before the athletes and coaches arrive. The field
where national flags will be raised as delegations arrive is still
a bare mound of earth with a steam shovel resting on it.
</P>
<P>
   But even when the suburbanites move into this ecologically
innovative planned community after it stops playing host to
Olympians, the roads will still bear the names of athletes like
Perkins, O'Neill and the Ethiopian marathoner Abebe Bikila. The
fate of Merlene Ottey Avenue depends on whether the Jamaican
sprinter is exonerated after testing positive for the banned
steroid nandrolone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 1954EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
