<HEADER>
A0177 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-LEITER-NYT &LR;      02-27 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-LEITER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEITER LOOKING TO EXPAND HIS OPTIONS ON THE MOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Al Leiter held the ball in his left hand,
lifted it above his shoulder to signal to Mike Piazza and
minor-league catcher Alan Probst that he was tossing a fastball and
then he unleashed the pitch. But Leiter was not tossing a four-seam
fastball and he was not being the same Leiter that the Mets know so
well.
</P>
<P>
   Under a penetrating sun and on an empty field, Leiter worked on
spotting his sinking fastball on the outside part of the plate.
Leiter grunted as he pumped the two-seam pitch off the corner to
Piazza. The fastballs were on the corner, just off the corner and
then on the corner again, stifling Piazza and making batting
practice seem like pitching practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect,'' Dave Wallace, the pitching coach, said to Leiter.
``Right?''
</P>
<P>
   His forehead glistening with sweat and a cup of water in his
hand, Leiter nodded and said, ``Yeah, perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Leiter's laboratory for the day. Two simulated innings,
60 pitches and most of them were two-seam fastballs or change-ups
designed to nick the outside corner against right-handed hitters.
Leiter already has a nasty cut fastball and a slider that lets him
control the inside part of the plate in powerful fashion, which is
how he has succeeded as a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Leiter reflected on his subpar 1999 season in which he
went 13-12 with a 4.23 earned run average, he decided to refine his
repertory to possibly return to the form he used to go 17-6 with a
2.47 ERA in 1998. While Leiter's cut fastball can be devastating
enough to carry him if his other pitches are average, hitters
adjusted to it last year, and Leiter struggled. Leiter, who is no
longer the Mets' ace because Mike Hampton is two lockers away,
wants to be able to confuse the hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably controlled the inside and outside one out of every
five starts last year,'' Leiter said. ``If you do that three or
four times out of five, you're looking at a 20-game winner.''
</P>
<P>
   So Leiter developed a plan to attack his weaknesses and he
worked on those changes Sunday. He threw a sinking fastball to
Piazza, who fouled it feebly along the right-field line. He tossed
another fastball and Piazza popped it to right field. Then Leiter
surprised Piazza with a cutter on the inner half and Piazza tapped
it weakly to third. Of the five dozen pitches Leiter threw, Probst
said his location was perfect on 56 or 57.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those pitches Mike fouled off looked like strikes, and then
broke out of the zone,'' Probst said. ``The hitter thinks he's
going to get the barrel of the bat on it, and then he hits it off
the end of the bat. That's what Al wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it is early, very early, in spring training. But
manager Bobby Valentine stood behind the backstop like a Little
League father and hollered encouragement to Leiter. At one point,
Valentine turned to reporters and gushed, ``Doesn't he look good?''
The manager praised Leiter for easily ``controlling both sides of
the plate'' and said that Leiter was returning ``to the pitching
mode that made him really successful two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Leiter said that the adjustments to pitching to the
outside corner more often involve repetition and trust. If Leiter
throws 100 pitches, 20 or 25 will be targeted for the outside
corner, but Leiter must believe that he has the two-seam fastball
and change-up in his arsenal. If Leiter has a 1-2 count on a tough
right-handed batter, like Atlanta's Brian Jordan, he does not want
Jordan to be able to expect an inside pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to believe in it,'' Wallace said. ``You can talk all
you want, but he has to really want to do it and execute it.''
</P>
<P>
   After Leiter's work was finished, he asked Probst how much his
two-seamer had darted. Then the last pitcher to start a game for
the Mets in 1999, a game where he gave up five runs to the Braves
and never recorded an out, walked away thinking about how 2000
could have a better ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have something to prove,'' Leiter said. ``I want to show
that the pitcher from two years ago is the type of pitcher I know I
am and can be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
