<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0178 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CUP-CUP_SFCHRON &LR;      02-27 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUP-CUP </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Internet Lands America's Cup  &HT;     By Jim Doyle 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
One of the highlights of the America's Cup races on New Zealand's
Hauraki Gulf is the emergence of a dramatic new Internet technology
that gives viewers a ringside seat on world-class sailboat races.
<P>
   Aided by a sophisticated mix of 3-D animation techniques and
dazzling computer graphics, Virtual Spectator _ a live Internet
sports channel _ represents a step toward the convergence of
broadcast television and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   While previous efforts to track yacht races have relied on
primitive graphics and lengthy transmission delays, Virtual
Spectator places the personal computer user in the catbird's seat
in a fully animated, almost instant re-creation of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Fans are able to select different perspectives of a live an &LR; 
ongoing  &LR; race including a wide-angle aerial view that shows the
boats' positions on the water as well as closer, telescopic views
from alongside the boats and near the turning marks, or buoys.
</P>
<P>
   During the America's Cup cq  &LR; trials, more than 70,000 people in
73 countries used Virtual Spectator to watch the challenger races
between 11 countries from seven nations _ live via the Internet.
Many of these viewers were based in U.S. and European cities where
there was little or no television coverage of the two-hour races.
The live Internet coverage hooked the interest of sailors and
nonsailors alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've created something that's a real-time interactive
experience and people are excited about it. It's actually reaching
a very wide audience of young and old,'' said Craig cq &LR;   &LR; Meek, one
of Virtual Spectator's founders. ``The whole idea is to open up the
sport to not only the farthest corners of the world, but also make
it more understandable.''
</P>
<P>
   The America's Cup match between cup defender Team New Zealand
and Italy's Prada continues this (feb 28 onward)  &LR; week. The Kiwis
now lead 3 to 0 in the best-of-9 series. Software for the America's
Cup match is downloadable for cq  &LR; $9.95 from Virtual Spectator's
Web site ( &LR; www.virtualspectator.com &LR; ) or through Quokkasports'
official America's Cup Web site ( &LR; www.americascup.org) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Spectator is the name of the Auckland, New Zealand,
-based  &LR; company as well as its Web site, technology and product.
</P>
<P>
   The firm has yet to turn a profit. But its yacht racing program
has caught the attention of financiers, Web sites and advertisers
searching for ways to capture the sustained interest of Web
surfers, who typically jump from one site to the next after only a
few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Spectator users watch a three-dimensional, animated
presentation of a sailboat race. The animations are driven by live
performance data that is transmitted from the racecourse by each
competing yacht. The position and relative speeds of each racer is
tracked around the course by small transponders using global
positional technologies. Wind speed and other weather data are is
 &LR; also relayed via the Internet and displayed on the user's computer
screen.
</P>
<P>
   To create the animated, on-screen presentation, the race data
are digitally linked via the Internet to highly - &LR; detailed boat
profiles that have been previously downloaded into the viewer's
personal computer. In addition, fans can replay earlier races on
their computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is revolutionary. It is the first technology to produce a
live animated sporting event,'' said Jay cq  &LR; Snider, who runs a
Philadelphia venture capital firm that recently invested more than
$1 million in Virtual Spectator. ``We've been looking around the
world for new sports technology and, of all places, we found it
here in New Zealand.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Spectator is developing a similar product for major golf
tournaments and also  &LR; experimenting with Internet coverage of motor
sports and soccer. Tests have been conducted on Formula One race
cars and gliders. ``Our biggest challenge now is to find new ways
to track things. Once we have the data, we can do all sorts of
amazing things with it,'' said Meek, adding that technicians are
designing unobtrusive and cost-effective tracking devices.
</P>
<P>
   For horse racing, a tiny transponder may be attached to a
horse's saddle. For track and field, the most effective tracking
device may be a reflector that's sewn into a runner's jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Spectator was created in response to a request by Bruno
Trouble, an organizer of the Louis Vuitton Cup, who asked Meek and
his partners how technology could be used to bring the America's
Cup cq  &LR; challenger series in New Zealand to a global audience.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Meek founded Terabyte Interactive Ltd., an
Auckland multimedia firm that developed CD-ROMs for clients and,
when that market collapsed, established online banking and bill
paying sites. His main partner in Virtual Spectator is Ian Taylor,
who years ago founded Animation Research Ltd., an award-winning
broadcast animation company in Dunedin, New Zealand. Taylor's firm
created most of Virtual Spectator's animated images using Silicon
Graphics computers.
</P>
<P>
   Early subscribers who purchased Virtual Spectator software on
CD-ROM for the America's Cup trials paid $69.95 for the untested
product. In the past four months, the program was used to cover
more than 200 challenger races. Technicians ironed out the
product's glitches and took steps to improve it.
</P>
<P>
   The early version included less-than-live commentary that was
poorly written and crawled across the screen at a snail's pace. It
also failed to clearly display umpires' penalty calls, which
further confused race fans.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the program has been streamlined to be more user friendly.
Umpires' calls are clear and live commentary by experts is
available in English, French, Spanish and Italian. Instead of
translations, the words are written in the commentator's native
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Spectator's creators say they are well positioned for
the next technological revolution: the convergence of digital
television and broadband computer cables that will easily transmit
video as well as high-end graphics.
</P>
<P>
   In the not-too-distant future, viewers will be able to choose
between a spectrum of video and animated images from the same
sporting event and to create their own custom displays. For
example, a fan may decide to follow a race for a while via a
large-scale animated presentation, while displaying live video
images from different camera angles in smaller corners of the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, you're putting people in control of content,'' said
Meek, adding that viewers around the world will be able to select
visuals and expert commentary. In the brave new world, interactive
sports fans will become the homegrown equivalents of ESPN
producers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
