<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0180 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-THINSIDE-THINSIDE_SFC     02-27 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THINSIDE-THINSIDE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Why Thin Computing Is In  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Because thin clients rely on network servers to run programs and
store data, they don't require as much horsepower as a stand-alone
computer.
<P>
   Typically, they have less memory and no drives (hard, floppy, or
CD-ROM) of their own, and since all they do is draw what the user
sees on the screen, a relatively modest and inexpensive
microprocessor is enough to deliver good performance.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, thin clients don't require a standard Windows license.
</P>
<P>
   Stripping out those costs translates into lower prices: Thin
clients typically cost between $350 and $700, depending on the
vendor and the software and hardware configuration. That makes them
a few hundred dollars less than a typical low-end business PC.
</P>
<P>
   Such savings, however, are only a drop in the bucket compared to
what the information technology industry calls the ``total cost of
ownership,'' which includes not only the upfront price of the
hardware, but also the much larger cost of installing, supporting
and updating the machine over time.
</P>
<P>
   It's in this domain, proponents say, that the real value of
thin-client computing lies:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Easy updates &LR; . When every desktop PC has its own software
installed, an upgrade _ whether of the operating system,
applications, drivers or utilities like security and antivirus
programs _ typically requires sending a technician to every desk, a
time-consuming, expensive and intrusive process. (Some large
companies now use special software that automatically upgrades
client machines over the network, but these programs introduce
costs and complexities of their own.)
</P>
<P>
   Since it's often impossible to upgrade everyone at once, large
organizations may face an awkward transition period during which
different versions of key programs are running on various machines.
In the thin-client model, because all key software runs on servers,
only one or a handful of machines needs to be updated. The new
software is immediately available to everyone, and outmoded
versions can't keep rearing their heads.
</P>
<P>
   It's the speed with which software can be upgraded across a
large organization that's turned out to be the most important
benefit of thin-client computing for National Semiconductor,
according to Bob Neuberger, manager of thin-client technology for
the Santa Clara chipmaker's information services group.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least in our industry,'' he said, ``time to market is
critical to profitability, because the first to market gets the
biggest margins,'' he said. ``If engineering or sales has a new
application ready to go, we just can't take months to roll it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Neuberger cited Lotus Notes, the communications
and collaboration software the company runs on. ``We have 7,000
users, and it used to take us three months for every upgrade,'' he
said. ``Now we can do it in four hours.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; No more instant obsolescence &LR; . As every PC owner knows, the
insatiable appetites of software developers render conventional
computers obsolete within a very few years.
</P>
<P>
   That puts users _ from information-technology professionals at
giant corporations to users with a single home PC _ in a bind:
either stick with aging software, foregoing the presumed benefits
of the latest releases, or face the hassle and expense of frequent
hardware upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   The thin-client model breaks this cycle. Since the desktop
machine has to manage only the user interface, a relatively modest
task, a thin client should last for many years, even across
multiple generations of software.
</P>
<P>
   This was the key element in recent decisions to move to thin
clients at two Bay Area organizations. Contra Costa County's IT
managers were asked to install new PeopleSoft applications on 360
desktops, but got no budget for the beefed-up PCs many of them
would have required, according to Steve Kaplan, president of Ryno
Technology, an integration company based in Benicia, that was hired
to help with the project. In the case of ABM Industries, according
to Anthony Lackey, chief technical officer of the San Francisco
company, there were two main ``drivers for change.'' One was the
Y2K problem, which required replacing roughly half of the company's
2,500 PCs. The other was a new corporate accounting package the
company had selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a PC it requires 128 megabytes of RAM and a 500-megahertz
Pentium,'' Lackey said. ``Only about a dozen of our PCs met that
requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, running the software on PCs would have
increased the burden on the communications network connecting the
company's 210 offices. ``We would have needed much bigger pipes _
by a factor of six, compared to what we ended up with for the thin
clients,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a company's servers often need to be upgraded or
replaced as more demanding software is introduced, but that's a
more manageable problem: Servers generally are more expandable than
desktop PCs, with room for extra memory, storage and processors.
And even when all-new hardware is required, only one or a few
servers need to be replaced, compared to scores or hundreds of
client PCs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; High reliability &LR; . Thin-client users can't fiddle with
configuration settings and have no way to introduce unauthorized
programs such as games and screensavers, not to mention viruses.
Since the servers are managed and monitored by professionals,
they're presumably far less susceptible to such problems. That
means lower support costs and less downtime.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, notes analyst Dan Kusnetsky of International Data
Corp., thin-client computing works like the telephone system: ``You
turn it on, it works. Enhancements and new services happen out on
the network, so you don't usually need new hardware on your end to
take advantage of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, thin-client computing isn't without downsides. The
biggest is that it makes an organization totally dependent on the
reliability of its servers and its network _ without them, thin
clients are useless.
</P>
<P>
   Thin clients also lack the flexibility of PCs: You can't just
plug in a scanner, for example, when an employee gets a new
assignment that requires one. And in a general sense server-based
computing eliminates much of the ``personal'' in personal
computing.
</P>
<P>
   For managers like National Semi's Neuberger, that's a plus, not
a minus. But some users may resent losing the freedom to install
digital pictures of their kids or the latest MP3 player.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely some re-education needed,'' Neuberger said,
``but most users get over it pretty quickly. After all, they can
see how big the benefits are, both for the organization and for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
