<SLUG> BC-FN-JETS-PASSRUSHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS SEEK A PASS-RUSHER IN THE DRAFT AND INEXPENSIVE FREE AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Searching for a pass-rusher _ the New York Jets have not had a
defensive lineman with more than 10 sacks since 1990 _ the club's
scouting brain trust and assistant coaches finished poking the
country's best collegians Sunday as the annual combine in
Indianapolis ended.
</P>
<P>
   Now the energies of the rest of the Jets' personnel staff will
be turned to free agency, as well as the college draft on April 15.
</P>
<P>
   Because the combine gave the Jets their first opportunity to
measure the collegians up close, the team made no significant
free-agent moves last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jets have not been proactive in free agency,'' said one
agent who has had long-time dealings with Bill Parcells. ``They
have been reactive.''
</P>
<P>
   Another agent said that his client, a tight end, got some early
interest from the Jets but has not heard from the team for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have a money problem _ and they want to see who
they can get cheap,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are about $1 million under the salary cap. The money
for the draft comes under a separate pool, however, and thus the
Jets will be able to afford to sign collegians, but not high-priced
free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets in recent years disguised their lack of a pass rush by
coming up with creative defensive schemes from Bill Belichick.
Belichick will now try to be as innovative as the Patriots new head
coach. And because the Jets are shifting to a 3-4 defense under
their new coach Al Groh, they would love to have a pass-rusher.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' veteran defensive linemen _ built around the
run-stopping nose tackle Jason Ferguson _ are the workmanlike
Anthony Pleasant, Rick Lyle, Ernie Logan and Bobby Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   As a unit, the Jets' defensive line had only nine sacks.
</P>
<P>
   One pass-rusher who might be available when the Jets pick at No.
16 in the draft is Shaun Ellis of Tennessee. He is 6 feet 4 inches,
weighs 260 pounds and is expected to run the 40-yard dash in 5
seconds flat.
</P>
<P>
   But they also need a tight end, someone who can snare more than
the 7 passes caught by Eric Green last season.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Jets have two first-round picks in the draft.
They have not had a first-round choice since 1997. But now, with
the 16th pick they received from New England for signing Belichick,
and their own No. 18, the Jets could get an impact player by
packaging the choices. In addition to Ellis, the other big ``need''
player available could be tight end Bubba Franks, the 6-5,
245-pounder from Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Jets are not talking about what they looked for
at the combine. Groh has maintained Parcells' policy of forbidding
his assistants to talk to the news media. Parcells, who remains as
chief of the club's football operations, has declined to discuss
free agency or the draft.
</P>
<P>
   But Dick Haley _ who was also in Indianapolis _ remains the
draft director, although Groh has been given final say on
personnel. As collegians were tested by position, the Jets'
assistants watched their specialty. Ray Hamilton, the new defensive
line coach, watched the pass-rushers; Ken Whisenhunt, the new tight
ends coach, assessed players at that position.
</P>
<P>
   These are not the only two positions the Jets are interested in
filling. They still are on the lookout for a speedy receiver, and
there will be interest in an offensive lineman as well as a
defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Jets have closely guarded the injury update of almost
a dozen players who had surgery in the past year, including four
starters whose 1999 seasons ended because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets do say, through a spokesman, that each player's
rehabilitation is on schedule. But it is difficult to discern how
big a part injuries will play in what the Jets do at the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Their investigations over the past few days focused on possible
replacements for the cadre of sidelined Jets. And that search will
continue during free agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
