<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Monday, Feb. 28 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Dennis Liff at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   RAMPART-PEREZ (Los Angeles) _ Rafael Perez's downfall _ and the
scandal that has erupted around it _ came about because of another
Perez. When Rafael Perez didn't return eight pounds of cocaine he
checked out of an LAPD evidence room, the paperwork went back to a
different officer Perez, who started an investigation to determine
who really had the cocaine. By Greg Gittrich and Beth Barrett.
(Will move in the ``a'' national news and ``n'' California news
files.)
</P>
<P>
   BACTERIA-RESIST (Los Angeles) _ A 70-year-old man was treated
with the usual antibiotics for an earache, but returned a week
later with a nagging infection that had attacked his heart and
pushed him near death. What doctors thought was a routine germ
actually was resistant to the usual antibiotics, leaving doctors no
choice but to use their third, last-best drug. He lived, an example
of a growing number of people contracting drug-resistant
infections. By Robert Monroe. (Will move in the ``a'' national news
and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   MORNING-SHOWS (Los Angeles) _ Morning is the only time period
where network TV viewership is expanding. Competition in that
lucrative 7 to 9 a.m. time shot is heating up. By David Kronke.
(Will move in the ``a'' national news and ``n'' California news
files.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 1957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
