<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0184 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-COOLNEWS-COOLNEWS_SFC     02-27 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOLNEWS-COOLNEWS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Ain't It Cool Ain't News But It's Fun  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Let's start with what Harry Knowles is not.
<P>
   He says he isn't a journalist, although his Web site, Ain't It
Cool News, is a leading online source for Hollywood dirt and
behind-the-scenes movie doings.
</P>
<P>
   He says he isn't a film critic, although he reviews just about
every new movie released and runs separate reviews by a stable of
other film buffs.
</P>
<P>
   So what is he?
</P>
<P>
   ``I call myself a `film advocate,''' he said the other day
before presenting a sneak preview of the new Ridley Scott movie
``Gladiator'' at the Metreon theaters in downtown San Francisco.
``I'm looking for good films and trying to help films get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Others might call Knowles, who runs Ain't It Cool News
(www.aint-it-cool-news.com) out of his house in Austin, Texas, the
ultimate Internet movie geek _ a guy who has managed to combine a
lifelong passion for film with technology that allows him to share
his interest with a global audience.
</P>
<P>
   And share he does. Knowles estimates that he spends as much as
16 hours every day cranking out his thoughts on just about anything
from the movie world that strikes his fancy. Much to the
consternation of studio executives, he also posts advance peeks at
test screenings throughout the country and glimpses of screenplays
in progress.
</P>
<P>
   His site, with about 500,000 daily hits, has more readers than
Variety and the Hollywood Reporter combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Knowles was one of the first to embrace the tools of the
Internet,'' said Jonathan Taylor, executive editor of Variety. ``He
has gone from being perceived as a pirate or a scalawag to almost
being part of the establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Taylor noted, Knowles is courted by the major studios
and invited to screenings. ``The strategy seems to be that if you
can't beat him, seduce him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Knowles' muscle was made clear in July 1997 when 20th Century
Fox held a test screening at the Mall of America in Minneapolis for
``Titanic,'' which at the time was foundering amid icebergs of bad
prerelease pre-release  &LR; buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Ain't It Cool News had spies at the screening, and their
subsequent raves online have been credited &UR;  &LR; with turning around the
film's prospects and helping it become the highest-grossing movie
of all time.
</P>
<P>
   However, the danger of Knowles' shoot-from-the-hip,
no-experience-required style was illustrated a couple of weeks ago
when he and an accomplice hacked into a computer they thought
contained a preannouncement list of Oscar nominees. The list, which
he posted on his site, turned out to be bogus.
</P>
<P>
   Knowles, 28, insists he's just another fan with just another Web
site. Ain't It Cool News, he said, ``is a nontraditional
non-traditional  &LR; look at the film business through the eyes of
someone who wants it to be better than it is.''
</P>
<P>
   But Knowles isn't just another fan. He's a guy who has appeared
with Roger Ebert on the latter's syndicated movie-review program,
has a book in the works and is developing a TV talk show he
describes as ```Wayne's World' meets `Entertainment Tonight.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Knowles keeps infiltrating test screenings and
passing along tidbits from a network of pseudonymous contributors
within and without the film business.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really infuriated a lot of people in the industry,'' said
Paula Parisi, who covers technology for the Hollywood Reporter.
``There are some studios that forbid their people to have anything
to do with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she thinks Knowles is a positive influence as well as a
thorn in the side of moviemaking. ``He brings a fresh perspective
to covering the entertainment industry,'' she said. ``It's
something the industry has been needing.''
</P>
<P>
   In person, Knowles can charitably be said to make a striking
impression. With a mane of shaggy red hair and a bushy red beard,
he was dressed for the Metreon screening all in brown, accented by
a bright green tie and fluorescent green shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Consistent with his self-styled image as the consummate Net
nerd, Knowles is hopelessly out of shape, and he carries his
300-plus pounds with the slow, rolling gait of a guy who seldom
gets out of the house _ which is, of course, precisely the case.
</P>
<P>
   Knowles by now has become so practiced at telling his story that
the anecdotes spill out in media-friendly sound bites. He tells of
the childhood in Texas hawking movie memorabilia with his father,
the failed stab at a college education, the accident that left him
bedridden for several months.
</P>
<P>
   He tells how Ain't It Cool News, named after a line from the
John Travolta movie ``Broken Arrow,'' was launched in early 1996 as
a way to continue selling movie trinkets online.
</P>
<P>
   Knowles got his first real taste of Internet publishing when he
spent a couple of months contributing movie snippets to Matt
Drudge, the online political columnist. ``He told me I could never
make a name for myself covering entertainment news,'' Knowles
recalled with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for movie buffs to stumble across Knowles'
Ain't It Cool News and to respond to his quirky, highly opinionated
reviews, which often read more like a diary entry than an
exploration of cinematic trends.
</P>
<P>
   Soon came the test-screening spy reports and insider views, and
Knowles' following really took off. Hollywood studios started
paying more attention when blistering early reviews of ``Batman and
Robin'' at Ain't It Cool News all but murdered the film prior to
its release.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press was saying that this was the death of Hollywood,''
Knowles said of his initial infamy. ``But I wasn't out to destroy
anything. I was like the character in `Network' who was mad as hell
and not going to take it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   His stature has since risen to the point where he can now call a
major studio and request a special screening of an unreleased film,
as was the case with his arranging a showing of Dreamworks'
``Gladiator.'' The movie is not slated to hit theaters until May.
</P>
<P>
   Knowles gave away tickets through his site and had no trouble
packing the theater with adoring fans. He told them before the
lights dimmed that ``this movie is going to kick your ass pretty
hard,'' and they loudly clapped their appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   (``Gladiator'' turned out be violent, unpleasant and largely
pointless, but Knowles subsequently pronounced it a great film, and
there can be little doubt that Ain't It Cool News will deliver the
crowds when it finally opens.)
</P>
<P>
   Knowles recognizes that, more than anything else, it's an
accident of good timing that he is where he is today _ and he
freely admits that he's grateful to have been among the first geeks
to get a movie site up and running on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where would I be without the Internet?'' he mused. ``I'd
probably still be selling movie posters at garage sales.''
</P>
<P>
   And the funny thing is, he'd probably be just as happy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail David Lazarus at davidlaz &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
