<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-BIOSCOPE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOSCOPE/TOM ABATE 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Boom in Biotech Stocks Brings Back Memories of Bubbles Past 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
All of a sudden the world seemed bio-crazy. Biotech stocks doubled
and tripled in a matter of months, fueled by media hype of medical
discoveries on the horizon. Biotech ruled Wall Street, temporarily
outshining high tech.
<P>
   That was in 1991, the last time biotechnology experienced
anything like the market frenzy it is enjoying today.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, by spring 1992, the bubble had  &LR; burst, plunging biotech
into a swoon from which it only fully recovered last July, when the
American Stock Exchange's ``BTK'' biotech index finally surpassed
the level it achieved in January 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, as biotech shares tripled, the question arose:
Could biotech crash again?
</P>
<P>
   No, never, not a chance, biotech industry observers say. The
industry is far more mature today than in 1991, and though some
correction seems inevitable, it won't be as severe as the '92 crash
_ which wiped out more than half the value of many biotech shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prices may come down 10 percent, but not 50 percent,''
predicted Steve Burrill, who runs his own biotech investment bank
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Burrill said the combined market capitalization of all 400 or so
biotech firms is only twice as large as one pharmaceutical giant,
Merck.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could buy this whole industry for what you could buy two
Mercks for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt von Emster, manager of the Franklin Biotechnology Discovery
Fund in San Mateo, said biotech has dozens of products poised to
come on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still in the first leg of a biotech rally which we
expect will last another decade,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, given the sudden euphoria over biotech, it seems wise to
compare this boom to the bubbles of past.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Dietz, biotech investment banker with Pacific Growth
Equities in San Francisco, said this rally began last fall, as the
success of the Genentech public offering, coupled with media
fascination with the Human Genome Project, began to focus attention
on a sector Wall Street had long ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Genomics _ the study of how genes control disease and
development _ was seen as a new era in drug discovery. Investors
bid up shares in companies like Celera, Incyte and others that were
discovering and patenting genes. The genomics fad emboldened Bay
Area firms _ Tularik, Caliper Technologies and Maxygen _ to test
Wall Street's appetite for biotech IPOs. Tired of dot-coms, Wall
Street bit. By January 2000 it was official _ biotech was hot.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics are stunning. The BTK index started at 200 in
October 1991 and peaked at 223.92 in January 1992. After sinking as
low as 77.56 in March 1995, the index took seven years to get back
to its starting point.
</P>
<P>
   But since May 1999, the BTK has gained an astonishing 460
points. It closed at 664 on Friday. In percentage terms, the BTK
has gained 487 percent over the last 52 weeks. In January and
February alone it has gained 273 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Rising share prices have meant jaw-dropping gains for biotech
mutual funds. Von Emster's Franklin fund is up almost 70 percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Performances like that attract money. Robert Adler, president of
AMG Services, which tracks the flow of money in and out of mutual
funds, said $800 million a week has poured into biotech mutuals
since mid-January. That's four times higher than anything he's ever
measured in biotech. Every week, the sheer inflow of money adds
about 2.5 percent to the amount of mutual fund money chasing
biotech stocks.
</P>
<P>
   What happens when more money chases a product in limited supply?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes investor demand overtakes performance and starts to
create the upward pressure on prices,'' Adler said. ``There's no
question some of that is happening now.''
</P>
<P>
   Biotech is doing its bit to add more stock to the market. In
January and February, 20 firms filed IPOs. That matches the number
of biotech firms that went public in 1998 and 1999 combined,
according to the IPO Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech has had booms before, but nothing like this.
</P>
<P>
   Hollings Renton, chief executive of Onyx Pharmaceuticals and a
20-year industry veteran, experienced the periods in 1980, 1984 and
1987, when biotech first seized the imagination of Wall Street and
the general public. The early booms, notably the one precipitated
by Genentech's 1980 IPO, were fueled almost exclusively on
promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1980s, biotech had almost no products,'' Renton said.
</P>
<P>
   That had changed by 1991, when biotech experienced its next _
and until now _ biggest surge of popularity in the press and on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Richard van den Broek, biotech analyst with Chase H&AMP;Q in New
York, said Amgen triggered the '91 boom with a one-two punch that
got Wall Street's attention. First Amgen won a patent battle that
secured its control over the anemia drug EPO. Then it won approval
to sell Neupogen, to prevent infection in people undergoing
chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market went nuts,'' van den Broek recalled. ``Everybody
was going to be the next Amgen.''
</P>
<P>
   In this atmosphere of euphoria, in October 1991, the BTK index
began with a base value of 200. It was comprised of 15 companies
that mirrored the performance of the entire industry. Some, like
Amgen, Chiron, Biogen and Immunex, are still there. Others have
gone away and been replaced.
</P>
<P>
   But the index faithfully recorded the crash that occurred in
1992, after several biotech firms failed to win approval for drugs
to control sepsis, an infectious disease. Investors lost faith in
the biotech miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was at least a three-year, grinding bear market for
biotechs in the midst of a bull market elsewhere,'' van den Broek
said.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting rock bottom in March 1995, biotech experienced
another brief revival. Scott Morrison, biotech consultant with
Ernst &AMP; Young in Palo Alto, said the '95 rally came after
Republicans in Congress killed the Clinton health plan, easing
industry fears of drug price controls.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area biotech firms like Gilead Sciences seized the chance to
go public. But the '95 rally was weak, and the BTK never got above
160 _ still shy of its 1991 starting point.
</P>
<P>
   The index was still bumping along at 200 in July 1999, when
fickle Wall Street started a new infatuation with biotech.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear what happened between July and today to triple
the value of biotech. Yes, firms have dozens of products in
late-stage clinical trials, and many will be blockbusters. But the
potential products aren't three times more valuable than they were
a few months ago. Biotech promoters will tell you that three months
ago the stocks were severely depressed and now they are properly
valued.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, our growing knowledge of human genes will ultimately
lead to new medicines. But even if scientists today discovered the
genes for stupidity and greed _ two factors in the current boom _
it would be a decade before they got a pill approved by the Food
and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Long before then Wall Street will prick this bubble. It's not a
question of whether, but rather when and how severe the ensuing
fall will be.
</P>
<P>
   Past biotech windows have lasted six to nine months. This one
started in October and accelerated in January.
</P>
<P>
   As for the severity of the fall, it is hard to envision a crash
as severe as in '92. Biotech's fundamentals are stronger than ever.
Biotech companies had $20 billion in sales in 1998 and currently
have more than 300 prospective drugs undergoing Phase II or III
clinical trials. Some will eventually win approval by the Food and
Drug Administration and lead to future sales.
</P>
<P>
   But the forces that have killed past booms continue to lurk in
the background. Drug price controls are being whispered about
again. A product flop or two, and who can predict what will happen.
</P>
<P>
   One thing we can probably count on is market overreaction. The
market overreacted by shunning biotech for seven years. It is
probably overreacting to biotech's promise now.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope the market discovers moderation when investors
realize that the payoff from genomics and today's other hot biotech
buzz words could be a decade away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Look for BioScope every Monday in the Business section. Send
your bio-feedback to Tom Abate by e-mail, abate &LR; sfgate.com; fax,
(415) 543-2482; or phone, (415) 777-6213.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
