<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0187 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-THIN-THIN_SFCHRON &LR;      02-27 1712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIN-THIN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 The NC _ With a Twist  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
As even a casual technology watcher can tell you, the NC, or
``network computer,'' was a big-time bust. What's not so widely
known is that an increasing number of major companies, including
many in the Bay Area, have enthusiastically adopted a variation on
the idea.
<P>
   The ungainly name for this new technology _ ``thin-client
computing'' _ is hardly a household word, even in Silicon Valley.
But for information-technology managers at many large
organizations, it's shaping up as the Next Big Thing.
</P>
<P>
   The NC, you may recall, was a concept introduced in 1996 by
Oracle CEO Larry Ellison, then taken up by Sun Microsystems' chief
Scott McNealy and other Silicon Valley bigwigs and pundits. The
idea was to replace the conventional PC, with all its cost and
complexity, with a cheap and simple terminal running a Web browser
and small applications downloaded as needed from high-powered
network servers.
</P>
<P>
   The idea resonated with tech managers tired of the high price
and constant hassle of upgrading and supporting PCs, and it
generated an enormous amount of discussion in high-tech circles.
Sun, IBM and other hardware makers began to produce NCs.
</P>
<P>
   There was just one problem: Hardly anyone bought them.
</P>
<P>
   In large part, that was because Ellison et al. made the NC part
of a crusade against Microsoft. Gripes about the software
behemoth's products and policies aren't uncommon among its
corporate customers, but few were prepared to abandon
well-established standards like Microsoft Office.
</P>
<P>
   That was especially true because the alternative _ miniprograms
written in Sun's Java language _ didn't even exist yet, and
developers who tried to create them found the going tougher than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Thin-client computing, however, promises most of the benefits of
the NC, without forcing customers to abandon Windows. And the new
idea even has Microsoft's support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thin'' refers to the fact that these machines lack many of the
hardware features of conventional PCs. They get by with less RAM
and slower processors because they rely on high-powered network
servers to do most of the work _ that's why they're called
``clients'' of the server. They don't have their own drives,
because applications and user data are stored on the server. And
they don't have expansion slots or most of the ports PCs do,
because the whole point is simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   For now, thin clients represent barely a ripple compared to the
PC tide. According to preliminary estimates by International Data
Corp., worldwide thin-client sales for 1999 amounted to about
700,000 units; for PCs the total was about 113 million. But 700,000
represents an increase of nearly 90 percent from thin-client
volumes in 1998, and Eileen O'Brien, director of the enterprise
thin-client program at IDC, projects that sales will nearly double
again this year and hit 6 million by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Amazon.com reportedly runs on thin clients, although
company officials won't confirm that fact. Parts of Coca-Cola and
Kodak do too, and FedEx is estimated to have 10,000 such machines.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, the latest thin-client convert is San
Francisco's ABM Industries. Founded in 1909 as a one-man
window-washing business, it now consists of nine operating
companies and 55,000 employees who provide engineering, janitorial,
parking and security services. ABM's 2,400 white-collar employees,
working at 210 offices nationwide, used to have conventional PCs,
but in recent months they've instead received new thin-client
systems.
</P>
<P>
   The transition has presented some challenges, according to
Anthony Lackey, the 36-year-old exec who's supervised the project,
but on the whole it looks like a big success. Because of it, he
estimates, ABM will see ``hard savings'' of $19 million over five
years, and the benefit will be much greater when you factor in
``soft savings'' _ like increased productivity because employees
will waste less time fiddling with computer settings, recovering
from crashes and resolving version conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the project's success, Lackey was just promoted from
assistant vice president to vice president of MIS and from director
to chief technical officer.
</P>
<P>
   National Semiconductor, the Santa Clara chipmaker, has been
moving in the thin-client direction since 1997, according to Bob
Neuberger, manager for thin-client technology. Today the company's
7,400 desktop computers, he said, include almost 700 thin clients,
plus a much larger number of PCs configured to run in client mode.
</P>
<P>
   Other Bay Area stalwarts such as Robert Half Associates and
CellularOne are also deploying thin clients, according to industry
sources. And Contra Costa County has recently installed hundreds of
the stripped-down machines in its county administration building
and court house in Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways the thin client is a throwback to the mainframe
era, when employees had to go through ``dumb terminals'' with no
processing power _ just keyboards and green screens for displaying
text and numbers carried over the wire from the corporate data
center.
</P>
<P>
   Today's thin clients, however, look and feel much more like PCs.
Almost all have a graphical user interface and a mouse. They run
familiar applications, like Microsoft Word and Excel, that few
would describe as thin. Increasingly they include a Web browser,
e-mail and even multimedia capabilities. And they're not dumb _
each has its own microprocessor, though it's used only to manage
communications with the server, where the real computing is done,
and to draw what the user sees on screen.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the biggest beneficiary of the thin-client movement
could turn out to be Microsoft. When Ellison, McNealy and friends
first proposed the NC, Microsoft pooh-poohed it as something no one
wanted. But when Gates et al. saw how much interest the concept
generated among corporate customers, they responded in
characteristic fashion, moving quickly to ``embrace and extend''
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Relying at first on technology licensed from Citrix, an
innovative software developer based in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.,
Microsoft released a special version of its Windows NT 4.0 server
software that allows thin clients to run standard Windows
applications from the server. It also came up with two operating
systems for thin clients: first a version of Windows CE, originally
developed for handheld devices, then a higher-powered alternative
called Embedded NT.
</P>
<P>
   And with the new Windows 2000, Microsoft built support for thin
clients directly into the standard server versions of the software.
In another characteristic move, the company is finding new ways to
make money off the trend: Windows 2000's license will force many
businesses with thin clients to pay increased ``client-access
fees.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Windows 2000 release, and the commitment to
thin-client computing it implies, have given a big boost to the
movement, according to Steve Kaplan, president of Ryno Technology.
His Benicia company once made and sold its own PC clones, but in
recent years it has focused on network integration services,
especially for thin clients.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Microsoft seems to be following its usual policy of
co-opting technological challenges into the Windows framework. And
its strategy seems to be working. Among the several types of client
systems IDC includes in the thin category, ``Windows-based
terminals'' _ running either Windows CE or Embedded NT _ now
represent a majority of unit sales. Of course, that's well short of
Microsoft's 90 percent share of the conventional operating systems
market. But sales of ``Windows-based terminals'' are growing faster
than any other thin-client category, according to O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Java-centric thin clients _ the original network
computers _ are going the way of the dodo. According to Dataquest,
144,433 were sold in 1997, but the figure has declined steadily to
17,323 last year. The research company expects sales to dwindle to
just 7,638 this year, then disappear.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? The problem was the inefficiency of the Java
language and the software ``virtual machines'' needed to run Java
applications, according to Jeff McNaught, vice president of
marketing at San Jose's Wyse Technology, the leader in thin clients
unit sales. (IBM is second, followed by an array of smaller
companies including Network Computing Devices of Mountain View and
Maxspeed of Palo Alto.)
</P>
<P>
   Wyse tried to build a Java-oriented NC, McNaught said, ``but it
just wasn't viable. The Java apps just got way too big and needed
way too much CPU and memory _ up to 96 megabytes. It would have
ended up costing more than a PC.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, McNaught noted, ``the applications people want are
Windows applications _ there's just no denying that point.''
</P>
<P>
   McNaught is also skeptical about the latest thin-client twist:
terminals based on the free Linux OS. Wyse developed one of those,
too, he said, but decided not to market it under its own name
because demand has been limited.
</P>
<P>
   Even the cost savings that might be expected from using a free
OS turn out to be mostly illusory, according to McNaught, because
Linux requires more memory in the client machine, including
relatively expensive flash RAM for storing the OS. Compared to
those costs, he said, the license fees Microsoft charges for its
thin-client systems are ``insignificant.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be too early to count Linux out of the thin-client
market, though. Numerous developers are working on leaner versions
of it. Citrix, SCO and other companies already offer ways to access
server-based Windows applications from Linux clients, and last
month Ottawa-based Corel announced plans to add such capabilities
to its desktop-oriented Linux version. (Corel is licensing the
software, called Bridges, from a Campbell company named GraphOn.)
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it's at least conceivable that businesses will be less
insistent on compatibility with Windows applications in the future,
as native Linux alternatives increase and mature and as more
applications become available through a browser interface.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
