<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: STRAWBERRY NEEDS TO ADDRESS HIS ADDICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Skedded earlier as BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY)  
(ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Darryl Strawberry is expected to learn this week
how long he will be suspended from baseball, and whether
Commissioner Bud Selig would grant him some loophole that will
allow him to return to the game in the last months of the 2000
season.
</P>
<P>
   After failing a drug test, his third violation under baseball's
aftercare program, Strawberry asked Selig for another chance last
week. Strawberry needs the structure of baseball, his friends
argue. He needs to have the hope of playing the game once again,
they say.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry turns 38 in a couple of weeks, and if taking batting
practice every day is what is preventing Strawberry from doing
cocaine, he is in big trouble. If anybody thinks that serving as
the designated hitter against most right-handed pitchers will keep
him from doing drugs, they are deluding themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry has four children and his wife is pregnant with a
fifth, and he still takes drugs. The fact that he faces a mountain
of debt has not caused him to confront his addiction, and for more
than 10 years, knowing that he could make a lot of money playing
baseball _ and support his family and pay off his debt _ has not
prevented him from doing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   For all of his trouble, Strawberry has never lost his sense of
entitlement. He apparently has never thought of himself as anything
other than a baseball player, capable of incalculable wealth.
According to the report filed with the Florida Department of
Corrections on Feb. 8, Strawberry has ``plans to build a home later
this year in Cheval,'' a gated community which is one of the most
expensive in the area. He is driving a top-of-the-line sport
utility vehicle. When he was out of baseball last year, the Yankees
stopped paying him his salary, and Strawberry did not seek
alternative employment to address his many outstanding obligations.
But he did have a personal trainer who worked on site with him at
Legends Field at the start of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   When police arrested him last year for possession of cocaine and
solicitation of prostitution, Strawberry told them that the drugs
belonged to a relative. He told teammates that there was something
unseemly about the arrest, that the police had it in for him.
Friends whispered to newspapers that the case against Strawberry
was legally flawed, that the charges would be dropped _ right up
until Strawberry meekly plead no contest.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry privately griped that reporters were treating him
unfairly, that they were trying to get him in trouble _ as if they
had anything to do with him circling the block repeatedly and
engaging the undercover officer in Tampa last April.
</P>
<P>
   The morning after his meeting with Selig last week, Strawberry
surprised everyone by appearing at Legends Field. He wanted to make
sure no one thought he was running and hiding, he said. Two hours
later he slipped through a side exit, and he has not been heard
from since.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Strawberry has been running and hiding for years,
using his baseball career as a cover. He has made at least three
separate appeals to Yankees owner George Steinbrenner to keep him
on his team, made his plea of no contest in order to facilitate his
return to baseball last summer, and last week, he tearfully asked
Selig for another chance to get back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for Strawberry to focus on everything that really
matters, all of which has nothing to do with baseball: his
addictions, his life, his kids, his obligations. Baseball officials
have given Strawberry many chances to right his career, believing _
hoping _ that he would take advantage of that opportunity. But it's
quite apparent by now that his baseball career cannot solve his
addiction or any of his other trouble. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry is well-liked by his teammates, who are drawn to his
good nature, his sense of humor. He possesses a presence, Yankees
Manager Joe Torre said the other day, because he has been a big
name in the big city. When he looks you directly in the eye, there
is still something vulnerable about Strawberry; you can see shadows
of an innocent and underprivileged 18-year-old kid and it's easy to
feel sorry for him. David Cone has seen the way Strawberry touches
others _ particularly young people _ when Strawberry speaks of his
own travails, and Cone knows there is good in his old friend.
</P>
<P>
   But Strawberry needs to address his own problems. He needs
stability, and it's not going to come from baseball, a sport played
eight months, day and night, in 29 cities located in two countries.
If Steinbrenner wants to help Strawberry, then he should get him
treatment, get him a job away from baseball, and force him to face
the challenges he must inevitably conquer once he leaves the game _
whether that departure takes place in two days or two years.
</P>
<P>
   Selig might be moved by Strawberry, but he should not be fooled
into thinking that giving him a chance to resume his baseball
career will have anything to do with addressing his addiction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
