<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0190 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-BOBJONES-ART-100     02-27 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BOBJONES-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH EXPRESSES REGRET FOR NOT SPEAKING OUT AGAINST BIGOTRY AT BOB
JONES U. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI with NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush expressed regret on Sunday for
not speaking out against racial and religious intolerance during a
visit to Bob Jones University in South Carolina, an appearance that
has come to haunt his campaign and challenge his claim to being a
new kind of conservative eager to expand the Republican Party's
appeal to all voters.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Cardinal John O'Connor, the Roman Catholic
archbishop of New York, and in a press conference on Sunday
afternoon in Austin, Texas, Bush said that he had erred by not
clearly separating himself from some of the anti-Catholic and
racially discriminatory sentiments that have been associated with
the university, a conservative Christian institution.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not apologize for making the visit to Bob Jones,
his letter was a striking about-face for the Texas governor, who in
recent weeks had brushed off suggestions that his appearance there
was a mistake, and it reflected the depth of concern in the Bush
campaign that the tenacious after-life of the episode was doing
Bush political damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``On reflection, I should have been more clear in disassociating
myself from anti-Catholic sentiments and racial prejudice,'' Bush
said in the letter to O'Connor, which the Bush campaign said was
mailed on Friday. ``It was a missed opportunity causing needless
offense, which I deeply regret.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Bush reiterated those sentiments, and
said that while he was unaware of some of the policies and
statements associated with Bob Jones University before he went
there, he was not offering that as a defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make no excuses,'' Bush said. ``I had an opportunity and I
missed it and I regret it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had gotten up then and seized the moment to set a
tone, a tone that I had set in Texas, a positive and inclusive
tone,'' he added. Bush and officials with his campaign said that
the letter to O'Connor, the spiritual leader of about 2.4 million
Catholics in the New York metropolitan area, was triggered in part
by the Bush family's longstanding friendship with the archbishop.
</P>
<P>
   But the letter also seemed to anticipate the potential
importance of Catholics in the Republican primary in New York on
March 7. Catholics represent an estimated 46 percent of the voters
likely to participate in that primary, the outcome of which could
be pivotal in determining whether Bush can put an end to the potent
challenge from Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not use the word ``apology'' in either his written or
spoken remarks, and his contrition was measured, possibly
underscoring his need for the continued support of the kinds of
religious conservatives who support Bob Jones University. Bush
neither condemned the school nor its officers, and he did not say
that his decision to go there was in and of itself a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Bush used his expressions of regret as an
opportunity to lash out at McCain for raising the specter of
anti-Catholic bigotry as a wedge to attack a political opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Early last week, before the Michigan primary, many Catholic
voters in the state received phone calls that informed them of
Bush's visit to Bob Jones University and of anti-Catholic
statements made by school leaders in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted in the news conference on Sunday that McCain and his
aides initially said that they were not sure who was making the
calls, but later acknowledged that they were behind the effort. On
Saturday, McCain admitted that he had approved the calls in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed in the senator,'' Bush told reporters.
``It was clear that he looked you in the press corps in the eye and
did not tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, campaigning in Virginia on Sunday night, said that he
had not yet been informed of Bush's expression of regret. But
Warren Rudman, a former senator from New Hampshire and the national
chairman of McCain's campaign, caustically noted that Bush's
statement came more than three weeks after his visit to the
university.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a long time in getting there,'' Rudman said.
</P>
<P>
   The political baggage that Bush picked up with his visit to the
school, which was part of an appeal to Christian conservatives in
South Carolina that helped ensure his victory in the primary,
seemed to grow heavier, not lighter, each day.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters grilled the governor about it on an almost daily
basis. Some prominent Republicans took public issue with the way
Bush was handling it. Political opponents latched onto it as a way
to discredit Bush's self-appointed mantle as ``a compassionate
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Peter T. King, R-N.Y., threw his support for Bush to
McCain and repeatedly took issue with Bush's appearance at the
university and his ties to Christian conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But as recently as the middle of last week, Bush was still
publicly saying that he would not make any apologies for his visit
to the school, because his appearance there was not an indication
of what was in his heart. And he made clear that he opposed all
bigotry, religious or racial.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, however, he and his advisers came to realize that he
had to make a public gesture more emphatic than that, both to
assure Catholic voters that he had not intended any insult and to
recapture his image as a centrist Republican, according to
officials with the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign's telephone calls to Catholic voters
provided another incentive, these officials said. Bush did not want
those calls' implicit charge of anti-Catholicism to go unanswered,
and aides said the governor was also genuinely pained at the
thought that anyone might regard him as a bigot.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign officials said that over several days last week, Bush
and his advisers weighed a number of ways for Bush to express his
regret, including writing an op-ed column for newspapers. They said
they did not initially intend to publicize the letter to O'Connor,
written as much out of friendship as anything else, but that
Catholic leaders in New York urged them to.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Bush says that racial and religious intolerance
``are personally offensive to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to erase any doubts about my views and values,'' Bush
added. ``As a public official, I take seriously my duty to
encourage tolerance and respect for the religious views of others.
As a Christian, I see Catholics as my brothers and sisters in
Christ, sharing the same ancient creed and core beliefs. And, as
you know, my own brother and sister-in-law are both Catholics.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also chastised people who used his appearance at the
university to draw conclusions about his values or cast aspersions
on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What no American should expect _ and what I will not tolerate
_ is guilt by association,'' Bush wrote. ``This is why I am
offended by any suggestion that I tolerate anti-Catholic bigotry _
and resent any attempt to create that impression.''
</P>
<P>
   The friction between Bush, McCain and their associates spilled
onto the Sunday morning television news programs. Appearing on
NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' Rudman and Karl Rove, the chief
strategist for the Bush campaign, got into a shouting match as they
quarreled over which of their candidates had the most to be sorry
for.
</P>
<P>
   Rove noted that Rep. Lindsey Graham, the South Carolina
Republican who was co-chairman of McCain's campaign in that state,
had accepted an honorary degree from Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   It was a reminder of how many politicians over time have had
ties to the school or spoken there without stirring the kind of
criticism that Bush's visit did.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of Bush's most prominent political allies, Gov.
George Pataki of New York, suggested in an interview on Sunday that
McCain was unfairly exploiting the episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should use religion in a campaign,'' Pataki said.
``It's just abhorrent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
