<HEADER>
A0192 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-27 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AT THE HEART OF THE DIALLO CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The cops had their day in court and were acquitted.
The system was twisted this way and that to insure that they were
treated fairly. More than fairly. The judge, Joseph Teresi,
trumpeted his sympathies as soon as the trial was over by
hobnobbing at a bed and breakfast with the defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The hope here is that the cops who killed Amadou Diallo for the
crime of breathing while black will turn in their badges and their
blue uniforms and move on. It would be best all around if they were
to seek vocational satisfaction in some other venue.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they do, the problems that they have come to epitomize
will remain _the humiliation and brutalization of thousands of
innocent New Yorkers, most of them black and brown, by police
officers who are arrogant, tyrannical, poorly trained, often
frightened and not infrequently racist. (Remember, from the
officers' perspective, the killing of Diallo was his fault.)
</P>
<P>
   Much of the city remains in deep denial about the extent of
these abuses. Only the most sensational cases draw the spotlight.
Everybody recognizes the name Amadou Diallo. But you will get only
a blank stare if you mention Brother Tyrone Davis, a teacher at a
parochial school in Harlem who was stopped so often by the police
he became reluctant to leave the school without his religious
collar.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo's mother, Kadiatou, zeroed in on a fundamental problem
when she complained about the cops viewing her son as suspicious in
the first place. Diallo was standing outside his home, breathing.
That was about it.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police, he also looked up and down the street.
``Peering'' was the pejorative verb they used. Now, that's really
suspicious. The next thing you know, he's dead.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the mayor nor the police commissioner seemed
particularly troubled by any of this. There is little in the way of
official acknowledgment that there is something terribly wrong in
the way that many of the city's police officers conduct themselves.
Rudolph Giuliani and Howard Safir seem not to understand that their
silence in the face of pervasive misconduct by the police is a way
of encouraging misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Or, perhaps they do.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani would have been the perfect person to order a halt to
the harassment of law-abiding New Yorkers, and to begin forging
closer relationships between the police and the communities they
are supposed to serve. But he did not, and it seems safe to say
that he will not. Perhaps when Giuliani leaves office the city will
get a mayor of all the people, and some progress will be made.
</P>
<P>
   But there were missed opportunities on the other side as well.
The impressive protests that followed the killing of Diallo drew
nationwide attention, but that spotlight was not used effectively.
The main thrust of the protests became a demand that the cops who
killed Diallo be indicted and, following that, convicted.
</P>
<P>
   I think that was a mistake. The spotlight drawn by the killing
of Diallo should have been thrown on the wide range of police
abuses that plague New York, from the unwarranted harassment of
innocent men, women and children who are stopped and frisked by the
scores of thousands for no good reason; to the use of numerical
quotas for summonses, gun seizures, arrests and other matters that
drive cops to ignore good sense and the Constitution in a mindless
attempt to satisfy mindless superiors; to the bullying and often
brutal physical abuse that accompanies many encounters between the
police and civilians and that results in tens of millions of
dollars in legal settlements and judgments every year; to the false
arrests that occur with horrifying frequency on matters large and
small (the humiliating experience of Alton White, a star of the
musical ``Ragtime'' comes immediately to mind); to the extreme
tragedies, deliberate or otherwise, like the Abner Louima case and
the slaughter of Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   I agree with Fernando Ferrer, the borough president of the
Bronx, who said, in the aftermath of the Diallo verdict: ``The
bigger issue is reform of the Police Department. That still has to
happen. And that is all about building a relationship of trust
between the community and its Police Department. That, at the end
of the day, is what will keep people in the community and police
officers safer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
