<DOCNO> NYT20000227.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0195 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CALIF-REPUBS-2TAKES(1     02-27 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-REPUBS-2TAKES(1100)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH-MCCAIN FIGHT STRAINS CALIFORNIA'S ALREADY BELEAGUERED GOP
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic and photo are being sent to NYT clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ As the presidential campaign moves to the
biggest states, George W. Bush and John McCain are battling
squarely for the biggest prize of all: California, whose
once-mighty Republican Party propelled Richard Nixon and Ronald
Reagan to the White House but has languished and feuded for much of
the 1990s as President Clinton and the Democrats came to dominate
the state.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican presidential nominee has won the Golden State
since the elder George Bush in 1988; the current Democratic
governor, Gray Davis, swept into office with a 20-point margin two
years ago. The Bush-McCain fight has opened new fault lines here
that California Republicans can ill-afford, and a major subtext of
the candidates' struggle is who would be best equipped to regain
the White House by blocking the Democrats from carrying what has
become a must-win state for them in November.
</P>
<P>
   For the reality is that both men are seeking the votes of a
California Republican Party that is older and whiter, and more
dominated at the grass-roots level by social conservatives than it
was in the 1980s, when a pragmatic fiscal conservatism reigned. At
the same time, the state as a whole is younger, browner and more
politically independent than it was a decade ago, and its striking
economic recovery from the severe recession of the early '90s has
helped make Clinton more popular here than in almost any other
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general electorate has gone exactly the other way from the
party leadership in terms of positions on immigration, ethnicity,
abortion, guns,'' said Stuart Spencer, the dean of Republican
strategists here who was one of Reagan's closest advisers from
Sacramento to the White House. ``Till they get their ship righted,
and move back to a more centrist, moderate position, they're going
to have trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   No place exemplifies that trend better than Pasadena, the
once-rock-solid old-line Republican enclave just east of Los
Angeles. In the mid-1990s, State Assembly seats in the area that
had been safely Republican since the 1940s went to Democrats
instead, and this year, the incumbent congressman, Rep. James E.
Rogan, is facing a stiff re-election challenge from a Democratic
state senator, Adam Schiff, in one of the most expensive and widely
watched races in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very much for George Bush, but I think he's just
waffled,'' said Dorie Hilton, a lifelong Republican and the wife of
a retired Navy captain who was shopping along Colorado Boulevard
this weekend. But now Hilton is for ``John McCain without a doubt;
he's such a contrast to Bill Clinton.'' She added: ``If the far
right takes over the Republican Party, we're all in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilton is precisely the kind of voter McCain must target to win
a state where only Republican votes will count in choosing
delegates March 7.
</P>
<P>
   She is Republican, female, moderate and likely to vote. And, on
paper, McCain would seem an almost ideal California candidate: a
Westerner, a proponent of campaign finance overhaul and government
reform in a state that regularly passes ballot measures to rein in
its elected officials, an opponent of tobacco in one of the
nation's most strongly anti-smoking states, a Navy veteran in a
state with legions of them.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Bush has consistently outpolled McCain by about
2-to-1 among Republican voters, nearly a third of whom identified
themselves as strongly conservative in a recent statewide Field
Poll, and nearly 40 percent of whom aligned themselves with the
religious right. A Time-CNN poll released Saturday had Bush leading
among Republicans 49 percent to 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has begun running television advertisements here
portraying himself as a ``proud Reagan Republican,'' in an effort
to rally the party's base. But even that strategy carries potential
risks in a state where the abortion issue has routinely led
moderate Republicans to support Democratic general election
candidates in statewide contests in recent years. Both Bush and
McCain oppose abortion, and no anti-abortion Republican has won at
the top of the statewide ticket since the elder Bush in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for either one of them to grab the majority of the
Republican vote here, they're both going to have to go to the
right, and that poses problems for both'' in a general election,
said Garry South, a Democratic political consultant who is Davis'
chief adviser. ``The Republicans that you see showing up to vote in
the fall don't look a lot like the ones you see voting in the
primary.''
</P>
<P>
   The state has its unusual ``blanket'' primary system, in which
the names of all candidates appear on the same ballot regardless of
party, because a moderate Republican, Rep. Tom Campbell, believed
he could have won the 1992 primary for U.S. Senate that he lost to
a more conservative candidate if crossover voters had been eligible
to participate.
</P>
<P>
   With financial backing from the computer magnate David Packard,
Campbell sponsored the 1996 ballot initiative that created the new
system.
</P>
<P>
   That means the primary will provide the first real test of how
Californians might vote in the general election. But because the
rules of both national parties expressly forbid selecting delegates
in a blanket primary, the parties cooperated here to pass a state
law requiring that only the votes of party members be used to
select that party's delegates. On the Republican side, all 162
delegates will be allocated to whoever gets the most Republican
votes statewide.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the 1990s, former Gov. Pete Wilson, a fiscal
conservative whose support for abortion rights gave him a moderate
tinge, managed to paper over internal differences with a
grass-roots party organization that was moving to the right on
social issues. But with the resounding defeat of State Attorney
General Dan Lungren, who ran to succeed Wilson in 1998, and of all
but two of the GOP's other candidates for statewide posts, the
differences became all too apparent and the party was left hundreds
of thousands of dollars in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's aggressive stands against illegal immigration and
affirmative action had alienated the state's growing Latino
population, who had once given both him and Reagan more than 40
percent of their votes. More than a year ago, virtually the entire
statewide Republican elected establishment here lined up behind
Bush because he was seen as a nonpolarizing figure whose successful
outreach to Hispanic voters in Texas might translate well here,
though some of the more conservative grass-roots groups held back,
flirting with candidates like Steve Forbes or Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In polls last year, Bush often ran about neck-and-neck with Vice
President Al Gore here. Now, Gore is outpolling the Texas governor
by double-digit margins, but running about even with McCain in
hypothetical general election matchups. That is not great news for
either Republican; Democrats hold about a 9-point edge in voter
registration here, though both major parties have lost strength to
independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``By definition, any nonincumbent Republican running statewide
in California is the underdog,'' said state Sen. Jim Brulte of
Rancho Cucamonga, who took over as the party's finance chairman
last year and got it out of debt with Bush's help. ``That's just
the way things work. The explosive growth of the Latino population
and the ever-increasing percentage of Asian voters in California is
changing the dynamic, and it's important for Republicans to reach
out to those communities. It's also important not to misread the
results of the 1990s: Pete Wilson did get elected twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Republicans make the primary choices next week, in
several counties around the state there are also hot contests for
the little-noticed posts of party central committees, with a
statewide group that calls itself ``mainstream'' trying to regain
control from more socially conservative groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on fire, but in the mainstream, nothing moderate about
us,'' said former state Assemblyman Brooks Firestone of Los Olivos,
north of Santa Barbara in the Central Coast wine-making country.
Firestone, a fiscal conservative who supports abortion rights and
gun controls, lost a bitter 1998 primary for Congress to a more
conservative candidate who had the support of Christian
conservative groups. Since then, Firestone has fought to reassert
the party's more socially moderate wing.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone is a strong Bush supporter, and he thinks ``there's no
question that Bush will win the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``While a lot of Republicans like McCain for who he is and what
he's meant for America,'' he adds, ``they're becoming upset with
his Democratic support as this become more and more obvious that
Democrats are playing around in these open primaries.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Scott Jessup, 44, a banker who was strolling in Pasadena with
his wife, Holly, is one Republican who finds no attraction to
either of his party's candidates this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no leadership at all in the California Republican
Party,'' Jessup said. ``There's no issue. Taxes just won't cut it
anymore. When the economy's very strong, people don't feel like
they need a tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Bush and McCain he said: ``They don't grab me. At least
McCain appears to have a little more fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
