<DOCNO> NYT20000227.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0197 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-DIALLO-REACT-NYT &LR;      02-27 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALLO-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM PULPIT TO STREET, DIALLO VERDICT PROTEST CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Words of anger, frustration and concern Sunday rose
from pulpits across the city, and more than 1,000 demonstrators
took to the streets for a third day of prayer and protest,
displaying the roiling emotions after the acquittal last Friday of
four police officers in the shooting death of Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Patrick's Cathedral, Auxiliary Bishop James McCarthy told
the congregation that Diallo's death should cause people to
``re-examine our own tendencies toward violence, toward fear, and
perhaps toward prejudice _ racial prejudice at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Mayor David N. Dinkins, speaking at First Sharon Baptist
Church on East 116th Street in Harlem, called on the parishioners
to make widely known their opposition to the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   At Abyssinian Baptist Church on West 138th Street in Harlem, the
Rev. Calvin O. Butts III compared the verdict to events in South
Africa that led once peaceful black leaders to turn to pick up
weapons in their struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a little like my Lord, I want to kick over some
tables.'' said Rev. Butts, who has at times been a strident critic
of Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani. Rev. Butts' comments were repeatedly
greeted with cheers and applause in the church, a bastion of the
Harlem establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sometimes volatile language, the day passed without
violence. But there were tense moments Sunday afternoon when some
of the more than 1,000 people who had assembled at the United
Nations for a prayer vigil began to head down Second Avenue,
disrupting traffic until police officials appealed to protest
organizers to contain the march.
</P>
<P>
   ``They walked onto this man's block, up to his doorstop and shot
him cold,'' said Frankie Lipsett, 39, a building superintendent
from the Soundview section of the Bronx, who joined the rally.
``This is just another example of what is wrong with this country.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict also reverberated in the Senate race, with Hillary
Rodham Clinton telling a national conference of Dominicans at City
College of New York that the Diallo case reflected a ``trust
divide'' in New York.
</P>
<P>
   She said police officers must work harder to understand the
communities they serve, and city residents need to better
appreciate the risk the police face each day. And she called on the
city to do a better job recruiting blacks, Hispanics and other
minorities to the police force, comments that brought almost
immediate criticism from her opponent, Giuliani, whose aides noted
that the police department had embarked upon aggressive minority
recruitment efforts in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   During the rally at the United Nations, both the Giuliani and
the police department were frequently ridiculed. Some demonstrators
wore pictures of Diallo, and others wore pins with a Giuliani
picture that had a red slash through his face.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, who organized the vigil to try to drawn
international attention to the Diallo case, called on people to
``hold their wallets,'' as Diallo was apparently doing when he was
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to boycott in this city,'' he said. ``We are
afraid to spend money with certain people because we are considered
suspects. Let's hold our wallets, let's hold our wallets.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks by Butts, made in two morning sermons to
standing-room-only crowds backed into the popular church, stood in
contrast to his actions last year when he hugged Giuliani at a
service organized by Cardinal John O'Connor at St. Patrick's
intended to ease tension over the Diallo shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Butts, who is considered a possible mayoral contender in 2001,
said that following the shooting of Diallo last February, he
received calls from leaders in the white community urging
restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those same leaders called me now to say let's get
together, let's sit down and talk,'' Butts said. ``I told them to
go to hell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
