<HEADLINE>
CANADA SURPRISES COLOMBIA IN FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- This was surely the greatest week in the history
of Canadian soccer, complete with a fairytale ending as soccer's
newest overachievers upset Colombia, 2-0, Sunday in front of 6,197
at the Coliseum to capture the 2000 Gold Cup -- a tournament that
began with CONCACAF giants Mexico and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first tournament championship ever on an
international stage for Canada, who came into the tournament ranked
85th in the world by FIFA -- with the worst reputation among the 12
participating team's.
</P>
<P>
   Canada, who had never been beyond the first-round in recent Gold
Cup competition, needed to win a coin flip over South Korea to gain
a birth in the quarterfinals. From there, the Canadians rewrote
history in Canada, defeating Mexico, Trinidad &AMP; Tobago and Colombia
all in the same week to finish the tournament, 3-0-2.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Devos and Carlo Corazzini each had goals for Canada, and
goalkeeper Craig Forrest, the MVP of the tournament, recorded his
second straight shutout. Forrest, who had a penalty kick save
Thursday against Trinidad &AMP; Tobago, saved another Sunday, guessing
correctly in the 85th minute, stopping Colombian striker Faustino
Asprilla's shot to the left side.
</P>
<P>
   Devos said he expects this to be headline news, at least for a
day, all over Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully this will be front page news at every newspaper and
station across the country,'' said Devos. ``This has never happened
before, we've never won a major trophy. It's a monumental
achievement, just unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Most experts expected Canada to fold after upsetting three- time
Gold Cup champion Mexico last week -- but Devos said the Canadians
never stopped believing something more special could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we go out on the pitch, we go out with the intention
of winning,'' said Devos. ``Historically, we haven't had much
success, but today we turned the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Canadian coach Holger Osieck said he hopes this victory improves
financial backing of Canada's national team program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we won it, I hope everybody in Canada will support us
and we can go further as a soccer nation,'' said Osieck.
``Hopefully this will pave the way to develop Canadian football the
way it should be developed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians, controlling most of the possession and showing
rare confidence, scored with time winding down in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Nash sent a corner kick to the far post, where Devos
outleaped Colombian defender Andres Mosquera, sending a header to
the near post. Colombian keeper Diego Gomez nearly grabbed the shot
off the line, but the ball rolled inches past in the 45th minute to
give Canada a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians extended their lead in the second half after
Jeffrey Clarke was tripped by Gomez on a breakaway, setting up a
penalty kick which Corazzini converted in the 67th minute for a 2-0
lead and his tournament leading fourth goal.
</P>
<P>
   In the 85th minute, Forrest preserved the shutout with another
brilliant penalty kick save -- further increasing his reputation on
the international stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely the best goalkeeper in CONCACAF and one of the
best in Europe,'' said Devos. ``Not just because of the two penalty
kick saves, but throughout the tournament he came up big for us and
that's what you need to win championships.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
