<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0208 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-HEZBOLLAH-FUTURE-ART-     02-27 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEZBOLLAH-FUTURE-ART-1090(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ARAB MILITIA, GLIMPSING VICTORY, COULD LOSE PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ No man has made himself more Israel's enemy in
recent years than Sheik Hassan Nasrallah, the portly, bespectacled
Shiite Muslim cleric who leads Hezbollah, the Lebanon-based,
Iran-backed Party of God that has evolved into a formidable
guerrilla movement and political party from the umbrella
organization that once directed the Middle East's most brutal
Islamic terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Nasrallah's predecessors were assassinated by Israel, the
last one by helicopter gunships that blasted his motorcade with
rockets. So when the militant Islamic leader showed up this month
to mark the eighth anniversary of that attack in Nabi Chit, a
shabby hamlet in the Bekaa region, he was taking a mortal risk.
</P>
<P>
   The rally _ venue and time previously announced _ was barely 10
minutes' flying time from bases in the nine-mile deep ``security
zone'' that Israel has maintained since 1985 in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, which has dispensed and suffered sudden death on a
numbing scale for 18 years, has more to celebrate these days than
what it hails as the martyrdom of its leaders. Unless events cause
a change of plan, Prime Minister Ehud Barak's commitment to
withdraw Israel's 1,000-man contingent from southern Lebanon by
July 7 has opened the way for Hezbollah to declare itself the lone
Arab force ever to ``defeat'' Israeli forces.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing has been simple in Lebanese politics since the
country began to deconstruct in the mid-1970s, and Hezbollah's
moment of triumph could also be a prelude to a painful transition
for the Islamic group. Many Lebanese predict that the Israeli
withdrawal could remake the political landscape here in ways that
will undermine Hezbollah, since it would strip the group of what,
until now, has been its political trump card.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, it is less the hint of change than the scent of
victory that has lured Nasrallah out of his secretive routines to
events like the one at Nabi Chit, which he reached in a battered
BMW with darkened windows while steely-eyed gunmen rode decoy
behind him in three Range Rovers.
</P>
<P>
   Nasrallah, 40, a vegetable vendor's son who was Hezbollah's
field commander in the south before becoming the group's leader in
1992, is making the most of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   With two bodyguards pressed tightly to his side on the podium at
Nabi Chit, and other armed men patrolling the hall, the
bushy-bearded cleric punched the air, pushed out his chest, and
repeatedly tipped back his black turban as he proclaimed Israel's
``total humiliation and disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I send this message to both the Zionists and the Americans:
You are fighting God in southern Lebanon, and those who fight God
are doomed to defeat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Israel, many concede that Hezbollah has won a classic
guerrilla victory _ by not losing, by outlasting the enemy, by
inflicting losses that erode support at home _ rather than by a
triumph of arms.
</P>
<P>
   In one of many similar articles in Israeli newspapers, Yoel
Marcus, a columnist for Haaretz, a newspaper long opposed to the
occupation of southern Lebanon, compared the promised pullout to
the United States' defeat in Vietnam. He concluded, ``This is one
war that we have lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The kind of Hezbollah action that has worn down Israeli
resistance is on display at an exhibition the group opened last
week in Beirut. Day after day, young Lebanese have clustered around
a television set playing a videotape that shows Hezbollah fighters
in camouflage fatigues and helmets storming Israeli posts on rocky
hillsides in southern Lebanon, or detonating roadside bombs as
Israeli military convoys wind their way along mountain roads.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks like those have killed hundreds of Israeli soldiers
since Israel's invasion of Lebanon in 1978, including seven in the
last month alone.
</P>
<P>
   What happens now will involve a complex political matrix, in
which Hezbollah's activities will be profoundly influenced by more
powerful players, including Iran and Syria, its two principal
backers, and the Lebanese government, as well as the terms of any
peace deals Israel can work out with Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The peace talks between Israel and Syria, suspended now but
likely to resume, will revive Israeli demands that Syria use the
power it wields in Lebanon, where it has 35,000 troops, to
guarantee that the power vacuum Israel leaves behind is filled not
by Hezbollah, but by Lebanon's 65,000-man army. The Lebanese
government, which wants its own peace with Israel, would then,
presumably, inhibit Hezbollah attacks into Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, senior Lebanese political and military officials
concede that Hezbollah's stepped-up military offensive against
Israeli forces in recent weeks _ attacks that prompted the Israeli
bombing raids that destroyed three Lebanese power plants on Feb. 8
_ were almost certainly encouraged by Syria.
</P>
<P>
   By this reckoning, Syria may have calculated that putting
pressure on Israeli forces in Lebanon would help wrest concessions
that Israel has so far refused in talks. By the same token, these
Lebanese officials say, Syria, once it achieves its own peace with
Israel, will not want to see it disturbed by continued fighting
across the Israel-Lebanon border.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah could thus could end up isolated, its 1,500 guerrilla
fighters too weak to maintain dominance in areas of southern
Lebanon and the western Bekaa region it now controls, and in effect
consigned to the diminished role of a political party competing in
Lebanon's sectarian politics.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that Shiite Muslims are the largest group in
Lebanon's population of 3.5 million Muslims and Christians, and
that Hezbollah is now indisputably the strongest Shiite political
force, the situation poses pressing questions. Will Hezbollah
continue the more moderate politics it adopted in the 1990s? And
will its professed conversion to democracy only cover the old
passions for a militant Islamic state in Lebanon?
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, there are major questions for the entire region,
since lasting Middle East peace may ultimately depend on whether
militant groups like Hezbollah and its Palestinian counterpart,
Hamas, abandon their historic goals of extinguishing Israel and
accept that it has a permanent place on the Middle East map.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the answers to these questions lie in Iran, the source
of Hezbollah's brand of Shiite fundamentalism, and of an estimated
$2 billion in support since the early 1980s, and in Syria, the
conduit through which the arms supplied by Iran have flowed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s Hezbollah rejected the very idea of an independent
Lebanon, as of an independent Israel, calling for the submersion of
both in a greater Islamic state. With the emergence of more
moderate policies in Iran, Hezbollah underwent what scholars here
call a ``Lebanonization'' and shifted toward the mainstream. It now
controls the largest single bloc in the 128-seat Parliament, with
seven seats of its own and influence over perhaps 50 others.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Hezbollah has established a substantial
presence in Lebanese life. Apart from two radio stations, a popular
television station and several newspapers, it has a far-reaching
network of hospitals, clinics, pharmacies, schools and martial arts
centers, as well as welfare and rehabilitation centers for those
injured by war and for their families, and pensions for relatives
of dead fighters.
</P>
<P>
   A Lebanese scholar who has written extensively on Hezbollah,
Nizar Hamzeh, says that under Nasrallah, ``the party has
concentrated more on the ballot box than on bullets,'' although
U.N. records continue to show a pattern of about 1,500 attacks a
year on Israeli troops. Still, Hamzeh says, the jury is out on what
Hezbollah's ultimate aims may be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate goal is still to capture the Lebanese state,'' he
said in an interview in his office at the American University of
Beirut, whose American president, Malcolm Kerr, was assassinated in
1984 by gunmen who were widely assumed to be linked to Hezbollah.
``But the question is, what kind of Lebanese state? There may be
those within Hezbollah whose attitude is `If we can't succeed in
creating an Islamic state from without, let's do it from within.'''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, no clear answers are available to those who
visit Hezbollah's center of strength in the crowded southern
suburbs of Beirut, in the Bekaa region along Syria's border and
amid the olive, orange and lemon groves of southern Lebanon where
fighters mount their attacks on the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Every question about Hezbollah's longer-range goals, including
whether it will seek to carry the war against Israel across the
border after Israeli troops leave, is met with polite evasions.
</P>
<P>
   Nasrallah lost his oldest son, Hadi, an 18-year-old Hezbollah
commando, in a skirmish with the Israelis in 1997, and stroked his
son's face in his coffin at the funeral 10 months later, when
Israeli forces returned the body. But the Hezbollah leader shows
little passion or bitterness when asked about the movement's future
attitude to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Pakistani Islamic scholar Eqbal Ahmad,
in June 1998, he said Hezbollah could not be more Palestinian than
Yasser Arafat. ``If their leaders compromise, there is little we
can do,'' he said in the interview, which was published in Dawn, a
newspaper in Karachi, Pakistan. ``We cannot substitute for their
leadership. If they decide to resist, we shall be on their side.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Hezbollah seems to have achieved a genuine popularity,
beyond working-class Shiites, who are its traditional constituency.
Its 20,000 active members now include many middle-class
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the reconstructed high-rises of west Beirut, risen from the
rubble of the 16-year civil war, drivers of expensive sedans wait
at ``friendly checkpoints'' set up by young Hezbollah activists in
yellow smocks, breezily tossing banknotes into plastic buckets in
return for candies.
</P>
<P>
   The donations help cover a sharp cutback in financing for
Hezbollah by Iran, which began urging the group to moderate its
policies when Iran began easing its Islamic policies in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Once Israel withdraws from Lebanon, however, Hezbollah's support
may shrink back more to its core: working-class Shiites. Sunni
Muslims, Christians and other religious groups and the middle class
seem grateful to Hezbollah for its part in driving Israeli troops
out, but convinced that peace would be better managed by other
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we support Hezbollah for driving out the Israelis _
they have been brave and we owe them much,'' said Antranik
Helvadjian, a bookstore manager of Armenian descent. ``But
Hezbollah to govern Lebanon? Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah has made a big push to remold its message, and some
Lebanese take comfort from Hezbollah officials' effort to expunge
elements of the group's past, including terrorism. In its offices,
officials' faces tighten, and Western reporters find visits and
interviews being canceled at short notice, when they merely mention
the word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hezbollah had nothing to do with any terrorist acts,'' Hussein
al-Khalil, Hezbollah's security chief in the 1980s and now chairman
of its politburo, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   That stretches credulity. According to Western intelligence
reports and other evidence, the 1983 bombings of the U.S. and
French embassies and marine compounds, the 1985 TWA hijacking and
about 50 kidnappings were carried out by Islamic splinter groups
that operated under pseudonyms, but always under Hezbollah's
control.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983 alone, at least 400 people were killed in Hezbollah
terror attacks in Beirut, including more than 250 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Hezbollah officials seem uneasy when discussing the
group's links to Iran. Its offices are a gallery of portraits of
Iranian religious leaders, and Hezbollah's leaders, clerics and
nonclerics alike, adopt Iran's Islamic dress codes.
</P>
<P>
   But Khalil, Hezbollah's politburo chief, insisted that this did
not translate into Iranian control. ``We are Lebanese 100
percent,'' he said. ``We have good relations with Iran, and we take
spiritual guidance from Iran's religious leaders, but our decisions
are taken by Hezbollah, not by Iran.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Lebanese scholars agree, noting more political and
financial independence and support that may even enable it to
resist orders from Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a real evolution within the movement, because
they have come to the conclusion that the Islamic revolution _ and
the revolutionary mentality _ cannot survive for long,'' said
Farouk Nassar, a Lebanese journalist who is now an editor with The
Middle East Reporter, a widely read political bulletin. ``They know
that they have to adjust, or they're doomed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
