<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELCHER HOPES TO RETURN IN APRIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. -- The biggest issue the Angels face in camp is
putting together a starting rotation, but one pitcher they can't
count on for the first month is Tim Belcher.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, in the second year of a two-year, $10.2 million
contract, had surgery to repair a torn flexor muscle in his right
elbow Dec. 2. These days he's playing catch every other day, slowly
increasing his arm strength. The club would like to have him
throwing off a mound for the first time March 10 or 11.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their plan for me is if I miss four or five starts in April
and I'm back by May 1, they'll be happy,'' Belcher said of the
rehab schedule. ''My thinking is if I'm throwing off the mound by
March 10, I should be able to throw an inning or two (in a spring
game) by the end of camp. If I can do that, there's no reason I
can't be ready by mid-April or the end of April.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll try to be as cautious as I can, but at the same time,
they're saying take baby steps but I feel like a premie.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Belcher is that the injury did not involve the
ligament. Had the ligament been torn instead of the muscle,
Belcher, 38, would have retired. And even the muscle tear wasn't
significant. In fact, Belcher said most of the pain resulted from
the build-up of scar tissue, which was removed during surgery.
</P>
<P>
   A healthy Belcher can certainly help a starting staff that will
have to rely heavily on young arms, but he says the outlook isn't
as bleak as it's made out to be.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been on staffs with more question marks than this one and
won,'' he said. ''A prime example is the (Dodgers) staff in '88 and
we won it all. Going in we had one guy who was established and
healthy -- Orel (Hershiser). Fernando's (Valenzuela) health was a
question mark, Tim Leary had never won and I was a rookie. And we
had just traded Bob Welch to Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ''But Leary has a breakout year and wins 17; I win 12 and we win
the World Series. We've got some good young arms here. The staff on
paper is the weakest part of the club, but that doesn't mean we
aren't any good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are also being cautious with Ken Hill, even though
Hill professes to ''feeling fine.'' Hill has an athritic right
elbow which usually becomes inflammed with excess work.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's at the stage where he is ready to face live hitting, but
we're also working on mechanics,'' manager Mike Scioscia said.
''He's coming along nicely.''
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Troy Glaus has switched his uniform number to 28
so that Scioscia could wear 14, the number Scioscia wore throughout
his major league career. Glaus said Scioscia called him at home
during the off-season to ask if the switch was OK. Glaus obliged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
