<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RABIN VOWED TO PULL BACK FROM GOLAN, BARAK SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel told his cabinet
Sunday that Yitzhak Rabin, the prime minister who was assassinated
in 1995, had given guarantees that Israel would fully withdraw from
the Golan Heights in exchange for security commitments by Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said he would not ``erase the past,'' hinting that he,
too, would be prepared to meet Syria's demand and withdraw down to,
or close to, the shores of the Sea of Galilee if Israel's security
needs were met.
</P>
<P>
   This has been the working assumption of diplomatic analysts
tracking the Israeli-Syrian peace effort _ that a complete
withdrawal to the June 4, 1967, line is the condition for a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Barak himself has repeatedly said he would honor the historical
record in the negotiations with Syria, which have been suspended
since January. But he never before made it clear publicly how the
Israeli government perceived that record, and had been vague about
what he was prepared to do.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli television and radio reporters treated his words as a
revelation. Channel 2 News here said Sunday night, ``It was the
first time that an Israeli prime minister has ever admitted'' that
Israel had agreed _ conditionally _ to a complete withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation was not exactly public. It leaked from a
closed-door cabinet meeting in classic Israeli style. But it leaked
so efficiently, to every Israeli radio and television broadcast,
that it was clearly meant as a roundabout way to start preparing
public opinion for possible concessions.
</P>
<P>
   It was also seen as a signal to Syria that Israel is willing to
talk specifically about borders.
</P>
<P>
   Angry that Israel refused to engage in in-depth discussions
about the possible extent of an Israeli withdrawal, Syria broke off
talks with Israel shortly after their negotiations resumed last
December.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian officials were embarrassed by the leak of a draft treaty
to an Israeli newspaper. The treaty, a working document prepared by
the Americans that summarized both sides' positions, made no
explicit mention of Israel's position on the border line but
revealed concessions on security that Syria was supposedly willing
to make.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, American diplomats have tried to restart the talks.
It is unclear what is going on secretly, but publicly the
relationship between Syria and Israel is characterized by vehement
hostility that in no way resembles a dialogue of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's state-run newspapers have run frequent references to
Israel as ``Nazi-like.'' And Israel has accused Syria of allowing
or even abetting increased guerrilla attacks on Israeli soldiers in
southern Lebanon. These attacks pushed Israel to bomb civilian
targets in Lebanon earlier this month and brought condemnation on
Israel, led by Syria, from the entire Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   What Barak told his cabinet ministers Sunday was that
Israeli-Syrian negotiations conducted by his immediate predecessors
all presumed a withdrawal from the Golan Heights and dealt with the
June 4, 1967, line, said Gadi Baltiansky, his spokesman, confirming
the leaks from the cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Barak appeared to confirm what Syria has long maintained _ that
Rabin had left a ``deposit'' with the Americans, a promise that a
full withdrawal would be undertaken if Syria conceded Israel's
demands on security.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Sunday that Benjamin Netanyahu, his immediate
predecessor, had agreed to withdraw from the Golan down to two
miles from the June 4, 1967, line at one point and ``significantly
less'' than two miles elsewhere, Baltiansky said.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu issued a statement denying this information, which
Barak said came from Ronald Lauder, the American businessman.
Lauder was Netanyahu's emissary to Syria for secret negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that everybody is talking now about a
complete withdrawal from the Golan Heights,'' Housing Minister
Yitzhak Levy said after the cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has pledged to pull out of Lebanon by July, but he
intended to do so as part of an agreement or near agreement with
Syria. Sunday his ministers began facing the possibility that an
agreement might not be reached and examining the risks and timing
of a withdrawal that would take place without Syria's assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
