<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-SOSA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE FIRST DAY, SOSA IS SWINGING, RUNNING AND SLIDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ Demonstrating veteran wiliness, Sammy Sosa stopped
running. The Chicago Cubs were running their post-workout sprints
in the outfield, and Sosa badly trailed the pack. But this was the
last sprint, so Sosa stopped well short of center field, his
destination, spun around and raced back to the right-field line,
easily beating the rest of the players. Then he collapsed to the
ground, exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   For Sosa, the first day of spring training was over Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was running, I was little bit tired,'' Sosa said,
meeting with reporters after he refreshed himself with a shower.
The slugger, however, fared better than his teammate Willie Greene,
who was also on the field for the first time. Sosa made it to the
end of the workout; Greene did not get through stretching
exercises.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently dehydrated, Greene, a third baseman, became
lightheaded and nauseated and had to leave the field. He wound up
in a hospital, receiving two liters of fluid intravenously.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, meanwhile, pumped life into the Cubs' workout, unleashing
a barrage of batting practice home runs reminiscent of his
performances the past two seasons, in which he hit a total of 129
home runs. Only Mark McGwire, with 135, has hit more in two
successive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect him to hit live, but he did,'' Don Baylor, the
Cubs' new manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who came to spring training late because he was recovering
from the flu, started slowly, hardly hitting the ball fair out of
the batting cage with his first 16 swings in four rounds of
hitting. Then he sent 13 balls soaring over the outfield fence in
his next 28 swings, many of the balls landing on Center Street and
menacing traffic. Fans stood behind the fences and scrambled after
the balls, jeopardizing their own well-being as they scooted
between moving vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   No, Sosa said, he was not surprised at the results of his first
batting practice, which lasted 10 rounds and 45 swings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is me; this is my swing,'' he said. ``When you've been
swinging the bat for the last two months, it doesn't surprise me. I
was hitting back home in the Dominican. I don't take long to get
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   In his early swings, he broke three bats. ``That's OK,'' he
said. ``Spring training's like that. The first couple days,
pitchers are trying to make the team. I don't mind breaking a
couple more bats.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Neal did not mind Sosa breaking bats. As he walked from
the hitting field to the running field at Fitch Park, Sosa reached
over a fence and handed the bat to Neal, a 5-year-old fan, who was
seated on her father's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in his workout, Sosa joined his teammates in sliding
practice. Now a player who hits the ball out of the park 66 times
or 63 times does not have to slide into any of the bases as he runs
around them. But Baylor has plans for Sosa, and they require
sliding. The manager wants his home run hitter to steal more bases
than the seven he had last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to take a few more chances,'' Baylor said. ``A lot
of guys will be given the green light to steal a bag if they want
to. He'll be one of the guys. But I'm not stupid. I'm not going to
make him do things he's not comfortable doing. But during the
course of the season, I think he will become a little more
comfortable with what we're trying to accomplish. We're trying to
take the extra base, move up runners. When he sees these other guys
doing it, he'll understand what we're trying to do. He's a very
smart player.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Sosa became the first player in Cubs history to go
30-30, hitting 33 home runs and stealing 36 bases. He reached that
level two years later with 36 homers and 34 steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe that I can steal 30 bases again,'' the
31-year-old Sosa said. ``When I was 30-30, I weighed 198. Now I'm
225, 230. When you gain some weight, you're supposed to become
slow. But I don't believe that. I believe if you know how to steal
bases, you're going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   And furthermore, he said, he's prepared to do what the manager
wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a problem with that,'' he said. ``Anything I can
do for my team to win the game, I'm willing to sacrifice myself and
go out there and do anything I can. If he wants me to steal, I love
to steal. I don't see why not. I'm ready. I came in to do whatever
he wants me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of Sosa's 63 home runs, the Cubs lost 95 games last
season, second most in the National League. That is why Baylor
intends to change the way the Cubs play. But can Sosa hit 60 for a
third successive season?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no limit for myself,'' he said. ``I'm still hungry. I
come back here and forget about what has happened the past two
years. This is a new year. I can't sit down and relax because I've
had two great years. I feel like a rookie. I'm still hungry. When
you're hungry, you're never satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa the past two years has waged scintillating home run battles
with McGwire, who plays for division rival St. Louis. Now Ken
Griffey Jr. has joined the National League Central. Sosa welcomed
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' he said of the trade that put Griffey with
Cincinnati. ``The National League is going to be more exciting
because we got Griffey, Mark and myself. Everybody is waiting for
us to go out there and put on a show.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
