<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0220 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      02-27 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: REGRETS WELL PLACED, IF QUESTIONABLY TIMED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Ill., Dela.)  (With BUSH-BOBJONES) 
(js) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush touched all the right bases
Sunday in expressing regret to Cardinal John O'Connor of New York
over his journey to Bob Jones University: the cardinal is the de
facto leader of the Roman Catholic Church in the United States and
he is widely respected across religious lines.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was determined to muffle the outcry before crucial
primaries in New York, California, Illinois and other states with
large Catholic constituencies. And the Texas governor sent a signal
to voters _ and his contributors _ that he is not too high and
mighty to admit a blunder.
</P>
<P>
   But there was one big problem: Bush's turnabout may have come
about 24 days too late.
</P>
<P>
   For days, Bush has been castigated by Sen. John McCain, his
rival for the Republican presidential nomination, and many of his
own supporters for opening his South Carolina campaign at Bob Jones
on Feb. 2 without condemning the ultraconservative school's
well-known history of forbidding interracial dating and promoting
anti-Catholic teaching. Many party strategists said the controversy
only escalated _ and became even more knotty to overcome _ because
Bush spent days trying to justify his pilgrimage to the university
and did not move quickly to admit his mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's handling of the Bob Jones firestorm underscores one of
his campaign's biggest weaknesses: while Bush and his operatives
are adroit at moving offensively to promote their agenda, they
often seem to linger as controversies swell around them. Last
summer, for example, Bush dragged out a controversy over whether he
used drugs years ago by dancing around the question for days,
modifying his explanations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to prepare themselves to have much quicker rapid
response, which is, in effect, damage control,'' said William Dal
Col, the campaign manager for Steve Forbes, who quit the Republican
race this month. ``If he's the nominee, the Gore people will come
in with brass knuckles and billy clubs.'' Dal Col added that the
apology was ``the right thing to do, but it would have been better
had they done it immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The episode also demonstrates the great degree to which the
McCain operation will go in stoking incidents that reflect poorly
on its opponent. McCain has emphasized that his will not be a
negative campaign. But he himself approved telephone calls to
Catholic voters in Michigan before that state's primary, alerting
them of Bush's visit to Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   The caller said: ``Bob Jones has made strong anti-Catholic
statements, including calling the pope the Antichrist and the
Catholic church a satanic cult. John McCain, a pro-life senator,
has strongly criticized this anti-Catholic bigotry, while Governor
Bush has stayed silent, while gaining the support of Bob Jones
University.''
</P>
<P>
   When the telephone calls first surfaced, McCain insisted that
his campaign had nothing to do with them.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, many of Bush's supporters said he should have
repudiated Bob Jones' policies in his speech, or moved forcefully
within a day or two to put out a letter like the one he sent to
O'Connor. Instead, as recently as Friday he still appeared
defensive _ and seemed to be trying out new explanations _ as he
struggled to move on to other subjects long after the victory in
the South Carolina primary on Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Once Bush's advisers decided they had to move on the Bob Jones
matter, they mulled over several alternatives, like having Bush
submit an explanation to a newspaper's editorial page. But they
settled on the letter to O'Connor, the leader of the archdiocese's
2.4 million Catholics in a state where roughly half the electorate
is Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   By specifically appealing to O'Connor, Bush was clearly trying
to mend relations with New York's Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't win the New York Republican primary without the
Catholic vote _ it can't be done,'' said Kieran Mahoney, a
strategist for Gov. George Pataki, who backs Bush. ``Time will tell
whether the statement will help. On balance, I think it will
because Bush has a fair amount of personal credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The question becomes how quickly Bush can extinguish the
firestorm. That depends in part on how Bush conducts himself. If he
sticks to his words of regret and does not backtrack _ and does not
appear frazzled by more questions about the appearance _ the matter
will blow over faster.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's reversal Sunday was particularly distasteful for him and
his advisers because, they note, many other Republicans (and
Democrats) have spoken at Bob Jones with barely a peep from their
opponents. The list includes Ronald Reagan, Bob Dole and Dan
Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   But to many Republicans, Bush's seeming embrace of the school's
policies was a disturbing contrast to his calls for ``compassionate
conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   The school's president, Bob Jones III, accused the press of
playing up the visit to damage Bush. ``The media hates George Bush
and has said the most unkind and untrue things about BJU in its
attempt to reflect on the governor,'' he said in a statement made
public before Sunday's development.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's advisers were stunned that the visit became such
a huge issue. ``The same people who are hollering about it now were
delighted that we did it at the time, and we won South Carolina by
11 points,'' said Warren Tompkins, Bush's top strategist in South
Carolina. ``We were all a bunch of geniuses on Feb. 19, and now
they're saying we'll all a bunch of idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   More than three weeks after he set foot on the red-carpeted dais
at Bob Jones, Bush is no doubt hoping that, finally, he can move
on. But the Democrats have other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm offended as a Catholic, I'm offended as a supporter of
civil rights; I'm just flat out offended,'' said Sen. Joseph R.
Biden Jr., D-Del. ``It should haunt them. And it will haunt them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
