<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0221 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-MEDIA-930(2T     02-27 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-MEDIA-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPER TUESDAY FORCES ADJUSTMENTS IN MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ With limited resources and a staggering media
challenge _ getting their message out in the 17 states that are
holding primaries in the next nine days _ the four leading
Republicans and Democrats in the race for president are engaged in
a feverish hopscotch of the nation, targeting television markets in
certain states, bypassing others and relying on the ``free media''
supplied by the press to make their cases to a larger extent than
before.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer volume of races _ in states representing 110 million
Americans and 13 of the country's top 25 media markets, including
New York, Los Angeles, Boston, Atlanta, Baltimore and San Francisco
_ has meant a fundamental shift in the way the campaigns are
communicating with the voters.
</P>
<P>
   No longer able to mount a sustained media blitz in a small state
like New Hampshire or South Carolina with the national press corps
as an audience in residence, candidates are being forced to spread
their advertising money so thin that the campaign may not yet be
registering with voters in some of the big states that are holding
primaries on Super Tuesday, March 7.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, neither Gov. George W. Bush of Texas nor Sen. John
McCain of Arizona has begun advertising on television in such
significant and complex Super Tuesday states as Georgia and
Missouri, choosing instead to concentrate on the biggest
battlegrounds: New York, Ohio and California. And even there,
political strategists say, the amounts they have allocated so far
are not close to the fortunes that have to be spent to have much
impact.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bush and McCain have laid out nearly $5 million apiece
for television in five crucial states from Jan. 11 to March 6:
Ohio, California, New York, Washington and Virginia. That McCain is
now matching Bush in television expenditures is an indication of
how far the senator has come; but neither campaign will disclose
how much more it might spend, or whether commercials will be
broadcast in appreciable volume in other Super Tuesday states.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia and Washington hold their primaries on Tuesday. So does
North Dakota, where Bush is unchallenged on the air with almost
$200,000 in commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we've really ever campaigned in Maryland,''
said Howard Opinsky, a McCain campaign spokesman. The omission is
simply a function of too many Super Tuesday states and too little
time and resources, he said. Missouri was also unlikely to be a
focus this week, he said, adding: ``And that's my home state. My
parents are really distraught about that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about big states,'' Opinsky continued, ``but
look, we're now at the stage where it's more of a national
campaign, where voters are going to make up their minds not so much
on local issues but on a gut feeling on the candidates and where
they stand on national issues.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, the emphasis is a little different.
Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, who has yet to win a
primary, is training much of his campaign's energies in Washington
state, where he is spending several days in hopes of securing his
first victory and some momentum, that elusive cachet that gets the
attention of voters and the press.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Berendt, the state's Democratic chairman and a supporter of
Vice President Al Gore, said that Bradley had spent $400,000 early
on television and radio here, and that Gore, playing catch-up, had
now spent about the same amount. (Both campaigns are running
commercials in New York and California but declined, for strategic
purposes, to provide other details.)
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the mother lode of contests on Super Tuesday has
blunted the impact of a big war chest. ``In gross terms, the
amounts of cash on hand sound big, but you need to spread it across
so many media markets,'' said Nelson Warfield, a Republican
consultant who served as Bob Dole's press secretary in 1996.
Indeed, even in delegate-rich states like California, where much of
the advertising money is being spent, the widespread expectation is
that the influence of commercials is going to be more marginal than
in prior years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be a lot of quick judgments made, based on
relatively little information that's generated within California,''
said Mark Baldassare, survey director for the Public Policy
Institute of California, based in San Francisco. ``We're going to
see these four candidates streaking across the state. A couple of
days of the Republicans, a couple of evenings with the Democrats
and that's it: Make up your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   At some level it is alchemy that determines what mix of
advertising and press coverage makes for a winning formula; this
year, too, under-the-radar appeals by direct mail, telephone and
special-interest radio commercials are playing major roles in some
states.
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials in both parties acknowledge that over the next
nine days the war for voters' hearts, particularly on the more
competitive Republican side, will be decided in arenas over which
they have little control: the free or ``earned'' media of local
newscasts, radio talk shows, newspaper columns, political Web sites
and Internet chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an earned media battle,'' said Joe Andrew, national
chairman of the Democratic National Committee. ``To buy a week on
television in Los Angeles alone would cost $800,000 to $900,000,
and they have to fight this on both coasts.'' Mark Miller,
executive director of the moderate Republican Leadership Council,
put it another way: ``For all those voters who said they were sick
of the 30-second commercials, they're about to get their wish.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In such a compressed race, with virtually no time to shape a
message or fashion a comeback if damage is done, the importance of
any event in which voters are able to compare the candidates _ like
the Republican and Democratic debates this week in Los Angeles _
could be greatly magnified. ``Given that voters aren't going to see
a string of debates,'' Baldassare said, ``the debates that do take
place may have just enormous consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Who benefits in this scenario is unclear. As Baldassare pointed
out, ``Mr. McCain's performance in debates has been, shall we say,
uneven.'' And in having to rely more extensively on free media,
Bush, meanwhile, is fully experiencing the downside of unscripted
encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught some of a live interview the other day with Bush on a
local talk-radio station in northern Virginia,'' said Warfield, the
Republican consultant. ``It was clear he wanted to talk about
drawing the liberal-conservative contrast with McCain. Instead, he
found himself answering questions about Bob Jones University. I can
guarantee you, if he were paying for that air time, he wouldn't be
talking about Bob Jones University.''
</P>
<P>
   Even earning the attention is difficult. Martin Kaplan,
associate dean of the Annenberg School of Communication at the
University of Southern California, said that Los Angeles television
stations, for instance, have little appetite for politics. ``Local
stations are superb at weather, sports and crime, but most don't
have political reporters anymore,'' he said. ``They do have
helicopters, so they can follow a motorcade as well as they do a
low-speed car chase.''
</P>
<P>
   To get as much free air time as they can, the campaigns are
using technology wherever possible to expand access. One strategy
is satellite interviews, remote conversations with news anchors in
prized markets. ``We've probably done 50 or 60 satellite interviews
in the March 7 primary states,'' said an aide in one of the
campaigns. ``We set up the satellite and do nine or 10 back to back
to back.''
</P>
<P>
   And of course, in some cases commercials still lead to coverage.
In Seattle, Gore got a lot of mileage out of a spot he began
running this past weekend, a sort of travelogue narrated by an
expert climber, Jim Frush, about scaling Mount Rainier in
Washington last summer with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single Washington state TV station played the entire ad
on their news at 6,'' Chris Lehane, a Gore campaign spokesman, said
triumphantly. ``And then the next morning they interviewed Frush.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
