u s BC-GLF-MATCH-PLAY-NYT &LR;      02-27 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MATCH-PLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARKE DOMINATES WOODS TO WIN $1 MILLION MATCH-PLAY PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ It was the kind of beating that Tiger Woods
has given to many others, but this time, he was on the receiving
end.
</P>
<P>
   As a decided underdog, playing a 36-hole match against the
world's No. 1 player, Darren Clarke believed the odds were against
him, but he also believed in his ability. From the first hole,
Clarke was in charge of his emotions, and he eventually took charge
of the match. With each drive that pierced the fairway, with each
iron shot that flirted with the flagstick, with every birdie putt
that fell, Clarke made another statement that he would not back
away.
</P>
<P>
   During the past year, some opponents have been intimidated by
Woods, and it has hampered their ability to beat him. But Clarke
was inspired, never allowing the situation to suffocate him and
earning a victory that may propel his career to another level.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the Andersen Consulting Match Play Championship, and the
$1 million first-place check, Clarke soundly defeated Woods, 4 and
3, in an eye-opening performance at La Costa Resort &AMP; Spa. Entering
the 64-player tournament as the No. 19 seed, Clarke won six matches
enroute to the title, knocking off Paul Azinger, Mark O'Meara,
Thomas Bjorn, Hal Sutton, David Duval and finally Woods.
</P>
<P>
   That is an impressive list of victims, but Sunday's victory was
Clarke's finest moment. With the match all square after 18 holes in
the morning, Clarke dominated the afternoon with a front-nine
assault from which Woods never recovered. Clarke birdied five of
the first eight afternoon holes to go 4 up, and his lead was never
less than 3 up thereafter. To Clarke, a two-time Ryder Cup player
and a consistent top-10 performer on the European Tour, this
victory confirmed that he can become one of the world's best.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play as solid as I did against Tiger, the best player in
the world, it's a great feeling,'' said Clarke, who rose to No. 14
in the world ranking with the victory. ``The 64 best players in the
world were here this week, and to come out No. 1 is great. I'm not
that old yet, I'm only 31. Hopefully, this will be a stepping stone
and I can improve.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been difficult for Clarke to improve on this
victory. To beat Woods is difficult; to dominate him is rare. But
Woods only led for one hole of the match, and Clarke played
brilliantly, missing only one fairway all day, and missing just
three greens in regulation. There was no miraculous comeback for
Woods, because Clarke never allowed it and because Woods did not
play up to his standards. He missed fairways and greens, he missed
crucial putts, and for one of the few times during the past eight
months, he failed to rise in a spotlight moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darren, to be honest, just flat outplayed me,'' said Woods,
who settled for the runner-up check of $500,000. ``He hit the ball
beautifully, he made a lot of putts. He played beautifully today.
And I just wasn't able to put a lot of pressure on him. I was just
trying to find my golf swing. I did a lot of it with smoke and
mirrors today, just trying to keep myself in the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Clarke was relentless, making birdies on 12 of the 32
holes and never giving Woods an opening. Clarke took the lead for
good in the afternoon on No. 4, the 22nd hole of the match,
sticking an approach shot to five feet, while Woods missed the
green with his second shot, leaving himself a tough chip from thick
rough. Woods' chip shot ran 20 feet past the hole, then he missed
the putt coming back and conceded the hole to Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Though he did not know it, Woods would never get any closer.
Clarke took a 2 up lead on the next hole, hitting another
near-perfect approach shot to 8 feet, then making the putt for
birdie. On the par-3 No. 7, Clarke hit his tee shot to 10 feet,
then made a difficult downhill putt for another birdie. Woods could
have answered with an 8-foot birdie putt, but he missed it, and
that gave Clarke a 3-up lead. And on the next hole, Clarke made it
4 up by making another 8-footer for birdie, after Woods missed a
16-foot birdie attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Woods won the par-5 No. 9 with a birdie and closed to 3 down,
but he gave another hole away on No. 10 with a bogey when he missed
a four and a half foot putt. Then after Woods birdied the par-3 No.
11, hitting a beautiful tee shot to two feet, he dropped another
hole with a bogey at No. 12, hitting his second shot into a
green-side bunker, then hitting a poor bunker shot that stayed in
the bunker. Woods blasted his next shot four and a half feet past
the hole. Then he missed the putt for par, and Clarke played Woods
even the next three holes to close the match.
</P>
<P>
   In victory, Clarke managed to negate two of Woods' advantages _
his length and his stamina. Though Woods outdrove Clarke by at
least 30 yards on many holes, Clarke's terrific approach shots kept
Woods on the defensive. By Clarke hitting first from the fairway,
and getting close to the pin, Woods was forced to aim at the flag,
and because he was not accurate with his irons Sunday, Woods kept
making mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tiger's length was to my benefit,'' Clarke said. ``It
gave me an opportunity to be hitting first into the greens, and as
soon as I got it close, that resulted in pressure on Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clarke is battling a weight problem at around 245
pounds, at least 20 pounds overweight. But while Woods went to the
range between the morning and afternoon sessions, Clarke rested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to walk down the hill again,'' Clarke said,
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke walked down some fairways smoking a cigar, but when he
stood over the ball, he was all business. According to his manager,
Chubby Chandler, Clarke's rotund build is deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not fit, but he's strong,'' Chandler said. ``He needs to
get more fit, but I think the adrenaline playing against Tiger
carried him through.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would do with the money,'' Clarke smiled and said,
``Spend it.''
</P>
<P>
   He had a right to be happy. Clarke wasn't even aware that the
championship match was 36 holes until Saturday afternoon, but he
proved fit enough and good enough to beat the world's best. For
Clarke and Chandler, that was a victory worth celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``British Airways better watch out,'' Chandler said. ``They may
not have enough champagne.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
