<SLUG> BC-SENEGAL-ELECTION-360&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY RESULTS IN SENEGAL INDICATE TIGHT RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAKAR, Senegal _ The results of this West African nation's
presidential election began trickling in Sunday night a few hours
after polling stations closed, showing a close race between the two
men most favored to lead Senegal for the next seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's election was considered a turning point in the history
of Senegal. For the first time, it was not clear what the outcome
would be, and voters were given a choice among four credible
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The race was too close to determine whether either of the top
two runners had garnered the 50 percent of the votes necessary to
win in the first round. Officials for President Abdou Diouf, who is
seeking his fourth consecutive term, said they believed that the
candidate could still muster the votes required to prevent a
run-off against Abdoulaye Wade, of the Democratic Party of Senegal.
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday, after casting his vote in central Dakar, Diouf was
asked about his chances of winning in the first round. He
responded: ``Only God knows that.'' But Wade sounded a combative
note at his home late Sunday night, insisting that Diouf could win
in the first round only by rigging votes. ``I believe I should win
in the first round,'' Wade said.
</P>
<P>
   An independent National Observatory for Elections, which
supervised Sunday's election, said the voting had been generally
free and fair. About 2.7 million people in this country of 9
million had been registered to vote.
</P>
<P>
   International observers from Europe and Africa also monitored
Sunday's vote, and there were no reports so far of widespread
irregularities. In general, international observers have said that
elections in Senegal have improved over the years in transparency,
and the 1998 legislative election was considered free and fair by
all participants.
</P>
<P>
   There were only a few reports of the violence that had marred
the last days of the campaign. The one exception was the southern
region of Casamance, where a separatist movement has operated for
20 years and where shots and rockets were reportedly fired in one
town. On Friday, a Socialist Party official was killed by a mob in
Casamance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Here in the capital _ where the opposition has traditionally had
greatest support and which Wade handily won _ calls for change were
heard often Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so tired of having the same government for 40 years,''
said Boubacar Diallo, 35, an artist voting in the neighborhood of
Diacksao. ``This government has been practicing ballot-box coups,''
he added, voicing a popular opinion that the ruling party had
rigged past elections.
</P>
<P>
   But the Socialist Party remained particularly strong outside
Dakar and the other cities, and it enjoyed the organizational
advantages of uninterrupted rule since independence from France in
1960.
</P>
<P>
   Seizing on the electorate's possible weariness after four
decades of the Socialist Party, the presidential candidates
emphasized the need for change, though none offered any detailed
vision how to accomplish that during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even Diouf talked of change, as his French campaign and media
managers subtly tried to tap into the mood without sacrificing the
man. ``Together, let's change Senegal,'' read billboards showing
Diouf with two children.
</P>
<P>
   Senegal, which has never suffered the military coups or rule
that afflicted most of its neighbors, was one of the first African
nations to introduce multi-party politics in the 1970s under its
first president, Leopold Senghor, also a famous poet.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the presidency never shifted away from the
Socialist Party. Diouf, who had served for a decade under Senghor
as his prime minister, became president in 1981. Diouf found his
foil in Wade _ the archetypal opposition figure seen in many other
African nations, although enjoying genuine and wide support
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The two men fought in three previous elections for the
presidency, the last time in 1993. In recent years, the Socialist
Party was weakened by the defection of heavyweight members, who had
hoped to succeed Diouf one day but whose ambitions had apparently
been derailed. Two of them, Djibo Ka and Moustapha Niasse, were
candidates Sunday, although given little chance of victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
