<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0226 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-WASH-970&AMP;ADD-     02-27 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-WASH-970&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WASHINGTON, BRADLEY STUMPS LIKE A WINNER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley never seems to hit his
oratorical stride until about midafternoon, so it was shocking to
see him stroll into an ornate hotel lobby packed with supporters at
9:30 a.m. recently and bellow with unusual verve, ``Good morning,
Spokane!''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley then gave one of the punchiest, most compelling stump
speeches of his campaign. Afterward, the crowd enveloped him as he
pecked cheeks, signed autographs and grasped every hand until none
were left. Eileen Davis was so moved by the event that tears welled
in her eyes as she shook his hand. ``Thank you for your charisma,''
she said, using a word not often applied to the staid and stoic
insurgent.
</P>
<P>
   Though he trails badly in most polls, is surrounded by advisers
resigned to his defeat and is opposed at every turn by his own
party's establishment, Bradley is still managing to run a spirited
campaign in this state, where he has staked his underdog hopes on a
victory in Tuesday's nonbinding primary.
</P>
<P>
   With a lightness that had been notably missing in recent weeks,
Bradley has been working harder than ever at the small gestures of
winning votes: tossing jelly doughnuts to workers on a picket line
in Spokane, dishing chili to supporters in downtown Seattle,
patiently enduring hours of questions from undecided voters at
late-night town meetings. He has even called the reporters who
cover his Democratic rival, Vice President Al Gore, playfully
cajoling them to write about him.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, he has shown few signs that he feels defeated,
despite Gore's double-digit lead in most polls. At a moment when
other politicians might become frantic or sullen, Bradley has
remained quintessentially himself: calm, self-possessed, almost
aggressively unruffled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every candidate creates his own problems,'' said Sen. Bob
Kerrey, D-Neb., who stumped with Bradley here on Saturday. ``But
when it comes to all the problems beyond his control, he's
suffering them very well.''
</P>
<P>
   There certainly have been more than enough problems to get him
down, not the least of which has been the continuing ability of the
Republican maverick, Sen. John McCain, to grab attention from his
campaign. Yet Bradley has more often than not displayed the loose,
jokey informality that marked his style months ago, when things
seemed less dire.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for instance, his staff instructed him to pose alone
for photographers on a pier overlooking Puget Sound and the
snow-capped Olympic Mountains. Pointing with mock solemnity at the
scene, he wryly declared, ``That's water.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he joked with reporters: ``That would be considered a
manufactured moment.'' And when he was introduced to an
environmental activist dressed in a salmon suit, he told her,
``Keep on swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Bradley has even donned clothes to express his
more unbuttoned mood, replacing his rumpled blue and gray suits
with green or brown V-neck sweaters, open-collar shirts and khaki
pants.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's energy level can fluctuate with the size and
enthusiasm of a crowd, and he has had some unexpectedly large ones
here. On Friday, more than 1,200 people packed into a ferry
terminal in Bellingham to hear him make the kind of upbeat speech
that typified his events last fall. He was animated and engaging
and the crowd responded, laughing at his well-worn jokes and
applauding raucously at just the right moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems the most presidential, the most dignified of the
candidates,'' Kris Berger, 35, said after the speech.
</P>
<P>
   The following morning in Spokane, Bradley gave a stump speech
abundantly salted with the kinds of punchy applause lines that his
speeches have often lacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can we do, what must we do, to leave no one behind?'' he
asked a hushed room. ``The people of Spokane who are earning under
$14,000 a year work too hard, care too much, deserve more, and
we're going to get them more.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there have been lost moments. On Saturday, he was to give
a speech laying out the differences between his health care plan
and Gore's outside a Seattle health clinic. The address was as
sharp and clear as any Bradley has given on the subject. But in the
cold drizzle, only about 60 people came out, despite his staff's
last-minute efforts to round up people on the street. And a visibly
disappointed Bradley delivered his prepared text in a stiff
monotone.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, Bradley gave a rendition of his standard
speech on race relations to the Seattle chapter of the NAACP that
failed to even mention his hosts. Even some of his supporters in
the half-filled banquet hall found his performance listless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I detected that maybe he was a bit tired,'' said Hubert Sims,
a 50-year-old banker who says he will vote for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   But more often than not, Bradley seems energized by his hunt for
votes. At a town meeting at Everett Community College on Friday, he
was as patient as a town councilman answering dozens of questions
and more than a few complaints, including one from a student who
said federal budget cuts had worsened his urinary tract infections.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he faced a more contentious crowd at Evergreen
College, known as a bastion of student radicalism, where he was
peppered with questions about trade policy, global warming,
American Indian rights and the price of a gallon of milk. (``About
$1.68,'' he answered.)
</P>
<P>
   The students booed when he said he opposed legalizing drugs and
hissed when he said he supported sanctions against Iraq. But he
took more questions than his staff wanted him to, and won the
respect of more than a few in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was really good,'' said Richard Myers, 20, a
junior. ``This is a difficult crowd to handle and he did a good
job.'' Still, Bradley did not quite close the deal with Myers, who
said he might vote for Ralph Nader on the Green Party line.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though his days are packed with events, Bradley still tries to
maintain the sort of loping pace that he seems to find more
comfortable. Sunday morning, after giving a speech on race
relations before more than 500 parishioners at an African Methodist
Episcopal church in Seattle, Bradley remained in his pew to watch a
play about slavery, even though he was scheduled to be at another
event.
</P>
<P>
   When an usher came by to ask if he was ready to go, Bradley
simply signaled to her with his hand: wait.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who can lose his temper in private, has managed to keep
his cool in public despite the pressure-cooker atmosphere of the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In New York early last week, for instance, Bradley was cut off
during live interviews with television stations in Oregon and
California. Both times, the lost satellite feeds ruined the
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose by 1,000 votes in San Francisco,'' Bradley began to
say after the second lost feed. And an aide finished his sentence,
``I'll take the blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Calmly, without apparent anger or dismay, Bradley simply
replied, ``That won't help me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
