<HEADLINE>
UMPIRES AND BASEBALL START THEIR NEGOTIATIONS TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Richie Phillips, the major league umpires' newly
deposed labor leader, formulated a mass resignation strategy last
July in an effort to induce baseball officials to begin early
negotiations for a new labor agreement. Seven months later, those
talks will begin, without Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   John Hirschbeck, a 17-year American League umpire, who was
elected Sunday to a three-year term as president of the World
Umpires Association, and Joe Brinkman, who was elected vice
president, will join the new union's lawyer, Joel Smith of
Baltimore, in meeting Monday with three officials of Major League
Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think baseball would like to get something done before
opening day and we'd like to get something done before opening
day,'' Hirschbeck said after the umpires' meeting. ``It would be
nice to start the season with a contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Representing Major League Baseball will be two executive vice
presidents, Rob Manfred, the top labor executive, and Sandy
Alderson, the baseball operations chief, and Ralph Nelson, an
Alderson assistant, who will oversee the umpiring staff. Baseball
wants to merge the separate league staffs into the commissioner's
office, and that will be a topic of negotiation. It is not expected
to be a difficult one.
</P>
<P>
   These will be the first talks for an umpires union that Phillips
will not lead. He had served as the head of the Major League
Umpires Association since 1978. But Phillips' union lost in an
election last November, and the National Labor Relations Board
certified the new union as the umpires' collective bargaining
representative on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires, mostly from the American League, who joined
Hirschbeck and Brinkman in the move to oust Phillips and the old
union, wanted a less confrontational approach to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The old contract expired on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck said 48 of the 71 umpires have joined the new union.
The holdouts are National League umpires who continued to support
Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to be open to all umpires and we welcome them,''
Hirschbeck said. ``We'd like them to join us. We will all continue
to encourage them to join us.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not they join the new union, the umpires will be
represented by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go in and try to get the best contract we can for all of
the umpires,'' Hirschbeck said.
</P>
<P>
   The one-sided nature of the membership of the new union was
reflected in the election of officers Sunday. The 39 umpires who
attended elected Hirschbeck and Brinkman plus Tim Welke as
secretary-treasurer and six members of the board of directors _
Larry Young, Tim McClelland, Rocky Roe, Jeff Nelson, Bill Welke and
Fielding Culbreth. All but Nelson are A.L. umpires. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
