<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-VANHORN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS' VAN HORN PUTS AGGRESSIVENESS INTO HIS GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Midway through the fourth quarter
Saturday night, Charlotte Hornets forward Derrick Coleman found his
spot just outside the lane, set himself and turned for a routine
jump shot. But as he released the shot, the long arm of Keith Van
Horn suddenly rose in front of him, snapping the ball back over
Coleman's head.
</P>
<P>
   Before Coleman could wipe the surprised look off of his face,
Van Horn was making long strides down the other end of the floor,
catching a pass from Kerry Kittles and authoritatively slamming the
ball through the rim as players ducked underneath.
</P>
<P>
   The aggressive play might have surprised Coleman, as well as the
18,481 fans at the Continental Arena, who watched Van Horn help the
Nets to a 104-93 victory. But for Van Horn, it may have had its
roots in a darkened video room, with Nets assistant coach Jim Lynam
showing the third-year forward the subtle flaws in his game.
</P>
<P>
   The two watched the tape from the previous game against Miami
earlier this week, a game in which he shot just 7 of 20 from the
floor, and Lynam held his thumb and forefinger just a sliver apart,
telling Van Horn that the slight gap is all that was separating
makes and misses. The lesson was to attack, to finish plays with
aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   While it worked once, the Nets and Van Horn can only hope that
the lessons stick, particularly with the next test coming Monday
night in Utah. For the Nets, it represents the beginning of an
arduous five-game trip. For Van Horn, it is his first time back as
a professional to the state where he became a local hero as a
collegiate star.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes proved helpful Saturday. But the next test for Van
Horn will come against Karl Malone, as rugged a task as his
new-found aggressiveness can find.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just saw that I was getting to the basket easily,'' Van Horn
said. ``I need to, instead of trying to finesse so much, be more
aggressive in taking it to the basket, get fouled, take it at the
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nets Coach Don Casey said: ``They made up a tape and I think
that helped, and also the fact that he caught the ball and made his
decision quickly. The defense didn't have time to hone in.''
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken Van Horn has absorbed some criticism this season
for his play, particularly at the end of games. But in the fourth
quarter against the Hornets, he scored 12 of his 29 points. He even
found himself being judged for his decision to remain home with his
wife in New Jersey two weeks ago following the birth of their
daughter rather than fly to Atlanta for that night's game.
</P>
<P>
   But, unlike Stephon Marbury, whose homecoming in Minnesota last
week was marked by ill will from the bitter crowd, this trip to
Utah will likely be a happy event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking forward to it,'' said Van Horn, who runs a
business in Utah that organizes basketball camps for children.
``It's a big basketball town. I still go there every summer, I have
a camp there, I'm still involved in the community to a certain
extent. My wife's family is from there and they all live there. A
lot of my folks' friends are there. I have my business there.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps that he and the Nets are hardly believed to pose a
threat to Malone and the Jazz. But if he plays with the
aggressiveness that he exhibited on Saturday, even family might be
booing him by the time he leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a quality win, especially with some of the teams we
have coming up,'' Van Horn said of Saturday's victory. ``We have
San Antonio, Utah, a good, young Denver team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our last road trip was disastrous. We lost those
buzzer-beaters. We lost to the Clippers. So I think we need to
prove to ourselves we can go on the road for a lengthy period of
time and win. It's a big challenge for us and we need to step up to
the challenge.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
