<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0229 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-KNOBLAUCH-N     02-27 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-KNOBLAUCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOBLAUCH OPENS THE BASE PATHS FOR ALL THE YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Chuck Knoblauch exuded a baserunning arrogance
when he played for the Minnesota Twins, striding purposefully off
first base, far away from the bag. His body language screamed to
pitchers and catchers that he was going to run, and that there was
not much anybody could do about it.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch muted that part of his game in his first two years
with the Yankees, but he worked the entire off-season to recover
his intimidating presence on the bases, and he intends to run often
this year. Manager Joe Torre wants all of the Yankees to be more
aggressive on the bases, something he has stressed in the first
workouts of spring training, and all of his players will have the
option of stealing bases any time they choose in the exhibition
games.
</P>
<P>
   Green lights for everybody: For Derek Jeter, who is still
developing the confidence to run; for Paul O'Neill, who can steal
10-15 bases a year by using his experience; for Bernie Williams,
whose exceptional speed has not translated into many stolen bases;
and for Ricky Ledee and Scott Brosius and Roberto Kelly, and anyone
else who sees an opportunity to place stress on the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to let them run at will and do what they want,''
said Torre. ``I told them, `Go out there, let me see your
decisions.' I'd rather have to explain to them why that was a bad
decision than not finding out what their capabilities are. Once
they prove it to themselves that they can run, then they develop
their confidence, and it's contagious.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidently so. Torre stressed aggressiveness in spring training
in 1998 and the Yankees opened that season seemingly in full
sprint, a lineup of larcenists, swiping 40 bases in the first month
of the year; they constantly pushed for the extra base, charging
from first to third, from first to home. Late that year, as
defenses began to concentrate more on limiting their leads, the
Yankees stopped running, and tended to hold their ground and wait
for a big hit.
</P>
<P>
   And they never really regained the brazenness last year, when
they did not register their 40th stolen base until June 12, six
weeks later than in 1998. Jeter was banging hits all over the place
and Knoblauch tended to wait at first for those hits, and with
O'Neill struggling, Jeter often stayed at first base, his feeling
being that the first baseman would have to hold him and O'Neill
would have a bigger hole to hit through on the right side of the
infield.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, Torre and third base coach Willie Randolph feel, the
Yankees just lost that aggressive attitude. They want that mindset
restored this year, ``and that starts at the top,'' Torre said _
with Knoblauch and Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch averaged 51 stolen bases in his last three years with
the Minnesota Twins, and in his first two years with the Yankees,
he averaged 40 stolen-base attempts. Knoblauch has not really
looked to run, and many times, he appeared more concerned with
making a mistake, taking tentative leads off first base.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to change this year. On those many warm days in New
York last November and December, Knoblauch went to Yankee Stadium
to work on his running, to strengthen his legs, and when the
weather turned cold, he did his form running in a spacious gym on
the West Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In his first two years with the Yankees, Knoblauch arrived in
spring training with his chest and shoulders thick from weight
training, in excellent physical condition. Randolph noticed he
looks much different this year, toned from the running _ in better
condition to play baseball, to steal bases, to be aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get back to running,'' Knoblauch said. ``Each
year that goes by, I'm a little more comfortable. My first two
years, I've felt like I've always gone from first to third well and
taken chances, and hopefully, I can get back to putting pressure
and stealing bases.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter stole 30 bases in 1998 and went into last year with an eye
on swiping 40, but he had just 27 attempts, and often, it was easy
to tell from his actions at first base whether he was serious about
running. Jeter picked his spots in '99, wanting to keep the
first-base hole open for O'Neill and Bernie Williams, the hitters
who followed him _ and the Yankees staff wants their runners to try
to be intelligent, rather than reckless, about when they run.
</P>
<P>
   But they do not want baserunners intent on holding their ground
for the benefit of the hitter behind them. If you want to help the
hitter behind you, Randolph said rhetorically, ``then get to second
base and let him drive you in from there.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill is 37 and does not possess great speed, but Randolph
says O'Neill breaks from a base and reaches his optimal speed as
quickly as any large-framed person he has seen. Williams might be
the fastest Yankee running first to third or first to home, but he
seems to lose milliseconds when leading off first base, at that
moment when the pitcher begins his motion homeward and Williams
needs to break for second. With speed like that of Jeter and
Williams, Randolph said, ``You don't have to have the perfect jump.
You just need to get a decent lead and break, and still beat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like O'Neill, Ledee could steal 10 to 15 bases, but Randolph
thinks Ledee needs to make adjustments in the way he takes leads,
in the way his body is balanced at the time he needs to make his
break. Ledee, too, tends to raise the upper half of his body first
and then move forward _ imagine a sprinter doing this _ and this is
something that can rob him of quick first steps. Brosius is a smart
baserunner with decent speed, but Randolph is looking for him to
stay lower.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have lost some of their bench speed over the last
two years, with the trades of Homer Bush and Chad Curtis. Kelly, a
non-roster invitee expected to make the club, probably will help:
He has 235 steals in his career, with a high success rate of 74
percent on his attempts. The Yankees will look to steal third more
often, something that many teams have begun to try with more
regularity in the last few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to try to get back that element to our game
and try to take advantage of it,'' Randolph said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
