<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0233 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-MATCHPLAY-HNS &LR;      02-27 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MATCHPLAY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
CARLSBAD, Calif. _ What a change of pace this must have been for
Tiger Woods, what with the spike marks on the other backside for a
change.
<TEXT>
<P>
   So many times as an amateur and pro, the world's best player and
match-play devotee had kicked his opponent into submission with
cold-blooded disregard in this format.
</P>
<P>
   But in the final of the Andersen Consulting Match Play
Championship on Sunday, it was Woods' turn to get trampled.
Northern Ireland's Darren Clarke unleashed a torrid stretch of
birdies to draw away from Woods on the second 18 holes for a
4-and-3 victory and a $1 million paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   Just call it a rare victory for those who like to pump pints
instead of iron.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke's physique is such that you half-expected ABC to go to a
station break while his swing made the wide path around his gut.
But the portly fellow with the carefree attitude and wry sense of
humor stayed even with Woods during a hotly contested first 18
holes, then turned up the heat by shooting 5-under-par 31 on the
front nine of the afternoon round in the 36-hole finale at La Costa
Resort.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke might never enter the gym now that he has proved a person
of girth can get the best of somebody as chiseled as Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play against Tiger, the No. 1 player in the world, and come
out on top is a great feeling,'' said Clarke, who added the week's
worth of golf was the best he has ever performed on a daily basis
over an extended period.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke's win Sunday meant he had taken down Woods and David
Duval _ the world's No. 1 and No. 2 players _ on consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if a win like this in a World Golf Championships event
would motivate him off the golf course as well as on it, Clarke
said: ``What are you trying to get at? That I have a fat gut? Is
that what you are trying to say?''
</P>
<P>
   Cracking a smile as he said it, Clarke didn't mind being the
butt of the joke, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to start working on my weight,'' he said. ``I have to
get in better shape. I was very lax about it over the winter.''
</P>
<P>
   But the regimen didn't start immediately, said Chubby Chandler,
Clarke's manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``British Airways might not have enough champagne for him
tonight,'' Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke was listed in British bookmaking as a 66-1 long shot
before the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darren flat-out outplayed me,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing else mattered. After the morning half of the finale
ended with the match even, Clarke birdied five of the first eight
holes in the afternoon and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has a 12-4 individual match-play record as a professional,
in addition to his amateur success in this format.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wasn't able to put a lot of pressure on him,'' Woods
said. ``I only hit one good shot in the afternoon. I did it
(played) with a lot of smoke and mirrors just to keep myself in the
ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he thought he gave himself a chance to win the match
even though he didn't think he played well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't played that bad for that long since Sunday at
Disney when I had a chance to win,'' Woods said. ``I shot 73 in the
last round and still won.''
</P>
<P>
   But in reality, he spent most of the afternoon on the ropes
before finally suffering the knockout blow. Even Woods' best might
not have been enough Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   If Woods was looking for a turning point, he could have picked
out two holes in the afternoon. First, on the 10th, Woods
three-putted from 35 feet, giving Clarke the hole with a par to go
4-up.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after winning the 11th hole, Woods was in the greenside
bunker on the par-5 12th with his second shot. But he took four
shots to get down and lost the hole, again to Clarke's par. Woods
left his first sand shot in the bunker, then couldn't get up and
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``On No. 10, I had the opportunity to put the approach close,
and to not put that shot inside of his and put some pressure on him
was frustrating,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of winning the hole, Woods lost it, essentially putting
him in a must-win situation on every ensuing hole.
</P>
<P>
   Woods had shown a little gamesmanship during the first 18 holes.
On the 13th hole, Woods made Clarke putt an 18-incher for par and
to halve of the hole. Clarke tapped in, then smiled at Woods as if
to say, ``Did you really think I was going to miss that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was messing with me there,'' Clarke said. ``I asked him if
we were playing medal play. But he was all right.''
</P>
<P>
   On the next hole, Woods had a one-footer for par. Clarke
conceded the putt.
</P>
<P>
   On the first nine holes of the day, which started in light fog
in the cool morning air, Woods and Clarke combined for 10 birdies,
five pars and three bogeys. Still, nobody led by more than a hole,
and Woods led for only one hole in the entire match.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Clarke took charge when he rolled in a 15-foot birdie
putt on the par-3 seventh to go 3-up. His lead never was less than
that the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   He closed it out in grand fashion, making a beautiful
up-and-down from the bunker on the par-3 14th and a routine par on
the 15th to clinch it.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke missed only one fairway and two greens during the 33
holes Sunday and was 11 under par. He made only one bogey, on the
fifth hole in the morning 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come over here (to the United States) quite a few times
and haven't fared that well,'' said Clarke, who won for the first
time on U.S. soil. ``I've had the potential these past few years.
But I've never actually finished the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think I was 11 under par for the whole play. To play as
well as that under the circumstances, and against the best player
in the world, certainly is very gratifying.'' &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
