<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
 GUARD'S DEVELOPMENT GIVES UT HOPES FOR A LONG
MARCH (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By MIKE JONES
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Ironically for a shooting guard, Darren Kelly's
favorite memory of a game-winning shot is by someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Flash back to last season's NJCAA Division II national
championship game. Kelly's team _ Brown Mackie (Kan.) College _ is
down by a point in the waning seconds. Kelly takes a pass and
penetrates the Danville (Ill.) Area CC zone defense, which
immediately converges. Seeing no opening for a clear shot, Kelly
quickly whips a pass back out to teammate Jay Rhodes, who knocks
down a 3-point shot that decides the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called it the assist of my life,'' said Kelly, who was
named the tournament's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of play-making ability is what Texas coach Rick Barnes
has been looking for most of the season from one of what has become
primarily a four-guard backcourt rotation _ someone other than
point guard Ivan Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes believes he found that individual on a recent afternoon
in Missouri, when he, in essence, put the ball in Kelly's hands
late in the second half. Kelly responded with 13 points in a
crucial 66-63 road victory. He has scored in double figures three
times in four games since and averaged 13 points a game, leading
Barnes to believe that he has found another reliable weapon as the
Longhorns begin to focus on tournament play.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for us to be the team we need to be in March, Darren
is a major player,'' Barnes said. ``I knew we had to get some guy
on the perimeter to give us some good numbers and he was the guy we
felt could do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darren can score in a lot of different ways. He's quick, he
has a good mid-range game, he can shoot from the perimeter and he's
learned to take the ball to the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes in particular likes Kelly's acumen in crunch-time
situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not afraid to take big shots,'' Barnes said with
appreciation. ``The hotter the situation, the better he likes it.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Barnes has put so much faith in him in February
has given Kelly, who averaged almost 22 points a game last season,
added assurance to relax and play his game after what was a
difficult assimilation into Barnes' style of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel good that coach Barnes has that type
confidence in me,'' Kelly said. ``He's been telling me all this
time that I had this potential, but I wasn't stepping up and doing
the things I needed to do. But now I'm getting more comfortable and
I've grown to have a lot more confidence in him. At first, I wasn't
buying into what he was saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider that Kelly, a product of inner-city Washington
basketball, has always been the offensive focus of his teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always played on a guard-oriented team,'' Kelly
explained. ``In junior college, I was The Guard. I created and
scored. But this team plays off Chris Mihm and Gabe Muoneke and
\Rearly\S I was trying to do things that weren't characteristic of
this team and I was hurting us, basically. Now, I cater to the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shots I've been making are good shots for me and coach
Barnes has been telling me to get more open looks. What I've been
doing helps the big guys, and that's the main thing. I complement
what they do. Other teams have to respect \Rdefensively\S what I've
been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Mihm, who has to depend on the Longhorns' guard play to
alleviate double and sometimes triple-team pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darren has been stepping up big-time,'' Mihm said. ``He's
playing with so much more confidence and that has been fun to see.
Coach has put it on Darren because of the fact that he's so quick,
a driver and a slasher and that's what we need. Both he and Will
\RClay\S have done a great job penetrating, whether it's shooting
the mid-range jump shot or getting to the basket. If we get those
kinds of good shots _ soft shots on the rim _ we'll clean up \Rwith
put-backs\S on those.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes continues to call Wagner the team's most valuable player.
Clay has proved to be the backcourt's defensive stopper as Kelly
has added needed offensive punch. Lawrence Williams hasn't been
able to establish any consistency after missing early playing time
because of a groin pull, but is capable of knocking down long-range
shots when he's on.
</P>
<P>
   The sum total is that as March approaches, Barnes feels much
better about his backcourt than he did a season ago, when Wagner
was playing too many minutes on a bad knee and the team simply ran
out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a totally different team,'' Barnes said. ``I have
confidence in our guards and it's no secret that when they're
playing well, we play our best basketball. Now, we're not so
one-dimensional. A year ago, we were.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
