 RANGERS REJECT TRADE OFFERS FOR
CATALANOTTO (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) BY T.R.
SULLIVAN c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Exhibition games haven't begun yet, but
trade talks are starting up. The Rangers have had three National
League teams call with interest in infielder Frank Catalanotto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said no,'' Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said.
``I told them we like his bat, he gives us a little bit of depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Catalanotto, a left-handed hitter, is a career .276 hitter with
34 doubles, 17 homers and 63 runs batted in in 525 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers need Catalanotto because they're not sure how many
games Luis Alicea will be able to play at second base. Alicea
played in a career-high 132 games in 1995, and that has steadily
decreased since. Last year he was bothered by a pulled hamstring
muscle and injured wrist that required surgery after the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are also going to take a long look at Edwin Diaz at
second base. Diaz was once a former top Rangers prospect who was
lost to the Arizona Diamondbacks in the 1997 expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin and manager Johnny Oates said Diaz is the best defensive
second baseman in camp, and he increased his value as a utility
player last year by playing 44 games at shortstop for the
Diamondbacks' Triple-A team in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   He also hit .311 for Tucson but walked only 17 times and struck
out 77 in 415 at-bats. Melvin said that is holding Diaz back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll drive the ball and get some hits, but his plate
discipline is not too good,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   But Melvin said Diaz has a chance to make the team, ``If he can
show us he can play shortstop on a part-time basis.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be an advantage. Catalanotto's best defensive
position is first base. He's considered adequate defensively at
second and third, but he's not considered a shortstop. Greer's
agent due Outfielder Rusty Greer's agent, Bo McKinnis, is due in
Port Charlotte today and is expected to meet with Doug Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have expressed an interest in signing Greer to a
long-term extension beyond 2001, but any talks right now are
preliminary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're going to chat, but that's about it,'' Greer
said.
Cannon arm Johnny Oates said center fielder Ruben Mateo may have
the best throwing arm in baseball. But there is a problem when
throwing to home plate.
</P>
<P>
   The pitcher's mound.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielders try to make their throws to the plate on one bounce.
Oates said if Mateo's throw to home plate bounces too close to the
catcher, it's going rocket right past him.
</P>
<P>
   But if he hits the pitcher's mound's the ball's going to bounce
high in the air and over the catcher's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws it that hard,'' Oates said. ``I'm afraid if Pudge
\RRodriguez\S has to jump for the ball, that runner is going to
look at Pudge's ribcage and say, `I've got a chance to take Pudge
Rodriguez out of the game.' I want Pudge down low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruben's got to know how to harness that arm.''
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Rafael Palmeiro was given permission to miss
yesterday's workout to attend to a personal matter in Miami. He's
expected back today.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Mike Venafro, sidelined with a strained ligament in his
left middle finger, is expected to throw off a mound today for the
first time in camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have two more days of pitchers throwing batting
practice before the first intrasquad game Wednesday. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
