 SMU SEARCHING FOR TOURNAMENT BID (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) By JOHNNY PAUL c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Opinions vary regarding a potential NCAA Tournament
berth for SMU's men's basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   This one comes from TCU coach Billy Tubbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question about it,'' said Tubbs,
whose Horned Frogs dealt the Mustangs one of their five losses this
season. ``I would almost think they're a lock regardless of what
they do from here on out. I really believe SMU should be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, SMU's fate likely depends on what it accomplishes this week
at Moody Coliseum and during the Western Athletic Conference
Tournament, scheduled for March 9-11 in Fresno, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, deserving and reality, as he knows, too, are two
different things,'' Mustangs coach Mike Dement said. ``I think
we've got to find 2-4 more wins. I think we're going to have to do
that. I'd like to think were deserving, but we've got more work to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   It will not be an easy chore for the Mustangs (21-5), who will
put their five-game winning streak on the line against the Horned
Frogs (15-13, 6-6) tonight at Moody Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   SMU can share the WAC regular-season title if it beats TCU and
Tulsa (26-3, 11-2) in its regular-season finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing our two toughest opponents,'' Dement said. ``I
think these two teams have given us the most problems
matchup-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU beat SMU, 92-75, on Jan. 29 in Fort Worth, and the Mustangs
lost at Tulsa five days later, 70-59.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to play so much differently than we did
before,'' Dement said. ``I'm hoping and wondering if we can do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   SMU also will be forced to overcome a nine-day layoff since its
83-81 victory at UT-El Paso, and Dement admits being ``worried
about being rusty.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA selection committee will not concern itself with SMU's
layoff, not with so many programs on the bubble to reach the
tournament's 64-team field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only about 6-8 spots, and there are about 25
schools,'' Dement said. ``Many of them are in the power
conferences. I think the committee will be looking for reasons to
start knocking people out to get it down to one or two because
there are so many.''
</P>
<P>
   The WAC lost its automatic bid to the NCAA Tournament after
eight of its members departed and formed the Mountain West
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   So, SMU and a slew of others _ Arizona State, Brigham Young,
Notre Dame, Louisville, DePaul, Wake Forest, Pepperdine, Gonzaga,
Utah State and Fresno State among others _ remain in search of the
NCAA Tournament's 35 at-large berths.
</P>
<P>
   SMU is ranked 38th in one version of the power ratings, and
Fresno State (19-9, 9-3) could be the Mustangs' chief obstacle
should the WAC receive only two NCAA berths. The Bulldogs were
ranked 39th in the same power ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've had a really good year because we've taken some
steps like beating Fresno State,'' Dement said. ``We've gotten to
20 wins, and we've never done that since I've been here. I think
we've had a good year, but what we need is a special year.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens this week likely will determine that.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
