<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
 RANGERS SEEKING IMPROVED GLOVE WORK (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) By T.R. SULLIVAN c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The Rangers made a strong push to improve
their pitching in the off-season. The moves could prove to be in
vain if they don't play better defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' defense, a point of pride with manager Johnny
Oates, has fallen off the past three years after leading the
American League in fielding in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   They've finished ninth in fielding the past three years, a
disappointing statistic for a team that is trying to emphasize
pitching and defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something I've talked to Johnny about where we have to
be better at,'' general manager Doug Melvin said. ``We have to play
better defense to make the pitching better.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates' goal every year is to have his team commit less than 100
errors, and the Rangers set a club record with 87 errors in 1996.
But they've averaged 120 errors per season since, including 119
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '96, I don't think we had any careless errors,'' Oates
said. ``We focused on catching the ball and throwing the ball.
There's no doubt in my mind we had at least 25 careless errors last
season. We need to get back to focusing on catching the ball and
throwing it and taking pride in defense.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the personnel changes in the off-season, Oates and
Melvin believe there are some reasons why the Rangers could be
better defensively this season. It's starts on the left side of the
infield, where Royce Clayton and Todd Zeile combined to commit 50
errors, the most by a shortstop-third base combination in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton, normally a strong defensive shortstop, was bothered by
an injured right shoulder for most of the first half of the season.
He needed three weeks on the disabled list in May and didn't reach
full strength until after the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it affected him a little bit,'' infield coach Bucky
Dent said. ``He was a lot better and played great in the second
half.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also insist they'll be better at third base despite
the risk of bringing in Mike Lamb from Double A to replace an
11-year veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile, a converted catcher, made a number of spectacular plays
last year but also committed many of his errors on routine
grounders. The Rangers are counting on Lamb to change that, even
though he committed 28 errors in 137 games with the Tulsa Drillers
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw him before last year, but he was outstanding the
first half,'' Drillers manager Bobby Jones said. ``He made just
eight errors. Second half, he started making a couple of errors and
started to dwell on it. A lot of them were throwing errors where he
got lazy, bounced his throw over first base, and the first baseman
couldn't come up with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat him down, told him, `You're going to make errors, but
don't worry about it. Just go out and make the plays, and if it
happens, it happens.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The defense on the other side of the infield could depend on how
many games Luis Alicea plays. Alicea has good hands, average range
and can turn the double play. But he's 34, and his durability is
questionable; his number of games has decreased each year since
playing a career-high 132 games in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Catalanotto is Alicea's backup, a player with decent hands
but limited range. The Rangers are taking a hard look at Edwin
Diaz, the best defensive second baseman in camp, as a utility
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alicea is pretty good,'' Oates said. `I don't think we give up
anything there losing \RMark\S McLemore, except going back for
pop-ups into right field. I'm just not sure how many games Alicea
can play and stay strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Outfield throwing is another area where the Rangers think they
can be better. Rangers outfielders combined for 21 assists last
year, the lowest of any team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler, who has an above-average arm, could make a
difference in right field by getting to more balls quicker than
Juan Gonzalez. But there's little doubt about Ruben Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goodwin, last year's starter, was the latest in a long line
of Rangers center fielders who had weak throwing arms. Oates said
Mateo might have the best arm in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruben could do the same thing in center field that Pudge
\RRodriguez\S did behind the plate,'' Oates said. ``He should be
able to shut down the other team going from first to third and make
runners think twice about scoring from second base.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo probably doesn't have Goodwin's speed and range yet, but
the Rangers could compensate for that by having Kapler in right
field instead of Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fielding is the one thing you can work hard at and improve,''
Melvin said. ``A guy either has bat speed or he doesn't. He either
has a strong throwing arm or he doesn't. But, with hands, you can
work hard at becoming a better fielder.''
</P>
<P>
   The general manager expects that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively,'' Melvin said. ``We're going to have to catch the
ball better than we have in the past.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 2121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
