<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HAVE EYE ON COOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. -- The Dodgers' search for a left-handed
reliever may be 25 desolate miles down Interstate 95.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are paying close attention to what develops at a
lefty-rich &UR;  &LR; Mets camp and have a special eye on one-time Dodger
Dennis Cook. The two teams have spoken about a possible trade,
baseball sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Cook told reporters at the Mets camp in Port St. Lucie he
expects to be &UR;  &LR; traded before spring training ends. He has $4.55
million remaining on the three-year contract he signed last season
with the Mets, and became expendable when general manager Steve
Phillips signed free agents Rich Rodriguez and veteran Jesse Orosco
to cheaper contracts during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   John Franco, who has veto rights in trades, is expected to be
the Mets' &UR;  &LR; set-up man.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is said to be still trying to identify Cook's value on
the trade market, but the Mets are looking for young starting
pitching. The Dodgers have that in Mike Judd and Jamie Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, last week's injury to Dodgers lefty Onan Masaoka has
club officials a bit concerned. It's the one area the club lacks
depth in. Masaoka's expected to miss another week with a sprained
left ankle and there are only three other unproven lefty relievers
in camp. The Dodgers seek that veteran lefty, and are prepared to
deal for it.
</P>
<P>
   Cook fits that role and is thought of highly by Dodgers
officials. He was 10-5 with a 3.86 ERA last, but had a 6.23 ERA
after the all-star break. Left-handers hit .211 (15 for 71) against
him.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers made overtures to acquire Orosco last season when he
was pitching with Baltimore, but sources said a deal was never
close. Again, the club is interested in Orosco, but since he just
signed as a free agent he can't be traded until June 15, unless he
agrees to it.
</P>
<P>
   Charting Checo: One of the running gags of spring is the
``Robinson Checo Watch,'' the only camp invitee yet to arrive.
Checo's visa problems are supposed to be straightened out today and
he could be in camp later this week. Of course, figuring out what
to do with him is another issue. Manager Davey Johnson isn't
fretting over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be in town, for all I know,'' Johnson joked. ``I'm
not in charge of the travel. I don't know where he is. I thought he
would be here....Last year he was right in the mix. This year I
don't know where he is; if he's in the mix, or where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was mostly joking about Checo's status, but it brings to
light a more serious issue on the matter. Checo was the principle
player the Dodgers received in a salary-dumping trade that sent
Dave Mlicki and Mel Rojas to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Once in Motown, Mlicki parlayed a 14-12 mark with a 4.60 ERA
into a multi-year contract. Rojas was released, but the Dodgers
still paid $4 million of his salary.
</P>
<P>
   Checo went 2-2 with a 10.34 ERA with the Dodgers and was last
seen crawling off the Astrodome mound after he walked five batters
and allowed four runs in one-third of an inning in last year's
season finale. Meanwhile, right-hander Apostle Garcia went 7-5 with
a 3.36 ERA at Double-A San Antonio and left- hander Rick Roberts
was 2-7 with a 6.58 ERA at Class A Vero Beach and Yakima.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a game: The Dodgers will hold their first intrasquad
game today. The notables sched uled to pitch are Chan Ho Park,
Darren Dreifort, Carlos Perez and Jamie Arnold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
