<HEADER>
A0242 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FARRAKHAN-SPEECH-NYT     02-27 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARRAKHAN-SPEECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARRAKHAN ENDS LONGTIME RIVALRY WITH ORTHODOX MUSLIMS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Declaring an end to more than two decades of bitter
rivalry, Minister Louis Farrakhan of the Nation of Islam embraced
W. Deen Mohammad, the son of the late Elijah Mohammad, on Sunday
and said the two men ``will be together until death takes us
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan, speaking to a group of about 20,000 people at the
group's annual Savior's Day rally, said that his Nation of Islam
and the nation's orthodox Muslims were uniting ``to work together
for the causes of Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan, 66, had been locked in a leadership struggle with the
family of Elijah Mohammad, the onetime leader of black Muslims who
died in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   W. Deen Mohammad, who leads more than 2 million black orthodox
members of the Muslim American Society, said he wished to convey a
``message of peace and love and undying friendship to Louis
Farrakhan,'' adding that ``Muslims are one community.''
</P>
<P>
   As Mohammad rose, the crowd chanted, ``Long live Mohammad, long
live Mohammad.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan, who has been battling prostate cancer, struck a tone
that was much more moderate than some of his earlier speeches, in
which he has harshly attacked Jews and others he has seen as
enemies of his teachings.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to ``rumors that Farrakhan got sick _ he's changed,''
the leader of the Nation of Islam said, ``has Farrakhan changed?
Yeah, I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was quoting the Bible, Farrakhan said, ``A fool
changes not, but a wise man will change often.''
</P>
<P>
   But he told his followers, ``I haven't abandoned you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You as a people should never doubt me after my years of
service,'' he said, adding that ``some of you are so anxious to put
down your brother on the basis of what you read in the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Farrakhan said that the U.S. government has sent
spies among the Nation of Islam to sow discord. The government, he
said, ``has been recruiting young college students and filling them
with vicious lies about me and the Nation and sending them in to
infiltrate us.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of what he called a ``near-death experience'' last year
from cancer, Farrakhan said that ``no man undergoes a trial and
comes out the same.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that his life had been saved by Allah, who wanted him to
pursue the unity with orthodox Muslims, setting off roars of
approval from the crowd, where men were largely dressed in the
trademark bow-ties of the movement, and women wore white habits and
veils.
</P>
<P>
   While Farrakhan did not single out Israel for criticism, a
Hasidic rabbi addressed the crowd and denounced Zionism.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Dovid Weiss told Farrakhan's followers, ``Please know the
difference between Judaism and Zionism _ they are diametrically
opposed.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We Jews feel for you, we relate to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mohammad, who received a standing ovation from the crowd at the
United Center, said that the unification was ``truly a sign that
God has always been with the sincere ones _ those who kept the
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Friday gathering that was also part of the Savior's Day
commemoration, Farrakhan called the reunification of orthodox
Muslims and his renegade group ``the last frontier.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Elijah Mohammad would have been joyous about the
end of the rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-five years later, I know that your father wanted
this,'' Farrakhan said on Friday. ``I know it in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nation of Islam has recently begun to embrace orthodox
traditions, including observance of Friday prayers and the Muslim
holiday Ramadan, a period of fasting.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony Sunday was started with a traditional Muslim prayer
from the Koran, which was a departure from Farrakhan's earlier
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan also spoke of the need for stronger families, and
urged people to take part later this year in a ``Million Family
March'' on Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He said blacks must break the bonds of self-hatred imposed by
``the robber of our father,'' referring to slavery and
discrimination by whites in America.
</P>
<P>
   He credited Elijah Mohammad for ``starting us on the road we are
now walking on,'' and said that ``words would never ever say how
much I personally thank his family and the early pioneers of Islam
in this country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
