<DOCNO> NYT20000227.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0246 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-SIXERS-ART     02-27 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SIXERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS CONTAIN IVERSON, AND THEN STOP HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chris Childs dutifully followed Allen Iverson around
screens for most of the day, trying everything to disarm pro
basketball's most potent offensive weapon. Lock and trail, coaches
call this _ a strategy aimed more at containment than prevention,
aimed at letting the All-Star gets his points with minimal damage.
</P>
<P>
   But, with less than 17 seconds left Sunday afternoon, defending
Iverson that way suddenly made no sense to Childs. The Knicks and
their point guard had worked so hard to reclaim the lead, erasing a
10-point deficit in the final 15 minutes to take a 1-point lead.
Madison Square Garden was percolating with noise. Lock and trail?
The Philadelphia 76ers had locked them up for most of four
quarters, and the Knicks had trailed nearly the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   Too safe, too conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had just called that same type of play and I got picked
off by my own guy,'' Childs said of the 76ers setting a screen for
Iverson. ``Instead of following the guy around the screen the last
time, I just stayed with him and decided to shoot the gap. I didn't
want to foul him, but I also didn't want him to beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Clogging the passing lane, denying Iverson with outstretched
arms and nimble feet, Childs refused to let the National Basketball
Association's leading scorer touch the ball on the final possession
_ a stingy and disruptive defensive play that illustrated how the
Knicks came back and won, thrillingly, 89-88.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Iverson, the point guard Eric Snow dribbled into the
forest. Triple-teamed, his bank shot was too hard. Tyrone Hill
tried to tip the miss in, but the Sixers forward mistimed his jump
and barely got his left hand on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Latrell Sprewell had cradled a long rebound and
dribbled the clock away, the Knicks (34-20) emerged with their
second straight double-digit comeback and were headed to Miami for
Monday night's game only a half-game behind the Heat in the
Atlantic Division standings.
</P>
<P>
   Life at the Garden was very good, though you would not have
known it through the first three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had us down most of the game,'' said an effusive Patrick
Ewing, whose 18 points and 10 rebounds led his team and countered
Iverson's 26 points.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was economical, taking only 14 shots, tying the game with
1 minute 15 seconds remaining on a strong inside layup and
unselfishly giving the ball up to Childs on the Knicks' final
possession. At 88-88, Childs passed to Ewing on the left side about
18 feet away from the basket. Childs cut along the baseline, a
routine play that usually begins with Ewing faking a pass to a
guard before keeping it himself and trying to break his defender
down.
</P>
<P>
   Childs suddenly found himself free from Iverson and with the
ball in his hands. He was fouled by Iverson with 16.9 seconds left,
he made the first of two free throws to give the Knicks the
eventual winning margin _ and their first lead since 8-7 in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was open,'' Ewing said. ``He was wide open.'' He smiled
before adding, ``Should I have shot it?''
</P>
<P>
   On a day when Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston had trouble
finding their rhythms offensively _ they shot a combined 9 of 24
from the field _ the Knicks received great complimentary
performances from Larry Johnson, Kurt Thomas and John Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   It was Johnson (13 points) who tied the game with 46.8 seconds
left, tipping in a missed putback by Ewing. He knocked down
consecutive 3-pointers in the third quarter as the Knicks fought
back from a 12-point deficit. Wallace kept the Knicks in the game
in the first half, scoring 13 of his 15 points on a brilliant array
of dunks and jumpers. And Thomas (10 points, 7 rebounds) was his
usual ornery self on defense, using his left forearm as effectively
as Houston uses his right wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Trying desperately to match Philadelphia's intensity, the Knicks
finally found a way in the final minutes. They limited the 76ers to
one field goal in the final 4:22.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson needed 26 shots to get his 26 points. As awesome as he
was at times, he had nowhere to go in the final seconds and was
frustrated enough afterward to abstain from interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Since they traded for Toni Kukoc, the 76ers appeared to shed
that middle-of-the-pack label. They look potent and diverse enough
to give the Knicks, Miami and Indiana trouble in late spring. But
their lack of a true offensive threat to support Iverson was
revealed. If that was not apparent, Kukoc's lax defense stood out.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Larry Brown kept pulling Kukoc out of the game. Kukoc was
burned repeatedly, but no worse than when Wallace shook him along
the left baseline in the first half. In what will surely go down as
a Knick highlight, Wallace dribbled the ball between his legs with
his back to the basket; he then spun around Kukoc along the
baseline and leaped high in the air, dunking and drawing a foul for
an eventual 3-point play _ a sequence shown several times on the
overhead scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was wild,'' Ewing said admiringly of the young forward's
move. ``That was a great move.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing also called Sunday's victory ``a great game,'' a kind of
post-All-Star gauge for a team with much hope and perhaps as much
possibility, the difference between a team who wants to contend for
the Eastern Conference title and another who has been there, done
that and now wants more. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
