u s BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     02-27 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: 76ERS TAKING THEIR TIME TO MEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before Sunday's game with the Knicks, Pat Croce, the
76ers' energetic 45-year-old president, conceded that this game at
Madison Square Garden was a litmus test for his team.
</P>
<P>
   True, it was only February and the season will not end until
mid-April. But this was a test.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the Knicks,'' Croce with typical gushing enthusiasm.
``They're the measuring stick; for us they've been the big barrier
_ especially here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had beaten the 76ers in their last six meetings at
the Garden; the last two by 85-70 and 91-72.
</P>
<P>
   But Croce was sure this game would be different. While the
Knicks had decided to stand pat on the trade front, the 76ers had
made a blockbuster three-player trade, landing Tony Kukoc, the
final pillar from the Bulls' championship dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited, we finally have someone who can complement
Allen,'' Croce said referring to the star point guard Allen
Iverson. ``He brings so much to this team, to this city. People are
starting to talk about the 76ers again.''
</P>
<P>
   Were the 76ers now equipped to beat the Knicks?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Croce said, smiling at his own audacity. ``I'm a
positive person. I felt we could have won without Tony, but now I'm
very excited.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have to be wary of a guy like Croce, an optimist who
really believes. Here's a man who is still recovering from a
serious motorcycle crash last June that shattered his leg in 10
places. In November Croce learned that the bones were finally
beginning to heal.
</P>
<P>
   He believes in healing.
</P>
<P>
   He mended fences with Andrew Toney, a former star guard who
became alienated from the previous owners; another former star,
Maurice Cheeks, is on the bench as an assistant coach; a third,
World B. Free, is in the front office. Iverson, Croce said, ``Will
be here as long as I'm here.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For three quarters Sunday the test went well for Philadelphia.
The 76ers opened up a 10-point lead. Iverson was going well,
Forward George Lynch was going well. Even centers Tyrone Hill and
Theo Ratliff were going well. The 76ers' jumping switching trapping
defense had the Knicks off balance.
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc was not a factor. He threw one or two nice passes but was
an immediate defensive liability. He replaced Lynch with 2 minutes
45 seconds left in the first quarter, the 76ers up by 10. He
immediately fouled Ewing while coming over to help. He gave up to
jumper to John Wallace, then a riveting spin dunk by Wallace. On
offense he missed a couple crucial shots as the Knicks started to
close in.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers had the lead for three quarters. Then the Knicks, like
the cagey distance runner who saves the monster kick for the end,
made their move. Ewing hit a hook; Larry Johnson tipped in a missed
shot and Chris Childs _ the invisible factor _ got the game-winning
points on two foul shots.
</P>
<P>
   On Philadelphia's final possession, the veteran Knicks clamped
down on Iverson with Childs. The defense forced guard Eric Snow to
take the final shot _a shot he did not want to take. Kukoc, the
would-be difference, was on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   A week after being shut down by the Lakers Kobe Bryant, Iverson
had another ``bolt game'' _ a day when he didn't feel like talking.
A day drenched in disappointment. So he bolted.
</P>
<P>
   Croce spoke instead. He shook his head and tried to put a
positive spin on the loss, but this one hurt. He cursed under his
breath. Pounded his fist in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had this game, we should have won this game,'' he said. ``I
can't believe we lost this game. We were right there. We had the
lead all game.''
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged his shoulders and smiled. He's an optimist. if
Philadelphia had won he would have said the game was a harbinger of
things to come. In defeat, he said this was only one game, with
lots more to play _ including a rematch with the Knicks in
Philadelphia on March 10.
</P>
<P>
   A subdued Kukoc only talked about becoming more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to get myself involved more,'' he said. ``I've been
trying to stay out of the way. I have to start looking more for my
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   As a team, Kukoc said, ``We have to find a way to get better
down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are a good team, a championship team until proven
otherwise. They pull games out of the fire. They run a smart race. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lynch, the 76ers' veteran forward, attempted to put the day in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a playoff-like test for us,'' he said. ``We wanted to
be a lot more competitive than we had been here when we'd lose by
10 or 20 points and be out of the game in the third quarter. We
played well, we didn't get blown out and if we played at home we
may have won by 10 points. But the Knicks have been together a long
time. They hit their free throws, they make clutch plays. We didn't
make the great shot when we needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a litmus test for Philadelphia; another game for the
Knicks. In a basketball sense the Knicks are at a near perfect
time: they have a perfect balance of age, of experience of depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get there,'' Croce said.
</P>
<P>
   He could not hide his disappointment Sunday, but Philadelphia's
time is on the horizon and the Knicks know it; they know it about
Toronto and they know it about Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers, much like the bones in Croce's shattered left leg,
are beginning to mend. Time. These things take time. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 2143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
