u a BC-NY-DIALLO-PROSECUTORS     02-27 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-PROSECUTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTION IN DIALLO CASE NOW FINDS ITSELF ACCUSED
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-DIALLO-REACT) 
(nk) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lawrence Teele, a school custodian, said while
walking home in Harlem on Saturday that the prosecution lawyers had
lacked passion and conviction. Barbara Ford, a Bronx woman
attending a rally up the street at the National Action Network, the
Rev. Al Sharpton's headquarters, said they had not prosecuted the
case ``as fully as it could have been.'' Francis Kallon, protesting
near the United Nations on Sunday, said he was angry that they had
not cross-examined the defendants more aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to explain the seemingly inexplicable _ how four
armed police officers could shoot and kill an innocent unarmed man
and walk away scot-free _ many of those outraged by the verdict in
the Amadou Diallo trial have arrived at one answer: that the Bronx
district attorney, Robert T. Johnson, botched the case.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's office, and some others who followed the trial
closely, vigorously dispute that, and even many critics praised the
summation by Eric Warner, the lead prosecutor. But after 12 Albany
jurors found that the prosecution had not proved any of six counts
against each officer, and after a juror pointed obliquely to the
prosecution's presentation of the case by way of explanation,
Johnson suddenly found himself excoriated this weekend in the
streets, at churches, and on talk radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should Bronx DA Be Brought to Task in Diallo Trial?'' the
front page of the newspaper Afro Times shouted this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not represent his community or his people,'' Frankie
Lipsett, 39, a building superintendent who lives in the Bronx
neighborhood where Diallo was shot, said of Johnson, who is black.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism, including calls for Johnson's resignation, has
been so vigorous that the Rev. Calvin O. Butts 3rd felt obliged to
comment on it during a fiery sermon Sunday at Abyssinian Baptist
Church in Harlem. ``This is not a time for black people to fight
amongst themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year ago, of course, Johnson was a hero to many of
those now attacking him. Withstanding criticism from the four
officers' defenders, he indicted them on second-degree murder
charges, and even opposed their application for bail.
</P>
<P>
   But over the course of the trial, as momentum seemed to shift to
the defense, the second-guessing began. The prosecution team, which
together has more than 75 years of experience, was criticized for
its cross-examination of the officers, for failing to cross-examine
the last defense witness, an expert on police practices, and for
not putting on a rebuttal case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying they were incompetent, but they were not
aggressive,'' said Michael A. Hardy, a lawyer who represents
Sharpton. ``They didn't have an appeal to the jury; they didn't
tell a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who followed the trial closely, however, said the
criticism was unfair _ that the prosecution put on as strong a case
as it could, given the consistent testimony and sympathetic
demeanor of the officers and the lack of witnesses to contradict
their version of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what else he could have done,'' said Eddie Hayes,
a lawyer who followed the trial as an anchor for Court TV, said of
Johnson. ``I think he has severe limitations, given that there are
no real eyewitnesses and the defense has four trained, experienced
witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Stephen Gillers, a law professor and vice dean at
New York University, said they felt Johnson effectively put police
policies on trial, which was as important as trying the officers
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we put on the strongest case we could,'' said
Johnson's spokesman, Steven Reed, who declined to respond to
specific criticism.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Aiello, a former prosecutor who is one of the lawyers
representing Saikou Diallo, Diallo's father, in a pending civil
action, said he was reluctant to second-guess the prosecution but
thought prosecutors should have tried harder to impeach the
officers' credibility. Even the defense lawyers said they had
prepared their clients for far more grueling cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   An objection raised by many _ that prosecutors chose not to
cross-examine James J. Fyfe, an expert on police procedures and the
last defense witness _ was echoed by a juror Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't cross-examine _ I was so surprised,'' said the
juror, Helen Harder.
</P>
<P>
   Aiello also said he thought the prosecutors should have asked
that the judge say in his instructions to the jury that, even if
the use of deadly force is necessary at first, it can become
unjustified later. Such a charge would have allowed the jury to
consider the validity of Officers Sean Carroll and Edward McMellon
firing 16 shots each.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, said the prosecution also erred by not insisting
that the judge more fully explain the law of street encounters.
Defense lawyers succeeded in persuading Justice Joseph C. Teresi to
read jurors the law of street encounters in New York, under which a
police officer has the right to make a basic inquiry of a citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said that, under New York law, a citizen is legally
entitled, if not necessarily wise, to ignore a police officer's
inquiry if he is not committing any crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where was the objection from the prosecution to the
instruction?'' Siegel asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
