u s BC-HKN-CANADIENS-DEVILS-     02-27 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CANADIENS-DEVILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS COME OUT FIRING AND END 0-4-1 SLUMP WITH A SHUTOUT
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Unaccustomed to losing four in a row,
the New Jersey Devils came out firing Sunday evening. Their shots
in the first 25 minutes were either wide by inches or pushed aside,
but three of their 48 shots eventually found the net for a 3-0
triumph over the Montreal Canadiens at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, who had gone five games without a victory for the
first time in five years, ended the streak in grand fashion. Petr
Sykora, Claude Lemieux and Bobby Holik scored the goals, but their
best player was goaltender Martin Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur turned aside all 30 shots he faced for his fourth
shutout of the season and the 40th of his career. He earned the
shutout with a number of brilliant saves, especially one on Turner
Stevenson's rebound after a shot by Martin Rucinsky with 4 minutes
20 seconds left in the scoreless first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to get out of it,'' Brodeur said of the 0-4-1
stretch, ``and I think we responded well. We needed this because
we're also going on the road for the next seven games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' trip starts in Nashville on Tuesday and concludes in
Pittsburgh on March 17, with stops in Colorado, Vancouver, Calgary,
Atlanta and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The road trip should be fun,'' said Brodeur, who absorbed the
overtime loss to the Canadiens in Montreal last Thursday. ``It'll
give us an opportunity to spend time as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, who broke a league record for road victories last
season with 28, are 12-13-4 on the road this season and have lost
their last two games away from Continental Arena. Their overall
record of 37-19-7 after Sunday's victory is the best in the Eastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   With help from Chicago's victory over St. Louis Sunday, the
Devils also have the same number of points as the Blues in the race
for the Presidents' Trophy, which goes to the team with the most
points in the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils capitalized on their second manpower advantage, with
Sykora opening the scoring 50 seconds after a penalty to Patrick
Poulin for tripping Jason Arnott at 4:38 of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 19th goal of the season and fourth on the power play
for Sykora, who scored after exchanging passes with Scott Gomez on
the right side. Sykora's is shot from a sharp angle deflected off
the skate on Eric Weinrich past Jeff Hackett, who stopped the first
20 shots he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stayed patient after we didn't score in the first,'' Sykora
said. ``We didn't get down on ourselves got that lucky bounce on
the first goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils doubled their lead just over two minutes later, when
Lemieux took a pass from Gomez on the right, as Montreal defenseman
Vladimir Malakhov lost his stick, and beat Hackett over the left
shoulder for his 19th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It was during the next two minutes that Brodeur shone just as
bright as he did on the save against Stevenson in the first period.
First, he denied Oleg Petrov when the diminutive right wing raced
toward him with tremendous speed on the right, and then he denied
Rucinsky's sharp backhander from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty played excellent,'' Coach Robbie Ftorek said of Brodeur,
who improved his record to 35-12-7. ``He had a lot of big saves,
especially in the second period.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Brodeur getting his 40th shutout, Ftorek said, ``I hope
50 comes quicker than 40 because it took him so long to get the
40th.''
</P>
<P>
   Any fear of a third-period letdown vanished 4:39 into the period
when Holik took a pass from Ken Daneyko down the right flank and
beat Hackett between the legs for his 20th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a good effort from everybody and we got a good
result,'' Scott Stevens, the Devils' captain, said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
