<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE DEAL IN HONG KONG SAID TO GET A NEW PLAYER
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Embargoed for 10:30 p.m. ET) 
 (nk) 
 By MARK LANDLER with ANDREW ROSS SORKIN 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. is on the verge of
investing $1 billion in Singapore Telecommunications, which could
enable it to sweeten its offer for Hong Kong's dominant telephone
company, Cable and Wireless HKT Ltd., executives close to the
negotiations said Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of a new player came after a board meeting of the
Hong Kong company's British parent, Cable and Wireless PLC, in
London on Sunday, at which the directors were presented with
competing bids from Singapore Telecommunications and Pacific
Century Cyberworks, a Hong Kong start-up.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century proposed to acquire Cable and Wireless HKT in a
stock-and-cash offer that values the company at $35 billion,
executives close to the talks said. Singapore Telecom's offer was
slightly lower than that, although the cash portion of its bid was
potentially larger, people briefed on the offer said.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century also made an all-stock offer worth $38.5
billion, but executives involved in the discussions said it was not
likely to be accepted. Cable and Wireless has pressed Pacific
Century to offer more cash.
</P>
<P>
   The Cable and Wireless board meeting ended without a decision on
Sunday night, and with the News Corp. added to the mix, the battle
for Hong Kong's phone company seems to be turning into a global,
multifront corporate war.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to Singapore Telecommunications said that as
part of its $1 billion investment, the News Corp. would set up an
Internet and TV venture in Singapore similar to the one it
announced late last year with Cable and Wireless HKT. If the
Singapore company merged with its Hong Kong counterpart, the joint
venture with News would become a region-wide service.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, however, Murdoch's involvement would enable
Singapore Telecommunications to increase its cash offer to Cable
and Wireless, which is currently about $6.4 billion for the
company's 54.4 percent stake in HKT.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding war for Cable and Wireless HKT has riveted Asia,
because it is the first takeover battle of the Internet age here
and because it pits the archrivals Hong Kong and Singapore against
each other. Singapore Telecommunications is controlled by the
Singapore government, while Pacific Century was started by Richard
Li, the 33-year-old son of Li Ka-shing, Hong Kong's mightiest
tycoon.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Li barged into merger negotiations between Singapore
Telecom and Cable and Wireless two weeks ago when he announced that
he wanted to acquire Cable and Wireless HKT. Since then, Li has
raised $1 billion through a share placement and roughly $10 billion
in loans from a consortium of banks, including the Bank of China
and HSBC Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   HSBC's role could prove contentious. Executives close to
Singapore Telecommunications said the company was considering suing
HSBC for conflict of interest because its investment banking arm
had advised Cable and Wireless HKT. According to Singapore Telecom,
that gave HSBC access to HKT's internal financial documents, which
it could use to help Pacific Century.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for HSBC, David Hall, declined to comment on a
potential lawsuit, saying the bank had not been contacted by
Singapore Telecommunications or its lawyers. But he said, ``We wish
to make it absolutely clear that at all times, we have acted
properly in our dealings with Cable and Wireless HKT.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to HSBC said the London-based bank had resigned
as an adviser to Cable and Wireless HKT last week. The threat of a
lawsuit by Singapore Telecom seemed calculated to sow doubt among
board members of Cable and Wireless about the soundness of Pacific
Century's financing.
</P>
<P>
   Although Singapore Telecom would seem to have more financial
leverage than Pacific Century, it is handicapped by political
considerations. Neither the Hong Kong government nor the mainland
Chinese have welcomed the prospect of a Singapore company taking
over Hong Kong's phone company.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers in Hong Kong reported over the weekend that China
Telecom, which owns 10.7 percent of Cable and Wireless HKT, would
vote to accept Pacific Century's offer. China Telecom is the Hong
Kong-based arm of China's state telephone company and is controlled
by Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how Murdoch would change the political dynamic.
The News Corp. has had an up-and-down history in China, though
Murdoch has gone to great pains in recent years to cultivate
Chinese leaders.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the most important constituency is the board of
Cable and Wireless. The board meeting on Sunday was spent outlining
the two bids, the executives said, with no real winner emerging.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 2159EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000227.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0261 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH0228-COX     02-27 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH0228-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush admits his mistake
 &HT;    By Ken Herman and Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After weeks of defending his speech at controversial
Bob Jones University, Gov. George W. Bush said Sunday he made a big
mistake by not condemning the fundamentalist school's anti-Catholic
beliefs when he was there.
</P>
<P>
   ``On reflection,'' Bush said in a letter to Cardinal John
O'Connor, archbishop of New York, ``I should have been more clear
in disassociating myself from anti-Catholic sentiments and racial
prejudice. It was a missed opportunity, causing needless offense,
which I deeply regret.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's confession came as he began a crucial nine-day period
leading up to the Super Tuesday contests on March 7 that could
determine whether he or Arizona Sen. John McCain will be the GOP
presidential nominee. Virginia and Washington state hold primaries
Tuesday, and North Dakota Republicans will meet in caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Bush narrowed McCain's lead in the race for
Republican national convention delegates by winning Puerto Rico's
winner-take-all primary. The 14 delegates Bush picked up Sunday,
along with the 12 he won Saturday in three other U.S. territories _
Guam, American Samoa and the Virgin Islands _ gives the Texas
governor 93 delegates, three behind McCain. A candidate needs 1,034
delegates to win the Republican nomination for president.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush picked up additional delegates, he cannot count on
getting votes from the islands' residents if he wins the
nomination. Residents of U.S. territories cannot vote in the
general election, but are allowed to participate in presidential
primaries and caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McCain announced Sunday that he won't take part in
Thursday's GOP presidential campaign debate in Los Angeles, and
aides say they pulled out because Bush was slow to agree to the
California event and that sparked scheduling conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he plans to attend the debate, if held, because it
would be an important discussion in a key state.
</P>
<P>
   McCain scored big wins in his home state and in Michigan last
Tuesday. The Michigan win, a shocker to the Bush camp, included
efforts by McCain to portray Bush as anti-Catholic because of his
speech at Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Sunday he did not know about the school's
anti-Catholic sentiments and ban on inter-racial dating until after
his speech that kicked off his South Carolina campaign in the
aftermath of McCain's big win in New Hampshire. The speech signaled
Bush's move to the right, a strategy that played well as he won
South Carolina but turned into a negative in last week's contest in
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   McCain fueled the fire with campaign phone calls alleging Bush,
by speaking at Bob Jones University, showed an anti-Catholic bias.
The university believes Catholicism and Mormonism are ``cults.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to O'Connor, Bush rejected that belief.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Christian, I see Catholics as my brothers and sisters in
Christ _ sharing the same ancient creeds and core beliefs,'' Bush
told O'Connor. ``And, as you know, my own brother and sister-in-law
are both Catholics.'' Florida Gov. Jeb Bush converted to
Catholicism after marrying his wife, Columba.
</P>
<P>
   As he headed to Seattle on Sunday, George W. Bush said he wrote
the letter to O'Connor and other Catholic leaders because he was
``deeply troubled by impressions that run contrary to my nature and
my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, I wish I had clearly condemned the sentiments
that pit one religion against another,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to trying to make the Bob Jones University
controversy go away, Bush on Sunday blasted McCain for his
involvement in Michigan phone calls claiming that Bush is
anti-Catholic. McCain initially denied any involvement in the
calls, but The New York Times reported Sunday that McCain approved
the scripts in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret campaigning against a man that says one thing and
does another, a person who says he will run a positive campaign
then approves the scripts of anti-Catholic bigotry in a state like
Michigan,'' said Bush, adding that the calls ``clearly implied that
I'm an anti-Catholic bigot.''
</P>
<P>
   The calls, identified as part of ``Catholic voter alert,'' said
Bush sought ``the support of Southern fundamentalists who have
expressed anti-Catholic views.'' The call mentioned Bush's speech
at Bob Jones University, and said Jones ``has made strong
anti-Catholic statements including calling the pope the anti-Christ
and the Catholic church a satanic cult.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who previously denied approving calls alleging Bush is
anti-Catholic, said Sunday the calls he OK'd were accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The call was that he attended an institution'' in South
Carolina, McCain said on ABC's ``This Week.'' ``My campaign came to
me and said we want to make some calls. I said as long as they are
factual and correct and the same thing I would say on the `Today'
show or any other program, fine. Then they were portrayed as some
calls that were somehow accusing Governor Bush of being
anti-Catholic or a bigot. That's not true, and that's not what I
take responsibility for.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter King, R-N.Y., and a former Bush backer now supporting
McCain, said Sunday that Bush invited criticism by speaking at Bob
Jones University. King, a Catholic, switched to McCain after the
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Governor Bush is at all bigoted, but he was
willing to shake hands with the devil to make the deal to get
himself elected in South Carolina,'' King said on NBC's ``Meet the
Press.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bob Jones controversy is not the first time Bush has found
himself at the precarious intersection of church and politics. In
1993, prior to his first gubernatorial campaign, Bush, a Methodist,
said he believes that heaven is open only to those who accept Jesus
Christ as their personal savior.
</P>
<P>
   Bush later clarified the comments to say he had not intended to
judge other people's religious beliefs. Abraham Foxman, president
of the Anti-Defamation League, which monitors anti-Semitism, has
said he is convinced Bush harbors no ill-will toward
non-Christians.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
