</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMY-GOSPEL-CHOIR-ART-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOSPEL CHOIR WINS PRAISE FOR SINGING LORD'S PRAISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The halls of the Brooklyn Tabernacle shook with the
exhortations of the Rev. Jim Cymbala on Sunday, and Carol Cymbala,
leading the choir, worked the piano as she has done for 27 years,
as if nothing at all were different about this day. But something
was.
</P>
<P>
   The 270-voice Brooklyn Tabernacle Choir was singing for the
first time in public since winning its third Grammy award last
week: best gospel choir or chorus album for ``High and Lifted Up.''
The title was appropriate not only for the album but also for the
mood among the throng in the Flatbush Avenue church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lift up your hands to the Lord,'' Jim Cymbala shouted, and the
congregation reached for the ornate pink and white ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you have a lot of praise for the Lord, like the choir
does today?'' he yelled$ and a wave of amens and shouts of joy
answered.
</P>
<P>
   The choir has recorded 18 albums and performed around the world,
including at Carnegie Hall and Radio City Music Hall. It won
Grammys in the gospel category in 1994 and 1996. The feat was
unusual considering that the pastor's wife does not read sheet
music and has no formal music training.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are choirs so much better than we are,'' said Carol
Cymbala, 52, during a break between services. ``We are not that
good. But any recognition there is, is an honor.''
</P>
<P>
   The nondenominational congregation is made up of 10,000
born-again Christians, a multiracial gathering that talks about God
with ease and passion and never fails to credit him for any good
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Fans, in turn, have given glory to the choir. It has sold 1.5
million albums, and its music is no small part of a service so
popular that people wait in line to get into the church long after
the service has begun.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of the first service on Sunday, the choir sang
seven songs, most of them accompanied by the worshippers' fervent
foot-stomping and hand-clapping.
</P>
<P>
   Was the crowd drawn by the music or the message?
</P>
<P>
   The Cymbalas have pondered this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so easy for church to be a happening rather than a
worship service,'' Jim Cymbala, 57, said during his sermon on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The choir's recording career began ordinarily enough.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Cymbala's father, the Rev. Clair Hutchins, asked the
Cymbalas to take over his struggling congregation, which then
worshipped in a storefront church on Atlantic Avenue in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed, but at first scrambled to draw new people to the
church and pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Their fortunes changed as interest grew. The choir that began
with eight singers and Carol Cymbala in 1973 had grown to 60 or so
singers by 1981.
</P>
<P>
   In that year, she thought it would be nice to make a tape so the
congregants could take the service home with them. She gave the
tape to a friend who had contacts in the recording industry and
passed it on to executives at Word, a Christian label in Nashville,
Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   The choir, to its members' amazement, was signed, and since then
has recorded an album every year or two.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the early days, anyone could join the choir. But today,
aspirants go through one or two auditions and a series of
interviews with the Cymbalas to reveal the depth of their faith.
``Now you need an FBI background check,'' Jim Cymbala said with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The recognition and publicity are surely welcome, if humbling.
The gospel awards are not presented during the national telecast;
they are among a group of awards given out in earlier ceremonies
and noted by a list that crawls across the television screen.
</P>
<P>
   One choir member, Esther Cedeno, said she fixed her eyes on the
screen when the list came up. ``It was like, `Who are we to win a
Grammy?''' she said. ``But then you think about it. It teaches us
we don't have to compromise. We don't have to cross over, like some
artists are doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
