<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-JUROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIALLO JUROR SAYS PROSECUTORS FAILED TO PROVE THEIR CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A juror who helped acquit four police officers
charged with murdering Amadou Diallo said Sunday that the
prosecution had failed to prove its case, but she believed the
officers should be held responsible for civil damages.
</P>
<P>
   In a 20-minute interview at her home, the juror, Helen Harder,
72, described the atmosphere in the jury room as generally
amicable, untainted by the racial overtones that have hovered over
the case. She said she empathized with Diallo's family, but
stressed that the prosecution had not proved that the officers
acted criminally. She also blamed police procedures for creating a
volatile confrontation. ``I still feel that they had some
responsibility _ that doesn't mean that I want them to be convicted
of manslaughter,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon, Kenneth Boss and Richard
Murphy, were acquitted of all charges Friday in the death of
Diallo. The police officers, who are white, fired on Diallo, an
unarmed African immigrant, 41 times and struck him 19 times as he
stood in the vestibule of his apartment building in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Harder, whose cozy home is filled with framed photos of her nine
children and 17 grandchildren, said she and the other jurors put
aside their personal feelings about the shooting during the more
than 30 hours of deliberations. She said they followed Justice
Joseph C. Teresi's instructions to consider only whether the
prosecution had proved its burden. It had not, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two or three days earlier, I would never have expected that
verdict,'' she said. ``It surprised me. We were charged by the
judge and told that the prosecution has to prove its case or there
is no case. Well, that made it different.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Harder said she was surprised, and disappointed,
that the prosecution had not asked any questions of the final
defense witness, James J. Fyfe, an expert on police procedures who
testified that the four officers had acted properly. She said the
prosecution did not present enough evidence against the officers
and left her with unanswered questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they probably didn't have enough to work with,'' she
said of the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Although the racial overtones of the Diallo shooting have
polarized communities throughout New York, Harder, who is white,
insisted that race had not been an issue during the deliberations.
Four of the jurors were black women and the rest were white men.
``There was not a racial aspect in the jury room,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Harder said that none of the jurors believed the officers were
guilty of murder, and that only one or two initially considered a
conviction for manslaughter or one of the lesser charges.
Eventually, she said, the jurors amicably reached an agreement as
they went through all the charges _ listed on a chalkboard _ one by
one for each officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody had reservations about whether the police acted
properly, but given the parameters, we decided they did,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Harder said the four officers and the police department
should be held responsible for the shooting in a civil lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the city is responsible, because they're responsible
for police procedures,'' she said. ``I think the whole unit they
belonged to wouldn't have had such a sharp look to the people who
lived there if there were some black police officers, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Harder spoke publicly about the Diallo trial for the first time
Sunday afternoon after meeting with six other jurors. Since the
verdict was read in court Friday, the jurors have dodged calls from
reporters, posted signs outside their homes asking to be left alone
and generally maintained their silence, in part, out of fear of the
repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so intense and we were so mind-boggled by it,'' Harder
said of the jury deliberations. ``We decided we didn't want to talk
to anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
