<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-DIPLOMAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN ENVOY HOLES UP IN CANADIAN EMBASSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ A Cuban diplomat expelled from the United States
after being accused of spying is seeking sanctuary at the Cuban
Embassy in Canada, to the apparent dismay of Canadian officials.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest twist in the saga, the Cuban government Sunday
said the diplomat, Jose Imperatori, 46, would remain on a hunger
strike at the embassy in Ottawa until the United States withdraws
allegations that he engaged in espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba also accused the United States of dragging Canada into the
messy affair by flying Imperatori to Montreal aboard a US plane
Saturday night after declaring him persona non grata.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the imperialists have done . . . is throw the hot potato
to its neighbor Canada,'' Cuba charged in a statement released in
Havana, blaming the Clinton administration for the imbroglio.
</P>
<P>
   Canada has for decades irked the United States by maintaining
friendly relations with the communist regime of Fidel Castro.
However, it was clear Sunday night that the country does not want
to get caught in the latest cross-fire between Washington and
Havana and does not intend to give haven to the alleged espionage
agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada agreed to facilitate his transfer,'' said a Foreign
Ministry spokesman, Patrick Hebert, adding that Ottawa had
consulted with both the Cuban and US governments. ``We expect he
will depart shortly'' for Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Imperatori, who hours before his expulsion from the United
States had showed a flair for the dramatic by announcing a hunger
strike to protest the allegations, caught Canada off-guard when he
bolted from the airport in Montreal for the Cuban Embassy in
Ottawa, leaving his wife and 3-year-old son to fly on to Havana.
</P>
<P>
   The Castro government has asked Canada to allow Imperatori to
stay in the country ``for the time necessary to find an honorable
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban government also announced that Imperatori would
maintain his hunger strike until the United States backs down from
the spy charges. Starvation is not a standard diplomatic tactic.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the United States and Cuba had shown signs of
modest improvement before bitter wrangling began late last year
over custody of Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban boy whose
mother drowned while trying to bring him to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators in Cuba Sunday chanted anti-US slogans and hailed
Imperatori as a national hero. Cuba said that the expulsion of
Imperatori represents a ``crude maneuver'' by the United States to
deflect attention from the plight of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Imperatori was forced to surrender his diplomatic post with the
tiny Cuban interests section in Washington after being accused last
week of maintaining illegal contacts with Mariano Faget, a veteran
officer of the US Immigration and Naturalization Service charged
with spying on behalf of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban officials implied that the United States had dumped
Imperatori on an unsuspecting Canada: ``The US government . . .
deceived Canadian authorities, lied to them,'' the Cuban official
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Canadian officials said they had given permission for
the transfer of the ousted diplomat via Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada is a usual route for Cuban diplomats to go to and from
the United States,'' Hebert said. ``And we expect him to abide by
the agreement and leave soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
