<HEADER>
A0277 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-HIDALGO-HN     02-27 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HIDALGO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Richard Hidalgo never thought playing in the
major leagues would be this painful.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hidalgo, one of the jewels of the Astros' farm system, has seen
his promising big-league career put on hold the last two seasons
because of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of bad luck,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During his rookie season in 1998, Hidalgo crashed into the
center-field wall at Denver's Coors Field and separated his right
shoulder. He missed nearly two months.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Last year, it was discovered that Hidalgo had a rare genetic
malformation in his left knee. It eventually required surgery and
sidelined him for the final two months.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is counting on the third time being the charm.
</P>
<P>
   After spending the last two seasons playing mostly left and
center field, the 24-year-old Venezuelan returns to the comfort of
his natural position in right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play a full season,'' said Hidalgo, who has missed
about 15 weeks of playing time since 1998. ``It's difficult to lose
two months. I think I can do a lot of things with a full season.''
</P>
<P>
   In only a short time, Hidalgo has showed glimpses of why the
Astros have refused to trade him when other clubs made inquiries
over the last few years. He batted .303 as a rookie, and he had 15
home runs and 56 RBIs last season before falling into a hitting
slump around the time he noticed pain in his knee in early August.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Hidalgo underwent season-ending surgery. A
three-times-a-week rehabilitation program this offseason has
Hidalgo's left knee around 95 percent. He played eight games in the
Venezuela winter leagues. And during the first week of spring
training, he has shown no ill effects while taking live batting
practice and fielding baseballs in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost as strong as the other knee,'' Hidalgo said.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for the Astros, who, with the return of Moises
Alou in left field, will shift Hidalgo back to right field this
year. Roger Cedeno, acquired from the Mets in the Mike Hampton
trade, will patrol center in place of Carl Everett, who was dealt
to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They believe in me and know what I've got,'' Hidalgo said. ``I
know I can do better. I'm focused on this season. I didn't worry
(about finding playing time). You just have to keep working hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo has been working with hitting instructor Tom McCraw on
his bat grip to get around more quickly on pitches. Manager Larry
Dierker envisions Hidalgo eventually hitting 20 to 30 home runs and
driving in 90 to 100 runs a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never really got going as a batter last season,'' Dierker
said. ``There is no concern whatsoever about his knee. In fact, I
think he's moving better this spring than I've ever seen him
move.''
</P>
<P>
   That should make Hidalgo even tougher to run on. Despite playing
a new position, left field, for the first time and battling knee
problems, Hidalgo was leading the National League with 15 outfield
assists when he went on the disabled list in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time we've had Richard Hidalgo playing in the outfield,
we've had a better defensive outfield than anything we could
configure without him,'' Dierker said. ``He's just an exceptional
fielder and can play all three positions. He gives us a lot of
flexibility in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really say that about any of the other outfielders
other than Glen Barker,'' Dierker said. ``Having him healthy is a
real asset to the team. When he's been out of action, we've really
missed him.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing pains have been especially tough, but Hidalgo and
his teammates see brighter days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw what he did last year banged up,'' second baseman
Craig Biggio said. ``Richard is getting older and smarter. He knows
what he is capable of doing now. He has a very high ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
