<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ COOLS OFF AT LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A long road trip and a lack of practice time have
reduced Shaquille O'Neal's free-throw hot streak to a low simmer.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal appeared to turn the corner on his lifelong battle with
the foul shot, making 75.9 percent (41 of 54) over a four-game
stretch that extended through the first week of the Lakers' recent
road trip.
</P>
<P>
   But he's 12 for 31 (38.7 percent) over the last four games,
including 2 for 6 in Sunday's victory over the Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson isn't concerned that O'Neal has reverted to
old, bad habits. He just needs practice time, which was at a
minimum as the Lakers traveled to six cities in nine days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's out of synch,'' Jackson said, ``and I think he got out of
it because he wasn't practicing. He didn't have practice time. And
now he's back and he can take some time to do his practice routine,
get his in-synch kind of rhythm back again. He's coming up too soon
and then standing flat-footed and shooting his shots, rather than
having lift on them. And I think that bothers him.''
</P>
<P>
   A frustrated O'Neal agreed he needs practice time. But he's not
getting as much as he wants. The Lakers' recently opened training
facility in El Segundo is intended to provide players added
practice time, but O'Neal said he wasn't allowed in after-hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could (bleeping) get into that brand-new (bleeping)
facility that they just built, then I could get some (bleeping)
practice,'' he said. ``I can't get in that B.S. building at
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson asked all the players to come early to Sunday's game to
get extra shooting time. He said O'Neal needs to regain his touch
soon, as the Portland Trail Blazers are likely to foul him often on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hes got to be able to go to the line on the road and complete
them,'' Jackson said, ``so it's going to be important for him to
get his rhythm back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Kobe Bryant's 18-point first quarter dashed any
concern that his bruised left calf might affect his game, though
Bryant said it still hurts. For his part, Jackson jokingly said
he'd like to see Bryant back off the 360-degree dunks, like the one
he put in Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the body takes it pretty tough, to twist your legs
like that and to take off at an angle,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said the body ain't meant for that,'' Bryant said. ``I said
(begin ital)your(end ital) body ain't meant for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Silent treatment: After declining all interviews for a week and
a half, Glen Rice spoke briefly on NBC at halftime of Sunday's game
. However, he waved off local reporters again afterward. Rice has
not offered a reason for his silence.
</P>
</TEXT>
