u l BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT &LR;      02-27 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' comments about life in the
Big Apple:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   As I was leaving my apartment to do errands one recent
afternoon, I stooped down to give a goodbye pat to Charlie, my cat.
Pop! Another button off my down coat. OK, I'd pick up some more
during my errands that day in my Village neighborhood. But where to
look? Old reliables like Woolworth's are gone, and the couple of
dry cleaners I checked _ figuring I'd have to pay $3 or more _
couldn't help. None had buttons to offer.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, I was near St. Luke's Thrift Shop. Surely it
would have something. Inside I was directed to an old shoe box
filled with hundreds of buttons in assorted sizes and shapes.
Fifteen cents for large ones, 10 cents for mediums and 5 cents for
smalls.
</P>
<P>
   What fun to pore over so many buttons, some old, some new, some
funny shapes and colors, but most simply classic and familiar. I
ran my hand through the pile. How delicious. It brought back
memories of my mother's classic Louis Sherry candy box of buttons
and tiny metal hooks and eyes (that had probably belonged to her
mother).
</P>
<P>
   Eventually I narrowed my choices to 20. I could afford to be
indulgent. I took my selections to the volunteer cashier and my
purchases came to $1.50, except _ my lucky day _ there was a
50-percent-off clearance sale. And so I got the lot for 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I've concluded that people should once again consider
keeping button boxes. They're too much fun not to have.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOAN ROSENFELT
</P>
<P>
   George Rosenfeld, walking along East 65th Street, passed a man
talking on his cell phone. He heard this snippet: ``I am sorry, but
I cannot give you this information now, since I am in the middle of
an important business meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   It was early one Sunday evening and the bus was inching down
Ninth Avenue, taking about 40 minutes to cover 10 blocks. The
passengers began to strike up conversations. One man of a certain
age opened a worn black leather case. Suddenly the mellow clarinet
sounds of a perfectly rendered ``Danny Boy'' enveloped the bus.
</P>
<P>
   When an encore seemed to be in order, he turned to a woman with
a well-lined face who was holding a wooden cane. He said he would
play ``Besame Mucho'' for her if she would sing for him. And so she
did, her melodic voice accompanying his music.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you know I was once a singer and dancer?'' she asked
when the song ended. ``I know these things,'' he said. ``I just
know.'' He then alighted from the bus and vanished into the night.
</P>
<P>
   _ L.E. FEINBERG
</P>
<P>
   RESUME
</P>
<P>
   Diets are broken,
</P>
<P>
   Cycling gets old,
</P>
<P>
   Fen-phen's verboten,
</P>
<P>
   Jogging? Too cold!
</P>
<P>
   Fasting is dicey,
</P>
<P>
   Lipo's no treat,
</P>
<P>
   Spas are pricey.
</P>
<P>
   You might as well eat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ELLEN CONFORD
</P>
<P>
   Eunice M. Ganteaume finds that scarcely a day passes when she is
not reminded that she lives in a multiethnic city. The most recent
example was at the height of rush hour on Madison Avenue. She
spotted a delivery van whose driver was skillfully maneuvering
through heavy traffic, one hand grasping the wheel, the other
manipulating chopsticks.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Finger's friend, Monique Van Vooren, is an animal lover
who knows all the animals in her apartment building. One of the
pets, a favorite, she called Mr. Jones in honor of his mistress.
(The name Jones is a pseudonym).
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, a notice was posted in the building that ``Mr.
Jones went to join the angels yesterday.'' Van Vooren wrote Mrs.
Jones extolling Mr. Jones' personality, noting how shiny and clean
he was and how frisky. She added that although it was difficult to
contemplate when a loss was fresh, her own experience indicated
that it was wise to replace a pet as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   A week later she encountered Mrs. Jones in the lobby. ``I
received your note, Miss Van Vooren,'' she said. ``It wasn't the
dog who died. It was my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   On my way to the doctor, I boarded a 96th Street crosstown bus
at the first stop on West End Avenue. A woman in a purple coat with
green trim was crocheting and I asked her where she got her yarn.
She told me she had bought 50 pounds at some out-of-town discount
place.
</P>
<P>
   I mentioned that I wanted to revive my interest in the craft and
she rummaged through her orange and white crocheted bag and came up
with a ball of deep purple yarn for me to start on. When I noted
that I didn't have a crochet hook, she rummaged through the bag
again and voila! By the time we were crossing Central Park I was
having my first lesson and I recalled some stitches I had learned
as a child.
</P>
<P>
   I got off at Fifth Avenue, sat in the doctor's office for over
an hour and for once didn't mind the wait _ I practiced on my
purple yarn.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURA GREENBERG
</P>
<P>
   It was a northbound not-too-crowded Lexington Avenue subway
train. Jan Vilcek observed a middle-aged Asian woman entering with
a little girl, perhaps 5 _ very likely a grandmother and
granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmother found a seat across the aisle from the little
girl, who wore sneakers with one shoelace untied. The grandmother,
speaking in either Mandarin or Cantonese, apparently, and very
audibly, explained to the child how to tie her shoelace. The
youngster made numerous efforts but couldn't manage it.
</P>
<P>
   When the train reached the 59th Street stop, a young man got in,
sat next to the girl and tried to help her tie the shoelace. The
grandmother screamed ``No'' and the young man gave up. The
grandmother kept on instructing and the child kept on trying, all
in vain. At the next stop, the grandmother moved to an empty seat
next to the girl and demonstrated how to tie the knot, but stopped
short of actually securing the lace.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the youngster succeeded. The passengers in the car,
most of whom could see, and all of whom were able to hear what was
going on, erupted in applause.
</P>
<P>
   Scene: Elevator at Citibank, Fifth Avenue and 13th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Players: Alice La Prelle, ready to push button, and elderly
well-dressed woman, entering hastily.
</P>
<P>
   La Prelle, politely: ``Which floor?''
</P>
<P>
   Elderly woman, lifting her skirt: ``It doesn't matter. I'm here
to pull up my tights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 2241EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
