u f BC-YAHOO-MURDOCH-NYT &LR;      02-27 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-MURDOCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YAHOO AND MURDOCH SAID TO BE IN TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The News Corp., the holding company for Rupert Murdoch's media
empire, and Yahoo Inc., the giant Internet portal, are discussing
an alliance that could include stock investments in each other's
operations, according to News Corp. executives close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies are interested in joining forces to counter
the recently announced merger of America Online and Time Warner.
But the executives said any deal was probably weeks away at best.
</P>
<P>
   A report published in the most recent New Yorker said that the
talks envisioned ``a wide-ranging alliance'' providing Yahoo with
access to the Fox News Channel and News Corp.-owned newspapers like
The Times of London and The New York Post. News Corp. in turn would
gain credibility for its recently announced effort to use its
extensive satellite networks to deliver Internet services to
consumers along with its television programming.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely that any deal would include cross investments by
Yahoo and the News Corp. although neither investment would come
close to a controlling interest, the New Yorker report said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Yang, the 31-year-old co-founder of Yahoo, and Peter
Chernin, president and chief operating officer of News Corp., have
held several meetings, the News Corp. executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Yang and Chernin could not be reached for comment. But a News
Corp. executive said that Yahoo was one of many companies the News
Corp. had been talking with in light of its announcement two weeks
ago that it planned to create a separate venture for its satellite
properties. At that time, he noted, the company said it would be
looking for partners that would invest in the venture and work with
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no agreement near with anybody,'' the executive said.
``Nothing has been nailed down.''
</P>
<P>
   Bankers and analysts said that no one would be surprised if a
substantial alliance emerged. ``Everyone has been talking to
everyone since AOL-Time Warner,'' said an investment banker
actively involved in the media industry.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo has already showed signs of rethinking its future since
America Online and Time Warner announced their deal. Where the
company Yang and David Filo created just six years ago once viewed
itself as a kind of Switzerland of the Internet, a neutral portal
through which all kinds of content providers could pass, it
recently has been moving to create content of its own, including a
financial news broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great content will win over time,'' Yang said on Sunday night
when questioned during a discussion at Stanford University on the
Internet's future about what will determine which of the many paths
to the Internet consumers will use.
</P>
<P>
   But creating content is a high-risk enterprise. Linking up with
Murdoch's empire might be a quicker and less expensive route toward
recreating Yahoo as a recognized source for specialized news and
services. The News Corp.'s digital media subsidiary, which is based
in New York, already provides some content to Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking with the News Corporation is another indication that
their perception of what they need to survive is changing,'' said
Robert Enderle, an analyst for the Giga Information Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
