<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARNHAM PROVIDES SPIRIT FOR BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Losers of six of seven, on the brink of NCAA
Tournament elimination, desperate and discouraged and searching for
help, the UCLA Bruins turned to ... (begin ital)Sean Farnham?(end
ital)
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Sean Farnham, the ebullient senior forward with modest
skills and irrepressible spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Steve Lavin inserted Farnham into the starting
lineup against the Oregon schools and removed slumping forward
Jerome Moiso. Although his numbers weren't impressive (five points,
four rebounds), Farnham provided a much-needed passion injection.
</P>
<P>
   After their weekend sweep, the Bruins improved to 10-1 with
Farnham in the lineup in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our leprechaun,'' Lavin said, smiling. ``Well, not
really. He just does the simple things well.''
</P>
<P>
   For Farnham, a former walk-on who has played sparingly most of
his career, the timing couldn't be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have gotten down,'' he said. ``There were four games
in a row (a few weeks ago) that I didn't see the court, and we
weren't performing well. But I kept my head up. It's been great to
get starts in two of my last four games in Pauley Pavilion.''
</P>
<P>
   Positive pine time: Moiso had no objection to his new role. In
fact, he enjoys being a reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows him to watch things and he gets more comfortable,''
Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso had 16 points and eight rebounds against Oregon State, his
best game in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The spring is back: UCLA's grueling schedule might ultimately
propel the Bruins into the NCAA Tournament. But in one instance -
playing at Syracuse on a Sunday, rather than a Saturday - it did
them more harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   With a Saturday game, the Bruins would have returned that night,
taken Sunday off, then had full practices Monday and Tuesday before
leaving for Arizona State on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they got home late Sunday night, took Monday off, then
crammed everything into Tuesday and an abbreviated workout
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's suicide to play that game in Syracuse, on a Sunday, with
a road trip the following week,'' a Pac-10 coach said. ``That takes
a lot out of you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had little choice in the matter; CBS set the date. To
their credit, they did not use heavy legs as an excuse for the
debacle in Tempe. But there's no doubt they looked refreshed
against the Oregon schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did play three road games in a week,'' guard Earl Watson
said. ``Maybe that took a little out of us. I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving up: UCLA climbed to 37th in the latest Sagarin power
ratings and 29th in the latest RPI rankings.
</P>
<P>
   But take note, Bruin fans: The RPI approximates the ratings used
by the NCAA Selection committee; it does not duplicate. For
instance, Kentucky is No. 2 in the latest RPI, which corresponds to
one of the four No. 1 seeds in the tournament. But there's no
chance the eight-loss Wildcats will be a top seed.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, UCLA's lofty ranking does not guarantee an
at-large bid.
</P>
<P>
   And finally: A ruling on JaRon Rush's appeal is expected today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-27-00 2311EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
