<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-27 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0410 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-CAMPAIGN-DEMOCRATS-SP     02-27 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-DEMOCRATS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, BRADLEY CAMPAIGN HEAVILY IN WASHINGTON STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vice President Al Gore bonded with Boeing strikers and
bashed health-care insurers Sunday, treating his 14th visit to
Washington since the 1996 election as a primary eve chance to put
away the Democratic challenge of former New Jersey Sen. Bill
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, with the state party apparatus and leading politicians
behind him, fired back at Bradley, who has attacked Gore's record,
consistency and credibility on issues of abortion rights, gun
control and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Bradley has stepped down to the level of personal
vilification, and I will not follow him into that,'' Gore said
during an interview Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president did appear curiously grateful to Bradley for
pressing the fight. ``I think the competition has been good for me
in helping me become a far better candidate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also tested themes for the general election, criticizing
Republican candidate Gov. George W. Bush for his environmental
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under George W. Bush's stewardship, Texas has become number
one of the 50 states _ number one in polluting the air, the water
and the land,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore-Bradley contest in Tuesday's primary is merely a beauty
contest, with no delegates at stake.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley needs a showing that will shine national attention
on his campaign with big primaries in California, New York, Ohio
and Massachusetts next week. He has campaigned in Washington for
the past six days, using speeches, radio ads and mailings to
criticize Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spent much of the weekend campaigning to see that Bradley
doesn't get the traction he needs. Each of the Democratic
candidates has spent an estimated $400,000 on media here, according
to state Democratic chairman Paul Berendt.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who also stopped to show solidarity with striking
Boeing workers, on Sunday delivered one of his most personal and
deeply felt speeches of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The former New York Knicks forward told an overflow congregation
at the First African Methodist Episcopal Church how he learned
about racial discrimination in the 1950s when his Little League
baseball team was thrown out of restaurants because the catcher and
left fielder were black.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley talked of how he was ``stunned'' at the New York jury
verdict Friday that acquitted four white police officers in the
shooting death of Amadou Diallo, an immigrant from West Africa. The
officers fired 41 bullets, 19 of which struck Diallo. They claimed
Diallo appeared to be reaching for a gun. It turned out to be his
wallet.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that experience says to me is that this is a tragedy, but
there is a deeper tragedy we must solve,'' Bradley said. He
identified the problem as racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``A wallet in the hand of a white man looks like a wallet (to a
police officer),'' Bradley said. ``A wallet in the hand of a black
man looks like a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Sunday, Gore was running as both the candidate of good
economic times, and as a tough Mr. Fix It. He fixed on the medical
crisis facing one Everett, Wash., family, calling for Congress to
enact a patient's bill of rights and bashing a major American
health insurer.
</P>
<P>
   Before a rally at Franklin High School here, Gore met with Dylan
and Christine Malone, whose six-month-old son, Ian, suffered severe
birth injuries. With the Malones' consent, Gore made public their
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid can't swallow,'' Gore told the rally. ``His lungs fill
with fluid. He requires around the clock nursing care. Right now,
his life is at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The family's insurance company, Aetna, has refused to pay for
the boy's nursing care. The boy's 12 hours of daily nursing care
will end March 2. Aetna will provide eight hours of care a day
through mid-March, after which Ian will receive no skilled care at
all. The cost of nursing runs to $200 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had a message for Aetna. ``Don't do this! Don't do this!''
he shouted. ``Don't cut off this child's coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Give 'em hell, Al!'' shouted one of the 500 supporters, mainly
union members, who cheered Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan Malone said he had faxed a newspaper article about Dylan
to the vice president's office, and received a call requesting that
he meet with Gore. ``He was honestly moved,'' said Malone, a
graphic artist. ``He said he would contact Aetna personally and put
pressure on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ian has become an accidental poster child for a health care
bill of rights, fine,'' added the young father. ``I don't want him
to become a martyr.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., a friend of Gore's for 24 years,
Sunday described Gore and Bill Clinton as ``a tremendous
partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   During his weekend visit, the somewhat guarded Gore showed what
he has learned about images and symbols of politics from the
outgoing Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bradley and Gore talked Saturday night to an NAACP dinner
in Seattle. They each defended affirmative action. Each decried
Republican candidates for failing to take a stand against flying
the Confederate battle flag from the South Carolina statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, however, was able to point to a woman named Donna Brazile
in the audience, and declare: ``She is the first African-American
presidential campaign manager in the history of campaigns.'' A
beaming Brazile received a standing ovation and more cheers than
her candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has also used his powers of office to help
what is a must-win state for Democrats in November. Talking about
how Gore has ``delivered for Washington,'' Dicks delivered a litany
of federal spending projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked him to put $100 million for West Coast salmon into
the budget,'' Dicks said. ``The money went into the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has spent the past week dwelling on what the
Clinton-Gore administration has not done. He has stressed, for
instance, that there are 44 million Americans without health
insurance _ more than when the Democrats took over the White House.
He has decried lack of action on campaign finance reform,
describing special interest money as a ``wall'' that blocks
Americans' access to political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have a cold mountain stream flow through Washington
(D.C.) and carry away the corruption,'' Bradley has told audiences
around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has also hammered at Gore's record as a senator and
congressman from Tennessee, notably Gore's support for amendments
restricting federal funding of abortions, and pro-gun votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at Al Gore in the past, and Al Gore in the
present, it is hard to know where his convictions lie,'' Bradley
has told audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Gore fired back Sunday, lifting a vote that Bradley cast for a
package of spending reductions in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't vote for Ronald Reagan's budget cuts and then
campaign like Robert Kennedy,'' he told backers at Franklin High.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's challenge has brought about a spate of furious
finger-pointing and letter writing in the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Led by state chairman Berendt, the Democratic establishment has
accused Bradley of running a campaign of ``personal attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing to Bradley, Dicks told the former senator: ``While you
talk about keeping our environment clean, your negative radio ads,
and now your misleading direct mail pieces pollute Washington
airwaves and mailboxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign has fired back, accusing the state Democratic
party of violating a pledge of neutrality. ``You have complained
publicly of the need to not divide the party: Why not start with
yourself?'' Walt Bowen, Thurston County Democratic chairman, wrote
to Berendt.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has tried to stay above the fray. ``I knew from the
beginning that I was up against entrenched power,'' he said in an
interview, ``but just before the primary I am not about to pick a
fight with the state Democratic Party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
