<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEZBOLLAH-FUTURE (Beirut, Lebanon) _ Hezbollah has much to
celebrate these days. Prime Minister Ehud Barak's commitment to
withdraw Israel's 1,000-man contingent from southern Lebanon by
July 7 has opened the way for Hezbollah to declare itself the lone
Arab force ever to ``defeat'' Israeli forces. But nothing has been
simple in Lebanese politics since the country began to deconstruct
in the mid-1970s, and Hezbollah's moment of triumph could also be
prelude to a painful transition for the Islamic group. By John F.
Burns.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-TALKS (Bogota, Colombia) _ Officially, peace talks
between the Colombian government and the largest rebel group are
stalled, with no date set for them to resume. Yet just the other
day, the government's chief negotiator boasted that ``we have
advanced further this month than in 40 years of conflict.'' That
apparent paradox is the result of an unusual new twist to efforts
to negotiate an end to a civil conflict that has killed 35,000
Colombians in the past decade. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CULT (Yokohama, Japan) _ It is not easy to visit the new
leader of the embattled Aum Shinrikyo religious cult who has been
holed up in the sect's branch office here since being released from
prison late last year. Visitors must pass through dozens of riot
police, submit to a body search, and often endure the heckling of
angry Japanese mobs that gather to denounce the cult, which was
behind the nerve gas attack that killed 12 people in the Tokyo
subways five years ago. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-PUERTO-RICANS (New York) _ Being Latino in New York City used
to mean being Puerto Rican. But over the last decade, the number of
Puerto Rican New Yorkers decreased for the first time since they
began arriving in the city in great numbers 60 years ago. Experts
say the decline is destined to continue. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   LARAMIE-PLAY (Denver) _ A play called ``The Laramie Project,''
based on the Matthew Shepard case, opened in Denver on Saturday
night, and many in the audience were people who were characters in
the play and residents of the Wyoming town where the gay college
student was murdered. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CALIF (Pasadena, Calif.) _ As the presidential campaign
moves to the biggest states, George W. Bush and John McCain are
battling squarely for the biggest prize of all: California, whose
once-mighty Republican Party propelled Richard Nixon and Ronald
Reagan to the White House but has languished and feuded for much of
the 1990s as President Clinton and the Democrats came to dominate
the state. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-MEDIA (Seattle) _ With limited resources and a
staggering media challenge _ getting their messages out in 17
states holding primaries in the next nine days _ the four leading
Republicans and Democrats in the race for president are engaged in
a feverish hopscotch of the nation, targeting television markets in
certain states, bypassing others and relying to an even larger
extent than before on the ``free media'' supplied by the press to
make their cases. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-WASH (Seattle) _ Everyone says it's over, but Bill
Bradley has once again found his voice and hit his stride in the
unlikely battleground of Washington state. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-WASH (Redmond, Wash.) _ Washington state, which will
account for only 2.2 percent of the delegates at the Democratic
National Convention this year, has unexpectedly emerged as a
battleground for the two men seeking the party's presidential
nomination, and Al Gore spent much of the weekend here trying to
make sure Bill Bradley would have nothing to show for his huge
investment of time and energy in the state's presidential primary
on Tuesday. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ASSESS (Washington) _ Gov. George W. Bush touched all the
right bases Sunday in expressing regret to Cardinal John O'Connor
of New York over his journey to Bob Jones University: the cardinal
is the de facto leader of the Roman Catholic Church in the United
States and he is widely respected across religious lines. Bush was
determined to muffle the outcry before crucial primaries in New
York, California, Illinois and other states with large Catholic
constituencies. And the Texas governor sent a signal to voters _
and his contributors _ that he is not too high and mighty to admit
a blunder. But there was one big problem: Bush's turnabout may have
come about 24 days too late. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AMTRAK-NEW-ROUTES _ After years of trying to balance its books
by cutting service, Amtrak has concluded that to succeed it should
instead create new routes, offer more frequent service on existing
lines and organize itself more like the airlines, so people can
change from train to train and get to places more efficiently. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   MINT-DIRECTOR-PROFILE _ The director of the mint introduces the
country to Sacagaweya. By Francis X. Clines.
