outside the realm of traditional advertising. The moves are
indicative of the additional emphasis being placed on fast-growing
services like media as well as the increasing importance of
segments of the mass market. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ The latest entrant in the Internet
economy's continuing game of buzzword bingo is ``business to
business,'' predictably shortened to ``B2B.'' The Digital Commerce
column. By Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-LEAP-COMPUTERS (Undated) _ Because computers have
encountered far fewer year 2000 date failures than anticipated, the
assumption is that computer users also fixed nearly all the
potential leap-year faults as they were spending billions on year
2000 precautions. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-TV (Washington) _ Under threat from the chairman of the
Federal Communications Commission, the cable television and
consumer-electronics industries have said that they have solved a
vexing problem slowing the transition to digital TV. But the issue
is still not fully resolved. It is the second time the two
organizations have made such an announcement. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-CHIP-TECHNOLOGY (Undated) _ Technologists for IBM Corp. will
describe new details this week of a next-generation chip-making
system that uses beams of electrons, rather than lightwaves, to
etch circuits onto chips. By John Markoff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUN-MICROSOFT-PRANK (San Francisco) _ Sun Microsystems'
chairman, Scott McNealy, is well known for his merciless teasing of
Bill Gates and Microsoft. But one recent attempted prank against
Microsoft appears to have fallen short. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   EMTV-MUPPETS-MEDIA (Munich, Germany) _ Though almost unknown
outside of Germany, Thomas Haffa, founder of EM.TV &AMP;
Merchandising,_ an 11-year old company built on selling just about
anything to do with children's television _ last week clinched the
biggest deal of his life: an agreement to buy the Jim Henson Co.
and its legendary Muppets for $680 million. A company profile. By
Edmund L. Andrews.
