<P>
   HARLEM-MUSEUM (New York) _ The Studio Museum in Harlem has long
been a respected if taken-for-granted presence in the New York art
world. But with the recent hiring of a new director and deputy
director, both from the very center of the art world, its
visibility is sure to increase. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   WRITERS-ON-WRITING (Undated) _ The ongoing series in which
writers explore literary themes. This week by Anne Bernays.
</P>
<P>
   MAUCERI-OPERA-PROFILE (New York) _ For John Mauceri the path to
Kurt Weill's ``Eternal Road,'' which he is conducting for six
performances beginning Monday at the Brooklyn Academy of Music, has
been long and winding. By Mervyn Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   TIPPING-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Malcolm Gladwell proposes a
fascinating and possibly useful theory in ``The Tipping Point: How
Little Things Can Make a Big Difference'': namely that ideas,
attitudes and behaviors tend to spread contagiously in the same way
as some infectious diseases. By Christopher Lehmann-Haupt.
</P>
<P>
   TV-BROWN-REVIEW (Undated) _ To the North's abolitionists John
Brown was a martyr. To many Southerners he was a fanatical
murderer. ``John Brown's Holy War'' finds justification for both
opinions. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   TV-GRAPEVINE-REVIEW (Undated) _ In the new romantic comedy
``Grapevine,'' a group of thirtyish, preternaturally good-looking
men and women live in Miami, gaze directly into the camera and
explain the tangled, ever-changing lines of love and friendship
that connect them. By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (New York) _ Bob Herbert comments on the Diallo
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ William Safire on the silent
turmoil in Chinese politics.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Column on the Knicks-76ers game.
By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-COUNTDOWN (Undated) _ Two hundred days before much of the
world turns its attention to Homebush Bay, the unlikely hub of the
next Summer Olympics, there is only one building crane still in
operation on the vast site that was once an abattoir and then a
dumping ground for household and industrial waste. By Christopher
Clarey.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY (Tampa, Fla.) _ On the Yankees column on
Darryl Strawberry. By Buster Olney.
